ructure, such as CPUs, storage, networking, GPUs, and DPUs as a seamless and dynamic operating environment, and also manages the complexity of a data center.&nbsp;
It virtualizes physical infrastructure into managed CPU, storage, and networking resources.vSphere
├── ESX (data plane)
├── vCenter Server (control plane)
└── Integrated services (HA, DRS, vMotion, etc.)
vSphere is a distributed system that provides the following:The two core components of VMware&nbsp;vSphere are <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br>
Whereas <a data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a> is the Web UI that interacts with the APIs of vSphere components.vSphere is a product contract, not a system.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> are the systems that implement that contract.Here is how vSphere facilitates LCM:
<br>Lifecycle management via pre-staging <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> images.
<br>Near-zero-downtime live patching for <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
<br>vSphere as a platform, manages <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a> performance in several dimensions:
With its GPU support, vSphere improves workload performance for modern AI workloads
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> enables automatic load balancing of resources allocated to workloads in a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>.
Storage DRS optimizes VM data placement as the VM is created and used over time.
Moving workloads seamlessly across the fabric, and ensuring things are always ship-shape, is what vSphere excels at:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">High Availability</a> with&nbsp;vSphere automatically restarts your VMs following physical machine failure.
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> provides continuous availability of any application in the event of a hardware failure with no data loss or downtime.
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> enables live migration of virtual machines with no disruption to users or loss of service, eliminating the need to schedule application downtime for planned server maintenance. Storage vMotion avoids downtime for planned storage maintenance. At vSphere security is by default, not an afterthought:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Identity Federation</a> with Microsoft Entra ID, ADFS and Okta.
Virtual Machine Encryption: Data-at-rest encryption for virtual machine data and disks.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Trust Authority" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Trust Authority</a>: Remote attestation for sensitive workloads.
Yesn’t.Saying “vSphere is ‘ESX and vCenter’.” is colloquially common, but technically incomplete.<br>See <a data-href="vSphere, ESX, and vCenter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere, ESX, and vCenter</a> for a more nuanced analysis.<br>You might also want to check <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> for an idea of what vSphere directly controls, and what capabilities it has.<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, one of the core components that makes vSphere, vSphere.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/vSphere.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 03:31:36 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[About VCF]]></title><description><![CDATA[
VCF is a full-stack <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="IaaS" data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)</a> platform that delivers software-defined compute, storage, networking, security, and management.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Integrated automation</a> enables a self-service platform to deploy VMs and containers for developer agility.
Hardened platform offering built-in resilience, scaling, and clustering for non-stop operations.
