]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/todo.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">TODO.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 00:12:08 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Performance Monitoring]]></title><description><![CDATA[Performance Monitoring within <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> focuses on ensuring applications and platform services consistently receive the resources they need—while enabling rapid detection, diagnosis, and resolution of performance issues.Rather than relying solely on static thresholds or isolated metrics, performance monitoring leverages continuous telemetry and analytics to understand how workloads behave over time, identify anomalies, and surface emerging risks before they impact users or SLAs.In practical terms, it answers:
Are my applications getting the resources they expect, and if not—why?
Performance monitoring collects and analyzes application-level metrics from virtual machines and supporting infrastructure.
CPU, memory, disk, and network utilization
Latency, throughput, and contention indicators
Performance baselines derived from historical behavior
Correlation between application performance and infrastructure conditions
This shifts the perspective from “is the host healthy?” to “is the application experiencing friction?”Advanced analytics and machine learning are applied to identify patterns and anomalies that traditional monitoring often misses.
Detects abnormal behavior relative to learned baselines
Correlates symptoms across compute, storage, and networking layers
Highlights probable root causes rather than isolated alerts
Enables faster time to resolution while avoiding unnecessary overprovisioning
The result is signal over noise, especially in large or dynamic environments.Performance monitoring ensures workloads maintain reliable access to required resources.
Identifies resource contention and saturation risks
Surfaces inefficient resource usage and imbalance
Supports proactive scaling and right-sizing decisions
Helps balance performance objectives against cost efficiency
This allows operators to protect performance without defaulting to over-allocation.A VCF Operations management pack is a modular integration that extends monitoring and analytics to specific infrastructure or platform components.
Collects metrics, events, and alerts from integrated systems
Normalizes telemetry into a common operational model
Enables deep, component-aware performance analysis
Supports consistent monitoring across heterogeneous environments
Management packs are what allow VCF Operations to scale from generic monitoring into domain-aware performance intelligence.Performance Monitoring is:
Application-aware and infrastructure-correlated
Predictive and analytics-driven
Focused on sustained performance and efficiency
Performance Monitoring is not:
Simple threshold-based alerting
A standalone APM tool
A workload deployment or governance mechanism Performance monitoring ensures applications continuously receive the resources they need
AI-driven analytics reduce noise and accelerate root-cause analysis
Management packs enable deep, system-specific insights at scale
The goal is sustained performance and cost discipline—not just uptime
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Observability and Health/Performance Monitoring.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 00:06:04 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Business Services Console]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" target="_self"><br>VCF Business Services Console are cloud service that provides the ability to manage VCF Usage, meter <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">appliances</a>, <a data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">User Roles</a>, and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Resource Pool" data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">resource access</a>.VCF Business Services Console (BSC) is the business-facing control plane for VCF that focuses on commercial governance, not infrastructure operations. It provides tenancy, subscription, entitlement, and usage visibility across organizations and projects.If vCenter answers “what is running?”, BSC answers:
“Who is entitled to what, who is using it, and how should it be charged?”
VCF
├── Infrastructure &amp; Ops
│ ├── vCenter / ESXi
│ ├── NSX / vSAN
│ └── VCF Automation
│
├── Metering
│ └── Usage Meter
│
└── Business Layer └── Business Services Console ├── Organizations ├── Subscriptions ├── Entitlements └── Usage visibility Audience: Platform owners, cloud business teams, service providers
Not for day-to-day infrastructure operators <br>Defines <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s as commercial entities
Associates: Subscriptions
Entitlements
Usage views This is a business boundary, not a technical one.
Tracks which orgs are entitled to: VCF capacity
Optional components (NSX, vSAN, etc.) Aligns commercial contracts with technical consumption
BSC does not provision resources — it governs access.
<br>Consumes data from <a data-href="VCF Usage Meter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-usage-meter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Usage Meter</a>
Presents usage in: Business-friendly terms
Aggregated per org / subscription Enables showback / chargeback workflows
Especially relevant for:
Internal private clouds with multiple business units
Service providers offering VCF-based services
BSC gives a single pane of glass for business accountability.BSC is governance and visibility, not execution.Think of BSC as:
The billing and entitlement desk of your private cloud Not the data center.
Not the scheduler.
Not the automation engine.
With subscription-based licensing:
“Installed” ≠ “Billable”
“Running” ≠ “Entitled”
BSC:
Bridges commercial reality and technical usage
Makes private cloud operate more like a public cloud business Cloud platform owners
Finance / FinOps teams
Service provider admins
Business unit IT leads
Rarely: day-to-day SREs.
VCF Business Services Console is the business control plane
Manages organizations, subscriptions, and entitlements
Consumes (but does not generate) usage data
Complements Usage Meter and VCF Automation
Essential for multi-tenant, subscription-driven VCF deployments
<br>Why not check out <a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a>, <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>, or <a data-href="VMware Live Recovery" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmware-live-recovery.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Live Recovery</a>?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Usage, Metering, and Business Ops/VCF Business Services Console.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 00:05:24 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vcf-business-services-featured-image]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 23:58:11 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Resource Pool]]></title><description><![CDATA[A Resource Pool in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a vSphere construct that carves up CPU and memory capacity inside a cluster and applies <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> controls (limits, reservations, shares) over how workloads consume those resources.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> inherits Resource Pools from <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>; it does not redefine them.<br>Think of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> as layered plumbing:VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere (via vCenter) └── Cluster └── Resource Pool └── VM / vApp <br>Owned by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Managed through: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br>Consumed by: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMs</a> (and <a data-href="vApp" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vApp</a>s), including those provisioned via <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> may target a resource pool, but does not create a new abstraction here.A Resource Pool lets you govern contention, not create capacity.
Resource Pools do not add resources — they only slice and prioritize what already exists in the cluster.
Think of a cluster as a water tank:
The tank size = physical host capacity
Resource Pools = valves
Shares = which valve opens wider under pressure
Reservations = minimum guaranteed flow
Limits = maximum allowed flow
No matter how many valves you add, the tank size never changes.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> itself does not require Resource Pools, but they are often used:
To separate platform workloads from tenant workloads
To protect management components from noisy neighbors
To enforce guardrails in shared clusters
Example:Cluster
├── Mgmt-RP (high shares, reservations)
│ ├── vCenter
│ ├── NSX Managers
│
└── Tenant-RP ├── App-VMs ├── DB-VMs
❌ Overusing limits
→ Causes artificial throttling and unpredictable latency❌ Deeply nested pools
→ Shares become multiplicative and hard to reason about❌ Using pools as security boundaries
→ They are not isolation mechanisms
❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not a billing unit
❌ Not a Kubernetes namespace
❌ Not a quota system (that’s layered above, e.g., VCF Automation) <br>A Resource Pool is a vSphere scheduling construct, fully inherited by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
It controls CPU and memory contention, not ownership or tenancy
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> may reference it, but does not redefine it
Use sparingly, with clear intent and shallow hierarchies
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, and <a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> are all related contents that you might want to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Inventory Objects/Resource Pool.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 23:54:06 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Trust Authority]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp" target="_self">vSphere Trust Authority (vTA) is a hardware-rooted security feature that separates “who can decrypt and attest” from “who runs the workload.”It uses trusted execution and attestation so that even infrastructure administrators cannot access protected secrets or plaintext data.In VCF, vTA is an optional, high-assurance security capability, not a default baseline.VMware Cloud Foundation
├── Trust Authority Cluster (isolated)
│ ├── Key Provider / Attestation Services
│ └── Hardware-backed trust (TPM, TEE)
│
└── Workload Domains └── Protected VMs / workloads <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
Integrated with: Key Management Interoperability Protocol (KMIP) providers
<br>Managed through: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Classic virtualization problem:
Infrastructure admins can ultimately see everything.
vTA introduces cryptographic separation of duties:
Infra admins manage hosts and clusters
They do NOT control keys
Decryption happens only after hardware attestation
This matters in:
Regulated environments
Confidential Computing
Insider-threat models
Sovereign cloud designs Trust Authority Cluster boots with TPM-backed identity
Hosts and workloads are attested
Only if attestation passes: Encryption keys are released
Protected workloads decrypt and run If trust breaks: Keys are withheld
Workloads remain encrypted / suspended Access to infrastructure ≠ access to data <br>Separate <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> cluster
Minimal admin surface
Hosts key and attestation services Uses CPU security features (e.g., SEV, TDX)
Prevents memory inspection Keys never live with workload admins
Often backed by HSMs
vTA is the strongest isolation boundary in vSphere.Typical usage:
Confidential VMs
Telco and Financial Workloads
Government / Sovereign Clouds
Typical non-usage:
General enterprise clusters
Cost-sensitive environments
Dev/Test
VTA is deliberately heavyweight.Think of vTA as:
“Even if someone owns the data center, they still cannot read the data.”
It is zero-trust applied to virtualization itself.
❌ Not a secrets manager
❌ Not an identity provider
❌ Not Kubernetes confidential computing (though complementary)
❌ Not required for VCF Strongest insider-threat protection
Hardware-rooted trust
Clear separation of duties Additional clusters and hardware
Operational complexity
Limited workload compatibility vSphere Trust Authority brings confidential computing to VCF
It cryptographically separates infra admins from data access
Optional, niche, but extremely powerful
Used when “root access is not enough” must be enforced
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, and <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/Security Services/vSphere Trust Authority.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 23:46:07 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>See Also: <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, a Project is a logical, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant-scoped</a> construct used for workload organization, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, and self-service consumption.It exists at the automation and policy layer, not the virtualization layer.A Project is a logical grouping within an organization.Projects:
Represent application teams or environments
<br>Contain one or more <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters
<br>Are mapped to one or more <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s
Define resource entitlements and policy boundaries
Key properties:
Projects can be renamed
Projects cannot be deleted if they contain VKS clusters
A VKS cluster belongs to exactly one Project
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> cannot span multiple Projects
Projects act as the bridge between organizational intent and infrastructure execution.Projects group workloads, users, quotas, policies, and lifecycle controls under a common administrative boundary. It is “a governed slice of cloud capacity” exposed to consumers.<br>Projects live primarily in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (formerly vRealize Automation / Aria Automation).It is not:
A vSphere cluster
A Kubernetes cluster
A resource pool
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> (though it may map to one)
Instead, it is a control-plane abstraction that binds together multiple lower-level constructs.VCF Instance └── Organization └── Project ├── Users &amp; Roles ├── Policies &amp; Quotas ├── Cloud Zones ├── Workload Deployments └── Supervisor Namespaces / VKS Clusters
<br>A project represents a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant</a> or sub-tenant:
Different teams
Different applications
Different environments (prod, staging, dev)
Each project is isolated from others by policy.Projects define who can do what:
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Project User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project User</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Advanced User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Advanced User</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Auditor</a>
These roles govern:
Who can deploy workloads
<br>Who can modify <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s
Who can see usage or costs
Projects define where workloads can land:
Which Cloud Zones they can use
Resource quotas (CPU, memory, storage)
Network constraints
Storage policies
This prevents a single tenant from exhausting shared infrastructure.Projects are the context in which users deploy:
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s
Kubernetes clusters (e.g., Supervisor-backed)
Application blueprints
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> operations (scale, update, destroy)
Everything a user deploys is always within a project.A Project maps to:
<br>
A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> One or more Kubernetes clusters A set of Kubernetes namespaces inside those clusters But the Project itself is not Kubernetes-native.
It’s a management abstraction above Kubernetes.Think of it as:
“A governance wrapper around Kubernetes and VM resources.”
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> supports both one-to-one and one-to-many mappings between Projects and <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s; the choice is an architectural pattern, not a platform constraint.Very common, very clean:Organization: Coca-Cola
├── Project: Coke-Prod → ns-coke-prod
├── Project: Coke-Stage → ns-coke-stage
└── Project: Coke-Dev → ns-coke-dev
This provides:
Clean blast-radius isolation
Clear RBAC and quotas per environment
Easy mental model
Common in regulated / prod-heavy setups
This is a design choice, not a platform requirement.(Equally valid, also common in larger deployments)Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke ├── ns-coke-dev ├── ns-coke-stage └── ns-coke-prod
This provides:
Shared governance (same people, same blueprints)
Environment separation handled at namespace level
Easier cross-env promotion workflows
Fewer projects to manage
<br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>:
A Project is a logical tenant boundary
It governs who can deploy what, where, and how
It sits above infrastructure and below the organization
It is the unit of consumption for developers and teams
<br>It enables <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a>, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, and self-service
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Consumption Abstractions/Project.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 23:27:22 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Validated Solutions]]></title><description><![CDATA[The purpose of VMware-Validated Solutions is to deploy a VMware-designed <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> to deliver common business use cases.<br><img alt="vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" target="_self">VMware Validated Solutions (VVS) are prescriptive, end-to-end solution blueprints built on top of VMware Cloud Foundation that combine architecture, configuration, workflows, and lifecycle guidance into a tested and supportable outcome.A VMware Validated Solution is a known-good way to solve a concrete problem on VCF — designed, tested, and supported as a whole.They answer a very practical question:<br>
“Given <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, how do I implement this specific enterprise capability correctly and safely?”
A VVS is more than documentation. It typically includes:
Component topology
Trust boundaries
Network flows
Failure domains
Scale assumptions Exact settings (not suggestions)
Supported variants
Guardrails and constraints
Explicit “do / don’t” guidance <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> (deployment)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-1</a> (onboarding, enablement)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> (upgrade, scale, recover) How the solution evolves with VCF upgrades
What breaks compatibility
What is safe to automate
Everything is validated together, not in isolation.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a platform, not an opinionated solution by default.Enterprises, however, want outcomes, such as:
Secure multi-tenancy
Kubernetes at scale
Identity-integrated access
Backup, DR, or compliance alignment
Without validated solutions:
Every customer invents their own pattern
Outcomes vary wildly
Support becomes guesswork
Validated Solutions reduce design risk and support friction.<br>Here, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a programmable substrate, and Validated Solutions as approved programs.While names and scope evolve, common categories include:
Secure Cloud Infrastructure
Identity and Access Integration
Kubernetes Platform Enablement
Multi-tenant Cloud Architecture
Business Continuity / DR
Compliance-aligned deployments
Each one narrows a broad platform into a specific, repeatable design.They are not:
Reference “ideas”
Whitepapers
One-off examples
Mandatory architectures You can deviate—but once you do, you own the risk.
For architects and platform owners, Validated Solutions provide:
Faster time to value
Reduced design ambiguity
Predictable upgrades
Clear escalation paths Less freedom
Opinionated choices
Slower adoption of bleeding-edge features
This trade-off is deliberate.
VMware Validated Solutions are prescriptive, supported blueprints
They sit above VCF, not beside it
They reduce risk by constraining choice
They align architecture, operations, and lifecycle
Deviating is allowed—but unsupported paths are yours to own
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, <a data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy</a>, or <a data-href="Policy as Code" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy-as-code.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy as Code</a> as the next few concepts to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/VMware Validated Solutions/VMware Validated Solutions.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 23:24:39 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 23:16:58 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[CNS]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp" target="_self">CNS (Cloud Native Storage) is the vSphere capability that makes Kubernetes storage first-class and lifecycle-aware.<br>
It bridges Kubernetes PersistentVolumes with vSphere storage (typically <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>) so that Kubernetes, not admins, drives volume lifecycle, while <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> retains visibility, <a data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy</a>, and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.<br>VCF relies on CNS wherever Kubernetes (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Cluster" data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> or <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">guest clusters</a>) consumes vSphere storage.VCF
├── vSphere
│ ├── vCenter Server
│ │ └── CNS (storage awareness &amp; lifecycle)
│ ├── vSAN / VMFS / NFS
│ └── ESXi
│
└── Kubernetes ├── Supervisor Cluster └── Guest Clusters (VKS) └── PVC → PV → vSphere Volume <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Integrated via: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> CSI Driver
<br>Observed/managed in: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Without CNS:
Kubernetes creates volumes
vSphere sees “random disks”
No linkage, no lifecycle alignment
With CNS:
<br>Kubernetes objects ↔ <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> volumes are linked
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> understands which PVC belongs to which pod
Storage policy, health, and cleanup are automatic CNS makes Kubernetes storage visible, governable, and safe in vSphere. Lifecycle mapping <br>PVC create/delete ↔ <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> volume create/delete Topology awareness Knows which cluster, namespace, pod owns a volume Policy enforcement <br>Applies <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> Storage Policies (SPBM) Operational visibility <br>Shows Kubernetes volumes in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Client" data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter UI</a> &amp; APIs Kubernetes creates a PVC
CSI driver requests a volume
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> provisions storage (<a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>)
CNS records: Kubernetes metadata
Volume ownership On PVC delete → CNS ensures correct cleanup
<br>Kubernetes stays declarative; <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> stays authoritative.
CNS is always on
StorageClasses map directly to vSphere policies CNS operates via CSI
<br>Still centrally visible in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Same mechanism, different consumption layers.
❌ Not a storage array
❌ Not a CSI driver itself
❌ Not Kubernetes-only
❌ Not a replacement for vSAN
CNS is the glue, not the storage.If CSI is:
“The driver that talks to storage”
Then CNS is:
“The brain that understands Kubernetes intent inside vSphere” Enables policy-driven storage for containers
Prevents orphaned volumes
Makes Kubernetes operationally sane for infra teams
Required for supported VCF Kubernetes designs CNS = Cloud Native Storage awareness in vSphere
Aligns Kubernetes volume lifecycle with vSphere
Essential for Supervisor &amp; TKG clusters in VCF- Turns storage into a first-class Kubernetes citizen
<br>Control plane elements, like <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> and <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> and two possible places to jump from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/CNS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 22:43:49 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Identity Broker]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>VCF Identity Broker (vIDB) is the identity-federation service used by VCF Single Sign-On (SSO) to provide a unified authentication configuration across multiple components in a VCF environment.vIDB centralizes authentication across the major VCF infrastructure components so that administrators and users can sign in once and seamlessly access those systems using a corporate identity provider (IdP) of choice.A practical way to think of it:
vIDB = the “SSO engine”
VCF SSO = the fleet-level “SSO product experience” that drives vIDB configuration and pushes/coordinates it across components
In real deployments, vIDB is positioned as the central place where you integrate with upstream identity sources (for example AD/LDAPS, or “corporate IdPs” such as Okta/Entra/ADFS), and then VCF components are configured to trust/use that SSO configuration.<br>At a high level, VCF Identity Broker is an identity federation/intermediary service that sits between your enterprise identity provider (e.g., Okta, Microsoft Entra ID/Azure AD, Ping Identity, ADFS, LDAP/OpenLDAP) and the VCF platform services (like <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, and the <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>/<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> stack).It:
Accepts authentication from an external IdP using modern protocols (e.g., SAML 2.0, OpenID Connect) or directory services (LDAP/AD).
Issues federated/standard tokens to VCF components to enable central SSO across the environment.
Provides user and group provisioning integration (SCIM, Just-In-Time provisioning, LDAP sync) so that IdP users and groups can be mapped into VCF RBAC.
vIDB acts as a universal “identity broker” in a federation chain—it trusts your enterprise IdP and then vouches for those identities to VMware Cloud Foundation services.The vIDB service is described in the field as supporting at least:
Embedded mode (configured inside the management domain’s vCenter context; no separate deployment) <br>Runs inside the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>’s <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> (VCF management cluster).
Easier to deploy, ideal for smaller or single-instance VCF environments.
Doesn’t require a separate appliance. <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Appliance</a> mode (a stand-alone vIDB appliance cluster) Deployed as a stand-alone appliance cluster (often a three-node cluster for high availability).
Recommended for larger, production, or fleet-wide SSO use cases.
Provides scalability and resilience across multiple VCF instances. <br>Once enabled, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> SSO aims to make authentication consistent across VCF components.Instead of logging separately into:
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> / <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> UI
VCF Operations for Logs, Networks, etc.
you authenticate once via your enterprise IdP, and VCF Identity Broker handles the rest, issuing tokens and enabling access to all components with a common identity.<br>By centralizing authentication, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> reduces administrative overhead (no separate local accounts to manage on each component) and supports modern enterprise identity standards.VCF Identity Broker supports a range of identity sources:
Modern cloud IdPs: Okta, Ping Identity, Microsoft Entra ID / Azure AD, ADFS.
Traditional directory services: Active Directory via LDAP, OpenLDAP. Centralized authentication and SSO—better user experience and reduced login friction.
Integrates with corporate IdPs—enables MFA, policy enforcement, and audit logging from your enterprise identity layer.
Scalable deployment options—embedded for simplicity, appliance for scale/resilience. Adds an additional component to deploy and manage (especially in appliance mode).
Requires careful role mapping and RBAC planning so that IdP groups/roles map correctly to VCF permissions.
Legacy components may not participate in SSO the same way — they might still require local accounts even after VCF Identity Broker is configured.
A very real operational problem in multi-tenant systems is: Users get recreated/reidentified when you switch identity providers (or change claims, subject formats, etc.).
If a tenant starts on IdP-A and later moves to IdP-B, you want a controlled way to preserve user access and authorization mappings.
Remapping is the “bridge” that avoids breaking RBAC simply because the upstream identity changed.
Remapping is usually about reconciling user identities inside the platform’s internal user store / directory representation when the upstream IdP changes. It’s not “magic federation”—it’s an administrative identity-correlation operation.
Upstream IdP (Okta/Entra/ADFS/LDAP-backed federation)
Authenticates the human. Issues identity assertions / tokens.
vIDB (VCF Identity Broker)
Provides VCF SSO: consistent auth configuration across VCF components.
VCF Automation OIDC Services / IdP Proxy
Provides tenant-aware OIDC proxying for relying parties and/or for tenant-specific auth experiences inside the Automation/Cloud Director plane. <br>VCF Identity Broker is the central identity federation and Single Sign-On facilitator in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
It integrates your chosen identity provider with VCF components, allowing a single set of credentials and seamless access across services.
<br>Supports modern authentication protocols and multiple IdP types, helping enterprises align <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> with corporate identity strategies.
vIDB is the identity federation service underpinning VCF SSO, aimed at consistent login across VCF components
VCF Automation as an OIDC IdP proxy is a separate capability (vCloud Director lineage) that enables tenant-aware OIDC proxying.
User remapping between IdPs exists to preserve access/RBAC continuity when tenants change upstream identity sources.
<br>API access tokens in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> are commonly handled via exchanging a refresh token at .../oauth/provider/token.
<br>PKCE matters for modern public clients; <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>-related guidance explicitly calls for “public OIDC client with PKCE enabled” in some integration scenarios.
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> or <a data-href="Security Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/security-and-compliance/security-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Security Management</a> are two tangentially-related topics that you can navigate from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/VCF Identity Broker/VCF Identity Broker.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 22:42:59 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace]]></title><description><![CDATA[A Supervisor that uses <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> networking supports network security policies defined through a SecurityPolicy Custom Resource (CRD).<br>These policies allow you to enforce network-level controls for workloads running on the Supervisor, including <a data-href="Supervisor Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Pod</a>s and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">virtual machines</a>, by leveraging NSX’s distributed firewall capabilities.As a DevOps user, you can define and apply a SecurityPolicy CRD to enforce network security rules within a Supervisor namespace.Security policies apply to:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s
<br>VMs running in the Supervisor (including <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS cluster nodes</a>)
Other workloads within the same namespace <br>Access to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>
Permissions to apply Kubernetes custom resources
Create a YAML file that defines the desired network security rules using the SecurityPolicy CRD.Apply the policy to the target namespace using kubectl:kubectl apply -f policy-name.yaml
This action instructs the NSX Operator to translate the policy into NSX distributed firewall rules.You can inspect the applied policy using standard Kubernetes commands.kubectl get securitypolicy policy-name
kubectl describe securitypolicy policy-name
Security policies applied through Kubernetes are also visible in the NSX Manager UI.From the NSX interface, administrators can:
View applied firewall rules
Monitor enforcement status
Troubleshoot traffic flows <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> provides network security for <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s through SecurityPolicy CRDs.
Policies are applied at the namespace level.
<br>Enforcement is handled by <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, not Kubernetes itself.
Policies protect traffic between vSphere Pods, VMs, and external networks.
<br>Management is possible via both kubectl and the <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> UI.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “Supervisor Namespace”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/adding-security-policies-to-a-supervisor-namespace.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 22:20:34 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[Connected to Supervisor Cluster:kubectl config use-context &lt;supervisor-context&gt;
kubectl get ns NAME STATUS AGE
default Active
kube-system Active
kube-public Active
kube-node-lease Active
my-team-a Active
my-team-b Active
Here, there is no such thing as a “regular Kubernetes namespace” in the tenant sense.
The namespace here:
Cannot be created freely.
Map to <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> inventory objects.
Quotas, storage, and networking are externally-enforced.
Connected to a guest clusterkubectl get ns
kubectl create ns foo
kubectl delete ns foo
All of these will work as expected.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s → owns the cluster.
<br><a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> namespace → normal Kubernetes semantics.
# check Supervisor-specific APIs
kubectl api-resources | grep -i vm virtualmachines vmoperator.vmware.com # look at the nodes
kubectl get nodes -o wide # look for VM Operator
kubectl get pods -A | grep vmoperator
Supervisor cluster nodes typically show:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>-backed control-plane VMs.
Special node labels
VM Operator components
Guest clusters look like:
Standard Linux nodes
kubelet-managed lifecycle
No VM Operator CRDs. In a Supervisor cluster, tenant namespaces are Kubernetes namespaces whose lifecycle, limits, and security are owned by vSphere.
In a guest cluster, namespaces are owned entirely by Kubernetes.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “Supervisor Namespace”</a><br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/kubectl-in-supervisor-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 22:16:27 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Namespace]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><img alt="vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg" target="_self">A Supervisor Namespace (vSphere Namespace) defines the resource and security boundary within which workloads—such as vSphere Pods, virtual machines, and VKS clusters—run on a vSphere Supervisor.A namespace is the fundamental construct that binds together:
Resource allocation
Access control
Workload isolation
Policy enforcement
<br>All workloads deployed through the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> operate within a Supervisor Namespace (vSphere Namespace).A Supervisor Namespace:
Defines where workloads can run
Controls how much compute, memory, and storage they can consume
Establishes administrative and security boundaries
<br>Acts as the bridge between <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> infrastructure and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes workloads</a>
<br>Namespaces are created and managed by <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s, not by Kubernetes users.When a Supervisor Namespace is created:
<br>A corresponding <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> is created in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
CPU, memory, and storage limits can be defined
Quotas apply to all workloads within the namespace
Limits are enforced at the infrastructure layer
<br>If the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> spans multiple <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> clusters (zones), the namespace’s resource allocation is distributed across all participating clusters.Example:
If a namespace is assigned 300 MHz CPU across a three-zone Supervisor:
Each cluster contributes 100 MHz
Scheduling is balanced across zones
Access to a Supervisor Namespace is controlled through:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> Single Sign-On (SSO)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">External identity providers (OIDC)</a>
Administrators assign permissions to users or groups, defining what operations they can perform inside the namespace.This access model governs:
Who can deploy workloads
Who can view or modify resources
Who can manage storage and policies
A Supervisor Namespace can host:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s (VM-backed Kubernetes pods)
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS cluster components</a>
All workloads deployed within a namespace inherit its resource constraints and access rules.A Supervisor Namespace is not the same as a Kubernetes namespace, even though it appears similar at first glance.A Supervisor Namespace contains Kubernetes namespaces, but is not itself one.
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> creates a namespace in the Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> allocates backing resources and policies.
Namespace becomes visible to Kubernetes users.
Workloads can be deployed using standard Kubernetes tooling. Kubernetes users cannot create or delete vSphere namespaces.
<br>Namespace lifecycle is owned by <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, not Kubernetes.
Namespace limits cannot be overridden from inside the cluster. <br>Namespace names are unique per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>, not globally.
The same namespace name may exist on multiple Supervisors.
<br>A namespace belongs to exactly one <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s belong to a single <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.
Example:Organization: AcmeCorp
├── Project: Retail
│ ├── Namespace: prod
│ └── Namespace: stage
└── Project: Logistics └── Namespace: prod
Here, prod appears multiple times but in different Supervisor contexts.<br>A <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> is a governance construct used to group and manage namespaces.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s define ownership and intent
They map to one or more Supervisor Namespaces
They are not visible inside Kubernetes
<br>They exist only in the <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> control plane
Projects allow administrators to:
Apply policies
Enforce quotas
Track ownership
Control access Supervisor Namespaces are Kubernetes-compatible, but not Kubernetes-native.
They look and behave like Kubernetes namespaces to workloads, but their lifecycle, limits, and permissions are governed entirely by vSphere.
Supervisor Namespaces are the execution boundary for workloads.
<br>They are created and managed by <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, not Kubernetes.
They enforce compute, storage, and security limits.
Kubernetes operates inside these boundaries.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s and <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s exist above namespaces to provide <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.
<br>Supervisor Namespaces are unique per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> and not globally unique.
You might want to check out:
<br><a data-href="Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/adding-security-policies-to-a-supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace</a>
<br><a data-href="Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/kubectl-in-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster</a>
<br><a data-href="Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/deploy-a-confidential-vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Supervisor Namespace.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 22:15:57 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vsphere-supervisor-simple-2a666aae-dc08-4c32-97fc-39152205b6a8.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-simple-2a666aae-dc08-4c32-97fc-39152205b6a8.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-isolated-094fee0e-aa08-4ea3-9a97-252cc21af9d2.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-isolated-094fee0e-aa08-4ea3-9a97-252cc21af9d2.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-combined-ec332fe0-48fb-4df8-98d9-39532459a54b.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-combined-ec332fe0-48fb-4df8-98d9-39532459a54b.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-management-isolated-c4acf25c-6f36-45e0-b698-7d874e8fffe9.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-management-isolated-c4acf25c-6f36-45e0-b698-7d874e8fffe9.original.svg" target="_self"><br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/overview/vsphere-supervisor-deployment-options.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Overview/vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 21:32:51 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-simple-2a666aae-dc08-4c32-97fc-39152205b6a8.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-simple-2a666aae-dc08-4c32-97fc-39152205b6a8.original.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>vSphere Supervisor is a control plane built in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> that integrates desired state and a single consistent API directly in the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="ESX" data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">hypervisor</a>.<br>vSphere Supervisor enables native deployment and management of Kubernetes clusters, declarative virtual machines, and&nbsp; <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s alongside traditional workloads. It transforms <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> to an extendable platform by providing a declarative API for self-service provisioning of modern infrastructure services in a resource boundaries enabled by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>s<br>The vSphere Supervisor lives as a set of Kubernetes control-plane VMs running on ESX hosts, instantiated, wired, and governed by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>.<br><img alt="supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" target="_self">vSphere Supervisor:
<br>Runs on: <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br>Created and managed by: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Implemented as: Kubernetes control-plane VMs
<br>Distributed across <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
<br>Backed by <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> / datastores
<br>Networked via <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (or <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Distributed Virtual Switch" data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VDS</a> in simpler setups) <br>When you “enable Supervisor” in <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>:<br>
<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>:
Creates a special-purpose Kubernetes cluster
Instantiates its control plane as VMs
Pins it tightly to: Cluster membership
Networking
Storage Treats it as part of the infrastructure, not a tenant workload
So the Supervisor is:
Not a workload cluster
Not user-managed Kubernetes
Not a vSphere product you install
<br>It is an infrastructure service owned by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.Physical Hosts
└─ ESX └─ vCenter Server (control plane) └─ Supervisor Cluster (Kubernetes control plane VMs) ├─ Supervisor Namespaces ├─ vSphere Pods └─ Guest / Workload Clusters
<br>The vSphere Supervisor is a Kubernetes control plane deployed as system-managed <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, whose lifecycle is owned entirely by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> and whose purpose is to expose Kubernetes semantics directly on <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> infrastructure.<br>
The <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> physically lives as a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>-managed Kubernetes control-plane VMs running on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts inside a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>.
vSphere Supervisor is the foundation of VCF consumption and can be enabled during workload domain creation or directly in vCenter.<br>It transforms <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s into modern application platforms by embedding a platform-level Kubernetes control plane directly into ESX hosts, exposing a unified declarative API surface.<br>This integration allows end users to provision and manage workloads, including VMs, containers via <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s, full Kubernetes clusters through <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>, OCI image registries, and data services through a consistent API interface.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> maintains enterprise-grade <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, security, and operational consistency through <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>, and&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>vSphere Supervisor's <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> provide the foundation for multi-tenancy, enabling GitOps-based workflows, and delivering cloud-like self-service in private data centers.Kubernetes didn’t replace VMs.
It replaced application scheduling semantics.VMware’s bet was:<br>
"Instead of forcing Kubernetes to run on top of <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>,<br>
we will make Kubernetes a native execution mode of <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>."
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> is that bet made concrete.
vSphere = substrate
Supervisor = Kubernetes-native personality of vSphere
VCF Automation = enterprise automation layer on top
<br>
vSphere Supervisor is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> running in a special Kubernetes-enabled mode.
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes what vSphere Supervisor exposes. <br>It is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> running in special Kubernetes-enabled mode.
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes what Supervisor exposes.
<br><img alt="supervisor-conceptual.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-conceptual.webp" target="_self">You can think of Supervisor as vSphere with Kubernetes fused into its control plane.<br><img alt="ks-ns.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ks-ns.png" target="_self"><br>When you enable Supervisor on a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>, you are activating a capability inside vSphere.
<br>Supervisor runs inside <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
<br>Uses <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> as the control plane.
<br>Creates <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s.
Exposes Kubernetes APIs, backed by native vSphere primitives.
So conceptually, Supervisor is vSphere operating in "Kubernetes-native mode".<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are not Kubernetes namespaces.<br><img alt="supervisor-diagram.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-diagram.webp" target="_self"><br>If classic <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> is "run VMs", <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> is "Run anything (VMs, Pods, services)" with the same primitives.<br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-cf6fb05a-eddd-448c-a4ff-fee4f42f207a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-cf6fb05a-eddd-448c-a4ff-fee4f42f207a.webp" target="_self">
<br>Supervisor runs on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
It enables Kubernetes semantics backed by vSphere primitives.
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> is optional and sits above Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s look like Kubernetes namespace on purpose.vSphere (authoritative substrate)
└── Supervisor ├── Kubernetes API (authoritative for some things) └── vSphere API/UI (authoritative for others)
Kubernetes manifest → vSphere policy enforcement.
Create VMs via VirtualMachine CRDs (VM Operator)
Create Pods / Deployments
Attach storage
Attach networks (within guardrails) PVCs backed by vSphere storage policies
Datastore selection via StorageClasses
Policy-based placement Declare “I need this secret”
Injector materializes it
VCF Secret Service enforces access <br>Pods/VMs attach to <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>-backed segments
Load balancers exposed via K8s Service abstractions
You don’t manage NSX topology in YAML, but you consume it declaratively.
<br><img alt="vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" target="_self">
Infrastructure topology
Tenancy and Governance constructs (Organization, Projects, Quoatas at Provider level, Approval, Chargeback) Those live in VCF Automation / vSphere UI, not Kubernetes. <br>So: vSphere Supervisor exposes a Kubernetes-native API surface for workload consumption (pods, VMs, storage, networking), while infrastructure topology, tenancy, and governance remain <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>-and <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>-controlled.<br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-c3733e8c-9204-4e01-8b0c-5bc816bdbf77.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-c3733e8c-9204-4e01-8b0c-5bc816bdbf77.webp" target="_self"><br>A <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> extends the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> inventory by introducing additional objects that represent Kubernetes-based workloads and their supporting infrastructure.
Within the vCenter inventory, a Supervisor exposes and manages the following objects:<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespaces</a> represent logical application environments within the Supervisor. They define where workloads can run and what resources they can consume.Each namespace:
Represents an isolated execution boundary
Is backed by a dedicated resource pool
Is governed by quotas and policies
Is associated with specific users and permissions
<br>For every <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>, the Supervisor creates a corresponding resource pool.
<br>In a single-cluster Supervisor, one <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> is created per namespace.
In a multi-zone (multi-cluster) Supervisor: <br>A <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> is created in each participating cluster.
Resource consumption is distributed across all clusters in the zone. <br>These <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s enforce CPU and memory limits defined at the namespace level.<br>Each <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a> can contain multiple types of workloads:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s
Lightweight VM-based pods managed by the Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>
Platform services deployed into the Supervisor environment.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster</a>s
Kubernetes clusters provisioned and managed by VKS.
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s
Traditional VMs deployed directly into the namespace.
Namespaces also encapsulate:
Network configuration and connectivity
Storage policies and persistent volumes
Access to shared or dedicated datastores
All networking and storage enforcement is handled by the underlying vSphere and NSX infrastructure.Each namespace includes role-based access control assignments that determine:
Which users or groups can access the namespace
What actions they can perform (deploy, modify, delete)
Which resources they can consume
Permissions are enforced by vCenter and integrated identity providers.``
