Owns runtime enforcement VCF Automation: Consumes Supervisor APIs
Provides self-service, governance, orchestration Supervisor enables capabilities
VCF Automation operationalizes them<br>The next topic of interest would be <a data-href="Supervisor Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>, that lists the platform-level extensions that vSphere Supervisor has.<br>Alternatively, you can check out <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/overview/vsphere-supervisor-deployment-options.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options</a> for various small-to-large-scale deployment topologies.Also, for a deeper dive into vSphere Supervisor you can check out:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Components" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-components.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Components</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Networking" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-networking.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Networking</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Storage" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-storage.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Storage</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Security" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-security.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Security</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Inventory" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-inventory.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Inventory</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/vSphere Supervisor.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 21:32:26 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Services]]></title><description><![CDATA[Supervisor Services are platform-level extensions for the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> that provide cloud-native infrastructure capabilities by packaging functionality as Kubernetes Operators and service bundles that run on the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>.These services enable foundational capabilities such as Kubernetes consumption, storage services, registry operations, DNS management, ingress controllers, and more— all integrated directly into the vSphere control plane.Supervisor Services are:
<br>Installed and managed per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>
Controlled by platform administrators
Versioned and upgradeable independently
<br>Consumed <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">by tenants</a> or platform components
<br>In addition to core production Supervisor Services, there is a Supervisor Services Labs Catalog that includes experimental or community services which can be installed on <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>s but are not yet part of the core catalog.
Labs services are typically not supported at the same guarantee level as core Supervisor Services and may be subject to change. Formerly known as the Tanzu Kubernetes Grid Service
Provides APIs to create and manage Kubernetes clusters
Enables declarative Kubernetes lifecycle management via Supervisor APIs. UI component for resource consumption inside Namespaces
Displays resources in the vSphere Client UI under Workload Management
Improves namespace Kubernetes consumption UX Framework for stateful services using vSAN
Enables highly available object and block storage services for cloud-native workloads Integrates Velero with Supervisor Kubernetes
Enables backup/restore of Kubernetes resources and volumes
Natively integrated into Supervisor cluster workflows Leverages cert-manager primitives
Issues certificates for workloads running on Supervisor or tenant clusters
Helps with workload TLS termination and secure communication Adds a container registry within the Supervisor cluster
Supports image scanning, signing, and lifecycle policies
Works with ingress and DNS services for external access
Ingress Controller (Contour):
Provides ingress routing and load balancing for Kubernetes workloads
Integrates with Envoy for traffic proxying
ExternalDNS:
Automatically updates DNS records based on exposed service endpoints
Connects to external DNS providers for dynamic record management
Supervisor Management Proxy:
Facilitates communication between management and workload networks when isolated
Ensures Supervisor components can reach required management endpoints
NSX Management Proxy:
Previously used for similar connectivity needs but is now deprecated in favor of Supervisor Management Proxy Enables native Supervisor APIs to expose data services to tenants
Integrates the Data Services Manager (DSM) with Supervisor Cluster workload consumption paths
Secret Store Service:
Native secret storage capabilities for Kubernetes workloads
ArgoCD Service:
Provides a GitOps delivery model for application deployments
Useful for declarative automation and continuous deployment workflows Supervisor Services are the core platform building blocks that make vSphere Supervisor extensible and cloud-capable.
These services cover Kubernetes lifecycle, storage, registry, ingress, DNS, certificate management, backup, data services consumption, secrets, and more.
They are installed per Supervisor Cluster, managed by platform administrators, and consumed by tenant workloads or automation layers like VCF Automation.
There is also a Labs Catalog for experimental or early-stage Supervisor Services.
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Services.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 21:25:57 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[
see also: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>
A vSphere Cluster (or Supervisor Cluster) is a logical grouping of ESX hosts that vCenter treats as a single resource pool and failure domain.
It exists only in vCenter
ESX hosts do not know they are “in a cluster”.
When you create a cluster in vCenter Server, you are telling:
“*These ESX hosts agree to be scheduled, balanced, and failed over together.”This enables cluster-level logic, such as
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> (Distributed Resource Scheduler): <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> decides which host should run which VM.
When to rebalance the load. <br>Uses <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> to move VMs between hosts. <br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> (High Availability) Hosts run a lightweight HA agent.
If a host dies: Other hosts detect it
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> (or preconfigured HA logic) restarts VMs elsewhere. Shared resource abstraction Instead of thinking: Host A: 64 cores Host B: 64 cores vCenter presents Cluster: 128 cores VM placement and limits are logical, not physical.A vSphere Cluster is not:Because from an operator’s perspective:
Hosts act like a pool
Failures are absorbed
Workloads move transparently
But architecturally:
The cluster is an illusion created by vCenter.
<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> is a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>-defined scheduling and failure domain over multiple <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts,[ Physical Servers ] ↓ ESX (many hosts) ↓ vCenter Server ↓ vSphere features and automation
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> is a vSphere Cluster that you might like to look at next, since it is a core component in everything <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Inventory Objects/vSphere Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 20:46:03 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX Edge Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="nsx-edge-t1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png" target="_self">An NSX Edge Cluster is a pool of dedicated NSX Edge Nodes that handle north–south traffic and advanced network services (routing, NAT, load balancing, VPN, firewall at the perimeter).
North–south routing Tier-0 Gateways (uplink to physical network)
Tier-1 Gateways (tenant / app routing) Perimeter services NAT
L4–L7 Load Balancing
VPN (IPsec, L2VPN)
Gateway firewalling High throughput datapath Optimized for packet forwarding
<br>Separate from <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host dataplane ❌ It does not run workloads
<br>❌ It does not manage policy (that’s <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>)
❌ It does not replace distributed firewall (DFW)
VCF
├── vSphere Cluster (compute)
│ └── Workload VMs
│ └── East–West traffic (DFW on ESXi)
│
├── NSX Edge Cluster
│ └── North–South traffic
│ ├── Tier-0 Gateway
│ └── Services (NAT, LB, VPN)
│
└── NSX Manager └── Policy &amp; control plane
<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts = east–west
NSX Edge Nodes = north–south Edge nodes are deployed as VMs
Grouped into Edge Clusters
Services can be: Active/Active (ECMP)
Active/Standby <br>Protected by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
Scaled horizontally by adding Edge Nodes NSX Edge Cluster = NSX’s north–south dataplane
It handles routing, NAT, LB, VPN, perimeter firewalling
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, Edge Clusters are foundational for routed, multi-tenant designs
<br>Why not check out <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>s?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/NSX Edge Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:42:59 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[nsx-edge-t1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/nsx-edge-t1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:37:57 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX Manager]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="nsx-manager-NSX-2.1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png" target="_self"><br>NSX Manager is the central management and control plane for <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>. It defines, stores, and enforces software-defined networking and security policy (switching, routing, firewalling) across the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> environment.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, NSX Manager is mandatory wherever <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> is used and is deployed and lifecycle-managed by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.<br><img alt="nsx-manager-nsx-components.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation
├── Management Domain
│ └── NSX Manager (3-node cluster)
│
└── Workload Domains └── NSX Data Plane (transport nodes) Role: Management and policy authority Not a data-path component <br>Consumes: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> inventory, clusters, hosts Policy management Segments (logical networks)
Tier-0 / Tier-1 gateways (routing)
Distributed Firewall (DFW) rules Control-plane orchestration Pushes intent to hosts and edges Inventory and Topology Knows which workloads live where API and UI Single source of truth for NSX state <br>NSX Manager is the “brain” of <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>.If NSX Manager goes down:
Existing traffic continues
No new changes can be made until it returns
NSX Manager is typically deployed as:
3-node cluster
Quorum-based
<br>Protected by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> Loss of one node → no impact
Loss of quorum → management freeze, not traffic loss VCF:
Deploys NSX Manager automatically
Enforces supported topologies
Handles upgrades, certificates, backups
Assumes NSX Manager is always present ❌ Not a router forwarding packets
❌ Not a firewall datapath
❌ Not optional in NSX-based VCF designs
❌ Not workload-aware beyond policy intent
If vCenter is:
“What compute exists and where?”
Then NSX Manager is:
“How workloads may talk to each other, and who is allowed.” NSX Manager is the control plane of NSX
It defines networking and security intent
Traffic keeps flowing without it, but change stops
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, it is foundational and non-optional when NSX is used
<br>Check out <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a> for another related networking concept.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/NSX Manager.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:35:32 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[nsx-manager-nsx-components]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:28:52 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[nsx-manager-NSX-2.1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/nsx-manager-NSX-2.1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:28:52 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX Segment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="nsx-segment-NSX-5.1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png" target="_self"><br>An NSX Segment is a logical Layer-2 network in <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>.<br>
It is where workloads (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMs</a>, containers) attach their NICs, just like plugging into a virtual switch—except it’s policy-driven, distributed, and decoupled from physical <a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>s.<br><img alt="nsx-segment-Screen-Shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-PM-1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-screen-shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-pm-1.png" target="_self">VCF
├── vSphere (compute)
│ └── VMs / Pods
│ └── vNIC
│ └── NSX Segment (L2)
│ └── Tier-1 Gateway (L3, optional)
│ └── Tier-0 Gateway → Physical network
└── NSX Manager (policy &amp; control) <br>Defined in: <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br>Enforced on: <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts (distributed dataplane)
Consumes: Overlay networking (GENEVE) Provides L2 connectivity between attached workloads
Enables east–west traffic within the segment
Acts as the policy anchor for: Distributed Firewall (DFW)
DHCP (optional)
MAC/IP learning and isolation NSX Segment is:
“A virtual Ethernet network with cloud-native policy.”
NSX Segments remove VLAN sprawl and enable fine-grained security.
Pure L2 broadcast domain
No routing out
Common for isolated tiers L3 routing enabled
North–south possible via Tier-0
<br>Most common in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> DFW rules are applied to vNICs on segments
Security is identity-and policy-based, not subnet-based
Zero-trust patterns become practical The segment is not the security boundary—the workload is.
In VCF:
Segments are first-class networking objects
Used by: VM workloads
Kubernetes (via NSX CNI)
<br>Automation <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s <br>Lifecycle managed and validated by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
You don’t hand-craft switch configs; you declare intent.If vSphere Port Group is:
“A virtual switch tied to a VLAN”
Then NSX Segment is:
“A logical network with built-in policy, security, and mobility” ❌ Not a physical network
❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not a router
❌ Not Kubernetes-specific (but integrates cleanly) NSX Segment = logical L2 network
Attaches workloads and anchors security policy
<br>Decoupled from physical <a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>s
<br>Foundational to zero-trust networking in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
<br>You can check out <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> and <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> which are other related networking topics.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/Object Model/NSX Segment.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:26:50 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[nsx-segment-NSX-5.1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/nsx-segment-NSX-5.1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:18:11 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[nsx-segment-Screen-Shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-PM-1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-screen-shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-pm-1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-screen-shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-pm-1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/nsx-segment-Screen-Shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-PM-1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:18:11 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-screen-shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-pm-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-screen-shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-pm-1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[DRS]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="drs-Load-balancing-in-a-VMware-DRS-cluster.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-load-balancing-in-a-vmware-drs-cluster.webp" target="_self"><br>DRS (Distributed Resource Scheduler) is the <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> service that continuously balances CPU and memory load by automatically placing and live-migrating VMs (via <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>) across hosts.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, DRS is foundational, not optional.<br><img alt="drs-1545135394507.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-1545135394507.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── Cluster ├── HA → “Can the VM run?” └── DRS → “Where should it run?” <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Executed via: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Acts on: VMs inside a cluster
VCF assumes DRS is enabled and automated for predictable behavior.<br><img alt="drs-add_drs_rules.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-add_drs_rules.jpg" target="_self">
Initial Placement – chooses the best host when a VM powers on
Continuous Balancing – monitors CPU and memory pressure
<br>Live Migration – moves VMs using <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
Rule Enforcement – respects affinity / anti-affinity constraints
<br>
If <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> answers “Can the VM run?”,
DRS answers “Where should the VM run right now?”
<br><a data-href="VMware Validated Solutions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Validated Solutions</a> assume Fully Automated DRS.DRS continuously evaluates:
Host CPU utilization
Host memory pressure
VM demand and entitlements
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> shares and limits
Affinity / anti-affinity rules
When imbalance exceeds a threshold:<br>
→ <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> is triggered
→ No VM restartDRS is performance and fairness, not failure recovery.DRS can enforce rules such as:
“These VMs must stay together”
“These VMs must never share a host”
Typical use cases:
App + cache locality
HA for clustered apps
Licensing constraints Over-constraining rules reduces DRS effectiveness.
DRS respects:
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> shares
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> reservations
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> limits DRS balances within the rules you define — it does not override governance.
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, clusters are typically:Cluster
├── HA: Enabled
├── DRS: Fully Automated
├── Admission Control: On
└── vMotion: Required
If DRS is disabled:
Initial placement degrades
Load hotspots form
HA restarts may fail due to poor placement ❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not a scaling mechanism
❌ Not application-aware
❌ Not Kubernetes scheduling
DRS operates strictly at the VM + host layer.❌ Disabling DRS for “predictability”
→ Creates hotspots and manual ops❌ Overusing VM-Host affinity rules
→ Breaks automatic balancing❌ Expecting DRS to fix under-provisioning
→ It redistributes; it does not create capacity
<br>DRS is the brain of a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>
It continuously optimizes where VMs run
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> assumes DRS is enabled and automated
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> + DRS together provide resilience + efficiency
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> (FT) is the next related topic to explore after DRS.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Cluster Services/DRS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:14:17 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-load-balancing-in-a-vmware-drs-cluster.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-load-balancing-in-a-vmware-drs-cluster.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[drs-1545135394507]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-1545135394507.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-1545135394507.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/drs-1545135394507.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:05:17 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-1545135394507.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-1545135394507.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[drs-add_drs_rules]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-add_drs_rules.jpg" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-add_drs_rules.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/drs-add_drs_rules.jpg</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:05:17 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-add_drs_rules.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-add_drs_rules.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Fault Tolerance]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" target="_self"><br>Fault Tolerance (FT) is a vSphere feature that provides zero-downtime protection for a single <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machin" data-href="Virtual Machin" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> by running a lockstep secondary copy of that VM on another host.If the primary host fails, the secondary immediately takes over with no reboot and no data loss.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> inherits FT from vSphere; it does not redefine it.<br><img alt="ft-308973.avif" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-308973.avif" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── Cluster └── Fault Tolerance (per-VM feature) ├── Primary VM └── Secondary VM (lockstep) <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Configured in: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Applies to: Individual VMs (opt-in)
<br><img alt="ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg" target="_self">
Executes the same CPU instructions on two VMs simultaneously
Streams execution state over a dedicated FT logging network
On host failure → instant switchover, no restart
<br>
<a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> restarts VMs.
FT never restarts them. <br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>: “If the server crashes, reboot it elsewhere”
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>: “Move servers around to keep things fair”
FT: “Run two brains in sync at all times”
FT is about continuity, not balancing or recovery speed.FT is powerful but expensive.
Limited VM sizes (CPU / memory caps)
No snapshots
No suspend
<br>No Storage <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
Requires identical CPU features across hosts
Heavy network and CPU overhead
Because of this, FT is typically reserved for:
Legacy apps that cannot tolerate any downtime
Single-instance workloads with no clustering option
VCF environments usually prefer:
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> + <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> for infrastructure resilience
*Application-level [[HA]] (clusters, replicas, quorum())
Kubernetes controllers for pod-level restart
<br>Site-level <a data-href="DR" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DR</a> for disasters
<br>FT remains available, but it is not a default design assumption in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.FT is like live brain mirroring: effective, but costly.❌ Using FT as a substitute for application HA
❌ Enabling FT broadly “just in case”
❌ Forgetting FT network requirements
❌ Expecting FT to scale like Kubernetes replicas
FT provides true zero-downtime VM failover
<br>It is a <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> feature, inherited by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
High overhead and strict limits
<br>In modern <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> designs, FT is the exception, not the rule
<br>Let’s check out <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> next, since it is “essentially” everywhere.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Cluster Services/Fault Tolerance.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 18:03:50 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[ft-001-unnamed__22_]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 17:32:08 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[ft-vmware-ft-architecture]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 17:32:08 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[HA]]></title><description><![CDATA[HA (High Availability*) in VCF is the vSphere-native mechanism that automatically restarts workloads when a physical host fails**.It is not a single VCF feature; rather, VCF relies on and standardizes HA across its managed infrastructure.<img alt="ha-vm_img04.gif" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif" target="_self"><br>HA is not invented by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>. It comes from <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> and is enforced consistently by VCF.VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── Cluster └── HA (enabled at cluster level) └── VM restart on host failure <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Configured in: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Consumed by: All VMs running in VCF-managed clusters
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> ensures HA is correctly configured, validated, and lifecycle-managed as part of its opinionated design.<br><img alt="ha-vmsc_2_1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.png" target="_self">
Detect host failure → restart affected VMs on surviving hosts <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts exchange heartbeats
A host stops responding
Remaining hosts declare it failed
vCenter selects new hosts
VMs are restarted from disk Note that VMs are restarted, not live-migrated
<br>Physical <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host failure
Power loss to a host
PSOD / host crash
Host isolation scenarios Guest OS crashes
Application-level failures
Storage corruption
Network partition inside the VM
Data loss between last write and crash
HA answers “Is the VM running?”, not “Is the app healthy?”<br>In VCF, every <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> cluster is typically:
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>-enabled
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>-enabled
Validated against design rules
Example:Workload Domain
└── Cluster ├── HA: Enabled ├── DRS: Fully Automated └── Admission Control: Enabled
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> expects HA to be on; disabling it usually breaks design assumptions.HA includes Admission Control, which prevents you from powering on too many VMs.Purpose:
Ensure enough spare capacity exists to restart VMs after a failure.
If Admission Control says “no”:
Nothing is broken
You are overcommitted beyond your failure tolerance
This is HA doing its job, not being restrictive.VCF HA is infrastructure HA, not cloud-native app HA.❌ Turning off HA to “fit more VMs”
→ Silent loss of failure guarantees❌ Expecting HA to replace app clustering
→ Wrong layer❌ Confusing HA with zero downtime
→ There is always a restart
HA in VCF = vSphere HA, standardized and enforced
It restarts VMs after host failure
It does not provide zero-downtime or app-level resilience
It is a non-optional baseline for VCF design assumptions
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> and <a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> nicely complement HA.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Cluster Services/HA.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 04:06:54 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif" length="0" type="image/gif"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[ha-vmsc_2_1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:59:33 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[ha-vm_img04]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/ha-vm_img04.gif</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:59:33 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif" length="0" type="image/gif"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Pod]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" target="_self"><br>A vSphere Pod is a Kubernetes Pod whose sandbox runs inside a lightweight VM (via <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>]), not inside a container runtime on a shared Linux node.A vSphere Pod is the VMware implementation of a Kubernetes Pod, running as a lightweight virtual machine instead of a traditional container runtime.Each vSphere Pod:
Runs inside its own virtual machine
Has a dedicated Linux kernel
Provides strong isolation similar to a VM
Is optimized for fast startup and low overhead
In other words, a vSphere Pod combines the security and isolation of a VM with the developer experience of containers.So:
API semantics → Kubernetes
<br>Runtime semantics → <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> / VM
Traditional Kubernetes Pods:
Share a Linux kernel
Rely on namespaces + cgroups
Are fast and efficient
But have weaker isolation (from a hypervisor POV)
vSphere Pods were created to:
Give VM-grade isolation
While keeping Pod-level developer UX
For multi-tenant / regulated environments
This matters a lot for:
Service providers
Telco
Regulated enterprise workloads
“Pods from different customers must never share a kernel” Strong Isolation
Each vSphere Pod runs in its own VM with a dedicated kernel, providing isolation comparable to a full virtual machine.
Precise Resource Allocation
CPU, memory, and storage are allocated exactly as specified for the workload.
Efficient Scheduling<br>
vSphere Distributed Resource Scheduler (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>) places vSphere Pods on appropriate hosts based on available resources.
High Performance
The lightweight VM model preserves fast startup times while avoiding the “noisy neighbor” problem common in shared-kernel container environments.
Operational Visibility
Administrators can monitor and manage vSphere Pods using standard vSphere tools and workflows.
vSphere Pods are compatible with the Open Container Initiative (OCI) specification.They can run OCI-compliant container images, provided the container image supports the target environment.<br>For a vSphere Pod to run, a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> must be created on the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>.<br><img alt="vsphere-pod-298459bc-258c-4430-81a5-fb5330d7ce24.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-298459bc-258c-4430-81a5-fb5330d7ce24.webp" target="_self"><br>vSphere Pods rely on <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> networking.Key characteristics:
<br>Networking is provided through the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Pod networking is isolated and managed through <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> constructs
Traffic management, routing, and security policies are enforced at the infrastructure level
<br>Each <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host runs a component called Spherelet.
Spherelet:
Acts as the kubelet for vSphere Pods
Integrates directly with the ESX host
Manages pod lifecycle operations (start, stop, monitor)
Communicates with the Supervisor control plane
<br>Spherelet allows <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> to participate as a node in the Kubernetes control plane without running a traditional Linux OS.vSphere Pods use multiple storage types depending on usage:
Ephemeral VMDKs
Used for temporary container storage.
<br>Persistent Volume <a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>s
Backed by vSphere storage policies and used for persistent data.
<br>Image Cache <a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>s<br>
Used to cache container images locally on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts. Storage policies define placement and performance characteristics.
<br>Storage policies are assigned at the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a> level.
<br>Persistent volumes are provisioned through the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> using <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>.
Regular Kubernetes:Node (Linux)
└── kubelet ├── Pod A ├── Pod B └── Pod C vSphere Pods:ESXi
├── Pod-VM A
├── Pod-VM B
└── Pod-VM C No shared container runtime
No shared kubelet per “node”
Each pod is scheduled directly by vSphere
Kubernetes still thinks it’s scheduling Pods — but vSphere translates that into VM placement.So in vSphereland, “One Pod ~= Tiny VM”<br><img alt="vsphere-pod-4.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-4.png" target="_self">
Kubernetes: Decides which pod should run vSphere: Decides where the pod-VM runs
Enforces CPU, memory, NUMA, HA, DRS
This is what “Kubernetes-native mode” really looks like under the hood. From the Pod’s perspective:
It has an IP
It mounts volumes
It exposes ports
Under the hood:
Networking is NSX-backed
Storage is datastore-policy-backe
Attach/detach happens at VM granularity
Again: Pod UX, VM machinery.
Despite the VM runtime, vSphere Pods still use:
Pod specs
Containers
Init containers
ConfigMaps
Volume mounts
Pod lifecycle (create/delete/restart)
Kubernetes Services (with some constraints)
So developers mostly don’t care—and that is by design. Regular Pod → process in a shared OS
vSphere Pod → process in its own micro-VM
Or:
Regular K8s → Linux container model
vSphere Pods → “micro-VM container” model
Essentially: vSphere Pods are not regular Kubernetes Pods
They are Pod-shaped workloads backed by per-Pod VMs
Kubernetes API semantics remain intact
Runtime isolation is hypervisor-level
This is intentional and central to Supervisor’s design vSphere Pods are VM-backed Kubernetes pods with strong isolation.
<br>They run on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts using Spherelet and Supervisor integration.
They support OCI-compatible containers.
<br>Storage, networking, and scheduling are all managed through <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.
vSphere Pods provide a secure, enterprise-grade alternative to traditional container runtimes.
<br><a data-href="VM Workload and Pod Workload" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vm-workload-and-pod-workload.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM Workload and Pod Workload</a> compares and contrasts VM Workloads and vSphere Pods.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Architecture and Core Concepts/vSphere Pod.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:56:22 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="confidential-compute-919a15ce-e4d4-4a68-a3fa-583edda06ab5.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/confidential-compute-919a15ce-e4d4-4a68-a3fa-583edda06ab5.original.png" target="_self"><br>You can run confidential vSphere Pods on a <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> cluster. These pods use hardware-backed memory encryption to protect guest memory from being accessed by the hypervisor or other privileged components.This capability is powered by AMD Secure Encrypted Virtualization–Encrypted State (SEV-ES).A confidential vSphere Pod is a Kubernetes Pod that runs inside a virtual machine configured with SEV-ES: This ensures that:
Memory contents are encrypted
CPU register state is protected
The hypervisor cannot read or tamper with guest memory
This is especially useful for workloads that require strong isolation guarantees, such as handling sensitive data or running regulated workloads.To enable confidential vSphere Pods, the following requirements must be met:
<br>The <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host must run on hardware that supports AMD SEV-ES. <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> 7.0 Update 2 or later is required.
SEV-ES must be enabled in the system BIOS.When enabling SEV-ES, configure the following: Minimum SEV non-ES ASID count
This value must be set to:
number of SEV-ES VMs + number of confidential vSphere Pods + 1 Example: 100 SEV-ES VMs
128 confidential vSphere Pods
→ Minimum value = 229 The maximum allowed value is typically 500, depending on hardware. To deploy a confidential pod, you enable SEV-ES at the pod specification level.Create a YAML manifest with the following key elements:
Enable confidential pod support via annotation
Explicitly set memory requests and limits (they must match)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata: name: photon-pod namespace: my-podvm-ns annotations: vmware/confidential-pod: enabled
spec: restartPolicy: Never containers: - name: photon image: wcp-docker-ci.artifactory.eng.vmware.com/vmware/photon:1.0 command: ["/bin/sh"] args: ["-c", "while true; do echo hello, world!; sleep 1; done"] resources: requests: memory: "512Mi" limits: memory: "512Mi" Memory requests and limits must be identical for confidential pods.
Apply the manifest:kubectl apply -f &lt;yaml-file&gt;.yaml
Once submitted:
<br>The Scheduler selects an <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host that supports SEV-ES
If no compatible host is available, the Pod remains unscheduled
If scheduled successfully, the Pod runs with encrypted memory
You can verify the pod deployment using:kubectl describe pod &lt;pod-name&gt;
From the vSphere side, administrators can see the pod listed with:Encryption Mode: Confidential Compute
Confidential vSphere Pods use AMD SEV-ES to protect memory contents.
Encryption is enforced at the hardware level and is transparent to workloads.
The feature requires: Compatible hardware
ESX 7.0 U2 or later
BIOS configuration for SEV-ES Configuration is done declaratively using Kubernetes YAML.
The Supervisor ensures scheduling only onto capable hosts.
<br>You might want to learn move about <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/deploy-a-confidential-vsphere-pod.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:46:45 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/confidential-compute-919a15ce-e4d4-4a68-a3fa-583edda06ab5.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/confidential-compute-919a15ce-e4d4-4a68-a3fa-583edda06ab5.original.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cloud Services]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> provides a set of cloud services which are accessible on a self-service basis using multiple interfaces, including UI, CLI, and API.<br>With this interface, users can provision the following types of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a>s:
VMs
Kubernetes workloads
Networking
Volumes
Secret stores
Databases
Harbor Container registries
External DNS
Certificates
AI workloads
<br>Additionally, application teams can also provision resources on a self-service basis from Catalogs which are backed by pre-configured <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Blueprint" data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload template</a>s.These self-service options help developers focus on application development instead of managing the underlying infrastructure.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VCF Automation”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Cloud Services/Cloud Services.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:18:42 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[My Mental Model]]></title><description><![CDATA[I think of mental models as compression algorithms for reality.A mental model is an internal, simplified representation of how something works in the real world. It’s the framework the mind uses to understand, predict, and decide—often without conscious awareness.It is a map, not the territory.In my view, a mental model is:
A conceptual structure in the mind
Built from experience, learning, and assumptions
Used to explain cause → effect and anticipate outcomes
It answers questions like:
“If I do X, what will probably happen?”
“Why did that fail?”
“What matters here—and what doesn’t?”
Imagine driving in a foreign city.
The actual city is reality: complex, messy, and full of detail
Your mental model is a rough subway map in your head
That map:
Omits small streets
Distorts distances
Focuses only on what helps you get from A → B
It is useful precisely because it ignores detail—even if it’s inaccurate in places.That is what this (mostly) directed acyclic graph of documents (with occasional—intentional—loops) is trying to establish for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>: A navigable mental map, not an exhaustive representation of reality.The goal is not to describe everything, but to surface the abstractions that help me (and you, dear reader) reason correctly.Mental models exist because the human brain cannot process full reality in real time.Mental models:
Reduce cognitive load
Enable faster decisions
Allow generalization from experience
A single concept can be viewed through multiple overlapping mental models.For example, a database can be seen as:
A storage engine
A consistency system
A failure domain
A political boundary (ownership and control) Each model is incomplete on its own.
Taken together, they are powerful.
This document intentionally favors some mental models over others—not because they are “more correct,” but because they are more useful for the problems at hand.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="index" data-href="index" href="./https://vcf.wtf/index.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to Index</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/about-me/my-mental-model.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">About Me/My Mental Model.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:10:08 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Cloud Foundation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vcf-overview.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" target="_self"><br>VMware Cloud Foundation (VCF) is a unified platform to design, plan, deploy, and manage your <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> by using <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">automation</a> capabilities.That is one of the core tenents of VCF, and thus, it requires clarification before anything else.In VCF-speak, the phrase “a workload is a workload” is not a tautology—it’s a deliberate abstraction boundary.It means that VCF intentionally collapses many very different execution models into a single management concept, and refuses to care about their internal form unless it must.Below is the precise meaning, layered from philosophy, to architecture, to consequences.From VCF’s point of view, a workload is simply “something that consumes resources and is governed by policy.”It is not:
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>
a Container
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod VM</a>
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> pod
<br>a <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>
a Helm release
Those are implementation details.VCF asks only:
Where does it run?
Who owns it?
What resources does it consume?
What policies apply?
What lifecycle rules govern it?
If those questions can be answered, VCF is satisfied.VCF exists above:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Kubernetes
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s
Containers
If VCF tried to manage each kind of workload differently, it would:
explode in complexity
duplicate logic
couple business policy to runtime mechanics
So instead, VCF defines:
Workload = Policy + Placement + Lifecycle + Resources
Everything else is delegated downward.All of the following are equally valid workloads in VCF:VCF deliberately does not rank or privilege any of these.In VCF, a workload is anything that consumes platform resources and is subject to platform policy—its internal shape is intentionally irrelevant.
VCF intentionally erases runtime distinctions
Governance &gt; implementation
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> is the abstraction bridge
If two things consume resources and obey policy, VCF treats them identically
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> makes it possible.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> converts:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pods</a> to lightweight VMs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> objects to vSphere-managed entities
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a> to policy and tenancy units From below, everything is Kubernetes.
<br>From above, everything is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> resources. VCF sits above Supervisor, so it sees:
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a>
Quotas
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policies</a>
The kind or form of the workload becomes irrelevant.VCF does not care:
whether the workload uses containerd or not
<br>whether it’s a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">PodVM</a> or classic VM
whether it runs Go, Java, or Bash
whether it was deployed via Helm, kubectl, or Terraform
whether it is “cloud-native” or “legacy”
Those are runtime-layer concerns, not platform-layer concerns.
A power grid doesn’t care if you plug in a toaster or a server rack—only how much power you draw and what safety rules apply.
This is why statements like these are true:
“Pod workloads are not special.”
“VM workloads are not special.”
“Guest clusters are just workloads.”
“Infrastructure doesn’t care about your app model.”
So, you don’t fight against the platform to fit the workload in; you design the workload to fit the platform’s (opinionated) invariants.To internalize VCF, don’t think in:
Pods vs VMs
Containers vs Processes
Control Planes vs Data Planes
<br>Instead, think in <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>:
Who owns this?
What are its limits?
How is it created and destroyed?
How does it fail?
How is it audited?
Don’t anchor your designs to what runs. Anchor them to how they are governed.If this does not make sense initially, give it some time and revisit this page once you navigate this website further. I assure you it will eventually click.<br>For now, let’s keep a mental note of this, and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="About VCF" data-href="About VCF" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/about-vcf.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">dive deeper into the VCF rabbit hole</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VMware Cloud Foundation.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:09:12 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCSA]]></title><description><![CDATA[
see also: <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>
<br>VCSA, is an acronym for “<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> Appliance”<br>It is a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> for <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a><br><img alt="Image" src="https://lazywinadmin.github.io/images/2013/20130401_Deploying_and_Configuring_vCenter_Server_Appliance_5.1/VMware-vCenter-Topology__452693609__-600x400.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br>In VCF, VCSA is the central control plane for vSphere infrastructure—the brain that manages <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and clusters across domains.
VCSA = vCenter, packaged as a Linux appliance
VCF uses VCSA everywhere to manage compute
No VCSA → no usable vSphere → no VCF
Think of VCF as an orchestration stack, and VCSA as the authoritative source of truth for the compute state.Inside VCF, VCSA is responsible for:
<br>Manages <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
Forms and manages vSphere clusters
Enforces cluster features: <br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s Everything “higher” in the stack talks to VCSA:
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (for host/cluster attachment)
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> (Kubernetes-on-vSphere)
If something needs to know “what hosts exist?” or “where does this VM live?”, it asks VCSA.
Integrates with SSO / identity providers
Issues and validates service identities
Acts as a trust anchor for many workflows
VCF is domain-based, and each domain has its own VCSA.
Always present
Contains: VCSA
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Manages itself and workload domains Each workload domain has: Its own VCSA
<br>Its own <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Isolated lifecycle and fault domains
This separation is deliberate:
Different upgrade cadences
Different blast radii
Different tenants / purposes
When someone says “VCF manages vSphere” what they actually mean is “VCF automates VCSA, which in turn manages ESX”
The Supervisor Cluster runs on vSphere
But: VCSA creates it
VCSA owns its lifecycle
VCSA exposes it via vSphere APIs Kubernetes is embedded into vSphere, but VCSA remains the authority.Without VCSA:
No cluster
<br>No <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>/<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br>No <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
No VM lifecycle
No policy enforcement
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is powerful because it standardizes and automates many VCSAs, not because it replaces them.
VCSA = vCenter, packaged as an appliance
It is the compute control plane inside VCF
Every domain has its own VCSA
All higher-level VCF services depend on it
VCF orchestrates VCSA; it does not replace it
<br>Since VCSA is a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>, you might want to look into <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> too.<br>
You might also want to check out <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> or <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> as related components.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/VCSA.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:07:15 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://lazywinadmin.github.io/images/2013/20130401_Deploying_and_Configuring_vCenter_Server_Appliance_5.1/VMware-vCenter-Topology__452693609__-600x400.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com" length="0" type="application/x-msdownload"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://lazywinadmin.github.io/images/2013/20130401_Deploying_and_Configuring_vCenter_Server_Appliance_5.1/VMware-vCenter-Topology__452693609__-600x400.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Distributed Virtual Switch]]></title><description><![CDATA[In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, a Distributed Virtual Switch (DVS) is the standard, centralized virtual networking fabric used across <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts in a <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>.<br>Distributed Virtual Switch is a cluster-wide virtual switch that provides consistent networking configuration across all <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.
It centralizes network policy (port groups, uplinks, security, QoS) instead of configuring each host individually.VCF standardizes on VDS as the baseline virtual networking fabric.<br><img alt="vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" target="_self"><br>In VCF, a Distributed Virtual Switch is the mandatory, centrally managed L2 networking fabric that ensures every <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host behaves identically so that <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, lifecycle management, and <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> can work reliably at scale.DVS provides consistent networking configuration, policy enforcement, and operational control at scale—something VCF depends on to behave predictably.DVS can be seen as:<br>
One logical network switch that spans many <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts,
configured once, and applied everywhere.
<br>Instead of configuring networking host-by-host, you configure it centrally, and every participating <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host follows that definition.VCF is opinionated and automated. Networking must be:
Deterministic
Centrally managed
<br>Compatible with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">lifecycle automation</a>
Consistent across hosts and clusters
That’s why VCF mandates DVS (not standard vSwitches) for system and workload networking.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts do not own the switch config — vCenter does.
VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── vCenter Server └── vSphere Distributed Switch (VDS) ├── ESXi Host A ├── ESXi Host B └── ESXi Host C └── Port Groups → VM vNICs Centralized L2 switching
Consistent port group configuration
NIC teaming &amp; uplinks
Traffic shaping, security, VLAN tagging
Host lifecycle safety (no per-host drift) “One virtual switch, shared by the whole cluster.”
A Distributed Port Group defines:
VLAN ID(s)
Security policies (promiscuous mode, MAC changes)
Traffic shaping
Teaming / failover
VM vNICs attach to port groups, not directly to the switch.
❌ Not a router (no L3)
<br>❌ Not an <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>
❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not optional in VCF
VCF automation (bring-up, scaling, patching, upgrades) assumes:A standard vSwitch breaks all of this because it is host-local and imperative.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> has a predefined VDS
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s get their own VDS
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> transport zones bind to VDS uplinks
Lifecycle (patching, expansion) assumes VDS presence
<br>You rarely “design” VDS in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>—it is opinionated and enforced.Typical VCF DVS port groups include:
Management
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Host TEPs VM networks (VLAN-backed)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> / Kubernetes traffic (when applicable)
VCF may create multiple DVS instances, for example:
One for system domain
One per workload domain <br>DVS ≠ <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
DVS provides L2 switching
NSX builds overlay networking (Geneve tunnels, logical segments) on top of DVS
You can have:
<br>DVS without NSX (<a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>-backed networking)
<br>However, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> requires DVS underneath
So DVS is the foundational substrate, not the SDN layer.
DVS = underlay L2 switch
NSX = overlay (L3) networking NSX creates overlay segments
Overlay traffic is encapsulated (GENEVE)
Encapsulated packets ride over VDS uplinks NSX does not replace VDS—it depends on it.
If DVS is:<br>
“A shared Ethernet switch for <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts”
<br>Then <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> is:
“A logical network built on top of that switch.”
Different layers, different jobs.
DVS is a control-plane object <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> caches its config locally, but authority lives in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> If vCenter is temporarily unavailable Traffic keeps flowing
You just can’t change switch config VCF LCM expects DVS invariants Port groups, uplinks, MTU, and teaming must match what SDDC Manager expects DVS is not optional in VCF VDS is the foundational virtual switch in VCF It is owned by vCenter, not hosts
It enables automation, scale, and consistency
Provides centralized, cluster-wide L2 networking
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> depends on it, but it is not NSX itself NSX overlays run on top of VDS, not instead of it Standard vSwitches are fundamentally incompatible with VCF’s design goals
<br>Diving into <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> might be the next logical step from here. Or maybe <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> (Cloud Native Storage), could be something fun to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/Distributed Virtual Switch.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:04:55 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere, ESX, and vCenter]]></title><description><![CDATA[Saying “vSphere is ‘‘ESX and vCenter’’” is colloquially common, but technically incomplete.Because vSphere is a platform, it is NOT a single product.Or, to put more simply: There is nothing you can curl called vSphere; similar to there is nothing that you can curl called AWS or Azure.<a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> is VMware’s virtualization platform built on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts managed by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, together providing cluster-level services such as <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, and Kubernetes integration.But still, that term is mostly, contextually “good enough” because, in practice:
You never run production vSphere without vCenter
ESX alone is just a hypervisor, not a platform; and it is very limited
vCenter alone does nothing
<br><img alt="what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" target="_self">vSphere includes:
<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> is the bare-metal hypervisor. <br>
<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> provides centralized management. Platform features: <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> (live VM migration)
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> / <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>es
Storage policies
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> <br>
You cannot have vSphere without <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>. <br>
You can have <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> without <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> (but it will be very limited). <br>For more information about what vSphere controls and manages, you might want to see <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> and <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>. After that, your next step could be to check out <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> and see how it enables declarative management of these constructs.<br>Exploring <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> might be the next logical area to navigate from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/Component Relationships/vSphere, ESX, and vCenter.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:04:25 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Constructs]]></title><description><![CDATA[
see also: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
A vSphere Construct is:
*A first-class infrastructure object that is _natively defined, owned, and enforced by the vSphere control plane (ESX + vCenter), not by Kubernetes or higher-level automation layers.
<br>Think of it as a primitive in vSphere’s own vocabulary. These are things that exist because <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> exists; they are not abstractions layered on top.
Virtual Machine
<br><a data-href="vCPU" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vcpu.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCPU</a>
<br><a data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vNUMA</a>
<br><a data-href="vApp" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vApp</a> <br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>
Shares / Limits / Reservations
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> rules
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> Admission Control Datastore
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> Object
<br>VM disk (<a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>)
Storage Policy Port Group
<br><a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>
<br><a data-href="VM NIC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vm-nic.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM NIC</a>
<br><a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a> / overlay constructs Snapshot
Clone
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
Storage vMotion
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> restart
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a>
<br>All of these are authoritative in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> and enforced by:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br>and <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
If you want to get closer to the metal, all of these are relevant areas to explore:
<br><a data-href="VM NIC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vm-nic.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM NIC</a>
<br><a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>
<br><a data-href="vApp" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vApp</a>
