<br><a data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vNUMA</a>
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Overview/vSphere Constructs.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:03:58 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Virtual Machine]]></title><description><![CDATA[A virtual machine (VM) is a software-defined computer that behaves like a physical machine but runs on top of a virtualization layer rather than directly on hardware.You can think of it as a full computer implemented in software.<img alt="virtual_machines.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/virtual_machines.webp" target="_self">Each VM:
Has its own CPU, memory, disk, and network
Runs its own operating system
Is isolated from other VMs
Believes it owns real hardware (even though it doesn’t)
The key component is the hypervisor.The hypervisor:
Intercepts CPU instructions
Schedules CPU time
Maps virtual memory → physical memory
Virtualizes I/O (disk, NIC, GPU, etc.)
From the VM’s perspective:
“I am running on bare metal.”
From reality:
“You are one of many guests sharing a host.”
A VM is not just an OS. It consists of:
Virtual hardware vCPU(s)
vRAM
Virtual disk(s)
Virtual NIC(s) Firmware BIOS or UEFI Operating system Linux, Windows, BSD, etc. Applications Databases, web servers, middleware, etc. Even though the term VM is generic, VCF treats the VM as a first-class workload unit:
A VM is: A managed workload
Governed by policies
Scheduled onto clusters
Subject to lifecycle operations (create, move, snapshot, delete) VCF doesn’t care why the VM exists
It cares how to place, secure, move, and operate it A VM is a full computer implemented in software
It runs an OS and applications like a physical machine
The hypervisor provides isolation and resource sharing
VMs remain foundational—even in modern cloud platforms
In VCF, a VM is a core workload primitive, not a legacy artifact
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/Virtual Machine.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:03:37 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/virtual_machines.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/virtual_machines.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VM NIC]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vmnic-net-diagram.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmnic-net-diagram.png" target="_self"><br>A VM NIC (often written vNIC) is a virtualized network adapter presented to a virtual machine by the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="ESX" data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">hypervisor</a>. From the guest OS’s point of view, it behaves like a physical Ethernet card; from the host’s point of view, it’s a software object that plugs into VMware’s virtual networking stack.Effectively, it is a software Ethernet card that lives inside the VM.
Appears as a standard network adapter (e.g., Intel or VMware-branded)
Has: A MAC address
Link state (up/down)
One or more IP addresses assigned by the guest OS Drivers inside the VM talk to it just like real hardware The vNIC is backed by VMware virtual networking
It connects to: A vSwitch (Standard or Distributed)
A Port Group Traffic is then forwarded to: Other VMs
The host
The physical network via uplinks (pNICs) VMware supports multiple vNIC “models,” each with different tradeoffs:A typical path looks like this:[ VM ] |
[vNIC] |
[Port Group] |
[vSwitch (VSS or VDS)] |
[pNIC / Uplink] |
[Physical Network] Port Group defines policies (VLAN, security, shaping)
vSwitch is the virtual L2 switch
pNICs are the host’s physical NICs Multiple vNICs per VM Separate traffic (management, data, backup) <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vNUMA" data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SR-IOV</a> VM bypasses vSwitch and talks almost directly to hardware
Very high performance, less flexibility Traffic Shaping and Security Promiscuous mode
MAC changes
Forged transmits A VM NIC (vNIC) is a virtual Ethernet adapter attached to a VM
It connects the VM to VMware’s virtual networking stack
VMXNET3 is the modern, high-performance choice
Networking is enforced through port groups and vSwitches
Multiple vNICs, policies, and offloads make it far more flexible than physical NICs
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vm-nic.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/VM NIC.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:02:16 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmnic-net-diagram.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmnic-net-diagram.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vApp]]></title><description><![CDATA[A vApp is a logical container in VMware that groups multiple VMs into a single, manageable application unit with shared lifecycle, networking, and (optionally) resource policies.It is best thought of as “an application-shaped wrapper around several VMs.”A vApp is a construct in VMware that lets you manage a set of related VMs as one application, with coordinated startup order, shared networking, and optional resource controls.vApps live and are managed in <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>.vApps were created to solve a very specific problem:
“How do I deploy and operate a multi-VM application as a single unit?”
Before Kubernetes, before Helm, before Operators—this was VMware’s answer.vApp: OnlineStore
├── Web VM
├── API VM
└── Database VM
You can:
Power on/off the whole application
Clone or export it
Track it as a single object
Critical feature.You can define:
DB starts first
App tier next
Web tier last
Reverse order on shutdown
This was huge in pre-container days.Inside a vApp you can:
Define isolated networks
Connect VMs to internal-only networks
Attach uplinks at the vApp boundary
It is like a “mini datacenter boundary for this application”.vApps support:
OVF / OVA packaging
Application-level metadata
Deployment parameters (IP, hostname, etc.)
This made vApps attractive for:
ISVs
Appliances
Repeatable deployments
vApp is an organizational and orchestration construct, not a runtime.vApps were ahead of their time, but eventually outpaced by containers.vApps are still relevant in:
<br>VMware <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>s (OVA-based)
Legacy multi-VM apps
Demo environments
Lab setups
But, they are rare in modern Cloud Native stacks:
Kubernetes replaced the need
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> layers supersede it
GitOps models don’t map cleanly
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/vApp.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:00:42 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VKS]]></title><description><![CDATA[VKS is essentially the evolution of what was previously known as Tanzu Kubernetes Grid Service (TKGs).
“What was formerly known as Tanzu Kubernetes Grid Service (TKGs) is now unified under a single, intuitive name: vSphere Kubernetes Service (VKS).”
VKS is: Upstream Kubernetes + VMware’s opinionated lifecycle, security, and infrastructure integration.
Runs on <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
Worker nodes are VMs
<br>Created and managed via <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Tightly integrated with: <br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> networking (<a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> / <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Distributed Virtual Stwitch" data-href="Distributed Virtual Stwitch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VDS</a>)
<br>vSphere storage (<a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>, <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>)
vSphere IAM / RBAC boundaries <br>Inside the <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>:
Kubernetes sees: Namespaces
RBAC
CRDs
Workloads It does not see: Organizations
Projects
Approval flows
Business tenancy Those live outside the cluster, enforced by:
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Automation layers (i.e., <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
This is similar to saying “a Docker container does not know which Jira project paid for the VM it runs on”.vSphere / ESX
└── Supervisor Cluster └── Supervisor Namespace └── TKG Workload Cluster (guest cluster) ├── Kubernetes API ├── Nodes = VMs └── Apps / Pods <br><img alt="vks-architecture-components-9a75be16-0327-4b31-9e8d-9de9173afe93.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-architecture-components-9a75be16-0327-4b31-9e8d-9de9173afe93.webp" target="_self">VKS exposes three layers of controllers to manage the lifecycle of a VKS cluster.<br>VKS provisions clusters that include the components necessary to integrate with the underlying <a data-href="vSphere Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a> resources. These components include:
A Cloud Provider Plug-in that integrates with the Supervisor
<br>Integration with VMware Cloud Native Storage (<a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>) for persistent volumes
Persistent volume requests from a VKS cluster are passed to the Supervisor, which handles storage provisioning.The Cluster API provides declarative, Kubernetes-style APIs for:
Creating clusters
Configuring clusters
Managing cluster lifecycle
Inputs to the Cluster API include:
A resource describing the cluster itself
Resources describing the virtual machines that make up the cluster
Resources describing cluster add-ons
The Virtual Machine Service provides a declarative, Kubernetes-style API for managing virtual machines and associated vSphere resources.Key concepts include:
Virtual Machine Classes, which define reusable hardware configurations
Lifecycle management of control plane and worker node VMs that host a VKS cluster
The components that run inside a VKS cluster fall into four functional areas:
Authentication Webhook
A webhook running inside the cluster that validates user authentication tokens. Container Storage Interface (CSI) Plugin
A paravirtualized CSI driver that integrates with CNS through the Supervisor. Container Network Interface (CNI) Plugin
Provides pod networking capabilities. Cloud Provider Implementation
Supports creation and management of Kubernetes LoadBalancer services.
The VKS API is used to provision and manage VKS clusters. It is a declarative API accessed using kubectl and YAML manifests.You can download the VMware-enhanced kubectl binary from the Supervisor API endpoint.With the declarative model:
You define the desired state (number of nodes, VM sizes, Kubernetes version, storage, etc.)
VKS reconciles the actual state to match the desired state
To manage a cluster:
Define the cluster configuration in YAML.
Apply it using kubectl.
Update the YAML to modify the cluster over time. <br><a data-href="VKS Cluster Networking" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-networking.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster Networking</a>
<br><a data-href="VKS Cluster Storage" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-storage.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster Storage</a>
<br><a data-href="What is a VKS Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/what-is-a-vks-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">What is a VKS Cluster</a> dives deeper into VKS Clusters.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/VKS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:43:25 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-architecture-components-9a75be16-0327-4b31-9e8d-9de9173afe93.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-architecture-components-9a75be16-0327-4b31-9e8d-9de9173afe93.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[What is a VKS Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[A VKS cluster is a Kubernetes cluster that is built and supported by VMware and that runs application workloads.VKS clusters are part of a vSphere Kubernetes Service (<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>) deployment. You use VKS cluster management to manage VKS clusters. Their lifecycle, however, is handled by the native <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> APIs.A VKS cluster is a Kubernetes cluster provisioned and managed through VKS.Characteristics:
<br>Built on <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Managed via the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Created and governed through <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
Runs standard Kubernetes workloads
<br>VKS clusters are where actual workloads execute, but they do not contain awareness of organizational hierarchy (i.e. they don’t know about <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, or <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s).VKS provides self-service lifecycle management of Kubernetes workload clusters.VKS is an implementation of the open-source Cluster API project, which defines a set of custom resources and controllers used to manage the lifecycle of Kubernetes clusters.<br>VKS is a component of the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>. The Supervisor acts as a source of compute resources that can be registered with <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>System administrators allocate Supervisor resources to organizations in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>. The Supervisor itself does not belong to any organization.<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>s request <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s for their projects, and <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> allocates the appropriate namespaces to match those requests.<br>A single <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> can provide resources to multiple <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> organizations.<br>Within a single organization, <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s can be moved between projects.<br>To function properly, <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster management relies on a set of agents and extensions that run in every VKS cluster.<br>When a VKS cluster is attached to VKS Cluster Management, the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> auto-attach service installs:
Required extensions
Cluster resource definitions
Agent components on each node
The agent configuration includes:
The VKS cluster management endpoint
The container image registry used by the cluster
Proxy configuration details
The overall health of a cluster is determined by aggregating the health of its nodes and components.
Healthy
All nodes and components are healthy, and a heartbeat is received every minute.
Unhealthy
One or more of the following are unhealthy: One or more control plane nodes
One or more cluster components Warning
A cluster enters a warning state when: One or more worker nodes are unhealthy or unknown, or
One or more nodes (control plane or worker) report a warning condition Unknown
The cluster is marked as unknown if: One or more control plane nodes are in an unknown state, or
No heartbeat has been received for more than three minutes Node health is derived from the NodeReady condition and other node-level signals such as:
MemoryPressure
DiskPressure
OutOfDisk
The node’s health state is evaluated as follows:
NodeReady is True
All other conditions are healthy NodeReady is False, or
NodeReady is True, but more than half of the other conditions are unhealthy NodeReady is True
Fewer than half of the other conditions are unhealthy NodeReady is neither True nor False, or
No heartbeat has been received from the node for more than three minutes
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster management monitors the health of the following control plane components:
kube-apiserver
scheduler
controller-manager
etcd components (etcd-0, etcd-1, etcd-2, etc.)
Each component periodically reports its health status.
Healthy
The last reported health condition is True.
Unhealthy
The last reported health condition is False.
Unknown
The last reported health condition is neither True nor False, or no heartbeat has been received for more than three minutes.
Below is a clean, consistently structured, and de-duplicated version of your content.
Nothing new is introduced; this is purely a clarity and organization pass so the conceptual layers are easy to understand and reference.VKS (vSphere Kubernetes Service) provides managed Kubernetes clusters running on vSphere.
It operates within the VCF Automation framework and relies on the Supervisor to provision and manage resources.VKS cluster management introduces a hierarchical model that separates:
<br>Control-plane governance (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
<br>Cluster lifecycle management (<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>)
<br>Runtime execution (<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> + Kubernetes)
VKS cluster management organizes resources using the following hierarchy:
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster</a>
<br>Kubernetes Namespaces (inside the cluster, these are NOT <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s)
<br>This hierarchy exists in the <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> control plane, not inside Kubernetes itself.Each VKS cluster contains standard Kubernetes namespaces:
These are normal Kubernetes namespaces
Managed using kubectl
Used for application isolation and RBAC within the cluster
<br>These namespaces are not the same as <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s or <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s.<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> exists at the Supervisor layer and is used to:
Allocate CPU, memory, and storage
Bind resource pools to consumers
Host VKS cluster resources
Important distinctions:
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are not Kubernetes namespaces (*but they are queries using kubectl, so they —look like– Kubernetes namespaces)
They are managed through the Supervisor API
<br>They serve as the execution boundary for <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters VCF Automation defines intent.
VKS enforces that intent.
Kubernetes executes the result.
The organizational model exists above Kubernetes and never becomes part of the Kubernetes API surface.<br><a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a> and <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> are two directly-related areas to explore.<br>You might also want to check <a data-href="VKS Cluster Storage" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-storage.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster Storage</a> and <a data-href="VKS Cluster Networking" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-networking.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster Networking</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/what-is-a-vks-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/What is a VKS Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:42:26 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VKS Cluster Storage]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png" target="_self"><br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, like other workloads running in a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, require persistent storage.Persistent storage for VKS clusters is provided through integration with vSphere storage services, using storage policies and CSI-based provisioning.To provide persistent storage to VKS clusters, a vSphere administrator defines storage policies that describe required storage characteristics (such as performance, availability, and placement rules).These storage policies are then:
Assigned to a vSphere Namespace
Exposed to VKS clusters deployed within that namespace
The storage policies determine:
Which datastores can be used
How volumes are provisioned
How placement and availability rules are enforced
Based on the assigned storage policies:
<br>The <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> automatically creates corresponding Kubernetes StorageClasses
These StorageClasses are made available inside the VKS cluster
Each storage policy results in two StorageClass variants:
One with Immediate volume binding
One with WaitForFirstConsumer volume binding
This allows DevOps teams to choose the appropriate provisioning behavior based on workload requirements.VKS clusters integrate with vSphere storage using Paravirtual CSI (pvCSI).
pvCSI is a modified version of the standard vSphere CNS-CSI driver
It runs inside the VKS cluster
It handles all storage-related operations initiated from the cluster
The pvCSI driver does not communicate directly with vCenter or CNS. Instead:
The pvCSI driver forwards storage requests to the Supervisor
The Supervisor routes the request to CNS (Cloud Native Storage)
<br><a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> performs the actual storage operation in vSphere
Unlike CNS-CSI, pvCSI:
Does not require vCenter credentials
Operates using a service account within the namespace
Relies on the Supervisor for secure mediation
<br><img alt="vks-pv-creation-a7a9c4ee-5c78-40fe-9406-6ee986c5d4d9.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-pv-creation-a7a9c4ee-5c78-40fe-9406-6ee986c5d4d9.original.png" target="_self">The following sequence describes how a persistent volume is created in a VKS cluster:
A DevOps engineer creates a PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) in the VKS cluster.
The request is received by the pvCSI driver.
pvCSI forwards the request to the Supervisor.
The Supervisor invokes the CNS API in vCenter to create the volume.
Once the volume is created, the information propagates back through the Supervisor.
The PVC and corresponding PV appear as Bound in both: The VKS cluster
The Supervisor view This ensures consistent visibility and lifecycle tracking across all layers.
VKS clusters rely on vSphere storage policies for persistent storage.
Storage policies determine where and how volumes are provisioned.
The Supervisor mediates all storage operations between VKS and vSphere.
pvCSI enables secure, credential-free storage operations from inside the cluster.
Storage resources appear consistently in both the VKS cluster and Supervisor views.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VKS”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-storage.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/Platform Integration/VKS Cluster Storage.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:41:09 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[
A mode / capability of a vSphere cluster
Means: “This vSphere cluster has Kubernetes enabled and is running the Supervisor control plane” or less wordy: “*a vSphere cluster with Supervisor enabled”. Not a physical thing by itself
Think of it as a feature flag + control plane. A vSphere Cluster with Supervisor enabled
A concrete, addressable object: ESX hosts
vCenter-managed cluster
Supervisor control plane VMs This is what you actually connect to with kubectl
In practice, people often say:
“deploy this on Supervisor”
“connect to the Supervisor”
“namespace on Supervisor”
What they mean is: “the Kubernetes API exposed by the Supervisor-enabled vSphere cluster”
So colloquially: Supervisor ≈ Supervisor Cluster
But technically:
Supervisor = the Kubernetes capability
Supervisor Cluster = the <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> cluster running it
<br>You might want to check <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> to dive deeper into the Supervisor internals, or <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Components" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-components.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Components</a> to see core components that make up <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Architecture and Core Concepts/Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:40:27 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VM Workload and Pod Workload]]></title><description><![CDATA[In VCF, a workload is:
A unit of compute that consumes CPU, memory, storage, and networking, and is subject to lifecycle, policy, and governance.
VCF doesn’t care what the workload is at a philosophical level. It cares about:
How it is instantiated
How it is isolated
How it is scheduled
How it is governed
Which control plane owns it
one virtual machine per workloadA VM Workload is a traditional virtual machine:
Runs on ESX
Has its own guest OS
Is managed by vCenter
Uses <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a>s directly <br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> is the authoritative control plane
VCF Automation wraps vCenter, but does not replace it CPU / memory allocated per VM
Strong isolation via hypervisor boundaries
Overcommitment controlled at ESX level Create VM
Power on/off
Snapshot
Clone
Patch guest OS
Backup VM image VM policies
Placement rules
Affinity / anti-affinity
HA / DRS
Backup &amp; DR policies
many disposable units forming a service.<br>A <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod Workload</a> is a Kubernetes Pod running on the vSphere Supervisor Cluster.<br>A pod on the vSphere Supervisor Cluster is not a traditional Kubernetes pod. It is a <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>—Kubernetes-shaped, but vSphere-implemented.Key point:<br>
A Pod Workload (<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>) is not a VM pretending to be a container.
<br>
<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s are VMs implementing container semantics, not containers implemented as VMs.
<br>
A <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a> is a Kubernetes Pod whose execution unit is a micro-VM, where the VM boundary replaces the Linux container boundary. The VM is the isolation primitive
The Pod is the semantic primitive
The container image is payload, not a process model
So the VM is not “pretending to be a container”—it is implementing the Pod abstraction using a VM instead of a process.
Pod (Kubernetes API object) └─ Backed by └─ Ultra-lightweight VM └─ ESX └─ Hardware
It is:
A Kubernetes-native unit
Scheduled by Kubernetes
Governed by Kubernetes APIs
<br>Backed by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> under the hood <br>Kubernetes API (<a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>) is authoritative
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> supplies infrastructure, not lifecycle semantics
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> governs Kubernetes intent, not individual pods CPU / memory requested via Kubernetes requests and limits
Scheduler decides placement
Isolation via: Namespaces
RBAC
Pod security Declarative (YAML)
Reconciliation-based
Pods are ephemeral
Restart ≠ failure
Replacement is normal Namespace-level quotas
Admission control
Image policies
Network policies VM workloads → legacy, stateful, pet-like systems
Pod workloads (vSphere Pods) → cloud-native, stateless, cattle-like systems
VCF’s value is:
Running both on the same physical infrastructure, with unified policy and automation, without forcing one model onto the other. Trying to manage pods like VMs breaks Kubernetes.
Trying to manage VMs like pods breaks operational reality.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> keeps them separate but coordinated.<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a> (Pod Workload) in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a Kubernetes-native execution unit scheduled and governed by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> Kubernetes control plane, consuming <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> resources indirectly through Kubernetes abstractions—unlike a VM workload, which is a hypervisor-managed, OS-bearing unit directly governed by vCenter.
“Pod workload” ≠ “small VM”
Pod Workloads are Kubernetes-first, not vSphere-first
VMs are stateful machines
Pods are replaceable execution instances
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> supports both because enterprises need both
<br>As another platform extension, you might want to look in to <a data-href="vSphere Trust Authority" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Trust Authority</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vm-workload-and-pod-workload.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Architecture and Core Concepts/VM Workload and Pod Workload.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:39:37 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSAN]]></title><description><![CDATA[vSAN&nbsp;aggregates local or direct-attached capacity devices of all <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts in a cluster and creates a single storage pool shared across all ESX hosts in the&nbsp;
vSAN cluster.Use&nbsp;vSAN&nbsp;as a VI administrator or storage administrator to enhance storage performance by aggregating local storage into a single shared pool across all hosts in a&nbsp;vSAN cluster.<br>You can use vSphere features that require shared storage, such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere HA</a>, vSphere <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>, and vSphere <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, without the need for external shared storage.vSAN provides operational consistency from edge to cloud, with complete visibility and lifecycle management of compute and storage from a single UI.You can perform consistent, VM-centric operations by using policy-based management. Within the vSAN ESA, per-VM policies increase flexibility of management, enabling compression policies, or customize data services on a per-VM basis.<br>Want some L2/L3 network magic? Then check out <a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/vSAN.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:36:28 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Networking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> leverages several components and technologies to establish management-plane and workload-plane networking.<br><img alt="supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="supervisor-nsx-segment-networking-c19ee74a-d0e9-4f05-b19f-e5fd1f5438ed.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-nsx-segment-networking-c19ee74a-d0e9-4f05-b19f-e5fd1f5438ed.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="single-mgmt-zone-nsx-segment-networking-77b549f9-eb55-4a44-93c4-8d12fd81e9c0.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/single-mgmt-zone-nsx-segment-networking-77b549f9-eb55-4a44-93c4-8d12fd81e9c0.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="supervisor-networking-with-avi-f7f80972-bfe1-493a-93eb-e5b000a5e516.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-with-avi-f7f80972-bfe1-493a-93eb-e5b000a5e516.original.svg" target="_self"><br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-networking.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Networking.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:24:02 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Domain]]></title><description><![CDATA[A VCF Domain is a core <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> platform construct.
<br>It is defined and lifecycle-managed by VCF itself (via <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>).
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes it for <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant</a> self-service and provisioning.
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> observes it for monitoring, health, and capacity.
<br>A VCF Domain is an isolated <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> unit inside VCF with its own full stack:Each domain is independently lifecycle-managed (upgrade cadence, patch windows, scaling).<br>A&nbsp;VCF Domain in a&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a> consists of the following components:
<br>One <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> instance.
<br>One or more <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere HA</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="DRS" data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere DRS</a> enabled.
<br>At least one <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Distributed Virtual Switch" data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Distributed Switch</a>es per cluster for system traffic and <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>s for workloads.
<br>Dedicated <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> instance, either specifically for the&nbsp;VCF Domain or shared between&nbsp;VCF Domains, for configuring and implementing software-defined networking.
<br>Optional: One or more <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>s, added after you create the Workload Domain, that connects the workloads in the Workload Domain for logical switching, logical dynamic routing, and load balancing.
One or more shared storage allocations as principal or supplemental storage.
There are two types of VCF Domains:
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> is created during the deployment or convergence process.
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> runs consumer workloads on <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a>.
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> and <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> gives further context about VCF Domains.<br>You might also want to check out <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>’s fleet and domain model by looking at <a data-href="VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Domain/VCF Domain.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:23:16 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Administrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, Supervisor Administrator is a new, platform-level role introduced to formalize control over the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> itself, and it sits orthogonally to— not above or below—the traditional <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> roles.<br>
Supervisor Administrator manages the platform that hosts tenants, while <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> manages the tenants themselves, and <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> manages what runs inside those tenants.
VCF separates responsibilities cleanly into three distinct administrative planes, each with its own roles:→ “How the Kubernetes substrate itself is operated”This is where the Supervisor Cluster lives.→ “Who consumes the infrastructure and how”<br>This is where <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, and quotas live.→ “What runs on top of it”<br>This is where Kubernetes <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workloads</a>, namespaces, and apps live.<br>Scope: <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> (platform level)Primary responsibility:
<br>Operates and governs the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> itself
Manages cluster-level capabilities that all tenants depend on
Typical responsibilities:
<br>Configure and manage <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> lifecycle
Control Supervisor services (e.g., Kubernetes control plane, CSI, CNI, storage integrations)
<br>Define which <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s can exist
<br>Enable or disable platform features available to <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
Maintain host, networking, and storage alignment required for Kubernetes workloads
Supervisor Administrator does not manage application workloads or tenant namespaces.From the Supervisor Administrator’s point of view:
“I run the Kubernetes platform that everyone else builds on.”
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> is the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant-level</a> authority.<br>Scope: <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> (tenant boundary)Role type: Consumer / tenant administratorResponsibilities:
<br>Create and manage <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Assign users to projects and roles
Define quotas and usage limits
Control access within their organization
Govern how their organization consumes platform capacity
They do not manage the Supervisor Cluster itself.<br>From the <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>’s perspective:
“I manage my organization’s slice of the platform.”
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> has <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload-level</a> control over the project they have access to.<br>Scope: Single <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> within an <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>Responsibilities:
Manage Kubernetes workloads (clusters, namespaces, services)
Manage users within the project
Configure project-level policies and resources
<br>They operate inside boundaries defined by the <a data-href="Organization Admin" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Admin</a> and enforced by the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>.<br>From <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>’s point of view:
“I manage workloads, not the platform.”
Supervisor Administrator
│
├── Organization Administrator
│ ├── Project Administrator
│ │ └── Application / Workload Operators
│ └── Project Users
│
└── (Multiple Organizations) Supervisor Admin ≠ Super Org Admin
They operate at different abstraction layers
Historically, roles like this were blurry or implicit (vSphere Admin, Cloud Admin, etc.).VCF introduces clear separation of concerns:This aligns VCF with cloud provider models (for, i.e., AWS control plane vs account admins).<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/supervisor-administrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Supervisor Administrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:59 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project User]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Project Users can only access the catalog and request catalog items. They can perform <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a> actions on their own deployments. They cannot use the IaaS services console.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Project User.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project Advanced User]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Project Advanced Users work within their <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s to request Catalog Items and create resources using the services console. They can perform <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a> on all resources.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Project Advanced User.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:45 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project Auditor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Project Auditor is the read-only version of <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-auditor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Project Auditor.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:41 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project Administrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>Project Administrators leverage the infrastructure that is created by the <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> to ensure that their project members have the resources they need for their development work.Project Administrators can:
<br>View all content for their <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>, including <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>, deployments, and so on
<br>Perform all <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a> actions on resources
<br>Manage users in the <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> and assign roles
<br>Manage <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>-level settings and administrator content
<br>Create resources using the IaaS services console in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> they created or have access to
Manage Catalog Approval Requests
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Project Administrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:33 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Organization User]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>An Organization User can log in to the organization portal. Must be added to a <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-user.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Organization User.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:29 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Organization Auditor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Organization Auditor is the read-only version of <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-auditor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Organization Auditor.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:23 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Organization Administrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>An Organization Administrator can access the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> portal and add users and groups to the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.Organization Administrators can:
<br>Manage <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s and <a data-href="Project User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project User</a>s
Configure integrations, such as Git
<br>Manage <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s and Catalog Items
<br>Manage <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> and associated resources
<br>Fully access <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> that they did not create
<br>Manage new <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>s and associated resources
<br>See all <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s and all Deployments
Create and manage Content Libraries
<br>Create and manage <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">policies</a> on resources and deployments
Create and manage event subscriptions
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Organization Administrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:17 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[User Roles]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Roles assigned to users and groups are an essential part to identity and access management in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>You can leverage identity providers with <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s to enable single sign-on to provision users and groups. Once the users and groups are added to the&nbsp;<a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>, they must be assigned roles to enable specific permissions and access to different features within&nbsp; <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>VCF Automation has several levels of user roles. These different levels control access to the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>, the <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s that produce or consume the <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s, Catalog Items, access to IaaS Services, and the ability for users to use or see individual parts of the user interface. These different levels give <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s different tools to apply any level of granularity that is required by their operational needs.<br>Here are the predefined user roles in **<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>. You can visit each link to see more details about them.
Organization Roles <br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization User</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Auditor</a> Project Roles <br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Auditor</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Advanced User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Advanced User</a>
<br><a data-href="Project User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project User</a> **Supervisor Roles <br><a data-href="Supervisor Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/supervisor-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Administrator</a> <br>
Defer to Identity Provider
User permissions can also be determined based on information received from the identity provider for the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.
<br><a data-href="Organization Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a> could be a good area to explore after getting acquainted with the user roles here. Additionally, you can find a more detailed listing of what permissions these roles have in <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/User Roles.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:08 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vMotion]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vmotion_migration_process.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg" target="_self"><br>vMotion is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>’s live-migration mechanism that moves a running VM from one <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host to another with no downtime.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, vMotion is foundational plumbing—it’s how higher-level services (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, maintenance workflows) actually move workloads.<br><img alt="vMotion-pagetrace2.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion-pagetrace2.webp" target="_self">VCF
└── vSphere ├── DRS → decides *when/where* to move ├── HA → may trigger restarts (not vMotion) └── vMotion → performs the *move* <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Orchestrated via: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br>Consumed by: <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, maintenance mode, admin actions DRS decides. vMotion moves. Pre-copy: VM memory is copied to the destination while the VM keeps running.
Iterative sync: Dirty pages are recopied until the delta is tiny.
Switchover: VM is briefly quiesced (milliseconds), CPU state flips.
Resume: VM continues on the new host with the same IP/MAC.
No reboot. No app restart.
Shared storage access
L2 network reachability
Compatible CPU features (or EVC)
vMotion-enabled VMkernel network with sufficient bandwidth
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> designs these prerequisites in by default.
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> load balancing (automatic)
Host maintenance mode (drain before patching)
Hardware refresh (zero-downtime)
Policy remediation (after placement decisions)
<br>You rarely “use vMotion” directly in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>—it’s constantly in use under the hood.
Not a scheduler (it doesn’t decide)
Not a failover mechanism
Not application-aware
Not cross-site DR by itself
It is transport, not policy.
“VCF places workloads with vMotion” → No. DRS places; vMotion moves.
“vMotion is free” → No. It consumes network and CPU headroom.
“vMotion fixes capacity issues” → No. It redistributes load only.
vMotion doesn’t choose destinations, and it doesn’t judge priorities—it just moves things safely when told.
vMotion = zero-downtime VM movement
Core building block for DRS and maintenance
Always present and assumed in VCF designs
Necessary—but never sufficient—by itself
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 0 Tasks</a>, <a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> could be nice places to visit from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Workload Mobility and Resilience/vMotion.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:45:50 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Operations Orchestrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[VCF Operations Orchestrator provides a library of workflows that perform common management tasks. VCF Operations Orchestrator also provides libraries of the individual actions that the workflows perform.<a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s combine actions, decisions, and results that, when performed in a particular order, finish a specific task or a specific process in a virtual environment.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s perform tasks such as provisioning virtual machines, backing up, performing regular maintenance, sending emails, performing SSH operations, managing the physical infrastructure, and other general utility operations. Workflows accept inputs according to their function.<br>You can create <a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s that run according to defined schedules, or that run if certain anticipated events occur.Information can be provided by you, by other users, by another workflow or action, or by an external process such as a Web service call from an application.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s perform some validation and filtering of information before they run.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s can be chained. That is, they can call upon other workflows. For example, you can have workflow that calls up another workflow to create a new virtual machine.You create workflows by using the&nbsp;VCF Operations Orchestrator’s integrated development environment (IDE), that provides access to the workflow library and the ability to run workflows on the workflow engine.The workflow engine can also take objects from external libraries that you plug in to&nbsp;the VCF Operations Orchestrator. This allows you to customize processes or implement functions that third-party applications provide.<br>Why not check out, <a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s, or maybe <a data-href="Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows</a>?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/VCF Operations Orchestrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:45:07 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Fleet Deployment]]></title><description><![CDATA[There are several different way you can deploy a <a data-href="VCF Fleet" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a>, each with its own benefits and liabilities.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vcf-fleet-deployment-d881e129-73ec-4b71-8940-e69541f380ef.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-deployment-d881e129-73ec-4b71-8940-e69541f380ef.webp" target="_self"><br>This model is ideal for organizations seeking a streamlined and scalable approach to deploying within a single availability zone or region. The design provides centralized management, enabling a unified framework for managing instances and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>s through a single&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> instance.<br>This is typically the first (and robust) starting point for deploying the first <a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>, with the flexibility to expand to multiple instances while maintaining centralized operations and automation.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-multi-az-d62fd633-c0c8-4bdf-ae11-fe7d14f8a2f3.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-multi-az-d62fd633-c0c8-4bdf-ae11-fe7d14f8a2f3.webp" target="_self">This is an ideal choice for organizations that require robust protection against site-wide failures and the ability to recover critical workloads in the event of a disaster.By building upon the former deployment design, this approach integrates disaster recovery capabilities to ensure business continuity.<br>It leverages VMware's advanced tools and technologies, such as <a data-href="VMware Live Recovery" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmware-live-recovery.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Live Recovery</a>, to enable seamless failover and failback between sites or regions. This design ensures that critical workloads are replicated and protected, minimizing downtime and data loss during unexpected events.Additionally, it supports flexible deployment models, including Single-Rack and Multi-Rack configurations, to meet diverse infrastructure needs.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-dr-f39c3fa5-a80d-4b0b-ab1b-e3c736ba88f4.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-dr-f39c3fa5-a80d-4b0b-ab1b-e3c736ba88f4.webp" target="_self"><br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> utilizes replication or backup and restore mechanisms to protect components at a secondary site, while&nbsp;<br>
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> relies on backup and restore processes for recovery at the secondary site.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-dr-fault-8224d2cf-6af2-4d51-8ebc-1d40a50059e2.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-dr-fault-8224d2cf-6af2-4d51-8ebc-1d40a50059e2.original.png" target="_self"><br>This is another Fleet Deployment topology with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Fault Tolerance" data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Domains</a> and Disaster Recovery, combining Disaster Recovery and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">High Availability</a> capabilities.<br>You might want to switch gears and check out <a data-href="VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-sdks,-apis,-and-clis.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/VCF Installer/VCF Fleet Deployment.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:42:40 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Concepts]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>Here is a list off top-level items in this category:
Tenancy <br><a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a> <br><a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a> <br><a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> Cloud <br><a data-href="VMware Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-cloud/vmware-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud</a>
<br><a data-href="VMware Validated Solutions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Validated Solutions</a> Governance and Compliance <br><a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>
<br><a data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy</a>
<br><a data-href="Policy as Code" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy-as-code.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy as Code</a> Topology <br><a data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Private Cloud</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Management Components" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-management-components.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Management Components</a> Fleet and Domain Model <br><a data-href="VCF Fleet" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains</a> <br><a data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Domain</a> <br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> Consumption Abstractions <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a> Other <br><a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Advanced Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/vcf-capabilities/vcf-advanced-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Advanced Services</a> ]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/concepts.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Concepts.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:41:56 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Policy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br><img alt="vcf-services-image_b975c3.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png" target="_self"><br>A Policy in VCF is a <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> Rule that defines what is allowed, constrained, or enforced across infrastructure and workloads.<br>
It exists across multiple layers of VCF, but it becomes a first-class, user-visible construct in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>If you think of <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> as a city:
Infrastructure → roads, power, zoning
Policies → zoning laws, speed limits, building codes
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> → city planning office that enforces them before you build
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> → inspectors that check compliance after things exist
<br>These are foundational, implicit, and exist below <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, often enforced automatically.Examples:
Storage policies (SPBM): RAID, availability, performance tiers
<br>Network policies: <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> security groups, microsegmentation rules
<br>Host policies: <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, admission control
These are:
<br>Defined in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> / <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
Consumed transparently by higher layers
Not tenant-facing by default
This is usually what people mean when they say “policy”.This is where Policy becomes a named, explicit, governable object.<br>In <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, policies define constraints and guardrails for consumers.Examples:
Who can deploy what
Where workloads can land
What sizes, images, or networks are allowed
Lease durations and approval requirements
Typical policy categories:
Placement policies: Which clusters, regions, zones
Sizing policies: CPU, memory, storage limits
Image policies: Approved OS images only
Network policies: allowed networks / isolation
Approval policies: manual gates for certain actions
Lease policies: TTL and reclamation rules
These policies are evaluated before provisioning.<br>In <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, policies are usually scoped to:<br>
- <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s<br>
- or <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>sThey act as guardrails, not implementation detailsExample:
“In Project Prod, only Gold storage, max 16 vCPU, and approval required.”
This is where policy intersects with consumption abstraction.<br>In **<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>, policy ≠ enforcement.VCF Operations uses policy indirectly.<br>In <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>:
Policies become: Alerts
Compliance checks
Drift detection
Optimization rules <br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> answers:
“Is reality still compliant with the policy?”
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> answers:
“Should this action be allowed at all, in the first place?” <br>A Policy in <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> is a governance rule, not a single product feature
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> is where policies are: Explicit
Named
Scoped
Evaluated before action <br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> observes and reports compliance
Infrastructure layers actually enforce the low-level mechanics
<br><a data-href="STIG" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/stig.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">STIG</a> can be an interesting topic that can complement policies.<br>You might also want to check out <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Governance and Compliance/Policy.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:32:45 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Advanced Services]]></title><description><![CDATA[VCF Advanced Services provide additional add-on functionality to the platform.The following sections summarize some of the *VCF Advanced Services.VMware Live Recovery is used to build powerful cyber and data resiliency for&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.It provides ransomware and disaster recovery in a unified management experience, accelerated recovery, and simplified consumption.You can use Data Services Manager to build enterprise-hardened data services with high availability, performance, backup, and monitoring.<br>You can use VMware Private AI Foundation to run NVIDIA NIM microservices on&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, which support AI models from NVIDIA and others in the community, and NVIDIA AI tools and frameworks.<br>You can use vDefend for built-in zone and application microsegmentation, threat detection and response, lateral security, ransomware and APT protection, reduced attack surface, and zero trust enforcement across&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> environments.<br>VMware Avi Load Balancer is a software-defined platform deeply integrated with&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> private cloud, delivering local and global load balancing, Kubernetes ingress, web application and API security and application analytics.<br>Network Observability extends the&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> management capabilities with end-to-end visibility into the network overlay, underlay, and applications hosted in a public or hybrid cloud.The solution provides actionable insights to automatically pinpoint problems, resulting in lower internal resource costs and faster issue resolution, quickly getting end-users back to revenue-producing activities.<br>How about checking out consumption abstractions such as <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>, and <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/vcf-capabilities/vcf-advanced-services.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/VCF Capabilities/VCF Advanced Services.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:31:14 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Organization]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a><br><img alt="VCF-Automation-Capabilities-1.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-automation-capabilities-1.webp" target="_self"><br>In <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, an Organization is not a technical runtime boundary—It is a business-facing logical entity that defines who is allowed to consume cloud capabilities, under which rules, and with which visibility.An Organization is the top-level administrative boundary.It is used to:
Group users, projects, and resources
Apply policies and governance
Define ownership and access boundaries
Support multi-tenant separation
An organization typically maps to a business unit or tenant.Organizations exist only in VCF Automation, not in Kubernetes.It is the outermost “contract boundary” for consumption, not execution.An Organization is a logical tenant boundary that groups identity, policy, quotas, visibility, and approval flows for consuming infrastructure and platform services.It answers:
Who is consuming?
What are they allowed to consume?
Under which business rules?
—not how workloads actually run.
<br>Because <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are the actual enforcement boundary, a single Organization can define <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">multiple tenants</a>.But those “tenants” are operational tenants, not consumption tenants.There are two different kinds of tenancy in VCF:They are deliberately decoupled.<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> enforces:
RBAC
Resource quotas
Network isolation
Storage policies
Pod security boundaries
Runtime blast radius
This is where:
Kubernetes says “no”
vSphere enforces limits
Workloads are actually prevented from crossing boundaries Namespace = hard enforcement boundary
<br>Organizations define intent and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.
An Organization:
Defines who is allowed to create tenants
Defines how many tenants
Defines under which rules
Defines approval and lifecycle policies
It’s closer to:
“Who is allowed to mint isolation boundaries?”
not:
“Where isolation happens.”
A single Organization can own:
Multiple Projects
Each Project can map to: <br>One <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>
Or several namespaces (depending on policy / model) Organization: Acme Corp
├── Project: Acme-Prod → ns-acme-prod
├── Project: Acme-Stage → ns-acme-stage
├── Project: Acme-Dev → ns-acme-dev
└── Project: Acme-Analytics → ns-acme-analytics
<br>Each <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace</a> is a real tenant boundary.But from a business standpoint:
Acme Corp is still one customer: One billing entity
One governance envelope
One policy domain This construct enables the following scenarios (which would have been impossible otherwise).Classic need:
Dev / Stage / Prod
Regulated vs non-regulated
Different trust zones
All under:
One contract
One identity plane
One catalog
Example:
Organization = “Platform Team”
Projects = internal product teams
Namespaces = per-team isolation
This would break if Organization == Namespace.Example:
Organization = External customer
Projects = customer environments
Namespaces = actual enforcement boundaries
Same model works for:
Internal IT
SaaS providers
Telco multi-tenant platforms
If something must be isolated, it must be isolated at the namespace level.Anything above that:
<br>Is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">governance</a>
Is visibility
Is policy
Is economy
Organizations define who may create tenants; namespaces are the tenants.Similar to:
AWS Account
Azure Subscription (with Management Groups layered above)
GCP Project (with Org/Folder hierarchy)
But in VCF, it’s explicitly framed as consumption-first, not infrastructure-first.
Separates consumers (e.g., companies, business units, external customers)
Enforces isolation in: Identity and Access
Visibility
Quotas and Limits
Chargeback / showback Organizations are where policies attach, such as:
Who can request what
Approval workflows
Budget limits
Lease durations
Allowed regions / environments
Allowed workload types (VM, Kubernetes, services)
These policies then flow downward.Everything inside an Organization is:
Visible only to that Organization (unless shared)
Governed consistently
This includes:
Projects
Blueprints / templates
Catalog items
Requests
Cost views
Organization
├── Projects
│ ├── Policies
│ ├── Quotas
│ ├── Users / Groups
│ └── Workload requests
│
└── (maps indirectly to) └── Cloud Zones └── Infrastructure (vSphere, Supervisor, VKS, etc.) Infrastructure never belongs to an Organization
Consumption always does
Organization deliberately hides infrastructure topology.From the Organization’s point of view:
<br>There is no <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
No cluster
No datastore
<br>No <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
There is only:
“What can I request?”
“What am I allowed to use?”
“Who approves this?”
“How much does it cost?”
This abstraction enables:
Multi-tenant platforms
Internal private clouds
Managed services
SaaS-like experience on top of VCF
If Organization is “who is the customer”,
then Project is “what they are working on”.Typical mapping:Organization: Acme Corp
├── Project: Acme-Prod
├── Project: Acme-Stage
└── Project: Acme-Dev
Projects:
Scope quotas
Bind to cloud zones
<br>Eventually map to <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s or runtime constructs
Organizations never do.
<br>Organization = <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> + visibility
It exists to model consumption, not execution
It owns policy, identity, and economics
It deliberately abstracts away infrastructure
<br>Everything technical happens below it, via <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s and Cloud Zones
<br>Check <a data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">IaaS</a> as a concept, or jump back to <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Consumption Abstractions/Organization.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 01:17:49 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-automation-capabilities-1.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-automation-capabilities-1.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Automation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>VCF Automation enables IT teams and cloud service providers to deliver a self-service private cloud for AI, Kubernetes, and VM-based applications.<br>The solution simplifies the process of provisioning and scaling a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">multi-tenant</a> private cloud with out-of-the-box Infrastructure as a Service (<a data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">IaaS</a>) offerings, accelerating the time to market for applications while maintaining control using policy-based governance.<br>VCF Automation provides <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> at the request and lifecycle level—controlling who can deploy which patterns, under what constraints and approvals—while runtime security, drift detection, and continuous enforcement are handled by downstream platforms.VCF Automation has the following capabilities:
<br><a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>: Provides a set of cloud services to meet the needs of application teams
<br><a data-href="Provider Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>: Supports IT teams and cloud service providers to effectively manage, deliver, and scale cloud services across multiple vCenter and VCF instances.
<br><a data-href="Organization Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a>: Provides capabilities that enable the organization administrator of a Line of Business or a tenant to further organize and govern resources allocated to them among application teams.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>: Provides the capability to run Kubernetes workloads directly on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and to create <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">upstream Kubernetes clusters</a> within dedicated <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>.
<br>From here, you can jump to <a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>, <a data-href="Provider Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>.<br>
Also, <a data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">User Roles</a> and <a data-href="Project Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/project-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Management</a> are other good candidates to explore. Or, dive directly into <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/VCF Automation.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:50:19 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Organization Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> improves <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> for users and resources by enabling <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s create and assign projects and vSphere Namespaces tailored for different application teams.<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s can set resource limits and policies while delegating network management through Virtual Private Clouds (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>s) for application teams.<br>Additionally, <a data-href="Policy as Code" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy-as-code.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy as Code</a> enables organization administrators to enforce instance-centric policies for Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) resources from a central location for compliance and reducing the risk of human error.<br>In, <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, an <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> is a top level entity that represents a line of business or a tenant. Each organization operates in a secure and isolated environment where users can access only allocated services and resources.<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s consume resources and cloud services from a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Resource Pool" data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">shared pool of resources</a>. The resources allocated to organizations can be further allocated to application teams which are modeled in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> as <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s.<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s have users with varying levels of permissions depending on their role and duties.<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> are created by the Provider Administrator in the&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> Provider Management Portal.<br>Each <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> has its own Organization Portal where users log in to consume resources and services. Every organization has its own identity source that they connect to and can import users from.<br>Organizations enable line-of-business or tenant [Organization Administrator]]s to further organize and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">govern</a> resources that are allocated to them among application teams through the following capabilities:
<br>Resource management for <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> teams.
<br>Centralized content management for the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.
Policy-based governance on usage of resources.
Quota-based management of networking resources.
<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a> orchestration and extensibility through event subscriptions.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCF Identity Broker" data-href="vCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Integration with identity providers</a> of their choice.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VCF Automation”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/Organization Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:49:42 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Provider Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>IT teams and Cloud Service Providers can model <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a> by using the concept of <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.This approach allocates resources and manages users specific to each Organization.This capability provides isolated environments with dedicated network setup. IT Teams and CSPs can monitor resource usage, control permissions, and provide managed services while ensuring security through comprehensive network isolation.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VCF Automation”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Provider Management/Provider Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:47:17 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Management Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>In VMware Cloud Foundation, the Management Cluster is the foundational cluster that runs the platform itself.
It hosts the management plane—the services that build, operate, upgrade, and secure the rest of the cloud.Put simply:
If the Management Cluster is down, you can’t manage the cloud—only the workloads keep running.
<br>The Management Cluster is part of the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> (a special Workload Domain). It is created first during <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0 bring-up</a> and is non-optional.Typical components include:
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> (management vCenter)
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> management services
These components do not belong to the tenants. They belong to the platform.It runs the services that:
Define topology
Enforce lifecycle sequencing
Validate upgrades
Maintain inventory and state
All VCF lifecycle operations (create domain, expand cluster, upgrade stack) are coordinated from here.Tenant workloads do not run here (by design):
No tenant VMs
No tenant Kubernetes workloads
No customer apps
This protects:
Stability
Security
Upgrade safety
It is not:
A tenant cluster
A workload execution environment
A shared resource pool for apps
Optional or replaceable
Treating it like a general-purpose cluster is a serious anti-pattern.This separation ensures:
Predictable upgrades (no tenant interference)
Clear blast-radius control
Strong security boundaries
Operational sanity at scale
It’s the same pattern used by:
Kubernetes (control plane vs worker nodes)
Public clouds (provider plane vs customer plane) Management Cluster → Kubernetes control plane nodes
Guest Clusters → Kubernetes worker nodes
SDDC Manager → Cluster lifecycle operator
You wouldn’t run apps on the Kubernetes control plane; same rule applies here.
Management Cluster is typically: Small (minimum viable size)
Highly available
Strictly protected If it fails: Existing workloads keep running
You lose management, scaling, and upgrades until restored The Management Cluster runs the cloud, not the workloads
<br>It is part of the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>
<br>It hosts <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>, <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s
It is isolated, mandatory, and high-blast-radius
Treat it as sacred infrastructure
<br>You can check out <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> or <a data-href="Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster</a> for the next set of items to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/Management Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:38:20 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[See also: <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>Yes’nt.<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> and a Supervisor Cluster are not the same thing. However, they are so tightly-related in a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor-enabled Namespace</a>, you can “colloquially” say that they are the same.Yet, they sit at different abstraction layers.This is the base construct.A vSphere Cluster is a classic virtualization construct:
A group of [[ESX] hosts
<br>Managed by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Provides: [DRS] (scheduling)
[HA] (failover)
Resource Pooling (CPU / memory)
Shared storage and networking However, vSphere Cluster alone does not imply
Any Kubernetes
Any namespaces
Any tenants
Any container workloads
You can run only VMs, forever, and never enable anything Kubernetes-related.This is the layer on top.A Supervisor Cluster is not a separate cluster of hosts.It is:<br>
A Kubernetes control plane embedded into a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>
<br>When you enable the Supervisor feature on <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>:
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> deploys Kubernetes control plane VMs
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts become Kubernetes worker nodes
vSphere exposes: <br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod Workload</a>s
<br><a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>s (e.g., <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>) <br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> becomes Kubernetes-aware
<br>The key point is: The same <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts of the same <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> are used, but now they serve two schedulers**:
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s)
Kubernetes (pods / guest clusters)
So the formal relationship is:
A Supervisor Cluster is a capability of a vSphere Cluster, not a different cluster type.
But, it walks like a duck, talks like a duck, and it surely is a very-sophisticated duck: Operationally, and practically, it is the same thing.<br>A Supervisor Cluster is a Kubernetes control plane that runs on and transforms a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> into a Kubernetes-aware platform.For the ontology-enthusiasts out there:This matters a lot.
vSphere cluster failure → everything dies
<br>Supervisor control plane failure → <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s keep running
Although subtle, this distinction becomes very important when discussing:
Security boundaries
Upgrade paths
Failure isolation
Scheduling semantics
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> mappings
<br>
In a Supervisor-enabled <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>, the Supervisor Cluster and the <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> are co-resident and inseparable operationally, but they remain distinct architectural constructs with different control planes and failure domains.
<br><a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> complements Supervisor Cluster. You might also want to explore <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>. Or check <a data-href="Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster</a> for a nuanced discussion of the terminology.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Inventory Objects/Supervisor Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:32:42 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Guest Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>In VMware Cloud Foundation, a Guest Cluster (workload cluster) is a cluster dedicated to running tenant workloads—VMs or Kubernetes-backed workloads—as opposed to running the platform itself.<br>It lives inside a <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> (VI Domain) and is where actual business applications execute.<br>
Guest Clusters run applications; <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>s run the cloud.
<br><img alt="Workload-Domain.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg" target="_self"><br>Once a <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> Guest Cluster (also known as “Workload Cluster”) is bound to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>:
<br>✅ The cluster knows which <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> it lives in
❌ It has no intrinsic knowledge of: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Automation</a> constructs
Approval flows
Business tenancy
<br>^ all of these concepts stop at the **<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> boundary. <br>When a guest cluster is bound to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, we are talking about a <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> workload cluster created by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.That implies:
The cluster is created via Supervisor APIs
<br>It is <a data-href="vSphere Namespaces" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespaces</a>-scoped
<br>It is lifecycle-managed by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>It runs on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> using VM-based worker nodes
VCF Platform
│
├── Management Domain
│ └── Management Cluster (platform services only)
│
└── Workload Domain (VI Domain) ├── Guest Cluster A ← tenant workloads ├── Guest Cluster B ← tenant workloads └── Guest Cluster C ← tenant workloads <br>A <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> can contain multiple Guest Clusters
Each cluster is an operational and failure boundary
<br>Tenants never see the <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>, but they consume resources from Guest Clusters Traditional virtual machines
App servers, databases, legacy systems
<br>Managed via <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
<br>Governed via <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (orgs, projects, policies) <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>-backed workloads
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">PodVM</a>-based workloads
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s mapped to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
The cluster itself is workload-agnostic; policy determines what lands there.This split is critical:
<br>Tenants use <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>-managed <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster bound to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s operate clusters
This is where:
CPU, memory, storage are consumed
Network traffic flows
Availability and performance matter most
Each Guest Cluster provides:
Fault isolation
Upgrade isolation
Security boundaries
A problem in one cluster should not affect others.Clusters are upgraded:
<br>Under <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> control
In a controlled, validated sequence
Independently of other clusters (within constraints)
It is not:
A management plane
<br>A place for <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> or <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s
A tenant abstraction by itself
A free-for-all environment
A Guest Cluster is shared infrastructure, not a tenant.There is an important nuance here:
Tenancy does not equal cluster
Multiple tenants can share: The same Guest Cluster
While remaining isolated via: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Microsegmentation Guest Clusters are capacity and fault boundaries, not business boundaries.
Strong fault isolation
Predictable lifecycle
Flexible placement strategies
Supports mixed workload types More moving parts
Requires capacity planning
Requires clear cluster placement policy
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for enterprise-scale control, not minimal topology.
Guest Clusters are where applications run
<br>They live inside <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload (VI) Domains</a>
<br>They are operated by <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s
They can host VM and Kubernetes workloads
They are shared but strongly governed
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> complements Guest Cluster. You might also want to explore <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>. Or check <a data-href="Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster</a> for a nuanced discussion of the terminology.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/Guest Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:32:01 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>NSX enables network connectivity, operations, and scale. It uses a software-defined approach to networking that spans data centers, clouds and application frameworks.NSX abstracts network services from the underlying hardware, enabling programmable infrastructure through APIs. You can implement policies and workflows to automate tasks like network provisioning, security enforcement, load balancing, streamlining operations, and improving efficiency.NSX provides a complete set of logical networking capabilities and services, including logical switching, routing, distributed load balancing, virtual private network (VPN), quality of service (QoS), and monitoring.Enable logical Layer 2 overlay extensions across a routed (Layer 3) fabric within and across data center boundaries.Dynamic routing between virtual networks that is performed in a distributed manner in the hypervisor kernel, and scale-out routing with active-active failover with physical routers. Static routing and dynamic routing protocols are supported, including support for IPv6.Complete data plane isolation among tenants with a separate routing table, network address translation (NAT), and edge firewall support in each VRF on the&nbsp;Support for bridging between VLANs configured on the physical network and&nbsp;NSX overlay networks, for seamless connectivity between virtual and physical workloads.Site-to-site and unmanaged VPN for cloud gateway services.By using&nbsp;NSX, you can move workloads between racks and data centers by decoupling them from the underlying networks.Centralized policy configuration and enforcement across multiple locations from a single pane of glass, enabling network-wide consistent policy, operational simplicity, and simplified disaster recovery architecture.Enable consistent networking and security across data center sites, and across private cloud boundaries, irrespective of underlying physical topology or cloud platform.NSX can manage the provisioning, deployment, operations and retirement of networking infrastructure and applications from a central control pane.<br>You can automate infrastructure operations and offload manual tasks with workflows and agile templating using tools such as&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, Terraform, and Ansible.&nbsp;<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>s provide isolated network environments within a shared infrastructure. You can use Virtual Private Cloud (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>) constructs to provision and manage network resources to business units or project teams independently, with granular control over networking policies and resource allocation.<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> for a more technical overview about NSX internal, or look at <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, or <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/NSX.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:25:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Components]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg" target="_self"><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> has the following components:
<br>Supervisor control plane VM. You can select to deploy the&nbsp; Supervisor with either one or three control plane VMs. For control plane <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, three VMs are recommended. The three&nbsp; Supervisor control plane VMs are load balanced as each one of them has its own IP address.
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> and Cluster API (CAPI). Modules running on the&nbsp;Supervisor and enable the provisioning and management of&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters.
<br>Virtual Machine Service. A module that is responsible for deploying and running stand-alone VMs and VMs that make up&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters.
<br>Spherelet. An additional process called Spherelet is created on each host. It is a kubelet that is ported natively to <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and allows the <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host to become part of the Kubernetes cluster.
<br>Container Runtime Executive (CRX) component. CRX is similar to a VM from the perspective of hostd and&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>. CRX includes a paravirtualized Linux kernel that works together with the hypervisor. CRX uses the same hardware virtualization techniques as VMs and it has a VM boundary around it. A direct boot technique is used, which allows the Linux guest of CRX to initiate the main init process without passing through kernel initialization. This allows&nbsp; vSphere Pods to boot nearly as fast as containers.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Components.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:24:22 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Storage]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> components, applications, and workloads need to store and retrieve data. Some applications and objects might use transient fast storage, while others require storage that persists.A vSphere Zone is a fault domain that can fail independently from another zones.&nbsp;<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> supports different storage topologies for zones. These topologies define how datastores are attached to&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and how they behave during zone failures.<br>A zonal datastore is local to a single vSphere Zone. It is attached to all the&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts that are part of the underlying cluster.
It can replicate data to provide higher availability within the zone.
Its availability depends on the zone. If the zone goes down, the zonal datastore also goes down.
Examples of a zonal datastore include: non-stretched vSAN, non-stretched vSAN storage cluster, non-stretched VMFS or NFS external storage.
<br>A cross-zonal datastore spans multiple vSphere Zones. It is attached to&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts from all the zones it covers.
It can be stretched storage, for example, stretched vSAN, or non-stretched storage that pools hosts from multiple zones, for example, non-stretched vSAN storage cluster.
It typically replicates data across zones.
It stays available if one of the zones goes down.
Examples of a cross-zonal datastore: stretched vSAN, stretched vSAN storage cluster, metro storage cluster, non-stretched vSAN or vSAN storage cluster deployed from hosts across multiple zones.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> uses storage policies to integrate with storage available in your <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> environment. The policies represent datastores and manage storage placement of such components and objects as control plane VMs,&nbsp;vSphere Pod ephemeral disks, and container images. You might also need policies for storage placement of persistent volumes and VM content libraries. If you use&nbsp;<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, the storage policies also dictate how the&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>&nbsp;cluster nodes are deployed.<br>Storage policies support any shared datastores in your environment, such as VMFS, NFS, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>, and vSAN ESA.<br>Depending on your <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> storage environment and the needs of DevOps, you can create several storage policies for different classes of storage. When you enable a&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> and set up <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>s, you can assign different storage policies to be used by various objects, components, and workloads.<br>For example, if a&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a> mounts three types of virtual disks and your vSphere storage environment has three classes of datastores, Bronze, Silver, and Gold, you can create storage policies for all datastores. You can then use the Bronze datastore for ephemeral and container image virtual disks, and use the Silver and Gold datastores for persistent volume virtual disks.<br><img alt="vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp" target="_self"><br>Image Service, an&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> component, is responsible for pulling container images from the image registry and transforming them into virtual disks to run inside the pod.<br><img alt="esx-can-cache-images-966c000f-edb1-4d4e-9c72-c5f571cc1647.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/esx-can-cache-images-966c000f-edb1-4d4e-9c72-c5f571cc1647.original.png" target="_self">Certain Kubernetes workloads that DevOps run on a namespace require persistent storage to store data permanently.<br>Persistent storage can be used by&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s,&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, VMs, and other workloads you run on the namespace. To make persistent storage available to the DevOps team, the vSphere administrator creates storage policies that describe different storage requirements and classes of services. The administrator then assigns storage policies and configures storage limits at a namespace level.<br><img alt="supervisor-cns-csi-8a7c342c-4c0b-4e84-9ab2-cf06dd7dc420.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cns-csi-8a7c342c-4c0b-4e84-9ab2-cf06dd7dc420.original.png" target="_self"><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> uses several components to integrate with vSphere storage.<br>The <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> component resides in&nbsp;<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>. It is an extension of&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> management that implements provisioning and lifecycle operations for persistent volumes.When provisioning persistent volumes, the component interacts with the vSphere First Class Disk functionality to create virtual disks that back the volumes. In addition, the CNS server component communicates with the Storage Policy Based Management to guarantee a required level of service to the disks.<br>The <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> also performs query operations that allow vSphere administrators to manage and monitor persistent volumes and their backing storage objects through&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-storage.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Storage.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 00:10:22 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Security]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> leverages vSphere security features and provisions&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters that are secure by default.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> is an add-on module to <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> that is able to leverage the security features that are built into&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> and <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.<br>The&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> encrypts all secrets stored in the database (etcd). The secrets are encrypted via a local encryption key file, which is provided at boot by&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>. The decryption key is stored in memory (tempfs) on the&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> nodes and on disk in encrypted form within <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> database. The key is available in clear text to the root users of each system.&nbsp;
All etcd connections are authenticated with certificates that are generated at installation and rotated during upgrades.&nbsp;<br>
In&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, you can run <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod" data-href="Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/deploy-a-confidential-vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">run confidential vSphere Pods</a> on compatible systems. You can create confidential&nbsp; vSphere Pods by adding Secure Encrypted Virtualization-Encrypted State (SEV-ES) as a security enhancement.<br>A <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster is secure by default. Restrictive Pod Security Admission is configured in <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> Clusters.&nbsp;If developers need to run privileged pods or root containers, at a minimum, a cluster administrator must create a RoleBinding that grants the necessary access&nbsp;<br>
VKS cluster has tenancy. As a result, there is no privilege escalation avenue for cluster operators or users: The authentication token used to access a&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster is scoped such that the token cannot be used to access the&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> or other&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters. This prevents cluster operators, or individuals who might try to compromise a cluster, from using their root-level access to capture a vSphere Administrator's token when they log in to a&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>
cluster.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-security.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Security.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 23:57:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Inventory]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg" target="_self">The&nbsp;vSphere Supervisor Inventory is a representation of the&nbsp; Supervisor folder and its associated resources.<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> configures separate&nbsp;Supervisor folders for each&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Cluster" data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> and all the associated resources. The namespaces and control plane VMs are mapped under the respective&nbsp;Supervisor folder isolating them from the resources of other&nbsp;Supervisors, even though names of namespaces must be unique within&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br>The&nbsp; <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s within each namespace are segregated into a folder called&nbsp;“vSphere Pods”. This ensures their isolation from other VMs and&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> Clusters that are in the same namespace and allows distinct and precise privilege allocation.<br>Each&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a> folder includes all workload entities created under it, such as VMs deployed through VM Service and&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a><br>
clusters (<a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>s). Additionally, each&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a><br>
folder contains a subfolder named&nbsp;vSphere Pods which contains all the&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s associated with the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace</a>.&nbsp;<br>
Since <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod VMs</a> primarily serve infrastructure purposes, the&nbsp;
vSphere Pods folder is configured with restrictive permissions to prevent users from performing any direct operations on the pods.<br><img alt="supervisor-vsphere-folder-structure-f8d271d6-e7e2-4e2d-b18c-4ed4d1ea612a.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-vsphere-folder-structure-f8d271d6-e7e2-4e2d-b18c-4ed4d1ea612a.original.png" target="_self"><br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-inventory.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Inventory.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 23:47:38 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VKS Cluster Networking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VKS”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-networking.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/Platform Integration/VKS Cluster Networking.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 23:08:06 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s provide a logical grouping of users and the infrastructure that they are assigned.<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s are used to represent real world teams which are in charge of development or operations. Each <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> has one or more <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> assigned to it. Each <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace</a> is an envelope of resources where applications can be deployed. Access controls for <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s are governed by pre-defined roles.<br>&nbsp;<a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s can create and attach one or more <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> to a project. Administrators can also delete a namespace at any time, which dissociates the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace</a> from the project.&nbsp;<br>
Every <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> comes with a default project. The default project doesn’t have users or namespaces. The <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> can change the name, description of the default project, and add users and namespaces to the default project.<br>&nbsp;A namespace class is a template that is used to create <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>. All components of a namespace, including limits on CPU, memory, and storage utilization, VM classes and storage classes, and content libraries can be defined as a reusable template. Namespace classes are created and maintained by <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s.<br>&nbsp;Infrastructure quota assigned to an organization can be subdivided and assigned to project teams in the form of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>]. Namespaces are isolated resource pools in which resources like VMs, <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, and volumes can be provisioned. <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s can override the resource limits specified in a namespace class during namespace creation.<br>&nbsp;The resource limits of a namespace can be satisfied from capacity in one or more <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> zones. When creating a namespace, <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s can select which zones the namespace can use.&nbsp;Namespaces count towards the organization quota. The sum total of resource limits of all created namespaces cannot exceed the organization quota.How many projects and namespaces you create depends on your organization needs.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s: Multiple projects are used when isolation boundaries between project teams are required. Only project members can access deployments and resources available to a project. Fewer projects are desired when isolation requirements can be traded off for a simpler operating model.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s: Multiple namespaces are used when strict resource limits are needed for each application. Namespaces are logical constructs that can be used to define application boundaries. Each application can be deployed on a namespace with prescribed resource limits for CPU, memory, and storage. For instance, a group of VMs and <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters that make up an application can be logically grouped together in a namespace.
<br><a data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">User Roles</a> is the next logical place to explore after here. Or you can check out <a data-href="Organization Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/project-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/Project Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 22:32:14 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Placement]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="workload-placement-1545135394507.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png" target="_self"><br>Workload Placement in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is the coordinated outcome of automation intent, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere" data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> scheduling (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>), networking availability (<a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>), storage policy (<a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>), and runtime mobility (<a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>).<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> is the mechanism, not the decision-maker.Workload Placement is a pipeline, not a switch—shaken, but not stirred:Intent → Eligibility → Initial Placement → Continuous Optimization → Recovery
Each stage is owned by a different layer of VCF.Answers: “what am I allowed to run, and where?”
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (formerly Aria Automation) The user requests a workload (VM, Kubernetes cluster, pod)
Constraints are applied: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
Quotas and approvals
<br>Target workload <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">domain</a> / cluster
Storage policy
Network intent There is no vMotion here: This is just pre-placement filtering.Answers: “Which clusters can even accept this?”
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> Cluster compatibility
HA admission control
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> limits
Storage policy compatibility
<br><a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> &amp; transport availability
Anything that fails here is never considered for placement.<br>This is where <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> takes the helm.
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> Chooses the best host at power-on time
Considers: CPU &amp; memory headroom
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vNUMA" data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NUMA</a> alignment
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> shares
Affinity / anti-affinity rules This happens before the VM ever runs.
This is placement — not vMotion.
<br>This is where <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> appears.
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> + <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> Load imbalance
Hotspots
Policy drift
Host entering maintenance
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> is:
How VMs move
NOT *why they move HA Host fails
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> re-places VMs on surviving hosts
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> may later rebalance
This is reactive placement, NOT optimization.<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> matters more than what’s seen on the surface.
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> / <a data-href="VCF Edge" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Edge</a>
Placement is invalid if:
Segment is not available on target host
Transport zone mismatch
Edge capacity insufficient (north–south)
Networking can veto otherwise valid placements.<br>Especially for Kubernetes (<a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>)
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> (for K8s)
Placement requires:
Policy-compatible datastore
Accessibility from host
Topology alignment (for StatefulSets, etc.)
For Kubernetes:
PVC → StorageClass → Storage Policy
<br><a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> enforces this during placement
So things are a tad bit more involved than “VCF places workloads using vMotion”.VCF places workloads using DRS decisions; vMotion is only the transport.
Workload placement in VCF is layered and collaborative
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> decides, <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> moves
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> re-places after failure
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> and storage can block or shape placement
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> governs who can ask for what
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/workload-placement.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Capacity and Cost Optimization/Workload Placement.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 21:56:06 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Edge]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vcf=edge=AD_4nXcv6rA 1.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf=edge=ad_4nxcv6ra-1.webp" target="_self"><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, VCF Edge refers to the extension of the VCF platform model to edge locations—sites that are geographically distributed, resource-constrained, and often operationally remote, but still need enterprise-grade consistency, security, and lifecycle management.In short:
VCF Edge brings “the VCF way” to thousands of small, remote sites—without turning each site into a snowflake.
<br><img alt="VCF-Edge-1 1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-edge-1-1.png" target="_self">Edge sites typically have constraints that central data centers do not:
Small host counts (often 2–4 nodes)
Limited on-site staff (or none)
Intermittent or high-latency connectivity (an edge-site not having Internet connectivity for a month is not uncommon)
Strict uptime requirements
Local data-residency or latency needs
VCF Edge is about operating under those constraints without abandoning platform discipline.However, even at the edge, the core VCF principles remain:
Centralized lifecycle control
Validated configurations
Strong isolation and security
Declarative operations
Consistent operational model
What changes is scale, footprint, and placement—not the philosophy.Central / Regional Site
├── Management Domain (SDDC Manager, vCenter, NSX)
├── Automation &amp; Ops
│
└── Edge Sites (many) ├── Small Workload Domain (or cluster) ├── Local workloads (VMs / K8s) ├── Local networking &amp; security └── Centrally managed lifecycle
So:
While, management stays centralized
execution happens at the edge
Depending on use case:
Telco workloads (RAN, core, MEC)
Retail store systems
Factory / OT workloads
Branch office services
Latency-sensitive apps
These workloads:
Run locally
Are managed remotely
Must survive site isolation <br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> governs lifecycle
Platform admins operate from a hub
Edge sites follow validated patterns Workloads keep running if disconnected
Local failover is possible
Management resumes when connectivity returns
This balance is critical for an edge site.VCF Edge supports:
Single-tenant edge (most common)
Logical multi-tenancy via: <br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="NSX Segment" data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segmentation</a> But:
Physical isolation per tenant is less common at edge
Operational simplicity is prioritized
Edge is where: Hyperscalers struggle with footprint and latency Enterprises need consistency across thousands of sites Telco and regulated industries dominate Unlike a traditional cloud or data center (where workloads are centralized to regions), edge is decentralized, and geographically spread. This is topologically opposite to a typical cloud deployment. <br>
<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Core</a> → Headquarters data center VCF Edge → Branch offices or cell sites (for Telco) <br>
<a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> → Central IT command center Edge clusters → Remote, self-sufficient execution zones <br>Essentially, the same VCF <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> rules apply, but with different topological constraints, different connectivity requirements, at a smaller, but vastly-distributed scale.
VCF Edge extends VCF to remote, constrained sites
Management remains centralized
Workloads run locally and survive disconnection
Edge is a pattern, not a separate product
It prioritizes consistency over customization
<br>Looking at <a data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Domain</a>, and specifically <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>, and <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> could be the next venue to explore from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Edge.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 21:06:11 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf" length="0" type="false"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload-Domain]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/Workload-Domain.jpg</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 21:05:14 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Private Cloud]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>A VCF Private Cloud is the highest level of management and consumption for the underlying <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> resources. A VCF Private Cloud can contain one or more VCF Fleets.<br>VCF Private Cloud is the customer-operated private cloud deployment model built on <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>
It delivers cloud-like operations, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, and lifecycle management on customer-owned or customer-controlled infrastructure (on-prem or dedicated colocation).
VCF Private Cloud = “You run the cloud, using VMware’s cloud platform.”
VCF Private Cloud is opinionated and integrated:
<br>Single lifecycle authority (<a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>)
<br>Validated stack (<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>)
Declarative operations
Strong separation of platform vs tenant
Built-in multi-tenancy
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> → <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> automation
This is fundamentally different from “installing vSphere and calling it a cloud.”These components are installed, upgraded, and validated as one system.VCF Private Cloud is deliberately split:
Runs in the Management Domain / Management Cluster
Controls lifecycle, upgrades, topology <br>Used by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenants</a>
<br>Exposed via <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">policies</a>
<br>Runs workloads in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload (VI) Domains / Clusters</a>
This mirrors public cloud responsibility boundaries.VCF Private Cloud supports enterprise-grade multi-tenancy:
<br>
<a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s → business tenants <br>
<a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s → sub-tenants (teams, environments) <br>
<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a> / <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s → execution boundaries <br>
<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="NSX Segment" data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segmentation</a> → network isolation <br>
<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Domains</a> / clusters → failure &amp; lifecycle isolation <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenancy</a> is logical and policy-driven, not per-cluster by default.VCF Private Cloud can be deployed on:
On-premises data centers
Dedicated colocation
Partner-hosted environments
<br>What matters is control, not location. <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for control and predictability, not infinite elasticity:
VCF Private Cloud ≈ “like AWS, but you run AWS yourself”
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> ≈ Cloud provider internal control plane
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s ≈ Accounts and subscriptions
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>s ≈ Capacity pools VCF Private Cloud is customer-operated cloud infrastructure
<br>Built on <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>
Strong separation of platform vs tenant
<br>Enterprise-grade <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a> and lifecycle
Cloud outcomes without giving up control
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>, as they are important topology elements in VCF Private Cloud.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Private Cloud.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 20:58:37 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Management Components]]></title><description><![CDATA[VCF management components are the platform control-plane services responsible for lifecycle management, networking, security, observability, and automation of the entire VCF instance, and are deployed exclusively in the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>.<br>Here are the management components of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> Inventory
Cluster logic
Resource scheduling
API surface for everything else <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts (management cluster) Run the Management VMs
Often capacity-isolated <br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (<a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> + control plane) Networking for management workloads
Overlay, routing, firewalling
Required even if workload domains use different topologies <br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Lifecycle orchestration
Domain creation
Upgrade coordination
Configuration drift control These are management components even though they feel “optional”:
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> (formerly vRealize / Aria Operations) Telemetry ingestion
Capacity planning
Health modeling
Alert correlation VCF Operations for Logs (if deployed) Centralized logging
Audit &amp; forensic workflows <br>These belong in the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> because:
They observe everything
They are trusted with cross-domain data
They are not tenant-scoped <br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (formerly vRealize / Aria Automation) <br>Tenant abstraction (<a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>)
Approval flows
Policy enforcement
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a> execution
Self-service APIs Even though it models consumer behavior, it is still a management component because:
It enforces platform policy
It brokers infrastructure authority
It is not itself a tenant workload
Often overlooked, but these are part of the management plane too:
Identity Integration AD / LDAP
<br>OIDC (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vIDB</a>, external IdP) Certificates Internal PKI
Trust distribution Secrets and credentials Platform credentials
Not tenant secrets These may not be a single product, but they are a functional plane of the management domain.A good litmus test:
If a tenant can delete it without breaking the cloud, it is not a management component.
<br>Other topological constructs such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>, <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Edge" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Edge</a> are all good options to dive from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-management-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Management Components.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 20:57:17 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Big Picture]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vcf-overview.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" target="_self"><br>VMware Cloud Foundation (VCF) is a unified platform to design, plan, deploy, and manage your <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> by using <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">automation</a> capabilities.That is one of the core tenents of VCF, and thus, it requires clarification before anything else.In VCF-speak, the phrase “a workload is a workload” is not a tautology—it’s a deliberate abstraction boundary.It means that VCF intentionally collapses many very different execution models into a single management concept, and refuses to care about their internal form unless it must.Below is the precise meaning, layered from philosophy, to architecture, to consequences.From VCF’s point of view, a workload is simply “something that consumes resources and is governed by policy.”It is not:
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>
a Container
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod VM</a>
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> pod
<br>a <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>
a Helm release
Those are implementation details.VCF asks only:
Where does it run?
Who owns it?
What resources does it consume?
What policies apply?
What lifecycle rules govern it?
If those questions can be answered, VCF is satisfied.VCF exists above:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Kubernetes
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s
Containers
If VCF tried to manage each kind of workload differently, it would:
explode in complexity
duplicate logic
couple business policy to runtime mechanics
So instead, VCF defines:
Workload = Policy + Placement + Lifecycle + Resources
Everything else is delegated downward.All of the following are equally valid workloads in VCF:VCF deliberately does not rank or privilege any of these.In VCF, a workload is anything that consumes platform resources and is subject to platform policy—its internal shape is intentionally irrelevant.
VCF intentionally erases runtime distinctions
Governance &gt; implementation
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> is the abstraction bridge
If two things consume resources and obey policy, VCF treats them identically
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> makes it possible.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> converts:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pods</a> to lightweight VMs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> objects to vSphere-managed entities
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a> to policy and tenancy units From below, everything is Kubernetes.
<br>From above, everything is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> resources. VCF sits above Supervisor, so it sees:
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a>
Quotas
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policies</a>
The kind or form of the workload becomes irrelevant.VCF does not care:
whether the workload uses containerd or not
<br>whether it’s a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">PodVM</a> or classic VM
whether it runs Go, Java, or Bash
whether it was deployed via Helm, kubectl, or Terraform
