<br>VCF APIs abstract platform intent (*<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">domains</a>, lifecycle, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenancy</a>**), not raw hypervisor knobs.SDDC Manager REST APIs expose everything SDDC Manager knows and controls:
Bring-up and expansion
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> lifecycle
Host add/remove
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cluster creation</a>
End-to-end upgrades (LCM)
Inventory, versions, and health
These APIs are the authoritative way to automate VCF without breaking supportability.
If it changes VCF topology or lifecycle, it goes through SDDC Manager APIs. CI/CD pipelines
Infrastructure-as-Code tools
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> automation frameworks
Internal platforms and runbooks
<br>These are about consumption and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.APIs for tenant-facing operations such as:
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Policies and approvals
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s / templates
Workload provisioning (VMs, Kubernetes-backed services)
These APIs sit closer to business intent than infrastructure detail.
SDDC Manager APIs → Build and maintain the cloud
VCF Automation APIs → Consume the cloud
These are both human and also script friendly.Used for:
Diagnostics
Operational workflows
Automation-friendly scripting
Break-glass scenarios
It is a thin wrapper over SDDC Manager APIs, with guardrails.This is:
A faster iteration than REST during ops
An easier integration into shell scripts
Provides consistent auth and context handling
CLIs are not separate systems — they are API clients.These are language bindings.Where available, VMware/Broadcom provides SDKs that wrap REST APIs in native language constructs:
Object models
Typed requests/responses
Auth helpers
Pagination, retries, error handling
These SDKs are ideal when:
You are building a platform or product
You need maintainable, testable code
Shell scripts are no longer enough
They do not:
<br>Replace <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> or <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> APIs
Provide low-level tuning knobs
Allow unsupported lifecycle paths
Let you bypass validation logic
<br>This is by design. <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for predictability and supportability over raw flexibility.
Git declares desired domains / versions
Pipeline calls SDDC Manager APIs
Platform converges safely Internal UI talks to VCF Automation APIs
End users never see infrastructure details Health checks
Controlled upgrades
Capacity expansion
All API-driven, no UI clicks.
VCF SDK APIs are the supported automation surface
SDDC Manager APIs control lifecycle and topology
VCF Automation APIs control consumption and governance
CLIs are just API clients
Using these APIs preserves VCF invariants and supportability
<br>Since it’s related to APIs, you might want to check out what a <a data-href="Gated SDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/gated-sdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Gated SDK</a> is.VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs<br><img alt="vcf-installer-Image-0.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp" target="_self"><br>VCF Installer is the one-time (or rare-use) bootstrap and bring-up tool for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>VCF Installer’s sole purpose is to stand up the very first VCF environment and hand control over to <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.<br>If <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> is the factory control system, VCF Installer is the factory construction crew that builds the factory in the first place.<br><img alt="vcf-installer-image-134.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-134.webp" target="_self">VCF Installer exists to answer a very specific question:
“Given raw hardware, how do I get to a fully functional VCF Management Domain with SDDC Manager running?”
Once that answer is executed successfully, VCF Installer is done.VCF Installer is responsible for:
Validating hardware readiness
Validating network configuration
Validating DNS / NTP / IPAM
Validating credentials and certificates
Orchestrating the initial deployment of: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> on hosts
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> components <br>This is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> only work.Before anything is deployed, VCF Installer runs extensive prechecks, including:
Hardware compatibility (HCL alignment)
Network reachability
MTU consistency
IP pool correctness
Time synchronization
DNS forward/reverse lookup
Credential access
Think of it as a fail-fast safety gate: Better to stop early than build a broken cloud.VCF Installer typically operates with:
Structured input (JSON / guided wizard)
Explicit topology definitions
Explicit IP assignments
You declare what you want, and the installer executes a deterministic build.There is no concept of “incremental evolution” here: That belongs to SDDC Manager.It is not:
A lifecycle manager
A long-running control plane
A tenant or consumption interface
A policy engine
An operations tool
After bring-up:
It is not used daily
It does not manage upgrades
It does not manage workload domains
<br>Those responsibilities move entirely to the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.Once installation completes:
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> becomes the authoritative owner
VCF Installer steps out of the picture
You can think of it as:
VCF Installer creates SDDC Manager; SDDC Manager creates and manages everything else.
A natural question is: “Why not just use SDDC Manager from the start?”Because:
SDDC Manager itself must be deployed
That deployment requires validated sequencing
That sequencing must run before SDDC Manager exists
VCF Installer solves this bootstrapping paradox.
VCF Installer → kubeadm init
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> → Kubernetes control plane (after init)
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> → Higher-level UX / APIs for consumers
You don’t run kubeadm init every day, and you don’t run VCF Installer every day either.
VCF Installer is a Day-0 tool
It bootstraps the Management Domain
<br>It deploys the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
It performs strict prechecks and validation
After success, it is effectively retired
<br>Why not look into <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a>?VCF InstallerVCF Operations OrchestratorVCF Operations OrchestratorSupervisor ClusterSupervisor Cluster]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/the-big-picture.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">The Big Picture.canvas</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 20:56:09 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF-Edge-1 1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-edge-1-1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-edge-1-1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/VCF-Edge-1 1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 08:54:20 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf" length="0" type="false"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[volkan-sm]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan-sm.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan-sm.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/volkan-sm.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 19:27:17 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan-sm.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan-sm.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[volkan]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/volkan.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 19:23:37 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/volkan.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Cloud]]></title><description><![CDATA[VMware Cloud is the umbrella brand and strategy for VMware’s cloud-delivered offerings, covering public cloud, hybrid cloud, and managed private cloud use cases.It is not a single product.Think of VMware Cloud as the distribution and consumption model, while <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> (VCF) is the core platform architecture underneath many of those offerings.
VMware Cloud is how VMware delivers and operates VMware platforms as a service across public, private, and hybrid clouds.
VCF is often the engine; VMware Cloud is the service wrapper.Examples include:
VMware Cloud on AWS
VMware Cloud on Azure
VMware Cloud on Google Cloud
VMware Cloud on OCI
These provide:
Native VMware stacks
Operated as managed services
Tight integration with hyperscaler services
From the customer’s point of view:
“I get vSphere/NSX/vSAN without running the platform myself.”
This is where things look very similar to VCF:
VMware (or a partner) runs VCF on your behalf
Can be hosted: On your premises
In a partner data center You consume it as a cloud service
Regardless of flavor, VMware Cloud aims to deliver:
Consistent VMware operational model
Reduced platform operational burden
Predictable lifecycle management
Enterprise-grade security and compliance
Hybrid portability (move workloads across clouds)
It is not:
A replacement for Kubernetes-native clouds
A single UI or API
A single SKU
Always customer-operated
It is a portfolio strategy, not a monolith.VMware Cloud = “VMware runs it for you”
VCF = “The platform being run”
vSphere/NSX = “The building blocks”
Or in cloud terms:
VMware Cloud ≈ AWS Managed Services
VCF ≈ AWS internal platform (you don’t see it directly)
vSphere/NSX ≈ EC2 / VPC equivalents Customers want cloud economics
But need enterprise control
And want to reuse VMware skills and tooling
VMware Cloud is VMware’s answer to:
“Give me cloud without forcing me to rewrite everything.” VMware Cloud is a service model, not a product
It spans public, private, and hybrid clouds
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is often the underlying platform
VMware Cloud reduces operational responsibility
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="VMware Validated Solutions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Validated Solutions</a> too.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-cloud/vmware-cloud.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/VMware Cloud/VMware Cloud.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 19:12:38 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Day 2 Tasks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="day-n-tasks.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation Day 2 tasks begin once real workloads exist.
This is where theory meets entropy: failures happen, usage grows, humans make mistakes, and the platform must keep working anyway.If:
Day 0 pours the concrete
Day 1 frames the building
Day 2 is living in it for years
Or:
Day 0 → Existence
Day 1 → Enablement
Day 2 → Sustainment
Day 2 is continuous, not a phase you “finish”.This is the obvious part—but it’s only the surface.
Deploy workloads (VMs, Pods, clusters)
Scale up/down
Start / stop / suspend
Migrate workloads
Retire workloads
Day 2 starts the feedback loop.
Platform health monitoring
Workload health monitoring
Capacity tracking
Performance baselines
Alert tuning (noise reduction)
Bad alerts = ignored alerts = outages.The real test of architecture.
Host failures
Network partitions
Storage degradation
Control plane issues
Application outages
Includes:
[HA] / [DRS] behavior
Failover validation
Backup &amp; restore
DR testing
<br>If this fails, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 0</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 1</a> didn’t matter.Security shifts from design to enforcement.
Certificate rotation
Secret rotation
Credential revocation
Firewall rule changes
Vulnerability remediation
Audit and compliance reporting
One of VCF’s core promises.
[] patching
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> upgrades
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> upgrades
Kubernetes version upgrades
Firmware alignment (BOM compliance)
All while:
Workloads are running
SLAs are enforced
This is why VCF is opinionated.Reality: resources are finite.
Capacity planning
Quota adjustments
Overcommit tuning
Chargeback / showback
Cluster expansion
This is where finance meets engineering.Day 1 defines policies.
Day 2 fights drift.
Detect misconfigurations
Enforce standards
Handle exceptions
Reconcile “special cases”
Without this, entropy wins.Day 2 success is measured socially, not technically.
Self-service reliability
Automation success rates
Time-to-resource
Support ticket volume
Developer trust
A stable platform feels boring. That’s success.Day 2 never freezes architecture.
Introduce new workload types
Add regions / clusters
Enable new services
Deprecate old patterns
VCF must evolve without reset.
VCF Day 2 = continuous operations
Includes incidents, upgrades, security, scale
<br>Validates <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 0</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 1</a> decisions
Workload type becomes irrelevant
Boring Day 2 is the highest compliment
<br>Why not explore <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a> or <a data-href="VCF Installer" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Installer</a> as platform enablers.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Day-N Operations/VCF Day 2 Tasks.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 19:07:23 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cloud Services Console]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" target="_self">Cloud Services Console is VMware’s SaaS control plane for identity, organizations, subscriptions, and service access across VMware cloud offerings.<br>If <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> answers “what is running?”, CSC answers:
“Who are you, what are you entitled to, and which VMware services can you access?”
<br><img alt="csc-featured-image.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-featured-image.png" target="_self">VMware SaaS Layer
└── Cloud Services Console (CSC) ├── Identity and Org management ├── Subscriptions &amp; entitlements └── Access to VMware cloud services On-prem / Private Cloud
└── VCF ├── vSphere / NSX / vSAN └── SDDC Manager
CSC:
Runs as: VMware-hosted SaaS
Audience: Org owners, platform leads, service-provider admins
Does not touch datapaths or place workloads Defines Organizations
Manages users, roles, and access
Integrates with enterprise IdPs (SSO)
<br>This is business identity, not <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> RBAC.
Shows what your org is entitled to: VCF subscriptions
Optional VMware services Central place to view contracts → services
CSC does not meter usage—that’s elsewhere.From CSC you access:
Support portals
VMware cloud SaaS
Management consoles (where applicable)
CSC is the front door, not the engine room.CSC ≠ BSC
CSC is VMware-global; BSC is VCF-specific.
CSC knows about your subscriptions
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> consumes those entitlements
CSC does not: Provision domains
Run LCM
Enforce quotas
Observe performance <br>That work stays on-prem with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> components.
Not part of the VCF runtime
Not an ops or automation tool
Not a billing/metering engine
Not a tenant boundary for workloads
If VCF is:
“Your private cloud platform”
Then CSC is:
“Your VMware account and service access hub” Cloud Services Console = SaaS identity and entitlement layer
Global across VMware services
<br>Adjacent to <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, not embedded in it
<br>Often confused with <a data-href="VCF Business Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Business Services Console</a>—they serve different roles
Why not check out Day-N Operations:
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 0 Tasks</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/cloud-services-console.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Managing the Cloud/Cloud Services Console.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:57:27 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[csc-featured-image]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-featured-image.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-featured-image.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/csc-featured-image.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:49:21 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-featured-image.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-featured-image.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:49:21 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> <a data-href="workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workflow</a>s run according to a logical flow of events.When you run a workflow, each schema element in the workflow runs according to the following sequence.
The workflow binds the workflow token variables and input parameters to the input parameters of the schema element.
The schema element runs.
The output parameters of the schema element are copied to the workflow token variables and workflow output parameters.
The workflow token variables and workflow output parameters are stored in the database.
The next schema element starts running.
This sequence repeats for each schema element until the end of the workflow.<br>When a workflow runs, each schema element is a check point. After each schema element runs,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> stores workflow token variables in the database, and the next schema element starts running.If the workflow stops unexpectedly, the next time the Orchestrator Server restarts, the currently active schema element runs again, and the workflow continues from the start of the schema element that was running when the interruption occurred.<br>That being said,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> does not implement transaction management or a rollback function.The workflow ends if the current active schema element is an end element.After the workflow reaches an end element, other workflows or applications can use the output parameters of the workflow.<br>You might like to check out <a data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fleet Management</a> or <a data-href="VMware Data Services Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-data-services-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Data Services Manager</a>, or <a data-href="VMware Skyline" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-skyline.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Skyline</a> as they tangentially relate to workflows.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:47:17 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Skyline]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="skyline-advisor-Skyline-Screenshot.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png" target="_self">VMware Skyline is a proactive support and health intelligence service that continuously analyzes your VMware environment and surfaces:
Configuration risks
Known issues
Upgrade blockers
Security advisories
Best-practice deviations
It answers:
“What is likely to break, and what should I fix before it does?”
<br><img alt="skyline-f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.webp" target="_self">VCF Environment
├── vCenter / ESXi
├── NSX
├── vSAN
├── SDDC Manager
│
└── Skyline ├── Telemetry collection ├── Health &amp; risk analysis └── Proactive recommendations Skyline observes the fleet — it does not control it.
Skyline is VCF-adjacent, not VCF-core.<br><img alt="skyline-ClusterHealth-Figure-01.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-clusterhealth-figure-01.png" target="_self">In VCF:
Skyline supports: <br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Skyline findings are especially valuable for: LCM readiness
Upgrade prechecks
Fleet hygiene Skyline correlates your environment against:
Known VMware issues
Field advisories
Support KB patterns
This is knowledge you cannot replicate locally.Before you run LCM in VCF:
Skyline can flag: Unsupported configs
Known bad upgrade paths
Latent drift issues You can think of it as:
“Support’s brain looking at your fleet before you upgrade.”
Skyline shines when:
<br>You have many <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">domains</a>
<br>You have many <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenters</a>
You want a single risk posture view
<br>This aligns naturally with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Fleet Deployment" data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet management</a>.Skyline is insight, not control.Skyline is the supportability lens.If SDDC Manager is:
“The mechanic that performs maintenance”
Then Skyline is:
“The service engineer who tells you what will fail next month.”
VMware Skyline
Provides proactive, VCF-global intelligence
Is best viewed as a support copilot for VCF fleets
Is especially valuable for LCM and large environments
<br><a data-href="VMware Data Services Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-data-services-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Data Services Manager</a> and <a data-href="Cloud Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/cloud-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services Console</a> are other adjacent tools that you might want to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-skyline.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Managing the Cloud/VMware Skyline.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:43:16 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[skyline-advisor-Skyline-Screenshot]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/skyline-advisor-Skyline-Screenshot.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:35:32 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[skyline-ClusterHealth-Figure-01]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-clusterhealth-figure-01.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-clusterhealth-figure-01.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/skyline-ClusterHealth-Figure-01.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:35:32 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-clusterhealth-figure-01.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-clusterhealth-figure-01.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[SDDC Manager]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" target="_self"><br>SDDC Manager is the foundational lifecycle-management and orchestration engine of <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.It is responsible for deploying, configuring, upgrading, and maintaining the entire VCF stack as a single, validated system rather than as independent products.<br><img alt="sddc-manager-8f57b8cd-3a43-48cc-98dc-b9cdf6132d20.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-8f57b8cd-3a43-48cc-98dc-b9cdf6132d20.webp" target="_self">If you think of VCF as a factory-built private cloud, SDDC Manager is the factory control system that ensures every component is installed correctly, stays in a supported state, and evolves safely over time.<br><img alt="sddc-manager-1.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-1.webp" target="_self"><br>
UI Deprecation Warning
In VCF 9.0+, Broadcom’s docs state that <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/building-your-private-cloud-infrastructure/sddc-manager-workflows.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com" rel="noopener nofollow" class="external-link is-unresolved" title="SDDC Manager Workflows in VMware Cloud Foundation 9.0" href="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/building-your-private-cloud-infrastructure/sddc-manager-workflows.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_self">SDDC Manager UI is being deprecated</a> and that SDDC Manager workflows can now be found in VCF Operations and vSphere Client—so many “platform lifecycle” workflows show up there now. ([
This is SDDC Manager’s primary job.SDDC Manager performs end-to-end lifecycle operations across the VCF stack:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> (hypervisor)
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
Other optional components.
Key characteristics:
Uses validated upgrade bundles
Enforces component compatibility
Executes sequenced, automated upgrades
Provides rollback and precheck logic
This is not just patching: It is system-level lifecycle orchestration.SDDC Manager is responsible for:
Initial VCF bring-up
Creating: Management Domain
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VI (Workload) Domains</a> Adding: Hosts
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Clusters</a>
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s Ensuring: Correct networking
Correct certificate trust
Correct inventory alignment Without SDDC Manager, you do not have VCF: That simple!—You will only have a loosely assembled VMware products.SDDC Manager acts as the system-of-record for:
What components exist
Their versions
Their relationships
Their lifecycle state
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> manages virtualization.
SDDC Manager manages the cloud system itself.SDDC Manager enforces:
Supported topologies
Supported versions
Supported upgrade paths
If you try to:
Upgrade NSX independently
Modify components outside supported flows
You risk breaking VCF supportability.
<br>This is intentional: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> favors predictability over freedom.It is not:
A tenant portal
A developer platform
A policy engine
A workload orchestrator
A replacement for vCenter, NSX Manager, or Kubernetes APIs
<br>Those functions live elsewhere (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, etc.).
SDDC Manager manages the cloud itself; everything else manages what runs inside that cloud.
Without SDDC Manager:
Enterprises would manually assemble components
Version skew would be common
Upgrades would be risky and expensive
Supportability would collapse
With SDDC Manager:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> becomes repeatable
Lifecycle becomes deterministic
VMware/Broadcom can guarantee outcomes
This is why SDDC Manager is non-optional in VCF.
SDDC Manager is the backbone of VCF
It owns lifecycle, topology, and compatibility
It enforces validated, supported states
It is infrastructure-centric, not tenant-centric
Without it, VCF does not exist as a product
<br>Since we are onto management and provisioning, <a data-href="VCF Installer" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Installer</a> can be the next topic to dive into.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/SDDC Manager/SDDC Manager.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:25:58 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vmotion_migration_process]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 18:09:15 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Gated SDK]]></title><description><![CDATA[VCF Gated SDK is a RESTful SDK around everything VCF.The VCF Gated SDK refers to the VMware Cloud Foundation Software Development Kit that is not publicly downloadable without authentication: You need to be an authorized VMware/Broadcom customer or partner to access it.So, “Gated” here means governed access, not technical limitation.In practice, “gated” means:
You must log in to the Broadcom Developer Portal with valid credentials.
Access is typically tied to an active support contract or partner agreement.
The SDK download link is hidden until your account is verified for entitlement.
VCF Gated SDK provides Java and Python libraries, API bindings, utilities, and sample code to automate and integrate with <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.
Contains proprietary VMware/Broadcom code.
Ensures only licensed customers/partners can use it.
Helps control distribution of sensitive API bindings and internal tooling.
VCF is not a generic API platform; it is a validated system.
Some APIs:
Control core lifecycle
Mutate global topology
Bypass normal UI guardrails
Can easily create unsupported states
Exposing these APIs broadly would:
Fragment platform behavior
Break upgrade guarantees
Explode support matrices
So VMware/Broadcom chooses controlled exposure instead of full openness.Gated SDKs often include APIs that:
Drive SDDC Manager internal workflows
Orchestrate LCM sequencing
Mutate domain-level state machines
Access pre-GA or evolving models
Bypass tenant-safe abstractions
These are platform-builder APIs, not tenant or end-user APIs.A Gated SDK usually implies one or more of the following:
Explicit enablement flag
Contractual agreement
Limited documentation access
No backward-compatibility guarantees
Direct escalation path to engineering
Strong expectations of platform literacy
You are expected to know what you are doing.A Gated SDK is official, but not democratized.It is not:
Unsupported
A hack
A private backdoor
A “use at your own risk” API
It is supported; but with conditions.If you see something described as a Gated SDK, it usually signals:
“This is powerful”
“This can break invariants”
“This is for platform-level integration”
“You need approval and discipline”
In other words:
This is not a convenience API — it is a responsibility API. A Gated SDK is an official but restricted VCF SDK
It protects lifecycle safety and supportability
It is intended for platform builders, not tenants
Access implies higher expectations and accountability
It exists to balance power vs stability
<br>You might want to explore <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Concepts" data-href="Concepts" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/concepts.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">other core VCF concepts</a> from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/gated-sdk.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/Gated SDK.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 17:42:58 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Installer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vcf-installer-Image-0.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp" target="_self"><br>VCF Installer is the one-time (or rare-use) bootstrap and bring-up tool for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>VCF Installer’s sole purpose is to stand up the very first VCF environment and hand control over to <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.<br>If <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> is the factory control system, VCF Installer is the factory construction crew that builds the factory in the first place.<br><img alt="vcf-installer-image-134.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-134.webp" target="_self">VCF Installer exists to answer a very specific question:
“Given raw hardware, how do I get to a fully functional VCF Management Domain with SDDC Manager running?”
Once that answer is executed successfully, VCF Installer is done.VCF Installer is responsible for:
Validating hardware readiness
Validating network configuration
Validating DNS / NTP / IPAM
Validating credentials and certificates
Orchestrating the initial deployment of: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> on hosts
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> components <br>This is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> only work.Before anything is deployed, VCF Installer runs extensive prechecks, including:
Hardware compatibility (HCL alignment)
Network reachability
MTU consistency
IP pool correctness
Time synchronization
DNS forward/reverse lookup
Credential access
Think of it as a fail-fast safety gate: Better to stop early than build a broken cloud.VCF Installer typically operates with:
Structured input (JSON / guided wizard)
Explicit topology definitions
Explicit IP assignments
You declare what you want, and the installer executes a deterministic build.There is no concept of “incremental evolution” here: That belongs to SDDC Manager.It is not:
A lifecycle manager
A long-running control plane
A tenant or consumption interface
A policy engine
An operations tool
After bring-up:
It is not used daily
It does not manage upgrades
It does not manage workload domains
<br>Those responsibilities move entirely to the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.Once installation completes:
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> becomes the authoritative owner
VCF Installer steps out of the picture
You can think of it as:
VCF Installer creates SDDC Manager; SDDC Manager creates and manages everything else.
A natural question is: “Why not just use SDDC Manager from the start?”Because:
SDDC Manager itself must be deployed
That deployment requires validated sequencing
That sequencing must run before SDDC Manager exists
VCF Installer solves this bootstrapping paradox.
VCF Installer → kubeadm init
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> → Kubernetes control plane (after init)
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> → Higher-level UX / APIs for consumers
You don’t run kubeadm init every day, and you don’t run VCF Installer every day either.
VCF Installer is a Day-0 tool
It bootstraps the Management Domain
<br>It deploys the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
It performs strict prechecks and validation
After success, it is effectively retired
<br>Why not look into <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a>?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/VCF Installer/VCF Installer.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 17:35:25 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Data Services Manager]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="dsm-2840bcee-02a4-4da0-a4de-7017c7f33fb7.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/dsm-2840bcee-02a4-4da0-a4de-7017c7f33fb7.original.png" target="_self">VMware Data Services Manager (DSM) is a Database-as-a-Service (DBaaS) control plane that lets platform teams offer databases as a managed service on top of VCF infrastructure—while keeping infrastructure, security, and lifecycle control centralized.<br><img alt="dsm_deploy_small.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/dsm_deploy_small.webp" target="_self">DSM answers:
“How do we provide self-service databases without giving users raw VM access?”
VCF
├── vSphere / vSAN / NSX
├── SDDC Manager (infra lifecycle)
│
└── VMware Data Services Manager ├── Control Plane (policies, APIs, UI) └── Data Plane └── Database VMs (Postgres, MySQL, etc.)
DSM:
Runs on: VCF infrastructure
<br>Consumes: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, storage policies
Exposes: A database service interface to users
DSM is above infrastructure, below applications.
Provision databases in minutes
Automated: Day-0 setup
Day-1 operations
Day-2 patching and upgrades Consistent configurations every time
No more hand-built “special” DB VMs.
Platform team controls: VM templates
>>>>>>> c0778dc (new article)
Storage policies
Pod security boundaries
Runtime blast radius
This is where:
Kubernetes says “no”
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> enforces limits
Workloads are actually prevented from crossing boundaries Namespace = hard enforcement boundary
<br>Organizations define intent and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.An Organization:
Defines who is allowed to create tenants
Defines how many tenants
Defines under which rules
Defines approval and lifecycle policies
It’s closer to:
“Who is allowed to mint isolation boundaries?”
not:
“Where isolation happens.”
A single Organization can own:
<br>Multiple <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br>Each <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> can map to: <br>One <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>
Or several namespaces (depending on policy / model) Organization: Acme Corp
├── Project: Acme-Prod → ns-acme-prod
├── Project: Acme-Stage → ns-acme-stage
├── Project: Acme-Dev → ns-acme-dev
└── Project: Acme-Analytics → ns-acme-analytics
<br>Each <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace</a> is a real tenant boundary.But from a business standpoint:
Acme Corp is still one customer: One billing entity
One governance envelope
One policy domain This construct enables the following scenarios (which would have been impossible otherwise).Classic need:
Dev / Stage / Prod
Regulated vs non-regulated
Different trust zones
All under:
One contract
One identity plane
One catalog
Example:
Organization = “Platform Team”
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s = internal product teams
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s = per-team isolation
This would break if Organization == Namespace.Example:
Organization = External customer
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s = customer environments
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s = actual enforcement boundaries
Same model works for:
Internal IT
SaaS providers
Telco multi-tenant platforms
If something must be isolated, it must be isolated at the namespace level.Anything above that:
<br>Is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">governance</a>
Is visibility
Is policy
Is economy
Organizations define who may create tenants; namespaces are the tenants.Similar to:
AWS Account
Azure Subscription (with Management Groups layered above)
GCP Project (with Org/Folder hierarchy)
But in VCF, it’s explicitly framed as consumption-first, not infrastructure-first.
Separates consumers (e.g., companies, business units, external customers)
Enforces isolation in: Identity and Access
Visibility
Quotas and Limits
Chargeback / showback Organizations are where policies attach, such as:
Who can request what
Approval workflows
Budget limits
Lease durations
Allowed regions / environments
Allowed workload types (VM, Kubernetes, services)
These policies then flow downward.Everything inside an Organization is:
Visible only to that Organization (unless shared)
Governed consistently
This includes:
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s / templates
Catalog items
Requests
Cost views
Organization
├── Projects
│ ├── Policies
│ ├── Quotas
│ ├── Users / Groups
│ └── Workload requests
│
└── (maps indirectly to) └── Cloud Zones └── Infrastructure (vSphere, Supervisor, VKS, etc.) Infrastructure never belongs to an Organization
Consumption always does
Organization deliberately hides the infrastructure topology.From the Organization’s point of view:
<br>There is no <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
No cluster
No datastore
<br>No <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
There is only:
“What can I request?”
“What am I allowed to use?”
“Who approves this?”
“How much does it cost?”
This abstraction enables:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-tenant</a> platforms
Internal private clouds
Managed services
<br>SaaS-like experience on top of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
If Organization is “who is the customer”,<br>
then <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> is “what they are working on”.Typical mapping:Organization: Acme Corp
├── Project: Acme-Prod
├── Project: Acme-Stage
└── Project: Acme-Dev
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s:
Scope quotas
Bind to cloud zones
<br>Eventually map to <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s or runtime constructs
Organizations never do.
<br>Organization = <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> + visibility
It exists to model consumption, not execution
It owns policy, identity, and economics
It deliberately abstracts away infrastructure
<br>Everything technical happens below it, via <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s and Cloud Zones
<br>Check <a data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">IaaS</a> as a concept, or jump back to <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Consumption Abstractions/Organization.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 18:00:27 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-automation-capabilities-1.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-automation-capabilities-1.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>A vSphere Cluster (or Supervisor Cluster) is a logical grouping of ESX hosts that vCenter treats as a single resource pool and failure domain.
<br>It exists only in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts do not know they are “in a cluster”.
When you create a cluster in vCenter Server, you are telling:
“These ESX hosts agree to be scheduled, balanced, and failed over together.”This enables cluster-level logic, such as
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> (Distributed Resource Scheduler): <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> decides which host should run which VM.
When to rebalance the load. <br>Uses <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> to move VMs between hosts. <br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> (High Availability) Hosts run a lightweight HA agent.
If a host dies: Other hosts detect it
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> (or preconfigured HA logic) restarts VMs elsewhere. Shared resource abstraction Instead of thinking: Host A: 64 cores Host B: 64 cores vCenter presents Cluster: 128 cores <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> placement and limits are logical, not physical.A vSphere Cluster is not:Because from an operator’s perspective:
Hosts act like a pool
Failures are absorbed
Workloads move transparently
But architecturally:
The cluster is an illusion created by vCenter.
<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> is a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>-defined scheduling and failure domain over multiple <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts,[ Physical Servers ] ↓ ESX (many hosts) ↓ vCenter Server ↓ vSphere features and automation
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> is a vSphere Cluster that you might like to look at next, since it is a core component in everything <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Inventory Objects/vSphere Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:52:29 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Multi-Tenancy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Tenants in Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenants in Supervisor</a><br>In a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>-based platform, tenant isolation is realized through vSphere <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, which serve as the enforced execution boundary for workloads.<br>A single tenant may be associated with one or more <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, typically aligned to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s within an <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s provide hard isolation for compute, networking, storage, and identity, while <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> operates above this layer to deliver governance, policy enforcement, and self-service without weakening those isolation guarantees.<br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, multi-tenancy is the ability to securely host multiple independent consumers (tenants) on the same physical cloud infrastructure, while preserving isolation, governance, and lifecycle safety.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> does not implement multi-tenancy at a single layer.
It is layered, intentional, and asymmetric:Where it lives
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vsphere Cluster" data-href="vsphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Clusters</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>s
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
Who owns it
Platform / Cloud Admins
What it provides
Strong isolation
Failure-domain separation
Compliance boundaries
Important
Infrastructure tenancy is coarse-grained
Tenants do not see this layer “Which hardware and fabric does this workload ultimately land on?”
Where it lives
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Policies, quotas, approvals
<br>This layer is primarily owned by <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
Top-level tenant boundary
Represents a company, business unit, or customer
Defines identity, access, quotas, and governance
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Sub-tenants within an organization
Environment—or team—scoped (Dev / Test / Prod, Team A / Team B)
This is where true SaaS-like multi-tenancy exists.Depending on workload type:
vSphere constructs
Backed by resource pools, folders, NSX isolation <br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s
Mapped (typically) 1-to-1 with Projects
<br>Enforced by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> + Kubernetes RBAC
<br>
<a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are execution boundaries, not business tenants.
They implement tenancy; they are not the tenant itself.
VCF Infrastructure (shared)
│
├── Organization: Acme
│ ├── Project: Acme-Prod → Supervisor Namespace ns-acme-prod
│ ├── Project: Acme-Dev → Supervisor Namespace ns-acme-dev
│ └── Project: Acme-Test → Supervisor Namespace ns-acme-test
│
├── Organization: Globex
│ ├── Project: Globex-Prod → Supervisor Namespace ns-globex-prod
│ └── Project: Globex-Dev → Supervisor Namespace ns-globex-dev <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s = business tenants
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s = operational sub-tenants
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s = runtime enforcement
Isolation is compositional, not singular.
Strong isolation without hardware duplication
Clear separation of duties
Supports enterprise and service-provider use cases
Preserves lifecycle determinism Conceptually complex
Multiple abstractions to understand
Requires discipline in mapping orgs/projects/namespaces
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for large-scale, regulated environments, not minimalism.<br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, multi-tenancy does not mean soft separation within a shared runtime. Instead, it is defined by:
Explicit tenant boundaries
Platform-enforced isolation
No cross-tenant visibility or control
Lifecycle independence between tenants
This design prioritizes predictability, security, and supportability over maximal flexibility.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> intentionally separates administrative constructs from enforcement points.
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s define who can do what
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s define what can actually run and where
<br>While <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s are essential for governance and delegation, isolation becomes real only at the <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> layer.<br>At this boundary, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> enforces:
Resource allocation and limits
Network segmentation
Storage policy enforcement
Identity and access scoping
A common tenant layout in VCF looks like this:
<br>One <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> represents a tenant (i.e. Coca Cola)
<br>One or more <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> exists within that <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> (i.e. Dev / Staging / Prod)
<br>Each <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> (typically) maps to one <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> (but can map to more than one)
A tenant may therefore own multiple namespaces, often separated by: Environment (dev / stage / prod)
Application domain
Regulatory or compliance boundary This model allows tenants to scale horizontally without eroding isolation.<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> provides the control plane for consumption, not the enforcement layer.It is responsible for:
Self-service access to platform capabilities
<br><a data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy</a>-driven approvals and quotas
<br><a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> and auditability
Abstraction of underlying platform complexity
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>:
<br>Does not bypass <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> isolation
Does not weaken platform guardrails
Does not act as the isolation mechanism itself
It governs access to platform-enforced boundaries—it does not replace them.If we think in layers:
<br>Infrastructure layer: Hosts, clusters, networking, storage (operated outside <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
<br>Isolation layer: <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s (hard tenant boundary)
<br>Governance layer: <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s (who can consume what)
<br>Workload layer: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMs</a>, Kubernetes clusters, and services
Multi-tenancy in VCF emerges from the composition of these layers, not from any single construct.
Multi-tenancy in VCF is layered <br>This layered design is foundational to <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>’s security and supportability This design balances power, safety, and scale <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s define business tenancy <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s provide governance, not isolation <br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s enforce runtime isolation Supervisor Namespaces are the hard isolation boundary in VCF
Tenants may span multiple namespaces <br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s protect lifecycle and failure domains
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> governs consumption without compromising isolation
<br>From here, <a data-href="Administrative Roles in VCF" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/administrative-roles-in-vcf.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Administrative Roles in VCF</a> would be a next complementary concept to check out.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Multi-Tenancy.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:47:57 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[IaaS]]></title><description><![CDATA[IaaS (infrastructure as a service) is a cloud computing model where you rent fundamental IT infrastructure—instead of owning and managing physical hardware.IaaS provides fundamental computing resources where the consumer can deploy and run arbitrary software, including operating systems and applications.In plain terms:
IaaS = someone else runs the data center; you control the machines.
The cloud provider gives you raw building blocks:
Compute → virtual machines (VMs)
Storage → block, object, file storage
Networking → virtual networks, IPs, load balancers, firewalls
You decide:
Which OS to run
How to configure the machine
What software to install
How to secure and scale it
Analogy:
Owning hardware → buying a house
IaaS → renting an empty apartment (walls and plumbing are there; furniture and rules are up to you) Amazon Web Services → EC2
Microsoft Azure → Virtual Machines
Google Cloud → Compute Engine
All of these give you VMs, networks, and storage—but no application opinion.Example:
IaaS → “Give me a Linux box”
PaaS → “Run my app”
SaaS → “Just let me use the app” Maximum control and flexibility
Works for legacy apps
Fine-grained networking &amp; security
Familiar mental model for infra engineers You manage OS patching and security
Higher operational burden
Easier to misconfigure
Less opinionated guardrails <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>-style VM workloads map very naturally to IaaS
VCF abstracts hardware, but still exposes infra
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes-on-VCF</a> starts moving you away from pure IaaS toward PaaS-like models
<br>That’s why <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">a workload is a workload is a workload</a>: From the platform’s perspective, VMs and pods are both just scheduled consumers of infrastructure.
IaaS = rented infrastructure
You control the OS and above
Most flexible, most responsibility
Foundation layer beneath PaaS and SaaS
Conceptually closest to traditional virtualization
<br>From here, going back to the beginning and exploring <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> with an understanding of what IaaS is, is not a bad choice.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Background and Context/IaaS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:45:48 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Cloud Foundation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="About VCF" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/about-vcf.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">About VCF</a><br><img alt="vcf-overview.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" target="_self"><br>VMware Cloud Foundation (VCF) is a unified platform to design, plan, deploy, and manage your <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> by using <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">automation</a> capabilities.That is one of the core tenents of VCF, and thus, it requires clarification before anything else.In VCF-speak, the phrase “a workload is a workload” is not a tautology—it’s a deliberate abstraction boundary.It means that VCF intentionally collapses many very different execution models into a single management concept, and refuses to care about their internal form unless it must.Below is the precise meaning, layered from philosophy, to architecture, to consequences.From VCF’s point of view, a workload is simply “something that consumes resources and is governed by policy.”It is not:
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>
a Container
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod VM</a>
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> pod
<br>a <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>
a Helm release
Those are implementation details.VCF asks only:
Where does it run?
Who owns it?
What resources does it consume?
What policies apply?
What lifecycle rules govern it?
If those questions can be answered, VCF is satisfied.VCF exists above:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Kubernetes
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s
Containers
If VCF tried to manage each kind of workload differently, it would:
explode in complexity
duplicate logic
couple business policy to runtime mechanics
So instead, VCF defines:
Workload = Policy + Placement + Lifecycle + Resources
Everything else is delegated downward.All of the following are equally valid workloads in VCF:VCF deliberately does not rank or privilege any of these.In VCF, a workload is anything that consumes platform resources and is subject to platform policy—its internal shape is intentionally irrelevant.
VCF intentionally erases runtime distinctions
Governance &gt; implementation
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> is the abstraction bridge
If two things consume resources and obey policy, VCF treats them identically
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> makes it possible.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> converts:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pods</a> to lightweight VMs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> objects to vSphere-managed entities
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a> to policy and tenancy units From below, everything is Kubernetes.
<br>From above, everything is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> resources. VCF sits above Supervisor, so it sees:
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a>
Quotas
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policies</a>
The kind or form of the workload becomes irrelevant.VCF does NOT care:
whether the workload uses containerd or not
<br>whether it’s a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">PodVM</a> or classic VM
whether it runs Go, Java, or Bash
whether it was deployed via Helm, kubectl, or Terraform
whether it is “cloud-native” or “legacy”
Those are runtime-layer concerns, not platform-layer concerns.
A power grid doesn’t care if you plug in a toaster or a server rack—only how much power you draw and what safety rules apply.
This is why statements like these are true:
“Pod workloads are not special.”
“VM workloads are not special.”
“Guest clusters are just workloads.”
“Infrastructure doesn’t care about your app model.”
So, you don’t fight against the platform to fit the workload in; you design the workload to fit the platform’s (opinionated) invariants.To internalize VCF, don’t think in:
Pods vs VMs
Containers vs Processes
Control Planes vs Data Planes
<br>Instead, think in <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>:
Who owns this?
What are its limits?
How is it created and destroyed?
How does it fail?
How is it audited?
Don’t anchor your designs to what runs. Anchor them to how they are governed.If this does not make sense initially, give it some time and revisit this page once you navigate this website further. I assure you it will eventually click.<br>For now, let’s keep a mental note of this, and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="About VCF" data-href="About VCF" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/about-vcf.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">dive deeper into the VCF rabbit hole</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VMware Cloud Foundation.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:35:44 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[About VCF]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>
<br>VCF is a full-stack <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="IaaS" data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)</a> platform that delivers software-defined compute, storage, networking, security, and management.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Integrated automation</a> enables a self-service platform to deploy VMs and containers for developer agility.
Hardened platform offering built-in resilience, scaling, and clustering for non-stop operations.
<br>It provides automation and orchestration to simplify <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 0</a>, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 1</a>, and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a> tasks.
It simplifies full stack deployment.
<br>The purpose of VCF is to design, plan, deploy, and manage your <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> by using <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">automation</a> capabilities.VMware Cloud Foundation is a unified private-cloud platform that combines the scale and agility of public cloud with security and performance of private cloud. delivering increased productivity and lower&nbsp;Total Cost of Ownership (TCO).VCF consists of the following parts:These are the heavy-lifters of VCF.
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> (compute and VM runtime)
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> (storage)
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (networking and security)
Management Plane is about platform control and lifecycle management.
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> (visibility, health, and optimization)
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (provisioning, policy, and workflows)
These are meta components. They neither run workloads, nor operate them directly. They enable installation, integration, and extensibility.
<br><a data-href="VCF Installer" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Installer</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-sdks,-apis,-and-clis.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs</a> <br><a data-href="VMware Live Recovery" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmware-live-recovery.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Live Recovery</a>
<br><a data-href="VMware Data Services Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-data-services-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Data Services Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Business Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Business Services Console</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Usage Meter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-usage-meter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Usage Meter</a>
<br><a data-href="VMware Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-cloud/vmware-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud</a>
<br><a data-href="VMware Skyline" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-skyline.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Skyline</a>
<br><a data-href="Cloud Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/cloud-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services Console</a>
<br><a data-href="Gated SDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/gated-sdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Gated SDK</a> <br><a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>
<br><a data-href="STIG" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/stig.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">STIG</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Single Sign-On" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/identity-and-access/vcf-single-sign-on.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Single Sign-On</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Identity Broker</a>
<br>VCF builds, manages, operates, secures, monitors, and govern an entire <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Private Cloud</a>.
Deploy a new VCF platform
Converge existing virtual infrastructure to a new VCF platform.
<br>Deploy a <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>
<br>Import an existing <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> instance to a Workload Domain.
<br>Add a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> or an <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host to a Workload Domain.
<br>Configure <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> Stretched Cluster
<br>Manage network connectivity using <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>s and Transit Gateways in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Manage virtual infrastructure in vCenter Licensing
Configure IAM and SSO
Link vCenter instances for centralized inventory management
<br>Manage certificates across the <a data-href="VCF Fleet" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a>
Manage password across the VCF Fleet
Manage tags across the VCF Fleet
Manage the configuration settings of vCenter instances and vSphere Clusters.
Backup and restore the VCF Fleet and its managed VCF Instances
Migrate workloads across Workload Domains and vCenter instances <br>Deploy and configure <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> for running Kubernetes Workloads and VM Workloads
Licensing
Configure alerts
Perform log analysis and troubleshooting
Monitor network operations
Monitor storage operations
Perform infrastructure diagnostics and VCF health monitoring
Configure and use monitoring dashboard and monitoring reports
Workload monitoring and observability
