│ - vCenter / NSX / vSAN │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
<br>VCF APIs abstract platform intent (*<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">domains</a>, lifecycle, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenancy</a>**), not raw hypervisor knobs.SDDC Manager REST APIs expose everything SDDC Manager knows and controls:
Bring-up and expansion
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> lifecycle
Host add/remove
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cluster creation</a>
End-to-end upgrades (LCM)
Inventory, versions, and health
These APIs are the authoritative way to automate VCF without breaking supportability.
If it changes VCF topology or lifecycle, it goes through SDDC Manager APIs. CI/CD pipelines
Infrastructure-as-Code tools
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> automation frameworks
Internal platforms and runbooks
<br>These are about consumption and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.APIs for tenant-facing operations such as:
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Policies and approvals
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s / templates
Workload provisioning (VMs, Kubernetes-backed services)
These APIs sit closer to business intent than infrastructure detail.
SDDC Manager APIs → Build and maintain the cloud
VCF Automation APIs → Consume the cloud
These are both human and also script friendly.Used for:
Diagnostics
Operational workflows
Automation-friendly scripting
Break-glass scenarios
It is a thin wrapper over SDDC Manager APIs, with guardrails.This is:
A faster iteration than REST during ops
An easier integration into shell scripts
Provides consistent auth and context handling
CLIs are not separate systems — they are API clients.These are language bindings.Where available, VMware/Broadcom provides SDKs that wrap REST APIs in native language constructs:
Object models
Typed requests/responses
Auth helpers
Pagination, retries, error handling
These SDKs are ideal when:
You are building a platform or product
You need maintainable, testable code
Shell scripts are no longer enough
They do not:
<br>Replace <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> or <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> APIs
Provide low-level tuning knobs
Allow unsupported lifecycle paths
Let you bypass validation logic
<br>This is by design. <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for predictability and supportability over raw flexibility.
Git declares desired domains / versions
Pipeline calls SDDC Manager APIs
Platform converges safely Internal UI talks to VCF Automation APIs
End users never see infrastructure details Health checks
Controlled upgrades
Capacity expansion
All API-driven, no UI clicks.
VCF SDK APIs are the supported automation surface
SDDC Manager APIs control lifecycle and topology
VCF Automation APIs control consumption and governance
CLIs are just API clients
Using these APIs preserves VCF invariants and supportability
<br>Since it’s related to APIs, you might want to check out what a <a data-href="Gated SDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/gated-sdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Gated SDK</a> is.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-sdks,-apis,-and-clis.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:33:55 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Gated SDK]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-sdks,-apis,-and-clis.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs</a>VCF Gated SDK is a RESTful SDK around everything VCF.The VCF Gated SDK refers to the VMware Cloud Foundation Software Development Kit that is not publicly downloadable without authentication: You need to be an authorized VMware/Broadcom customer or partner to access it.So, “Gated” here means governed access, not technical limitation.In practice, “gated” means:
You must log in to the Broadcom Developer Portal with valid credentials.
Access is typically tied to an active support contract or partner agreement.
The SDK download link is hidden until your account is verified for entitlement.
<br>VCF Gated SDK provides Java and Python libraries, API bindings, utilities, and sample code to automate and integrate with <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.
Contains proprietary VMware/Broadcom code.
Ensures only licensed customers/partners can use it.
Helps control distribution of sensitive API bindings and internal tooling.
VCF is not a generic API platform; it is a validated system.
Some APIs:
Control core lifecycle
Mutate global topology
Bypass normal UI guardrails
Can easily create unsupported states
Exposing these APIs broadly would:
Fragment platform behavior
Break upgrade guarantees
Explode support matrices
So VMware/Broadcom chooses controlled exposure instead of full openness.Gated SDKs often include APIs that:
Drive SDDC Manager internal workflows
Orchestrate LCM sequencing
Mutate domain-level state machines
Access pre-GA or evolving models
Bypass tenant-safe abstractions
These are platform-builder APIs, not tenant or end-user APIs.A Gated SDK usually implies one or more of the following:
Explicit enablement flag
Contractual agreement
Limited documentation access
No backward-compatibility guarantees
Direct escalation path to engineering
Strong expectations of platform literacy
You are expected to know what you are doing.A Gated SDK is official, but not democratized.It is not:
Unsupported
A hack
A private backdoor
A “use at your own risk” API
It is supported; but with conditions.If you see something described as a Gated SDK, it usually signals:
“This is powerful”
“This can break invariants”
“This is for platform-level integration”
“You need approval and discipline”
In other words:
This is not a convenience API — it is a responsibility API. A Gated SDK is an official but restricted VCF SDK
It protects lifecycle safety and supportability
It is intended for platform builders, not tenants
Access implies higher expectations and accountability
It exists to balance power vs stability
<br>You might want to explore <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Concepts" data-href="Concepts" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/concepts.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">other core VCF concepts</a> from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/gated-sdk.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/Gated SDK.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:32:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Installer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br><img alt="vcf-installer-Image-0.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp" target="_self"><br>VCF Installer is the one-time (or rare-use) bootstrap and bring-up tool for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>VCF Installer’s sole purpose is to stand up the very first VCF environment and hand control over to <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.<br>If <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> is the factory control system, VCF Installer is the factory construction crew that builds the factory in the first place.<br><img alt="vcf-installer-image-134.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-134.webp" target="_self">VCF Installer exists to answer a very specific question:
“Given raw hardware, how do I get to a fully functional VCF Management Domain with SDDC Manager running?”
Once that answer is executed successfully, VCF Installer is done.VCF Installer is responsible for:
Validating hardware readiness
Validating network configuration
Validating DNS / NTP / IPAM
Validating credentials and certificates
Orchestrating the initial deployment of: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> on hosts
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> components <br>This is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> only work.Before anything is deployed, VCF Installer runs extensive prechecks, including:
Hardware compatibility (HCL alignment)
Network reachability
MTU consistency
IP pool correctness
Time synchronization
DNS forward/reverse lookup
Credential access
Think of it as a fail-fast safety gate: Better to stop early than build a broken cloud.VCF Installer typically operates with:
Structured input (JSON / guided wizard)
Explicit topology definitions
Explicit IP assignments
You declare what you want, and the installer executes a deterministic build.<br>There is no concept of “incremental evolution” here: That belongs to <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.It is not:
A lifecycle manager
A long-running control plane
A tenant or consumption interface
A policy engine
An operations tool
After bring-up:
It is not used daily
It does not manage upgrades
It does not manage workload domains
<br>Those responsibilities move entirely to the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.Once installation completes:
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> becomes the authoritative owner
VCF Installer steps out of the picture
You can think of it as:
VCF Installer creates SDDC Manager; SDDC Manager creates and manages everything else.
A natural question is: “Why not just use SDDC Manager from the start?”Because:
SDDC Manager itself must be deployed
That deployment requires validated sequencing
That sequencing must run before SDDC Manager exists
VCF Installer solves this bootstrapping paradox.
VCF Installer → kubeadm init
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> → Kubernetes control plane (after init)
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> → Higher-level UX / APIs for consumers
You don’t run kubeadm init every day, and you don’t run VCF Installer every day either.
VCF Installer is a Day-0 tool
It bootstraps the Management Domain
<br>It deploys the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
It performs strict prechecks and validation
After success, it is effectively retired
<br>Why not look into <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a>?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/VCF Installer/VCF Installer.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:31:15 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Fleet]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a>VCF Fleet is an environment that is managed by a single set of fleet-level management components:&nbsp;
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>
<br>and&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br>A&nbsp;VCF Fleet contains one or more&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>s and might contain one or more standalone&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> instances, managed by the&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> instance for the fleet.The components of a VCF Fleet are:
<br><a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> Instances
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains</a>&nbsp;nicely compares and contrasts how&nbsp;Fleet,&nbsp;Domain, and&nbsp;Instances&nbsp;relate to each other.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Fleet and Domain Model/VCF Fleet.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:30:51 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Fleet Deployment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VCF Fleet" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a><br>There are several different way you can deploy a <a data-href="VCF Fleet" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a>, each with its own benefits and liabilities.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vcf-fleet-deployment-d881e129-73ec-4b71-8940-e69541f380ef.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-deployment-d881e129-73ec-4b71-8940-e69541f380ef.webp" target="_self"><br>This model is ideal for organizations seeking a streamlined and scalable approach to deploying within a single availability zone or region. The design provides centralized management, enabling a unified framework for managing instances and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>s through a single&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> instance.<br>This is typically the first (and robust) starting point for deploying the first <a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>, with the flexibility to expand to multiple instances while maintaining centralized operations and automation.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-multi-az-d62fd633-c0c8-4bdf-ae11-fe7d14f8a2f3.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-multi-az-d62fd633-c0c8-4bdf-ae11-fe7d14f8a2f3.webp" target="_self">This is an ideal choice for organizations that require robust protection against site-wide failures and the ability to recover critical workloads in the event of a disaster.By building upon the former deployment design, this approach integrates disaster recovery capabilities to ensure business continuity.<br>It leverages VMware's advanced tools and technologies, such as <a data-href="VMware Live Recovery" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmware-live-recovery.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Live Recovery</a>, to enable seamless failover and failback between sites or regions. This design ensures that critical workloads are replicated and protected, minimizing downtime and data loss during unexpected events.Additionally, it supports flexible deployment models, including Single-Rack and Multi-Rack configurations, to meet diverse infrastructure needs.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-dr-f39c3fa5-a80d-4b0b-ab1b-e3c736ba88f4.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-dr-f39c3fa5-a80d-4b0b-ab1b-e3c736ba88f4.webp" target="_self"><br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> utilizes replication or backup and restore mechanisms to protect components at a secondary site, while&nbsp;<br>
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> relies on backup and restore processes for recovery at the secondary site.<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-dr-fault-8224d2cf-6af2-4d51-8ebc-1d40a50059e2.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-dr-fault-8224d2cf-6af2-4d51-8ebc-1d40a50059e2.original.png" target="_self"><br>This is another Fleet Deployment topology with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Fault Tolerance" data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Domains</a> and Disaster Recovery, combining Disaster Recovery and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">High Availability</a> capabilities.<br>You might want to switch gears and check out <a data-href="VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-sdks,-apis,-and-clis.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/VCF Enablers/VCF Installer/VCF Fleet Deployment.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:30:27 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-8e4db722-a16d-4a51-ab59-442828d317a4.original.svg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>vSphere Supervisor is a control plane built in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> that integrates desired state and a single consistent API directly in the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="ESX" data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">hypervisor</a>.<br>vSphere Supervisor enables native deployment and management of Kubernetes clusters, declarative virtual machines, and&nbsp; <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s alongside traditional workloads. It transforms <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> to an extendable platform by providing a declarative API for self-service provisioning of modern infrastructure services in a resource boundaries enabled by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>s<br>The vSphere Supervisor lives as a set of Kubernetes control-plane VMs running on ESX hosts, instantiated, wired, and governed by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>.<br><img alt="supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" target="_self">vSphere Supervisor:
<br>Runs on: <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br>Created and managed by: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Implemented as: Kubernetes control-plane VMs
<br>Distributed across <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
<br>Backed by <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> / datastores
<br>Networked via <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (or <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Distributed Virtual Switch" data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VDS</a> in simpler setups) <br>When you “enable Supervisor” in <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>:<br>
<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>:
Creates a special-purpose Kubernetes cluster
Instantiates its control plane as VMs
Pins it tightly to: Cluster membership
Networking
Storage Treats it as part of the infrastructure, not a tenant workload
So the Supervisor is:
Not a workload cluster
Not user-managed Kubernetes
Not a vSphere product you install
<br>It is an infrastructure service owned by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.Physical Hosts
└─ ESX └─ vCenter Server (control plane) └─ Supervisor Cluster (Kubernetes control plane VMs) ├─ Supervisor Namespaces ├─ vSphere Pods └─ Guest / Workload Clusters
<br>The vSphere Supervisor is a Kubernetes control plane deployed as system-managed <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, whose lifecycle is owned entirely by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> and whose purpose is to expose Kubernetes semantics directly on <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> infrastructure.<br>
The <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> physically lives as a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>-managed Kubernetes control-plane VMs running on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts inside a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>.
vSphere Supervisor is the foundation of VCF consumption and can be enabled during workload domain creation or directly in vCenter.<br>It transforms <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s into modern application platforms by embedding a platform-level Kubernetes control plane directly into ESX hosts, exposing a unified declarative API surface.<br>This integration allows end users to provision and manage workloads, including VMs, containers via <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s, full Kubernetes clusters through <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>, OCI image registries, and data services through a consistent API interface.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> maintains enterprise-grade <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, security, and operational consistency through <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>, and&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>vSphere Supervisor's <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a> provide the foundation for multi-tenancy, enabling GitOps-based workflows, and delivering cloud-like self-service in private data centers.Kubernetes didn’t replace VMs.
It replaced application scheduling semantics.VMware’s bet was:<br>
"Instead of forcing Kubernetes to run on top of <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>,<br>
we will make Kubernetes a native execution mode of <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>."
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> is that bet made concrete.
vSphere = substrate
Supervisor = Kubernetes-native personality of vSphere
VCF Automation = enterprise automation layer on top
<br>
vSphere Supervisor is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> running in a special Kubernetes-enabled mode.
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes what vSphere Supervisor exposes. <br>It is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> running in special Kubernetes-enabled mode.
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes what Supervisor exposes.
<br><img alt="supervisor-conceptual.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-conceptual.webp" target="_self">You can think of Supervisor as vSphere with Kubernetes fused into its control plane.<br><img alt="ks-ns.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ks-ns.png" target="_self"><br>When you enable Supervisor on a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>, you are activating a capability inside vSphere.
<br>Supervisor runs inside <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
<br>Uses <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> as the control plane.
<br>Creates <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s.
Exposes Kubernetes APIs, backed by native vSphere primitives.
So conceptually, Supervisor is vSphere operating in "Kubernetes-native mode".<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are not Kubernetes namespaces.<br><img alt="supervisor-diagram.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-diagram.webp" target="_self"><br>If classic <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> is "run VMs", <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> is "Run anything (VMs, Pods, services)" with the same primitives.<br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-cf6fb05a-eddd-448c-a4ff-fee4f42f207a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-cf6fb05a-eddd-448c-a4ff-fee4f42f207a.webp" target="_self">
<br>Supervisor runs on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
It enables Kubernetes semantics backed by vSphere primitives.
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> is optional and sits above Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s look like Kubernetes namespace on purpose.vSphere (authoritative substrate)
└── Supervisor ├── Kubernetes API (authoritative for some things) └── vSphere API/UI (authoritative for others)
Kubernetes manifest → vSphere policy enforcement.
Create VMs via VirtualMachine CRDs (VM Operator)
Create Pods / Deployments
Attach storage
Attach networks (within guardrails) PVCs backed by vSphere storage policies
Datastore selection via StorageClasses
Policy-based placement Declare “I need this secret”
Injector materializes it
VCF Secret Service enforces access <br>Pods/VMs attach to <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>-backed segments
Load balancers exposed via K8s Service abstractions
You don’t manage NSX topology in YAML, but you consume it declaratively.
<br><img alt="vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" target="_self">
Infrastructure topology
Tenancy and Governance constructs (Organization, Projects, Quoatas at Provider level, Approval, Chargeback) Those live in VCF Automation / vSphere UI, not Kubernetes. <br>So: vSphere Supervisor exposes a Kubernetes-native API surface for workload consumption (pods, VMs, storage, networking), while infrastructure topology, tenancy, and governance remain <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>-and <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>-controlled.<br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-c3733e8c-9204-4e01-8b0c-5bc816bdbf77.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-c3733e8c-9204-4e01-8b0c-5bc816bdbf77.webp" target="_self"><br>A <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> extends the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> inventory by introducing additional objects that represent Kubernetes-based workloads and their supporting infrastructure.
Within the vCenter inventory, a Supervisor exposes and manages the following objects:<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespaces</a> represent logical application environments within the Supervisor. They define where workloads can run and what resources they can consume.Each namespace:
Represents an isolated execution boundary
Is backed by a dedicated resource pool
Is governed by quotas and policies
Is associated with specific users and permissions
<br>For every <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>, the Supervisor creates a corresponding resource pool.
<br>In a single-cluster Supervisor, one <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> is created per namespace.
In a multi-zone (multi-cluster) Supervisor: <br>A <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> is created in each participating cluster.
Resource consumption is distributed across all clusters in the zone. <br>These <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s enforce CPU and memory limits defined at the namespace level.<br>Each <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a> can contain multiple types of workloads:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s
Lightweight VM-based pods managed by the Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>
Platform services deployed into the Supervisor environment.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster</a>s
Kubernetes clusters provisioned and managed by VKS.
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s
Traditional VMs deployed directly into the namespace.
Namespaces also encapsulate:
Network configuration and connectivity
Storage policies and persistent volumes
Access to shared or dedicated datastores
All networking and storage enforcement is handled by the underlying vSphere and NSX infrastructure.Each namespace includes role-based access control assignments that determine:
Which users or groups can access the namespace
What actions they can perform (deploy, modify, delete)
Which resources they can consume
Permissions are enforced by vCenter and integrated identity providers.``
