Owns runtime enforcement VCF Automation: Consumes Supervisor APIs
Provides self-service, governance, orchestration Supervisor enables capabilities
VCF Automation operationalizes them<br>The next topic of interest would be <a data-href="Supervisor Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>, that lists the platform-level extensions that vSphere Supervisor has.<br>Alternatively, you can check out <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/overview/vsphere-supervisor-deployment-options.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options</a> for various small-to-large-scale deployment topologies.Also, for a deeper dive into vSphere Supervisor you can check out:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Components" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-components.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Components</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Networking" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-networking.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Networking</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Storage" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-storage.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Storage</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Security" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-security.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Security</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor Inventory" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-inventory.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor Inventory</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/vSphere Supervisor.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:29:35 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Guest Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VKS Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster</a>, <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>In VMware Cloud Foundation, a Guest Cluster (workload cluster) is a cluster dedicated to running tenant workloads—VMs or Kubernetes-backed workloads—as opposed to running the platform itself.<br>It lives inside a <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> (VI Domain) and is where actual business applications execute.<br>
Guest Clusters run applications; <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>s run the cloud.
<br><img alt="Workload-Domain.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg" target="_self"><br>Once a <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> Guest Cluster (also known as “Workload Cluster”) is bound to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>:
<br>✅ The cluster knows which <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> it lives in
❌ It has no intrinsic knowledge of: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Automation</a> constructs
Approval flows
Business tenancy
<br>^ all of these concepts stop at the **<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> boundary. <br>When a guest cluster is bound to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, we are talking about a <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> workload cluster created by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.That implies:
The cluster is created via Supervisor APIs
<br>It is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>s-scoped
<br>It is lifecycle-managed by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>It runs on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> using VM-based worker nodes
VCF Platform
│
├── Management Domain
│ └── Management Cluster (platform services only)
│
└── Workload Domain (VI Domain) ├── Guest Cluster A ← tenant workloads ├── Guest Cluster B ← tenant workloads └── Guest Cluster C ← tenant workloads <br>A <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> can contain multiple Guest Clusters
Each cluster is an operational and failure boundary
<br>Tenants never see the <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>, but they consume resources from Guest Clusters Traditional virtual machines
App servers, databases, legacy systems
<br>Managed via <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
<br>Governed via <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (orgs, projects, policies) <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>-backed workloads
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">PodVM</a>-based workloads
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s mapped to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
The cluster itself is workload-agnostic; policy determines what lands there.This split is critical:
<br>Tenants use <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>-managed <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster bound to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s operate clusters
This is where:
CPU, memory, storage are consumed
Network traffic flows
Availability and performance matter most
Each Guest Cluster provides:
Fault isolation
Upgrade isolation
Security boundaries
A problem in one cluster should not affect others.Clusters are upgraded:
<br>Under <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> control
In a controlled, validated sequence
Independently of other clusters (within constraints)
It is not:
A management plane
<br>A place for <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> or <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s
A tenant abstraction by itself
A free-for-all environment
A Guest Cluster is shared infrastructure, not a tenant.There is an important nuance here:
Tenancy does not equal cluster
Multiple tenants can share: The same Guest Cluster
While remaining isolated via: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Microsegmentation Guest Clusters are capacity and fault boundaries, not business boundaries.
Strong fault isolation
Predictable lifecycle
Flexible placement strategies
Supports mixed workload types More moving parts
Requires capacity planning
Requires clear cluster placement policy
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for enterprise-scale control, not minimal topology.
Guest Clusters are where applications run
<br>They live inside <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload (VI) Domains</a>
<br>They are operated by <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s
They can host VM and Kubernetes workloads
They are shared but strongly governed
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> complements Guest Cluster. You might also want to explore <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>. Or check <a data-href="Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster</a> for a nuanced discussion of the terminology.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/Guest Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:27:26 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Management Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>In VMware Cloud Foundation, the Management Cluster is the foundational cluster that runs the platform itself.
It hosts the management plane—the services that build, operate, upgrade, and secure the rest of the cloud.Put simply:
If the Management Cluster is down, you can’t manage the cloud—only the workloads keep running.
<br>The Management Cluster is part of the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> (a special Workload Domain). It is created first during <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0 bring-up</a> and is non-optional.Typical components include:
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> (management vCenter)
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> management services
These components do not belong to the tenants. They belong to the platform.It runs the services that:
Define topology
Enforce lifecycle sequencing
Validate upgrades
Maintain inventory and state
All VCF lifecycle operations (create domain, expand cluster, upgrade stack) are coordinated from here.Tenant workloads do not run here (by design):
No tenant VMs
No tenant Kubernetes workloads
No customer apps
This protects:
Stability
Security
Upgrade safety
It is not:
A tenant cluster
A workload execution environment
A shared resource pool for apps
Optional or replaceable
Treating it like a general-purpose cluster is a serious anti-pattern.This separation ensures:
Predictable upgrades (no tenant interference)
Clear blast-radius control
Strong security boundaries
Operational sanity at scale
It’s the same pattern used by:
Kubernetes (control plane vs worker nodes)
Public clouds (provider plane vs customer plane) Management Cluster → Kubernetes control plane nodes
Guest Clusters → Kubernetes worker nodes
SDDC Manager → Cluster lifecycle operator
You wouldn’t run apps on the Kubernetes control plane; same rule applies here.
Management Cluster is typically: Small (minimum viable size)
Highly available
Strictly protected If it fails: Existing workloads keep running
You lose management, scaling, and upgrades until restored The Management Cluster runs the cloud, not the workloads
<br>It is part of the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>
<br>It hosts <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>, <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s
It is isolated, mandatory, and high-blast-radius
Treat it as sacred infrastructure
<br>You can check out <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> or <a data-href="Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster</a> for the next set of items to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/Management Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:26:45 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VKS Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a><br>A VKS cluster (also referred as <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>)is a Kubernetes cluster that is built and supported by VMware and that runs application workloads.<br>VKS clusters are part of a vSphere Kubernetes Service (<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>) deployment. You use VKS cluster management to manage VKS clusters. Their lifecycle, however, is handled by the native <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> APIs.A VKS cluster is a Kubernetes cluster provisioned and managed through VKS.Characteristics:
<br>Built on <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Managed via the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Created and governed through <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
Runs standard Kubernetes workloads
<br>VKS clusters are where actual workloads execute, but they do not contain awareness of organizational hierarchy (i.e. they don’t know about <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, or <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s).VKS provides self-service lifecycle management of Kubernetes workload clusters.VKS is an implementation of the open-source Cluster API project, which defines a set of custom resources and controllers used to manage the lifecycle of Kubernetes clusters.<br>VKS is a component of the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>. The Supervisor acts as a source of compute resources that can be registered with <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>System administrators allocate Supervisor resources to organizations in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>. The Supervisor itself does not belong to any organization.<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>s request <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s for their projects, and <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> allocates the appropriate namespaces to match those requests.<br>A single <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> can provide resources to multiple <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> organizations.<br>Within a single organization, <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s can be moved between projects.<br>To function properly, <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster management relies on a set of agents and extensions that run in every VKS cluster.<br>When a VKS cluster is attached to VKS Cluster Management, the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> auto-attach service installs:
Required extensions
Cluster resource definitions
Agent components on each node
The agent configuration includes:
The VKS cluster management endpoint
The container image registry used by the cluster
Proxy configuration details
The overall health of a cluster is determined by aggregating the health of its nodes and components.
Healthy
All nodes and components are healthy, and a heartbeat is received every minute.
Unhealthy
One or more of the following are unhealthy: One or more control plane nodes
One or more cluster components Warning
A cluster enters a warning state when: One or more worker nodes are unhealthy or unknown, or
One or more nodes (control plane or worker) report a warning condition Unknown
The cluster is marked as unknown if: One or more control plane nodes are in an unknown state, or
No heartbeat has been received for more than three minutes Node health is derived from the NodeReady condition and other node-level signals such as:
MemoryPressure
DiskPressure
OutOfDisk
The node’s health state is evaluated as follows:
NodeReady is True
All other conditions are healthy NodeReady is False, or
NodeReady is True, but more than half of the other conditions are unhealthy NodeReady is True
Fewer than half of the other conditions are unhealthy NodeReady is neither True nor False, or
No heartbeat has been received from the node for more than three minutes
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster management monitors the health of the following control plane components:
kube-apiserver
scheduler
controller-manager
etcd components (etcd-0, etcd-1, etcd-2, etc.)
Each component periodically reports its health status.
Healthy
The last reported health condition is True.
Unhealthy
The last reported health condition is False.
Unknown
The last reported health condition is neither True nor False, or no heartbeat has been received for more than three minutes.
Below is a clean, consistently structured, and de-duplicated version of your content.
Nothing new is introduced; this is purely a clarity and organization pass so the conceptual layers are easy to understand and reference.VKS (vSphere Kubernetes Service) provides managed Kubernetes clusters running on vSphere.
It operates within the VCF Automation framework and relies on the Supervisor to provision and manage resources.VKS cluster management introduces a hierarchical model that separates:
<br>Control-plane governance (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
<br>Cluster lifecycle management (<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>)
<br>Runtime execution (<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> + Kubernetes)
VKS cluster management organizes resources using the following hierarchy:
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster</a>
<br>Kubernetes Namespaces (inside the cluster, these are NOT <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s)
<br>This hierarchy exists in the <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> control plane, not inside Kubernetes itself.Each VKS cluster contains standard Kubernetes namespaces:
These are normal Kubernetes namespaces
Managed using kubectl
Used for application isolation and RBAC within the cluster
<br>These namespaces are not the same as <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s or <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s.<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> exists at the Supervisor layer and is used to:
Allocate CPU, memory, and storage
Bind resource pools to consumers
Host VKS cluster resources
Important distinctions:
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are not Kubernetes namespaces (*but they are queries using kubectl, so they —look like– Kubernetes namespaces)
They are managed through the Supervisor API
<br>They serve as the execution boundary for <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters
<br>
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> defines intent.<br>
<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> enforces that intent.
Kubernetes executes the result.
The organizational model exists above Kubernetes and never becomes part of the Kubernetes API surface.<br><a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a> and <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> are two directly-related areas to explore.<br>You might also want to check <a data-href="VKS Cluster Storage" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-storage.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster Storage</a> and <a data-href="VKS Cluster Networking" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-networking.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS Cluster Networking</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/VKS Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:25:58 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>Connected to <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>:kubectl config use-context &lt;supervisor-context&gt;
kubectl get ns NAME STATUS AGE
