Here, there is no such thing as a “regular Kubernetes namespace” in the tenant sense.The namespace here:
Cannot be created freely.
<br>Map to <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> inventory objects.
Quotas, storage, and networking are externally-enforced.
<br>Connected to a <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>:kubectl get ns
kubectl create ns foo
kubectl delete ns foo
All of these will work as expected.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s → owns the cluster.
<br><a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> namespace → normal Kubernetes semantics.
# check Supervisor-specific APIs
kubectl api-resources | grep -i vm virtualmachines vmoperator.vmware.com # look at the nodes
kubectl get nodes -o wide # look for VM Operator
kubectl get pods -A | grep vmoperator
Supervisor cluster nodes typically show:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>-backed control-plane VMs.
Special node labels
VM Operator components
Guest clusters look like:
Standard Linux nodes
kubelet-managed lifecycle
No VM Operator CRDs. <br>In a <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant namespaces are Kubernetes namespaces</a> whose lifecycle, limits, and security are owned by vSphere.
<br>In a <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>, namespaces are owned entirely by Kubernetes.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “Supervisor Namespace”</a><br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/kubectl-in-supervisor-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:23:52 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Pod]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VM Workload and Pod Workload" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vm-workload-and-pod-workload.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM Workload and Pod Workload</a><br><img alt="vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" target="_self"><br>A vSphere Pod is a Kubernetes Pod whose sandbox runs inside a lightweight VM (via <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>]), not inside a container runtime on a shared Linux node.A vSphere Pod is the VMware implementation of a Kubernetes Pod, running as a lightweight virtual machine instead of a traditional container runtime.Each vSphere Pod:
Runs inside its own virtual machine
Has a dedicated Linux kernel
Provides strong isolation similar to a VM
Is optimized for fast startup and low overhead
In other words, a vSphere Pod combines the security and isolation of a VM with the developer experience of containers.So:
API semantics → Kubernetes
<br>Runtime semantics → <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> / VM
Traditional Kubernetes Pods:
Share a Linux kernel
Rely on namespaces + cgroups
Are fast and efficient
But have weaker isolation (from a hypervisor POV)
vSphere Pods were created to:
Give VM-grade isolation
While keeping Pod-level developer UX
For multi-tenant / regulated environments
This matters a lot for:
Service providers
Telco
Regulated enterprise workloads
“Pods from different customers must never share a kernel” Strong Isolation
Each vSphere Pod runs in its own VM with a dedicated kernel, providing isolation comparable to a full virtual machine.
Precise Resource Allocation
CPU, memory, and storage are allocated exactly as specified for the workload.
Efficient Scheduling<br>
vSphere Distributed Resource Scheduler (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>) places vSphere Pods on appropriate hosts based on available resources.
High Performance
The lightweight VM model preserves fast startup times while avoiding the “noisy neighbor” problem common in shared-kernel container environments.
Operational Visibility
Administrators can monitor and manage vSphere Pods using standard vSphere tools and workflows.
vSphere Pods are compatible with the Open Container Initiative (OCI) specification.They can run OCI-compliant container images, provided the container image supports the target environment.<br>For a vSphere Pod to run, a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> must be created on the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>.<br><img alt="vsphere-pod-298459bc-258c-4430-81a5-fb5330d7ce24.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-298459bc-258c-4430-81a5-fb5330d7ce24.webp" target="_self"><br>vSphere Pods rely on <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> networking.Key Characteristics:
<br>Networking is provided through the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Pod networking is isolated and managed through <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> constructs
Traffic management, routing, and security policies are enforced at the infrastructure level
<br>Each <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host runs a component called Spherelet.
Spherelet:
Acts as the kubelet for vSphere Pods
Integrates directly with the ESX host
Manages pod lifecycle operations (start, stop, monitor)
Communicates with the Supervisor control plane
<br>Spherelet allows <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> to participate as a node in the Kubernetes control plane without running a traditional Linux OS.vSphere Pods use multiple storage types depending on usage:
Ephemeral VMDKs
Used for temporary container storage.
<br>Persistent Volume <a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>s
Backed by vSphere storage policies and used for persistent data.
<br>Image Cache <a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>s<br>
Used to cache container images locally on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts. Storage policies define placement and performance characteristics.
<br>Storage policies are assigned at the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a> level.
<br>Persistent volumes are provisioned through the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> using <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>.
Regular Kubernetes:Node (Linux)
└── kubelet ├── Pod A ├── Pod B └── Pod C
vSphere Pods:ESX
├── Pod-VM A
├── Pod-VM B
└── Pod-VM C No shared container runtime
No shared kubelet per “node”
Each pod is scheduled directly by vSphere
Kubernetes still thinks it’s scheduling Pods; but, vSphere translates that into VM placement.So in vSphereland, “One Pod ~= A Tiny VM”<br><img alt="vsphere-pod-4.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-4.png" target="_self">
Kubernetes: Decides which pod should run vSphere: Decides where the pod-VM runs
Enforces CPU, memory, NUMA, HA, DRS This is what “Kubernetes-native mode” really looks like under the hood.From the Pod’s perspective:
It has an IP
It mounts volumes
It exposes ports
Under the hood:
Networking is NSX-backed
Storage is datastore-policy-backed
Attach/detach happens at VM granularity
Again: Pod UX, VM machinery.Despite the VM runtime, vSphere Pods still use:
Pod specs
Containers
Init containers
ConfigMaps
Volume mounts
Pod lifecycle (create/delete/restart)
Kubernetes Services (with some constraints)
So developers mostly don’t care—and that is by design. Regular Pod → process in a shared OS
vSphere Pod → process in its own micro-VM
Or:
Regular K8s → Linux container model
vSphere Pods → “micro-VM container” model
Essentially: vSphere Pods are not regular Kubernetes Pods
They are Pod-shaped workloads backed by per-Pod VMs
Kubernetes API semantics remain intact
Runtime isolation is hypervisor-level
This is intentional and central to Supervisor’s design vSphere Pods are VM-backed Kubernetes pods with strong isolation.
<br>They run on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts using Spherelet and Supervisor integration.
They support OCI-compatible containers.
<br>Storage, networking, and scheduling are all managed through <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.
vSphere Pods provide a secure, enterprise-grade alternative to traditional container runtimes.
<br><a data-href="VM Workload and Pod Workload" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vm-workload-and-pod-workload.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM Workload and Pod Workload</a> compares and contrasts VM Workloads and vSphere Pods.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Architecture and Core Concepts/vSphere Pod.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:21:04 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VM Workload and Pod Workload]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>See also: The “A Workload is a Workload is a Workload” section in <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, also: <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>In VCF, a workload is:
A unit of compute that consumes CPU, memory, storage, and networking, and is subject to lifecycle, policy, and governance.
VCF doesn’t care what the workload is at a philosophical level. It cares about:
How it is instantiated
How it is isolated
How it is scheduled
How it is governed
Which control plane owns it
one virtual machine per workloadA VM Workload is a traditional virtual machine:
Runs on ESX
Has its own guest OS
Is managed by vCenter
<br>Uses <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a>s directly <br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> is the authoritative control plane
VCF Automation wraps vCenter, but does not replace it CPU / memory allocated per VM
Strong isolation via hypervisor boundaries
Overcommitment controlled at ESX level Create VM
Power on/off
Snapshot
Clone
Patch guest OS
Backup VM image VM policies
Placement rules
Affinity / anti-affinity
HA / DRS
Backup &amp; DR policies
many disposable units forming a service.<br>A <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod Workload</a> is a Kubernetes Pod running on the vSphere Supervisor Cluster.<br>A pod on the vSphere Supervisor Cluster is not a traditional Kubernetes pod. It is a <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>—Kubernetes-shaped, but vSphere-implemented.Key point:<br>
A Pod Workload (<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>) is not a VM pretending to be a container.
<br>
<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s are VMs implementing container semantics, not containers implemented as VMs.
<br>
A <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a> is a Kubernetes Pod whose execution unit is a micro-VM, where the VM boundary replaces the Linux container boundary. The VM is the isolation primitive
The Pod is the semantic primitive
The container image is payload, not a process model
So the VM is not “pretending to be a container”—it is implementing the Pod abstraction using a VM instead of a process.
Pod (Kubernetes API object) └─ Backed by └─ Ultra-lightweight VM └─ ESX └─ Hardware
It is:
A Kubernetes-native unit
Scheduled by Kubernetes
Governed by Kubernetes APIs
<br>Backed by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> under the hood <br>Kubernetes API (<a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>) is authoritative
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> supplies infrastructure, not lifecycle semantics
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> governs Kubernetes intent, not individual pods CPU / memory requested via Kubernetes requests and limits
Scheduler decides placement
Isolation via: Namespaces
RBAC
Pod security Declarative (YAML)
Reconciliation-based
Pods are ephemeral
Restart ≠ failure
Replacement is normal Namespace-level quotas
Admission control
Image policies
Network policies VM workloads → legacy, stateful, pet-like systems
Pod workloads (vSphere Pods) → cloud-native, stateless, cattle-like systems
VCF’s value is:
Running both on the same physical infrastructure, with unified policy and automation, without forcing one model onto the other. Trying to manage pods like VMs breaks Kubernetes.
Trying to manage VMs like pods breaks operational reality.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> keeps them separate but coordinated.<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a> (Pod Workload) in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a Kubernetes-native execution unit scheduled and governed by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> Kubernetes control plane, consuming <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> resources indirectly through Kubernetes abstractions—unlike a VM workload, which is a hypervisor-managed, OS-bearing unit directly governed by vCenter.
“Pod workload” ≠ “small VM”
Pod Workloads are Kubernetes-first, not vSphere-first
VMs are stateful machines
Pods are replaceable execution instances
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> supports both because enterprises need both
<br>As another platform extension, you might want to look in to <a data-href="vSphere Trust Authority" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Trust Authority</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vm-workload-and-pod-workload.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Architecture and Core Concepts/VM Workload and Pod Workload.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:19:14 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Trust Authority]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:security" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#security">#security</a><br><img alt="vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp" target="_self">vSphere Trust Authority (vTA) is a hardware-rooted security feature that separates “who can decrypt and attest” from “who runs the workload.”It uses trusted execution and attestation so that even infrastructure administrators cannot access protected secrets or plaintext data.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, vTA is an optional, high-assurance security capability, not a default baseline.VMware Cloud Foundation
├── Trust Authority Cluster (isolated)
│ ├── Key Provider / Attestation Services
│ └── Hardware-backed trust (TPM, TEE)
│
└── Workload Domains └── Protected VMs / workloads <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
Integrated with: Key Management Interoperability Protocol (KMIP) providers
<br>Managed through: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Classic virtualization problem:
Infrastructure admins can ultimately see everything.
vTA introduces cryptographic separation of duties:
Infra admins manage hosts and clusters
They do NOT control keys
Decryption happens only after hardware attestation
This is importan in:
Regulated environments
Confidential Computing
Insider-threat models
Sovereign cloud designs Trust Authority Cluster boots with TPM-backed identity
Hosts and workloads are attested
Only if attestation passes: Encryption keys are released
Protected workloads decrypt and run If trust breaks: Keys are withheld
Workloads remain encrypted / suspended Access to infrastructure ≠ access to data <br>Separate <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> cluster
Minimal admin surface
Hosts key and attestation services Uses CPU security features (e.g., SEV, TDX)
Prevents memory inspection Keys never live with workload admins
Often backed by HSMs
vTA is the strongest isolation boundary in vSphere.Typical usage:
Confidential VMs
Telco and Financial Workloads
Government / Sovereign Clouds
Typical non-usage:
General enterprise clusters
Cost-sensitive environments
Dev/Test
VTA is deliberately heavyweight.You can think of vTA as:
“Even if someone owns the data center, they still cannot read the data.”
It is zero-trust applied to virtualization itself.
❌ Not a secrets manager
❌ Not an identity provider
❌ Not Kubernetes confidential computing (though complementary)
❌ Not required for VCF Strongest insider-threat protection
Hardware-rooted trust
Clear separation of duties Additional clusters and hardware
Operational complexity
Limited workload compatibility vSphere Trust Authority brings confidential computing to VCF
It cryptographically separates infra admins from data access
Optional, niche, but extremely powerful
Used when “root access is not enough” must be enforced
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, and <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/Security Services/vSphere Trust Authority.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:14:26 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vta-0537bb8f-675c-4632-89cf-ea0e8bf9c167.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vNUMA]]></title><description><![CDATA[Let’s start with physical NUMA.<img alt="NUMA-1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/numa-1.png" target="_self">NUMA stands for non-uniform memory access.NUMA is a physical server architecture used by modern multi-socket systems.
Each CPU socket has: Its own local memory
Faster access to that local memory Accessing memory attached to another socket is slower
non-uniform here does not mean “processes access memory unevenly”; it is from a hardware perspective, and simply means “memory access latency is not the same for all memory locations”Hence: Memory access time is not uniformYou can think of it as:
Two cities (CPU sockets)
Each city has its own warehouse (memory)
Shipping inside the city is fast
Shipping between cities takes longer
NUMA provides massive performance gain if locality is respected.Assume there is a workload that:
Runs on CPU-0
But frequently accesses memory on CPU-1
Then, performance will drop due to latency and cache penalties. This is invisible at the OS level unless NUMA-aware.In a NUMA-aware system, CPU threads are scheduled to prefer running on CPUs that are near the memory they already use, not the other way around.
All DRAM is: Equidistant (or close enough)
Reached through a shared memory controller or fabric Differences exist, but: They are not tied to CPU identity
They are mostly hidden from software Software does not (and cannot) reason about “which CPU core owns which memory” From the OS perspective: “Memory is one big pool” Latency variance exists, but not topologically anchored.
In contrast, in NUMA, each CPU socket has its own local memory controller and DRAM; remote memory is reached via an interconnect and is slower.vNUMA is how a hypervisor exposes NUMA topology to a VM.
The VM sees virtual NUMA nodes
Each vNUMA node has: vCPUs
Assigned memory Guest OS can schedule intelligently inside the VM
vNUMA is NUMA-awareness for virtual machinesWithout vNUMA:
Guest OS thinks memory is uniform
Hypervisor silently shuffles memory
Cache locality is lost
With vNUMA:
Guest OS: Allocates memory locally
Schedules threads close to memory Databases, JVMs, etc., perform much better
Tangential (but not directly-related-to) NUMA is SR-IOV.<br><img alt="sriovarchitecture.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sriovarchitecture.png" target="_self">SR-IOV allows one physical PCIe device (NIC, GPU, HBA) to present:
One Physical Function (PF)
Multiple Virtual Functions (VFs)
The number of VFs an SR-IOV-enabled device can expose is fundamentally limited by the device’s hardware design, firmware, and onboard resources.SR-IOV devices expose a capability like:Total VFs supported: NThis value is:
Burned into silicon
Sometimes further capped by firmware
Sometimes configurable downward (but not upward)
Typical real-world numbers:
8
16
32
64
128
(High-end SmartNICs may go higher)
You cannot exceed this, no matter what the OS or hypervisor wants.Each VF:
Can be assigned directly to a VM
Bypasses the hypervisor datapath
When a VF is assigned:
<br>The VF is bound to the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>
<br>The <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> sees it as a native PCIe device
The guest driver talks directly to hardware
Packets do not traverse: vSwitch
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VM NIC" data-href="VM NIC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vm-nic.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vNIC</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Distributed Virtual Switch" data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VDS</a>
software datapaths <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> does not schedule or inspect traffic
This is why SR-IOV delivers:
Near bare-metal latency
Deterministic throughput
Minimal jitter <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> flexibility (often)
Snapshot support (often)
Hypervisor mediation
Some observability
They solve different problems:An SR-IOV VF is physically attached to:
A PCIe root complex
Which belongs to one NUMA node
If:
VM vCPUs run on NUMA node 0
SR-IOV NIC VF is on NUMA node 1
You now have remote memory + remote I/O: Worst-case latency scenario.This is critical for performance workloads.When using SR-IOV:
Align: <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> vCPUs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> memory
PCIe device To the same NUMA node
This may require:
NUMA-aware placement
Host pinning
Careful cluster design
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/vNUMA.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:13:10 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/numa-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/numa-1.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMDK]]></title><description><![CDATA[In VMware virtualization, VMDK stands for Virtual Machine Disk. It is the file format used by VMware to represent a virtual hard disk—the persistent storage attached to a virtual machine.A VMDK file behaves like a physical hard drive, but for a VM.
From the guest OS point of view, it looks like /dev/sda, C:\, etc.
From the <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>’s point of view, it’s one or more files on a datastore.VMDKs are stored on VMware datastores, which may be backed by:
VMFS (block storage)
NFS
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
Local disks
Object storage (via vSAN ESA / integrations)
A “VMDK” is usually not a single file:
Ends in .vmdk
Contains metadata: Disk size
Geometry
Provisioning type
Backing extent file name Examples: disk-flat.vmdk
disk-s001.vmdk, disk-s002.vmdk Holds the actual data blocks
Snapshots and special configurations add more files.In the VMware ecosystem:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> handles block I/O
VMDK is the disk abstraction
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> manages lifecycle
Storage Policy Based Management (SPBM) governs behavior
<br>All of this is orchestrated under <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/VMDK.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:09:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VM NIC]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vmnic-net-diagram.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmnic-net-diagram.png" target="_self"><br>A VM NIC (often written vNIC) is a virtualized network adapter presented to a virtual machine by the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="ESX" data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">hypervisor</a>. From the guest OS’s point of view, it behaves like a physical Ethernet card; from the host’s point of view, it’s a software object that plugs into VMware’s virtual networking stack.Effectively, it is a software Ethernet card that lives inside the VM.
Appears as a standard network adapter (e.g., Intel or VMware-branded)
Has: A MAC address
Link state (up/down)
One or more IP addresses assigned by the guest OS Drivers inside the VM talk to it just like real hardware The vNIC is backed by VMware virtual networking
It connects to: A vSwitch (Standard or Distributed)
A Port Group Traffic is then forwarded to: Other VMs
The host
The physical network via uplinks (pNICs) VMware supports multiple vNIC “models,” each with different tradeoffs:A typical path looks like this:[ VM ] |
[vNIC] |
[Port Group] |
[vSwitch (VSS or VDS)] |
[pNIC / Uplink] |
[Physical Network] Port Group defines policies (VLAN, security, shaping)
vSwitch is the virtual L2 switch
pNICs are the host’s physical NICs Multiple vNICs per VM Separate traffic (management, data, backup) <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vNUMA" data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SR-IOV</a> VM bypasses vSwitch and talks almost directly to hardware
Very high performance, less flexibility Traffic Shaping and Security Promiscuous mode
MAC changes
Forged transmits A VM NIC (vNIC) is a virtual Ethernet adapter attached to a VM
It connects the VM to VMware’s virtual networking stack
VMXNET3 is the modern, high-performance choice
Networking is enforced through port groups and vSwitches
Multiple vNICs, policies, and offloads make it far more flexible than physical NICs
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vm-nic.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/VM NIC.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:08:27 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmnic-net-diagram.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmnic-net-diagram.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Virtual Machine]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>A Virtual Machine (VM) is a software-defined computer that behaves like a physical machine but runs on top of a virtualization layer rather than directly on hardware.You can think of it as a full computer implemented in software.<br><img alt="virtual_machines.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/virtual_machines.webp" target="_self">Each VM:
Has its own CPU, memory, disk, and network
Runs its own operating system
Is isolated from other VMs
Believes it owns real hardware (even though it doesn’t)
The key component is the hypervisor.The hypervisor:
Intercepts CPU instructions
Schedules CPU time
Maps virtual memory → physical memory
Virtualizes I/O (disk, NIC, GPU, etc.)
From the VM’s perspective:
“I am running on bare metal.”
From reality:
“You are one of many guests sharing a host.”
A VM is not just an OS. It consists of:
Virtual Hardware vCPU(s)
vRAM
Virtual disk(s)
Virtual NIC(s) Firmware BIOS or UEFI Operating System Linux, Windows, BSD, etc. Applications Databases, web servers, middleware, etc. Even though the term VM is generic, VCF treats the VM as a first-class workload unit:
A VM is: A managed workload
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governed</a> by policies
Scheduled onto clusters
Subject to lifecycle operations (create, move, snapshot, delete) <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> doesn’t care why the VM exists
It cares how to place, secure, move, and operate it A VM is a full computer implemented in software
It runs an OS and applications like a physical machine
The hypervisor provides isolation and resource sharing
VMs remain foundational—even in modern cloud platforms
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, a VM is a core workload primitive, not a legacy artifact
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/Virtual Machine.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:08:03 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/virtual_machines.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/virtual_machines.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCPU]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vCPU.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcpu.webp" target="_self"><br>In the context of <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, a vCPU (virtual CPU) is a logical processor that vCenter assigns to a <a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>, abstracting and time-sharing the physical CPUs (pCPUs) of the underlying <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.You can think of it as CPU time and execution context, not a physical core.<br>A vCPU is a scheduling unit presented to a <a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>, which the <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> scheduler maps onto physical CPU cores or hardware threads on demand.<br>A <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> with 4 vCPUs does not get 4 dedicated cores: It gets permission to run up to 4 execution threads concurrently when physical CPU time is available.A vCPU is not:
a physical core
pinned hardware (unless you explicitly do CPU pinning)
a guaranteed slice of CPU time
A vCPU is:
a schedulable execution context
<br>backed by <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>’s CPU scheduler
mapped dynamically to cores or hyperthreads
exposed to the guest OS as a CPU socket or core <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> uses time-slicing + SMT awareness
Multiple vCPUs can run on the same physical core at different times There is no 1:1 relationship unless: CPU affinity is configured (rare, advanced, some Telco use cases demand it)
Real-time workloads are used <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> itself does not execute workloads. It:
Defines VM configuration (number of vCPUs)
Enforces resource policies: CPU limits
CPU reservations
Shares <br>Coordinates placement decisions (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>)
Observes performance (CPU Ready, Co-Stop, etc.)
<br>The actual execution and scheduling happens on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.When you assign vCPUs, you also define topology:
Sockets
Cores per socket
Example:
4 vCPUs as 1 socket × 4 cores
or 2 sockets × 2 cores
This affects:
Guest OS licensing
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vNUMA" data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NUMA</a> behavior
Cache locality
Some applications (databases, especially)
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> lets you control this explicitly.Oversubscription is normal, expected, and intentional.In real environments:
Physical cores: 32
Total vCPUs across VMs: 200+
This is normal.This will work because:
Most VMs are idle most of the time
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> schedules based on demand
Problems only appear when too many vCPUs want to run at once
CPU Ready Time is one of the key metrics here:
vCPU wants to run but can’t get scheduled.
Start small (1–2 vCPUs)
Scale up, not down
Avoid wide VMs unless needed
Watch: CPU Ready
Co-Stop (for multi-vCPU VMs) Prefer fewer vCPUs with higher utilization over many idle vCPUs vCPU = schedulable execution context, not a core
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> defines and governs, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> executes and schedules
Oversubscription is by design
More vCPUs ≠ more performance
Correct sizing matters more than raw allocation
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vcpu.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/vCPU.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:05:21 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcpu.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcpu.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vApp]]></title><description><![CDATA[A vApp is a logical container in VMware that groups multiple VMs into a single, manageable application unit with shared lifecycle, networking, and (optionally) resource policies.It is best thought of as “an application-shaped wrapper around several VMs.”A vApp is a construct in VMware that lets you manage a set of related VMs as one application, with coordinated startup order, shared networking, and optional resource controls.vApps live and are managed in <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>.vApps were created to solve a very specific problem:
“How do I deploy and operate a multi-VM application as a single unit?”
Before Kubernetes, before Helm, before Operators—this was VMware’s answer.vApp: OnlineStore
├── Web VM
├── API VM
└── Database VM
You can:
Power on/off the whole application
Clone or export it
Track it as a single object
Critical feature.You can define:
DB starts first
App tier next
Web tier last
Reverse order on shutdown
This was huge in pre-container days.Inside a vApp you can:
Define isolated networks
Connect VMs to internal-only networks
Attach uplinks at the vApp boundary
It is like a “mini datacenter boundary for this application”.vApps support:
OVF / OVA packaging
Application-level metadata
Deployment parameters (IP, hostname, etc.)
This made vApps attractive for:
ISVs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Appliances</a>
Repeatable deployments
vApp is an organizational and orchestration construct, not a runtime.vApps were ahead of their time, but eventually outpaced by containers.vApps are still relevant in:
<br>VMware <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>s (OVA-based)
Legacy multi-VM apps
Demo environments
Lab setups
But, they are rare in modern Cloud Native stacks:
Kubernetes replaced the need
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> layers supersede it
GitOps models don’t map cleanly
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/vApp.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:04:19 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br>See also: <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>Yes’nt.<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> and a Supervisor Cluster are not the same thing. However, they are so tightly-related in a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor-enabled Namespace</a>, you can “colloquially” say that they are the same.Yet, they sit at different abstraction layers.This is the base construct.A vSphere Cluster is a classic virtualization construct:
A group of [[ESX] hosts
<br>Managed by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Provides: [DRS] (scheduling)
[HA] (failover)
Resource Pooling (CPU / memory)
Shared storage and networking However, vSphere Cluster alone does not imply
Any Kubernetes
Any namespaces
Any tenants
Any container workloads
You can run only VMs, forever, and never enable anything Kubernetes-related.This is the layer on top.A Supervisor Cluster is not a separate cluster of hosts.It is:<br>
A Kubernetes control plane embedded into a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>
<br>When you enable the Supervisor feature on <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>:
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> deploys Kubernetes control plane VMs
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts become Kubernetes worker nodes
vSphere exposes: <br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod Workload</a>s
<br><a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>s (e.g., <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>) <br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> becomes Kubernetes-aware
<br>The key point is: The same <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts of the same <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> are used, but now they serve two schedulers**:
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s)
Kubernetes (pods / guest clusters)
So the formal relationship is:
A Supervisor Cluster is a capability of a vSphere Cluster, not a different cluster type.
But, it walks like a duck, talks like a duck, and it surely is a very-sophisticated duck: Operationally, and practically, it is the same thing.<br>A Supervisor Cluster is a Kubernetes control plane that runs on and transforms a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> into a Kubernetes-aware platform.For the ontology-enthusiasts out there:This matters a lot.
vSphere Cluster failure → everything dies
<br>Supervisor control plane failure → <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s keep running
Although subtle, this distinction becomes very important when discussing:
Security boundaries
Upgrade paths
Failure isolation
Scheduling semantics
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> mappings
<br>
In a Supervisor-enabled <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>, the Supervisor Cluster and the <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> are co-resident and inseparable operationally, but they remain distinct architectural constructs with different control planes and failure domains.
<br><a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> complements Supervisor Cluster. You might also want to explore <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>. Or check <a data-href="Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster</a> for a nuanced discussion of the terminology.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Inventory Objects/Supervisor Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:02:15 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Resource Pool]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>A Resource Pool in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a vSphere construct that carves up CPU and memory capacity inside a cluster and applies <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> controls (limits, reservations, shares) over how workloads consume those resources.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> inherits Resource Pools from <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>; it does not redefine them.<br>Think of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> as layered plumbing:VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere (via vCenter) └── Cluster └── Resource Pool └── VM / vApp <br>Owned by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Managed through: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br>Consumed by: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMs</a> (and <a data-href="vApp" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vApp</a>s), including those provisioned via <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> may target a resource pool, but does not create a new abstraction here.A Resource Pool lets you govern contention, not create capacity.
Resource Pools do not add resources — they only slice and prioritize what already exists in the cluster.
Think of a cluster as a water tank:
The tank size = physical host capacity
Resource Pools = valves
Shares = which valve opens wider under pressure
Reservations = minimum guaranteed flow
Limits = maximum allowed flow
No matter how many valves you add, the tank size never changes.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> itself does not require Resource Pools, but they are often used:
To separate platform workloads from tenant workloads
To protect management components from noisy neighbors
To enforce guardrails in shared clusters
Example:Cluster
├── Mgmt-RP (high shares, reservations)
│ ├── vCenter
│ ├── NSX Managers
│
└── Tenant-RP ├── App-VMs ├── DB-VMs
❌ Overusing limits
→ Causes artificial throttling and unpredictable latency❌ Deeply nested pools
→ Shares become multiplicative and hard to reason about❌ Using pools as security boundaries
→ They are not isolation mechanisms
❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not a billing unit
❌ Not a Kubernetes namespace
❌ Not a quota system (that’s layered above, e.g., VCF Automation) <br>A Resource Pool is a vSphere scheduling construct, fully inherited by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
It controls CPU and memory contention, not ownership or tenancy
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> may reference it, but does not redefine it
Use sparingly, with clear intent and shallow hierarchies
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, and <a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> are all related contents that you might want to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Inventory Objects/Resource Pool.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 17:00:32 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[HA]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>HA (High Availability) in VCF is the vSphere-native mechanism that automatically restarts workloads when a physical host fails.It is not a single VCF feature; rather, VCF relies on and standardizes HA across its managed infrastructure.<br><img alt="ha-vm_img04.gif" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif" target="_self"><br>HA is not invented by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>. It comes from <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> and is enforced consistently by VCF.VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── Cluster └── HA (enabled at cluster level) └── VM restart on host failure <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Configured in: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Consumed by: All VMs running in VCF-managed clusters
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> ensures HA is correctly configured, validated, and lifecycle-managed as part of its opinionated design.<br><img alt="ha-vmsc_2_1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vmsc_2_1.png" target="_self">
Detect host failure → restart affected VMs on surviving hosts <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts exchange heartbeats
A host stops responding
Remaining hosts declare it failed
vCenter selects new hosts
VMs are restarted from disk Note that VMs are restarted, not live-migrated
<br>Physical <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host failure
Power loss to a host
PSOD / host crash
Host isolation scenarios Guest OS crashes
Application-level failures
Storage corruption
Network partition inside the VM
Data loss between last write and crash
HA answers “Is the VM running?”, not “Is the app healthy?”<br>In VCF, every <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> cluster is typically:
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>-enabled
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>-enabled
Validated against design rules
Example:Workload Domain
└── Cluster ├── HA: Enabled ├── DRS: Fully Automated └── Admission Control: Enabled
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> expects HA to be on; disabling it usually breaks design assumptions.HA includes Admission Control, which prevents you from powering on too many VMs.Purpose:
Ensure enough spare capacity exists to restart VMs after a failure.
If Admission Control says “no”:
Nothing is broken
You are overcommitted beyond your failure tolerance
This is HA doing its job, not being restrictive.VCF HA is infrastructure HA, not cloud-native app HA.❌ Turning off HA to “fit more VMs”
→ Silent loss of failure guarantees❌ Expecting HA to replace app clustering
→ Wrong layer❌ Confusing HA with zero downtime
→ There is always a restart
HA in VCF = vSphere HA, standardized and enforced
It restarts VMs after host failure
It does not provide zero-downtime or app-level resilience
It is a non-optional baseline for VCF design assumptions
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> and <a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> nicely complement HA.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Cluster Services/HA.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:59:47 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif" length="0" type="image/gif"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ha-vm_img04.gif&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Fault Tolerance]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br><img alt="ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" target="_self"><br>Fault Tolerance (FT) is a vSphere feature that provides zero-downtime protection for a single <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a> by running a lockstep secondary copy of that VM on another host.If the primary host fails, the secondary immediately takes over with no reboot and no data loss.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> inherits FT from vSphere; it does not redefine it.<br><img alt="ft-308973.avif" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-308973.avif" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── Cluster └── Fault Tolerance (per-VM feature) ├── Primary VM └── Secondary VM (lockstep) <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Configured in: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Applies to: Individual VMs (opt-in)
<br><img alt="ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-vmware-ft-architecture.jpg" target="_self">
Executes the same CPU instructions on two VMs simultaneously
Streams execution state over a dedicated FT logging network
On host failure → instant switchover, no restart
<br>
<a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> restarts VMs.
FT never restarts them. <br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>: “If the server crashes, reboot it elsewhere”
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>: “Move servers around to keep things fair”
FT: “Run two brains in sync at all times”
FT is about continuity, not balancing or recovery speed.FT is powerful but expensive.
Limited VM sizes (CPU / memory caps)
No snapshots
No suspend
<br>No Storage <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
Requires identical CPU features across hosts
Heavy network and CPU overhead
Because of this, FT is typically reserved for:
Legacy apps that cannot tolerate any downtime
Single-instance workloads with no clustering option
VCF environments usually prefer:
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> + <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> for infrastructure resilience
<br>*Application-level <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> (*clusters, replicas, quorum())
Kubernetes controllers for pod-level restart
Site-level DR (disaster recovery) for disasters
<br>FT remains available, but it is not a default design assumption in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.FT is like live brain mirroring: effective, but costly.❌ Using FT as a substitute for application HA
❌ Enabling FT broadly “just in case”
❌ Forgetting FT network requirements
❌ Expecting FT to scale like Kubernetes replicas
FT provides true zero-downtime VM failover
<br>It is a <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> feature, inherited by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
High overhead and strict limits
<br>In modern <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> designs, FT is the exception, not the rule
<br>Let’s check out <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> next, since it is “essentially” everywhere.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Cluster Services/Fault Tolerance.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:58:07 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/ft-001-unnamed__22_.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[DRS]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br><img alt="drs-Load-balancing-in-a-VMware-DRS-cluster.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-load-balancing-in-a-vmware-drs-cluster.webp" target="_self"><br>DRS (Distributed Resource Scheduler) is the <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> service that continuously balances CPU and memory load by automatically placing and live-migrating VMs (via <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>) across hosts.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, DRS is foundational, not optional.<br><img alt="drs-1545135394507.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-1545135394507.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── Cluster ├── HA → “Can the VM run?” └── DRS → “Where should it run?” <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Executed via: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Acts on: VMs inside a cluster
VCF assumes DRS is enabled and automated for predictable behavior.<br><img alt="drs-add_drs_rules.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-add_drs_rules.jpg" target="_self">
Initial Placement – chooses the best host when a VM powers on
Continuous Balancing – monitors CPU and memory pressure
<br>Live Migration – moves VMs using <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
Rule Enforcement – respects affinity / anti-affinity constraints
<br>
If <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> answers “Can the VM run?”,
DRS answers “Where should the VM run right now?”
<br><a data-href="VMware Validated Solutions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Validated Solutions</a> assume Fully Automated DRS.DRS continuously evaluates:
Host CPU utilization
Host memory pressure
VM demand and entitlements
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> shares and limits
Affinity / anti-affinity rules
When imbalance exceeds a threshold:<br>
→ <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> is triggered
→ No VM restartDRS is performance and fairness, not failure recovery.DRS can enforce rules such as:
“These VMs must stay together”
“These VMs must never share a host”
Typical use cases:
App + cache locality
HA for clustered apps
Licensing constraints Over-constraining rules reduces DRS effectiveness.
DRS respects:
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> shares
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> reservations
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> limits DRS balances within the rules you define — it does not override governance.
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, clusters are typically:Cluster
├── HA: Enabled
├── DRS: Fully Automated
├── Admission Control: On
└── vMotion: Required
If DRS is disabled:
Initial placement degrades
Load hotspots form
HA restarts may fail due to poor placement ❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not a scaling mechanism
❌ Not application-aware
❌ Not Kubernetes scheduling
DRS operates strictly at the VM + host layer.❌ Disabling DRS for “predictability”
→ Creates hotspots and manual ops❌ Overusing VM-Host affinity rules
→ Breaks automatic balancing❌ Expecting DRS to fix under-provisioning
→ It redistributes; it does not create capacity
<br>DRS is the brain of a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>
It continuously optimizes where VMs run
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> assumes DRS is enabled and automated
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> + DRS together provide resilience + efficiency
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> (FT) is the next related topic to explore after DRS.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Cluster Services/DRS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:57:17 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-load-balancing-in-a-vmware-drs-cluster.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/drs-load-balancing-in-a-vmware-drs-cluster.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCSA]]></title><description><![CDATA[See Also: <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>, <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a><br>VCSA, is an acronym for “<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> Appliance”<br>It is a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> for <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a><br><img alt="Image" src="https://lazywinadmin.github.io/images/2013/20130401_Deploying_and_Configuring_vCenter_Server_Appliance_5.1/VMware-vCenter-Topology__452693609__-600x400.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br>In VCF, VCSA is the central control plane for vSphere infrastructure—the brain that manages <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and clusters across domains.
VCSA = vCenter, packaged as a Linux appliance
VCF uses VCSA everywhere to manage compute
No VCSA → no usable vSphere → no VCF
Think of VCF as an orchestration stack, and VCSA as the authoritative source of truth for the compute state.Inside VCF, VCSA is responsible for:
<br>Manages <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
Forms and manages vSphere clusters
Enforces cluster features: <br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s Everything “higher” in the stack talks to VCSA:
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (for host/cluster attachment)
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> (Kubernetes-on-vSphere)
If something needs to know “what hosts exist?” or “where does this VM live?”, it asks VCSA.
Integrates with SSO / identity providers
Issues and validates service identities
Acts as a trust anchor for many workflows
VCF is domain-based, and each domain has its own VCSA.
Always present
Contains: VCSA
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Manages itself and workload domains Each workload domain has: Its own VCSA
<br>Its own <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Isolated lifecycle and fault domains
This separation is deliberate:
Different upgrade cadences
Different blast radii
Different tenants / purposes
When someone says “VCF manages vSphere” what they actually mean is “VCF automates VCSA, which in turn manages ESX”
<br>The <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> runs on vSphere
But: VCSA creates it
VCSA owns its lifecycle
VCSA exposes it via vSphere APIs Kubernetes is embedded into vSphere, but VCSA remains the authority.Without VCSA:
No cluster
<br>No <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>/<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br>No <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
No VM lifecycle
No policy enforcement
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is powerful because it standardizes and automates many VCSAs, not because it replaces them.
VCSA = vCenter, packaged as an appliance
It is the compute control plane inside VCF
Every domain has its own VCSA
All higher-level VCF services depend on it
VCF orchestrates VCSA; it does not replace it
<br>Since VCSA is a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>, you might want to look into <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> too.<br>
You might also want to check out <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> or <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> as related components.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/VCSA.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:54:56 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://lazywinadmin.github.io/images/2013/20130401_Deploying_and_Configuring_vCenter_Server_Appliance_5.1/VMware-vCenter-Topology__452693609__-600x400.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com" length="0" type="application/x-msdownload"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://lazywinadmin.github.io/images/2013/20130401_Deploying_and_Configuring_vCenter_Server_Appliance_5.1/VMware-vCenter-Topology__452693609__-600x400.jpg?utm_source=chatgpt.com&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCenter Server]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VCSA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>vCenter&nbsp;is the service through which you manage multiple hosts connected in a network pool host resources.<br>vCenter Server runs as a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> (<a data-href="VCSA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>)—a prebuilt VM—on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.Concretely:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> is not bare metal
It is deployed as an OVA
That OVA becomes one VM (sometimes functionally “a group of services”, but still a single VM)
Internally, that VM runs:
A hardened Linux-based OS
vCenter services
Database (embedded or external, depending on scale)
Physical hardware
└── ESX └── vCenter Server Appliance (VM) └── vCenter services vCenter Server is the centralized control plane
Manages: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
<br><a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
Policies Orchestrates: <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
Lifecycle <br><img alt="ESXi-vs-vSphere-vs-vCenter-overview.png.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/esxi-vs-vsphere-vs-vcenter-overview.png.webp" target="_self"><br>vCenter Server does not run workloads: it tells <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> what to do instead.<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br>Connects many <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.
Maintains inventory and state
<br>Enforces <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">cluster-level</a> logic.
Orchestrates features that require coordination. <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> between hosts
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> placement decisions
<br>Cluster <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> (for Kubernetes / VCF) <br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> is a set of backend services:
Inventory (hosts, clusters, VMs)
State and configuration database
<br>Scheduling logic (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>)
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> coordination
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> orchestration
RBAC, roles, permissions
APIs (REST, SOAP)
<br><img alt="What-is-VMware-vSphere-vSphere-Client.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.jpg" target="_self"><br>See <a data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a> for how a UI is served around the vCenter capabilities.You might want to check:
<br><a data-href="VCSA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>, which is directly-related to vCenter,
<br>or <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, which is the Type-1 Hypervisor that everything runs on
<br>or <a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>, if you are in a networking mood.
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/vCenter Server.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:54:21 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/esxi-vs-vsphere-vs-vcenter-overview.png.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/esxi-vs-vsphere-vs-vcenter-overview.png.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[ESX]]></title><description><![CDATA[ESX is the virtualization platform where you create and run <a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s and <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>s, Kubernetes <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a>s, and AI/ML <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload</a>s.&nbsp;
ESX is a Type-1 (bare-metal) hypervisor
Runs directly on hardware
Owns: CPU scheduling
Memory management
Device virtualization Does not coordinate clusters by itself
You can run standalone ESX without vCenter, but:
No clustering
<br>No <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
<br>No <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br>No <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> orchestration
ESX is a hypervisor, it is not a traditional Linux OS.<br>In <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, there is no general-purpose userland like you’d expect in Linux or Windows.ESX is a purpose-built, bare-metal hypervisor operating system whose kernel (VMKernel) directly manages hardware resources and runs virtual machines.<br>Exploring the relationship between <a data-href="vSphere, ESX, and vCenter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere, ESX, and vCenter</a> may clarify some of of the dangling question marks, if you have any.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/ESX.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:52:41 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere, ESX, and vCenter]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>Saying “vSphere is ‘‘ESX and vCenter’’” is colloquially common, but technically incomplete.Because vSphere is a platform, it is NOT a single product.Or, to put more simply: “*There is nothing you can curl called vSphere*; similar to “*there is nothing that you can curl called AWS or Azure”.<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> is VMware’s virtualization platform built on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts managed by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, together providing cluster-level services such as <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, and Kubernetes integration.But still, that term is mostly, contextually “good enough” because, in practice:
You never run production vSphere without vCenter
ESX alone is just a hypervisor, not a platform; and it is very limited
vCenter alone does nothing
<br><img alt="what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" target="_self"><br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> includes:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> is the bare-metal hypervisor.
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> provides centralized management.
Platform features: <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> (live VM migration)
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> / <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>es
Storage policies
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> <br>
You cannot have <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> without <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
You can have <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> without <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> (but it will be very limited).
<br>For more information about what vSphere controls and manages, you might want to see <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> and <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>. After that, your next step could be to check out <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> and see how it enables declarative management of these constructs.<br>Exploring <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> might be the next logical area to navigate from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/Component Relationships/vSphere, ESX, and vCenter.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:51:55 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Client]]></title><description><![CDATA[vSphere Client is:
A Web UI (HTML / JS)
Running inside either <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> (embedded) or <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Consuming backend APIs
It consumes REST and legacy SOAP / internal APIs
Functionally: It is an API consumer
It behaves differently depending on where it is placed:
Same UI codebase:
Connected to ESX → host-scoped
Connected to vCenter Server → environment-scoped
The UI is not “smart”: The backend defines reality.<br>There is exactly ONE UI name (“<a data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a>”), but it can connect to TWO different backends.
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> Hosts
## Mode 1
Browser ↓
ESX Host ↓
Embedded vSphere Client ## Mode 2
Browser ↓
vCenter Server ↓
vSphere Client ↓
Many ESX hosts
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, one of the core components that makes vSphere, vSphere.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Access and Interfaces/vSphere Client.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:50:21 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Distributed Virtual Switch]]></title><description><![CDATA[In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, a Distributed Virtual Switch (DVS) is the standard, centralized virtual networking fabric used across <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts in a <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>.<br>Distributed Virtual Switch is a cluster-wide virtual switch that provides consistent networking configuration across all <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.
It centralizes network policy (port groups, uplinks, security, QoS) instead of configuring each host individually.VCF standardizes on VDS as the baseline virtual networking fabric.<br><img alt="vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" target="_self"><br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, a Distributed Virtual Switch is the mandatory, centrally managed L2 networking fabric that ensures every <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host behaves identically so that <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, lifecycle management, and <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> can work reliably at scale.DVS provides consistent networking configuration, policy enforcement, and operational control at scale—something VCF depends on to behave predictably.DVS can be seen as:<br>
One logical network switch that spans many <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts,
configured once, and applied everywhere.
<br>Instead of configuring networking host-by-host, you configure it centrally, and every participating <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host follows that definition.VCF is opinionated and automated. Networking must be:
Deterministic
Centrally managed
<br>Compatible with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">lifecycle automation</a>
Consistent across hosts and clusters
That’s why VCF mandates DVS (not standard vSwitches) for system and workload networking.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts do not own the switch config — vCenter does.
VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── vCenter Server └── vSphere Distributed Switch (VDS) ├── ESX Host A ├── ESX Host B └── ESX Host C └── Port Groups → VM vNICs Centralized L2 switching
Consistent port group configuration
NIC teaming &amp; uplinks
Traffic shaping, security, VLAN tagging
Host lifecycle safety (no per-host drift) “One virtual switch, shared by the whole cluster.”
A Distributed Port Group defines:
VLAN ID(s)
Security policies (promiscuous mode, MAC changes)
Traffic shaping
Teaming / failover
VM vNICs attach to port groups, not directly to the switch.
❌ Not a router (no L3)
<br>❌ Not an <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>
❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not optional in VCF
VCF automation (bring-up, scaling, patching, upgrades) assumes:A standard vSwitch breaks all of this because it is host-local and imperative.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> has a predefined VDS
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s get their own VDS
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> transport zones bind to VDS uplinks
Lifecycle (patching, expansion) assumes VDS presence
<br>You rarely “design” VDS in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>—it is opinionated and enforced.Typical VCF DVS port groups include:
Management
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<<<<<<< HEAD
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Host TEPs VM networks (VLAN-backed)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> / Kubernetes traffic (when applicable)
VCF may create multiple DVS instances, for example:
One for system domain
One per workload domain <br>DVS ≠ <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
DVS provides L2 switching
NSX builds overlay networking (Geneve tunnels, logical segments) on top of DVS
You can have:
<br>DVS without NSX (<a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>-backed networking)
<br>However, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> requires DVS underneath
So DVS is the foundational substrate, not the SDN layer.
DVS = underlay L2 switch
NSX = overlay (L3) networking NSX creates overlay segments
Overlay traffic is encapsulated (GENEVE)
Encapsulated packets ride over VDS uplinks NSX does not replace VDS—it depends on it.
If DVS is:<br>
“A shared Ethernet switch for <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts”
<br>Then <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> is:
“A logical network built on top of that switch.”
Different layers, different jobs.
DVS is a control-plane object <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> caches its config locally, but authority lives in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> If vCenter is temporarily unavailable Traffic keeps flowing
You just can’t change switch config VCF LCM expects DVS invariants Port groups, uplinks, MTU, and teaming must match what SDDC Manager expects DVS is not optional in VCF VDS is the foundational virtual switch in VCF It is owned by vCenter, not hosts
It enables automation, scale, and consistency
Provides centralized, cluster-wide L2 networking
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> depends on it, but it is not NSX itself NSX overlays run on top of VDS, not instead of it Standard vSwitches are fundamentally incompatible with VCF’s design goals
<br>Diving into <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> might be the next logical step from here. Or maybe <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> (Cloud Native Storage), could be something fun to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/Distributed Virtual Switch.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:49:37 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[CNS]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br><img alt="cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp" target="_self">CNS (Cloud Native Storage) is the vSphere capability that makes Kubernetes storage first-class and lifecycle-aware.<br>
It bridges Kubernetes PersistentVolumes with vSphere storage (typically <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>) so that Kubernetes, not admins, drives volume lifecycle, while <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> retains visibility, <a data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy</a>, and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.<br>VCF relies on CNS wherever Kubernetes (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Cluster" data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> or <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">guest clusters</a>) consumes vSphere storage.VCF
├── vSphere
│ ├── vCenter Server
│ │ └── CNS (storage awareness &amp; lifecycle)
│ ├── vSAN / VMFS / NFS
│ └── ESX
│
└── Kubernetes ├── Supervisor Cluster └── Guest Clusters (VKS) └── PVC → PV → vSphere Volume <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Integrated via: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> CSI Driver
<br>Observed/managed in: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
Without CNS:
Kubernetes creates volumes
vSphere sees “random disks”
No linkage, no lifecycle alignment
With CNS:
<br>Kubernetes objects ↔ <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> volumes are linked
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> understands which PVC belongs to which pod
Storage policy, health, and cleanup are automatic CNS makes Kubernetes storage visible, governable, and safe in vSphere. Lifecycle Mapping <br>PVC create/delete ↔ <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> volume create/delete Topology Awareness Knows which cluster, namespace, pod owns a volume Policy Enforcement <br>Applies <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> Storage Policies (SPBM) Operational Visibility <br>Shows Kubernetes volumes in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Client" data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter UI</a> &amp; APIs Kubernetes creates a PVC
CSI driver requests a volume
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> provisions storage (<a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>)
CNS records: Kubernetes metadata
Volume ownership On PVC delete → CNS ensures correct cleanup
<br>Kubernetes stays declarative; <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> stays authoritative.
CNS is always on
StorageClasses map directly to vSphere policies CNS operates via CSI
<br>Still centrally visible in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Same mechanism, different consumption layers.
❌ Not a storage array
❌ Not a CSI driver itself
❌ Not Kubernetes-only
❌ Not a replacement for vSAN
CNS is the glue, not the storage.If CSI is:
“The driver that talks to storage”
Then CNS is:<br>
“The brain that understands Kubernetes intent inside <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>” Enables policy-driven storage for containers
Prevents orphaned volumes
Makes Kubernetes operationally sane for infra teams
Required for supported VCF Kubernetes designs CNS = Cloud Native Storage awareness in vSphere
Aligns Kubernetes volume lifecycle with vSphere
Essential for Supervisor &amp; TKG clusters in VCF- Turns storage into a first-class Kubernetes citizen
<br>Control plane elements, like <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> and <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> and two possible places to jump from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/CNS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:48:21 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/cns-d2cb2ded-080e-4cf9-85fa-2e56c8719e7a.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX Manager]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br><img alt="nsx-manager-NSX-2.1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png" target="_self"><br>NSX Manager is the central management and control plane for <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>. It defines, stores, and enforces software-defined networking and security policy (switching, routing, firewalling) across the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> environment.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, NSX Manager is mandatory wherever <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> is used and is deployed and lifecycle-managed by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.<br><img alt="nsx-manager-nsx-components.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-components.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation
├── Management Domain
│ └── NSX Manager (3-node cluster)
│
└── Workload Domains └── NSX Data Plane (transport nodes) Role: Management and policy authority Not a data-path component <br>Consumes: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> inventory, clusters, hosts Policy management Segments (logical networks)
Tier-0 / Tier-1 gateways (routing)
Distributed Firewall (DFW) rules Control-plane orchestration Pushes intent to hosts and edges Inventory and Topology Knows which workloads live where API and UI Single source of truth for NSX state <br>NSX Manager is the “brain” of <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>.If NSX Manager goes down:
Existing traffic continues
No new changes can be made until it returns
NSX Manager is typically deployed as:
3-node cluster
Quorum-based
<br>Protected by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> Loss of one node → no impact
Loss of quorum → management freeze, not traffic loss VCF:
Deploys NSX Manager automatically
Enforces supported topologies
Handles upgrades, certificates, backups
Assumes NSX Manager is always present ❌ Not a router forwarding packets
❌ Not a firewall datapath
❌ Not optional in NSX-based VCF designs
❌ Not workload-aware beyond policy intent
If vCenter is:
“What compute exists and where?”
Then NSX Manager is:
“How workloads may talk to each other, and who is allowed.” NSX Manager is the control plane of NSX
It defines networking and security intent
Traffic keeps flowing without it, but change stops
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, it is foundational and non-optional when NSX is used
<br>Check out <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a> for another related networking concept.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/NSX Manager.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:46:50 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-manager-nsx-2.1.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX Edge Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br><img alt="nsx-edge-t1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png" target="_self">An NSX Edge Cluster is a pool of dedicated NSX Edge Nodes that handle north–south traffic and advanced network services (routing, NAT, load balancing, VPN, firewall at the perimeter).
North–south routing Tier-0 Gateways (uplink to physical network)
Tier-1 Gateways (tenant / app routing) Perimeter services NAT
L4–L7 Load Balancing
VPN (IPsec, L2VPN)
Gateway firewalling High throughput datapath Optimized for packet forwarding
<br>Separate from <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host dataplane ❌ It does not run workloads
<br>❌ It does not manage policy (that’s <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>)
❌ It does not replace distributed firewall (DFW)
VCF
├── vSphere Cluster (compute)
│ └── Workload VMs
│ └── East–West traffic (DFW on ESX)
│
├── NSX Edge Cluster
│ └── North–South traffic
│ ├── Tier-0 Gateway
│ └── Services (NAT, LB, VPN)
│
└── NSX Manager └── Policy &amp; control plane
<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts = east–west
NSX Edge Nodes = north–south Edge nodes are deployed as VMs
Grouped into Edge Clusters
Services can be: Active/Active (ECMP)
Active/Standby <br>Protected by <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
Scaled horizontally by adding Edge Nodes NSX Edge Cluster = NSX’s north–south dataplane
It handles routing, NAT, LB, VPN, perimeter firewalling
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, Edge Clusters are foundational for routed, multi-tenant designs
<br>Why not check out <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>s?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/NSX Edge Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:45:57 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-edge-t1.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>NSX enables network connectivity, operations, and scale. It uses a software-defined approach to networking that spans data centers, clouds and application frameworks.NSX abstracts network services from the underlying hardware, enabling programmable infrastructure through APIs. You can implement policies and workflows to automate tasks like network provisioning, security enforcement, load balancing, streamlining operations, and improving efficiency.NSX provides a complete set of logical networking capabilities and services, including logical switching, routing, distributed load balancing, virtual private network (VPN), quality of service (QoS), and monitoring.Enable logical Layer 2 overlay extensions across a routed (Layer 3) fabric within and across data center boundaries.Dynamic routing between virtual networks that is performed in a distributed manner in the hypervisor kernel, and scale-out routing with active-active failover with physical routers. Static routing and dynamic routing protocols are supported, including support for IPv6.Complete data plane isolation among tenants with a separate routing table, network address translation (NAT), and edge firewall support in each VRF on the&nbsp;Support for bridging between VLANs configured on the physical network and&nbsp;NSX overlay networks, for seamless connectivity between virtual and physical workloads.Site-to-site and unmanaged VPN for cloud gateway services.By using&nbsp;NSX, you can move workloads between racks and data centers by decoupling them from the underlying networks.Centralized policy configuration and enforcement across multiple locations from a single pane of glass, enabling network-wide consistent policy, operational simplicity, and simplified disaster recovery architecture.Enable consistent networking and security across data center sites, and across private cloud boundaries, irrespective of underlying physical topology or cloud platform.NSX can manage the provisioning, deployment, operations and retirement of networking infrastructure and applications from a central control pane.<br>You can automate infrastructure operations and offload manual tasks with workflows and agile templating using tools such as&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, Terraform, and Ansible.&nbsp;<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>s provide isolated network environments within a shared infrastructure. You can use Virtual Private Cloud (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>) constructs to provision and manage network resources to business units or project teams independently, with granular control over networking policies and resource allocation.<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> for a more technical overview about NSX internal, or look at <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, or <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/NSX.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:45:01 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[NSX Segment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="nsx-segment-NSX-5.1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png" target="_self"><br>An NSX Segment is a logical Layer-2 network in <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>.<br>
It is where workloads (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMs</a>, containers) attach their NICs, just like plugging into a virtual switch—except it’s policy-driven, distributed, and decoupled from physical <a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>s.<br><img alt="nsx-segment-Screen-Shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-PM-1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-screen-shot-2018-01-12-at-1.44.50-pm-1.png" target="_self">VCF
├── vSphere (compute)
│ └── VMs / Pods
│ └── vNIC
│ └── NSX Segment (L2)
│ └── Tier-1 Gateway (L3, optional)
│ └── Tier-0 Gateway → Physical network
└── NSX Manager (policy &amp; control) <br>Defined in: <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br>Enforced on: <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts (distributed dataplane)
Consumes: Overlay networking (GENEVE) Provides L2 connectivity between attached workloads
Enables east–west traffic within the segment
Acts as the policy anchor for: Distributed Firewall (DFW)
DHCP (optional)
MAC/IP learning and isolation NSX Segment is:
“A virtual Ethernet network with cloud-native policy.”
NSX Segments remove VLAN sprawl and enable fine-grained security.
Pure L2 broadcast domain
No routing out
Common for isolated tiers L3 routing enabled
North–south possible via Tier-0
<br>Most common in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> DFW rules are applied to vNICs on segments
Security is identity-and policy-based, not subnet-based
Zero-trust patterns become practical The segment is not the security boundary—the workload is.
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
Segments are first-class networking objects
Used by: VM workloads
Kubernetes (via NSX CNI)
<br>Automation <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s <br>Lifecycle managed and validated by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
You don’t hand-craft switch configs; you declare intent.If vSphere Port Group is:
“A virtual switch tied to a VLAN”
Then NSX Segment is:
“A logical network with built-in policy, security, and mobility” ❌ Not a physical network
❌ Not a tenant boundary
❌ Not a router
❌ Not Kubernetes-specific (but integrates cleanly) NSX Segment = logical L2 network
Attaches workloads and anchors security policy
<br>Decoupled from physical <a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>s
<br>Foundational to zero-trust networking in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
<br>You can check out <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> and <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> which are other related networking topics.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/NSX/Object Model/NSX Segment.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:44:12 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/nsx-segment-nsx-5.1.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><img alt="vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" target="_self">VCF Operations&nbsp;helps your organization build, manage, operate and secure your private cloud infrastructure by deploying and maintaining its fleet-level components, providing visibility and enhanced performance across the workload and infrastructure stack, and helping your organization stay compliant with regulatory standards and organizational guidelines.VCF Operations has these functional areas:
<br><a data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fleet Management</a> Enables operational consistency and efficient resource management of the&nbsp;VCF infrastructure at scale. <br><a data-href="Operations Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operations Management</a> Provides monitoring and optimization of performance, cost and capacity, and faster troubleshooting. <br><a data-href="Workload Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Operations</a> &nbsp;Ensures that critical applications are running as expected. <br><a data-href="Performance Monitoring" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Performance Monitoring</a> Ensures applications have continuous access to resources <br><a data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">FinOps and Capacity</a> Helps you analyze your infrastructure expenses and optimize capacity usage. <br><a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a> Provides support for migrating and interconnecting workloads within and across VCF private cloud. <br><a data-href="Security Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/security-and-compliance/security-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Security Management</a> Provides security management to ensure that your VCF private cloud is operationally secure. VCF Operations does not:
Own tenancy boundaries
Gate workload creation
Enforce business approval flows
Define org/project constructs
Those remain in:
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>
Upstream automation layers
VCF Operations observes those constructs after the fact.Day 0 / Day 1 → VCF-A - Who can create? - What can be created? - Under what policies? Day 2 → VCF-O - Is it healthy? - Is it over/under-utilized? - Is it behaving strangely?
Here is a very high-level look at VCF’s control plane:VCF (the platform)
├── VCF Automation (formerly Aria Automation)
├── VCF Operations (formerly Aria Operations)
├── Supervisor / vSphere
└── Workloads
Here is how things looks from each layer’s point of view:<br>Once a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload cluster</a> is instantiated in a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, it has no awareness of <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> constructs such as Organization or Project—Those concepts exist only at the governance layer (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>) and are not part of the runtime execution model (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>).<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Operations Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operations Management</a>, <a data-href="Performance Monitoring" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html" class="intern