built into <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>. It combines the power of VMware Hybrid Cloud Extension (HCX) with VCF’s operational tooling to simplify application migration, workload rebalancing, and business continuity across data centers and clouds.You can perform secure and automated migrations without requiring changes to applications or network configurations.Thus, you can place workloads based on business requirements. The platform minimizes downtime during migrations, improves scalability, and supports compliance and security throughout workload transitions.<br>HCX stands for Hybrid Cloud eXtension—it’s not just another name for <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>. It’s a comprehensive application mobility platform from VMware that enables workload migration, workload rebalancing, and business continuity across data centers and clouds.VCF Operations HCX has the following capabilities:
Seamless workload migration. Migrate VMs and applications in waves live or in bulk with minimal or zero downtime.
Network extension. Extend networks while preserving IP addresses and topologies to maintain application connectivity.
Inter-and intra-VCF mobility. Enable workload mobility within and across multiple&nbsp;VCF instances, including site-to-site and region-to-region migrations.
Application placement optimization. Enables high-performance application mobility across different environments, making it easier to optimize workload placement based on business requirements.
At its heart, VCF Operations HCX is an application mobility platform that:
**Connects environments—on-premises data centers, private clouds, and public clouds—with optimized, secure network interconnectivity.
Enables workload migration—live or bulk migration of virtual machines (VMs) and applications between environments with minimal downtime.
Supports hybrid cloud adoption—making it easier to modernize, consolidate, or balance workloads across sites.
Essentially, it extends the capabilities of VCF so that moving workloads into, out of, or around your VCF estate is seamless and automated.VCF Operations HCX automates the process of moving VMs and applications from one environment to another. This includes:
Live migrations (zero or near-zero downtime)
Bulk migrations for large-scale moves
Cross-platform migrations (including non-vSphere sources in some scenarios)
Network extension so IPs/MACs remain consistent during migration
This makes migrations faster, less error-prone, and less disruptive than traditional approaches.HCX builds a secure, encrypted interconnect between sites that:
Extends Layer-2 networks across sites
Preserves VM networking so that workloads keep their addresses
Provides optimized tunnels tailored for high-speed bulk movement
Cloud adoption isn’t a one-time event — usage patterns change. HCX enables:
Moving workloads based on performance needs
Rebalancing for cost or compliance reasons
Continuous optimization of where workloads run
This is key in hybrid environments where business needs or performance requirements evolve over time.VCF Operations HCX has deeper integration with VCF:
Unified management &amp; single sign-on with other VCF components
Shared licensing managed through VCF Operations
Integrated planning &amp; execution workflows with VCF Operations for Networks
Easier deployment with a single unified HCX Manager appliance
That means less separate manual setup and a smoother experience from discovery to execution.Imagine you’re relocating a city’s services (libraries, police stations, hospitals) to a new smart city:
Traditional migration = manually moving each building piece by piece.
VCF Operations HCX = building a dedicated transit corridor where services can shift live without interruption, while preserving all their connections and addresses — all orchestrated by a central operations dashboard instead of manual labor.
<br>vMotion is VMware’s native live-migration technology for moving a running VM between <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts (including memory and CPU state), usually within the same <a data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Domain</a> or cluster.HCX doesn’t replace vMotion; it leverages it as one migration method (called “HCX vMotion”) when moving workloads between HCX-connected sites. It also supports:
Cold Migration: Powered-off VMs
Bulk Migration: Parallel, batched workloads
Replication-Assisted vMotion: Parallel live migrations via replication + vMotion
So, vMotion is a component inside HCX’s larger orchestration and connectivity framework. VCF Operations HCX is VMware’s integrated workload mobility solution within VMware Cloud Foundation.
It simplifies application migration and workload rebalancing across on-prem, hybrid, and multi-cloud environments.
Via optimized network extension and interconnects, it preserves application connectivity and minimizes disruption.
Recent integrations with VCF improve deployment, management, and operational workflows.
