<br>If <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> is:
“What exists and how it runs”
Then Usage Meter is:
“What you should be billed for” Low resource footprint
Read-only access
Typically one per environment (or per domain)
Periodic export / reporting cadence
It is intentionally boring and predictable — by design.
VCF Usage Meter = billing-grade consumption measurement
<br>Tracks real usage across <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
Required for subscription reporting &amp; compliance
Not involved in runtime, placement, or enforcement
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a> which makes hypercloud mobility as boring as it can get (which is a good thing).]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-usage-meter.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Usage, Metering, and Business Ops/VCF Usage Meter.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:39:37 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/usage-meter-screen-shot-2021-05-04-at-4.21.08-pm-1024x438.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/usage-meter-screen-shot-2021-05-04-at-4.21.08-pm-1024x438.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Business Services Console]]></title><description><![CDATA[See also: <a data-href="Cloud Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/cloud-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services Console</a><br><img alt="vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" target="_self"><br>VCF Business Services Console are cloud service that provides the ability to manage VCF Usage, meter <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">appliances</a>, <a data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">User Roles</a>, and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Resource Pool" data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">resource access</a>.VCF Business Services Console (BSC) is the business-facing control plane for VCF that focuses on commercial governance, not infrastructure operations. It provides tenancy, subscription, entitlement, and usage visibility across organizations and projects.If vCenter answers “what is running?”, BSC answers:
“Who is entitled to what, who is using it, and how should it be charged?”
VCF
├── Infrastructure &amp; Ops
│ ├── vCenter / ESX
│ ├── NSX / vSAN
│ └── VCF Automation
│
<<<<<<< HEAD
├── Metering
│ └── Usage Meter
│
└── Business Layer └── Business Services Console ├── Organizations ├── Subscriptions ├── Entitlements └── Usage visibility Audience: Platform owners, cloud business teams, service providers
Not for day-to-day infrastructure operators <br>Defines <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s as commercial entities
Associates: Subscriptions
Entitlements
Usage views This is a business boundary, not a technical one.
Tracks which orgs are entitled to: VCF capacity
Optional components (NSX, vSAN, etc.) Aligns commercial contracts with technical consumption
BSC does not provision resources — it governs access.
<br>Consumes data from <a data-href="VCF Usage Meter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-usage-meter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Usage Meter</a>
Presents usage in: Business-friendly terms
Aggregated per org / subscription Enables showback / chargeback workflows
Especially relevant for:
Internal private clouds with multiple business units
Service providers offering VCF-based services
BSC gives a single pane of glass for business accountability.BSC is governance and visibility, not execution.Think of BSC as:
The billing and entitlement desk of your private cloud Not the data center.
Not the scheduler.
Not the automation engine.
With subscription-based licensing:
“Installed” ≠ “Billable”
“Running” ≠ “Entitled”
BSC:
Bridges commercial reality and technical usage
Makes private cloud operate more like a public cloud business Cloud platform owners
Finance / FinOps teams
Service provider admins
Business unit IT leads
Rarely: day-to-day SREs.
VCF Business Services Console is the business control plane
Manages organizations, subscriptions, and entitlements
Consumes (but does not generate) usage data
Complements Usage Meter and VCF Automation
Essential for multi-tenant, subscription-driven VCF deployments
<br>Why not check out <a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a>, <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>, or <a data-href="VMware Live Recovery" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmware-live-recovery.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Live Recovery</a>?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Usage, Metering, and Business Ops/VCF Business Services Console.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:38:53 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-business-services-featured-image.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cloud Services Console]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>, <a data-href="VCF Business Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Business Services Console</a><br><img alt="csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" target="_self">Cloud Services Console is VMware’s SaaS control plane for identity, organizations, subscriptions, and service access across VMware cloud offerings.<br>If <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> answers “what is running?”, CSC answers:
“Who are you, what are you entitled to, and which VMware services can you access?”
<br><img alt="csc-featured-image.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-featured-image.png" target="_self">VMware SaaS Layer
└── Cloud Services Console (CSC) ├── Identity and Org management ├── Subscriptions &amp; entitlements └── Access to VMware cloud services On-prem / Private Cloud
└── VCF ├── vSphere / NSX / vSAN └── SDDC Manager
CSC:
Runs as: VMware-hosted SaaS
Audience: Org owners, platform leads, service-provider admins
Does not touch datapaths or place workloads Defines Organizations
Manages users, roles, and access
Integrates with enterprise IdPs (SSO)
<br>This is business identity, not <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> RBAC.
Shows what your org is entitled to: VCF subscriptions
Optional VMware services Central place to view contracts → services
CSC does not meter usage—that’s elsewhere.From CSC you access:
Support portals
VMware cloud SaaS
Management consoles (where applicable)
CSC is the front door, not the engine room.<br>CSC ≠ <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Business Services Console" data-href="VCF Business Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">BSC</a>
CSC is VMware-global; BSC is VCF-specific.
CSC knows about your subscriptions
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> consumes those entitlements
CSC does not: Provision domains
Run LCM
Enforce quotas
Observe performance <br>That work stays on-prem with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> components.
Not part of the VCF runtime
Not an ops or automation tool
Not a billing/metering engine
Not a tenant boundary for workloads
If VCF is:
“Your private cloud platform”
Then CSC is:
“Your VMware account and service access hub” Cloud Services Console = SaaS identity and entitlement layer
Global across VMware services
<br>Adjacent to <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, not embedded in it
<br>Often confused with <a data-href="VCF Business Services Console" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/usage,-metering,-and-business-ops/vcf-business-services-console.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Business Services Console</a>—they serve different roles
