<br><a data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 0 Tasks</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/cloud-services-console.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Managing the Cloud/Cloud Services Console.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:38:03 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/csc-vmc-accounts_roles_02.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Operations Orchestrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows</a>VCF Operations Orchestrator provides a library of workflows that perform common management tasks. VCF Operations Orchestrator also provides libraries of the individual actions that the workflows perform.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s combine actions, decisions, and results that, when performed in a particular order, finish a specific task or a specific process in a virtual environment.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s perform tasks such as provisioning virtual machines, backing up, performing regular maintenance, sending emails, performing SSH operations, managing the physical infrastructure, and other general utility operations. Workflows accept inputs according to their function.<br>You can create <a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s that run according to defined schedules, or that run if certain anticipated events occur.Information can be provided by you, by other users, by another workflow or action, or by an external process such as a Web service call from an application.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s perform some validation and filtering of information before they run.<br><a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s can be chained. That is, they can call upon other workflows. For example, you can have workflow that calls up another workflow to create a new virtual machine.You create workflows by using the&nbsp;VCF Operations Orchestrator’s integrated development environment (IDE), that provides access to the workflow library and the ability to run workflows on the workflow engine.The workflow engine can also take objects from external libraries that you plug in to&nbsp;the VCF Operations Orchestrator. This allows you to customize processes or implement functions that third-party applications provide.<br>Why not check out, <a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s, or maybe <a data-href="Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows</a>?]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/VCF Operations Orchestrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:36:36 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a><br><a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> <a data-href="Workflow" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workflow</a>s run according to a logical flow of events.When you run a workflow, each schema element in the workflow runs according to the following sequence.
The workflow binds the workflow token variables and input parameters to the input parameters of the schema element.
The schema element runs.
The output parameters of the schema element are copied to the workflow token variables and workflow output parameters.
The workflow token variables and workflow output parameters are stored in the database.
The next schema element starts running.
This sequence repeats for each schema element until the end of the workflow.<br>When a workflow runs, each schema element is a check point. After each schema element runs,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> stores workflow token variables in the database, and the next schema element starts running.If the workflow stops unexpectedly, the next time the Orchestrator Server restarts, the currently active schema element runs again, and the workflow continues from the start of the schema element that was running when the interruption occurred.<br>That being said,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> does not implement transaction management or a rollback function.The workflow ends if the current active schema element is an end element.After the workflow reaches an end element, other workflows or applications can use the output parameters of the workflow.<br>You might like to check out <a data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fleet Management</a> or <a data-href="VMware Data Services Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-data-services-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Data Services Manager</a>, or <a data-href="VMware Skyline" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/vmware-skyline.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Skyline</a> as they tangentially relate to workflows.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:36:14 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Skyline]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br><img alt="skyline-advisor-Skyline-Screenshot.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-advisor-skyline-screenshot.png" target="_self">VMware Skyline is a proactive support and health intelligence service that continuously analyzes your VMware environment and surfaces:
Configuration risks
Known issues
Upgrade blockers
Security advisories
Best-practice deviations
It answers:
“What is likely to break, and what should I fix before it does?”
<br><img alt="skyline-f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.webp" target="_self">VCF Environment
├── vCenter / ESX
├── NSX
├── vSAN
├── SDDC Manager
│
└── Skyline ├── Telemetry collection ├── Health &amp; risk analysis └── Proactive recommendations Skyline observes the fleet — it does not control it.
Skyline is VCF-adjacent, not VCF-core.<br><img alt="skyline-ClusterHealth-Figure-01.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/skyline-clusterhealth-figure-01.png" target="_self"><br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
Skyline supports: <br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Skyline findings are especially valuable for: LCM readiness
Upgrade prechecks
Fleet hygiene Skyline correlates your environment against:
Known VMware issues
Field advisories
Support KB patterns
This is knowledge you cannot replicate locally.<br>Before you run LCM in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
Skyline can flag: Unsupported configs
Known bad upgrade paths
Latent drift issues You can think of it as:
“Support’s brain looking at your fleet before you upgrade.”
Skyline shines when:
<br>You have many <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">domains</a>
<br>You have many <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenters</a>
You want a single risk posture view
<br>This aligns naturally with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Fleet Deployment" data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet management</a>.Skyline is insight, not control.Skyline is the supportability lens.If SDDC Manager is:
“The mechanic that performs maintenance”
Then Skyline is:
