structure, security, and lifecycle control centralized.<br><img alt="dsm_deploy_small.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/dsm_deploy_small.webp" target="_self">DSM answers:
“How do we provide self-service databases without giving users raw VM access?”
VCF
├── vSphere / vSAN / NSX
├── SDDC Manager (infra lifecycle)
│
└── VMware Data Services Manager ├── Control Plane (policies, APIs, UI) └── Data Plane └── Database VMs (Postgres, MySQL, etc.)
DSM:
Runs on: VCF infrastructure
<br>Consumes: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, storage policies
Exposes: A database service interface to users
DSM is above infrastructure, below applications.
Provision databases in minutes
Automated: Day-0 setup
Day-1 operations
Day-2 patching and upgrades Consistent configurations every time
No more hand-built “special” DB VMs.
Platform team controls: VM templates
Storage policies
Network placement
Backup and security posture Application teams control: DB provisioning
Scaling (within limits)
Credentials (scoped) <br>This maps cleanly to enterprise <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">governance</a> models.Databases are deployed with:
