=======
├── Organization: Globex
│ ├── Project: Globex-Prod → Supervisor Namespace ns-globex-prod
│ └── Project: Globex-Dev → Supervisor Namespace ns-globex-dev Organizations = business tenants Projects = operational sub-tenants Namespaces = runtime enforcement It is not: Just Kubernetes namespaces Just vCenter folders Just NSX segments A single RBAC model VCF deliberately avoids one-layer tenancy, because no single layer can satisfy: Security Governance Lifecycle safety Operational clarity Isolation is compositional, not singular. Strong isolation without hardware duplication Clear separation of duties Supports enterprise and service-provider use cases Preserves lifecycle determinism Conceptually complex Multiple abstractions to understand Requires discipline in mapping orgs/projects/namespaces VCF optimizes for large-scale, regulated environments, not minimalism.But: no single analogy maps perfectly — this is a hybrid cloud model. Multi-tenancy in VCF is layered Organizations &amp; Projects define business tenancy Supervisor Namespaces enforce runtime isolation Workload Domains protect lifecycle and failure domains This design balances power, safety, and scale If you want, next we can: Walk through RBAC flows across org → project → namespace Compare VCF multi-tenancy vs pure Kubernetes Discuss anti-patterns (where people get this wrong) Map multi-tenancy to chargeback / showback models ]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/merge-me-and-replace-incoming-links-tenant-admin.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/MERGE ME AND REPLACE INCOMING LINKS Tenant Admin.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 01:33:28 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://www.cloud13.ch/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/vRealize-Automation-Enterprise-VPC.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.cloud13.ch/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/vRealize-Automation-Enterprise-VPC.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[Workload Operations focuses on ensuring that applications—whether virtual machine–based or container-based—are available, performant, and delivering the expected end-user experience. It bridges the gap between infrastructure health and actual workload behavior, allowing operators to reason about issues in terms of applications rather than underlying components.At its core, Workload Operations answer:
Is the application running correctly from the user’s point of view—and if not, where is the breakdown?
Workload Operations continuously assess whether applications are functioning as intended.
Tracks <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a> availability and responsiveness
Monitors performance indicators relevant to application behavior
Detects degradations before they escalate into outages
Distinguishes between infrastructure noise and real workload impact
This ensures operators focus on what matters to consumers, not just raw resource metrics.Beyond infrastructure signals, workload operations account for how applications are perceived by users.
Correlates performance data with service responsiveness
Helps identify issues that are invisible at the host or cluster level
Supports prioritization of incidents based on user impact
Improves alignment between platform teams and application owners
In effect, it reframes operations around service outcomes, not components.<br>For container-based applications, <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> provides native awareness of Kubernetes workloads running on the platform.
<br>Automatic discovery of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>-managed Kubernetes environments
<br>Granular visibility into vSphere Kubernetes Service (<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>) clusters
Monitoring at cluster, namespace, and workload levels
Correlation between container behavior and underlying infrastructure signals
This tight integration eliminates blind spots that traditionally exist between virtualization and Kubernetes operations.By correlating workload-level symptoms with infrastructure-level signals, workload operations significantly shorten troubleshooting cycles.
Rapid isolation of whether issues originate in compute, storage, networking, or the application layer
Reduced hand-offs between infrastructure and platform teams
Faster root-cause identification for mixed VM and container environments
Improved mean time to resolution (MTTR)
Instead of “ping-pong debugging,” operators get end-to-end context.Workload Operations is:
Application-centric rather than component-centric
Equally applicable to VM-based and container-based workloads
Focused on availability, performance, and user impact
Workload Operations is not:
A deployment or CI/CD system
A replacement for application-level instrumentation
A tenant self-service or governance mechanism Workload Operations shift operational focus from infrastructure health to application outcomes
Native integration with Supervisor and VKS enables deep visibility for Kubernetes workloads
Correlated insights reduce troubleshooting time and operational friction
The end goal is reliable applications with predictable user experience, not just healthy infrastructure
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Observability and Health/Workload Operations.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 01:26:49 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Security Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[The Security Management area of <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> includes capabilities such as Security Operations, Event Auditing, and Compliance Checks.
