Certificates
AI workloads
<br>Additionally, application teams can also provision resources on a self-service basis from Catalogs which are backed by pre-configured <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Blueprint" data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload template</a>s.These self-service options help developers focus on application development instead of managing the underlying infrastructure.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VCF Automation”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Cloud Services/Cloud Services.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:31:25 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Performance Monitoring]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br>Performance Monitoring within <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> focuses on ensuring applications and platform services consistently receive the resources they need—while enabling rapid detection, diagnosis, and resolution of performance issues.Rather than relying solely on static thresholds or isolated metrics, performance monitoring leverages continuous telemetry and analytics to understand how workloads behave over time, identify anomalies, and surface emerging risks before they impact users or SLAs.In practical terms, it answers:
Are my applications getting the resources they expect, and if not—why?
Performance Monitoring collects and analyzes application-level metrics from virtual machines and supporting infrastructure.
CPU, memory, disk, and network utilization
Latency, throughput, and contention indicators
Performance baselines derived from historical behavior
Correlation between application performance and infrastructure conditions
This shifts the perspective from “is the host healthy?” to “is the application experiencing friction?”Advanced Analytics and machine learning are applied to identify patterns and anomalies that traditional monitoring often misses.
Detects abnormal behavior relative to learned baselines
Correlates symptoms across compute, storage, and networking layers
Highlights probable root causes rather than isolated alerts
Enables faster time to resolution while avoiding unnecessary overprovisioning
The result is signal over noise, especially in large or dynamic environments.Performance Monitoring ensures workloads maintain reliable access to required resources.
Identifies resource contention and saturation risks
Surfaces inefficient resource usage and imbalance
Supports proactive scaling and right-sizing decisions
Helps balance performance objectives against cost efficiency
This allows operators to protect performance without defaulting to over-allocation.A VCF Operations management pack is a modular integration that extends monitoring and analytics to specific infrastructure or platform components.
Collects metrics, events, and alerts from integrated systems
Normalizes telemetry into a common operational model
Enables deep, component-aware performance analysis
Supports consistent monitoring across heterogeneous environments
Management packs are what allow VCF Operations to scale from generic monitoring into domain-aware performance intelligence.Performance Monitoring is:
Application-aware and infrastructure-correlated
Predictive and analytics-driven
Focused on sustained performance and efficiency
Performance Monitoring is not:
Simple threshold-based alerting
A standalone APM tool
A workload deployment or governance mechanism Performance Monitoring ensures applications continuously receive the resources they need
AI-driven analytics reduce noise and accelerate root-cause analysis
Management packs enable deep, system-specific insights at scale
The goal is sustained performance and cost discipline—not just uptime
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Observability and Health/Performance Monitoring.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:30:12 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Operations Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> delivers the observability, analytics, and operational intelligence layer for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> environments. It focuses on understanding system behavior, maintaining platform health, and enabling proactive operations across compute, storage, and networking—both in real time and over longer planning horizons.<br>Where <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> answers “what should be deployed and governed?”,<br>
<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> answers “how is the platform behaving, and where are risks emerging?”VCF Operations continuously ingests telemetry, events, metrics, and logs from across the VCF stack to provide operators with actionable insights rather than raw data.Provides a holistic, continuously evaluated view of platform health across domains and components.
Validates configuration consistency against VMware best practices
Detects drift, misconfigurations, and version incompatibilities
Surfaces health scores and risk indicators at fleet, domain, and component levels
Helps operators move from reactive firefighting to preventive maintenance
This provides a continuous “wellness check” for the entire VCF environment.Enables rapid root-cause analysis when issues arise.
Correlates symptoms across compute, storage, and networking layers
Analyzes historical trends to distinguish transient issues from systemic problems
Provides guided troubleshooting workflows and impact analysis
Reduces mean time to detect (MTTD) and mean time to resolution (MTTR)
Instead of isolated alerts, diagnostics focus on cause-and-effect relationships.Centralizes and contextualizes logs generated across the VCF stack.
Aggregates logs from infrastructure and platform components
Enables search, filtering, and correlation across time and services
Supports security investigations, audits, and post-incident analysis
Complements metrics-based monitoring with forensic-level visibility
Logs become evidence, not noise.Monitors and analyzes the health, performance, and behavior of networking components.
Tracks latency, packet loss, throughput, and flow patterns
Detects anomalies and deviations from normal traffic behavior
Helps identify bottlenecks, misrouted traffic, and configuration issues
Provides visibility across logical and physical networking layers
This bridges the traditional gap between virtual networking abstractions and real network behavior.Delivers insight into capacity, performance, and reliability of storage resources.
Monitors IOPS, latency, throughput, and utilization trends
Predicts capacity exhaustion and performance degradation
Identifies imbalanced workloads and storage hotspots
Supports informed decisions around scaling and optimization
Storage operations turn capacity planning from guesswork into data-driven forecasting.<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> is:
Observability and operational intelligence
Predictive and preventive rather than purely reactive
Focused on platform behavior and risk
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> is not:
A workload deployment or provisioning system
A policy enforcement or approval engine
A tenant-facing self-service layer <br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> is the operational nervous system of VCF
It emphasizes insight, correlation, and prediction—not just monitoring
<br>It complements <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> by ensuring the platform remains healthy, performant, and secure over time
Its value compounds as environments scale and diversify
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Observability and Health/Operations Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:28:45 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Day 2 Tasks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br><img alt="day-n-tasks.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation Day 2 tasks begin once real workloads exist.
This is where theory meets entropy: failures happen, usage grows, humans make mistakes, and the platform must keep working anyway.If:
Day 0 pours the concrete
Day 1 frames the building
Day 2 is living in it for years
Or:
Day 0 → Existence
Day 1 → Enablement
Day 2 → Sustainment
Day 2 is continuous, not a phase you “finish”.This is the obvious part—but it’s only the surface.
Deploy workloads (VMs, Pods, clusters)
Scale up/down
Start / stop / suspend
Migrate workloads
Retire workloads
Day 2 starts the feedback loop.
Platform health monitoring
Workload health monitoring
Capacity tracking
Performance baselines
Alert tuning (noise reduction)
Bad alerts = ignored alerts = outages.The real test of architecture.
Host failures
Network partitions
Storage degradation
Control plane issues
Application outages
Includes:
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> / <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> behavior
Failover validation
Backup and restore
DR testing
<br>If this fails, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 0</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 1</a> didn’t matter.Security shifts from design to enforcement.
Certificate rotation
Secret rotation
Credential revocation
Firewall rule changes
Vulnerability remediation
Audit and compliance reporting
One of VCF’s core promises.
[] patching
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> upgrades
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> upgrades
Kubernetes version upgrades
Firmware alignment (BOM compliance)
All while:
Workloads are running
SLAs are enforced
This is why VCF is opinionated.Reality: resources are finite.
Capacity planning
Quota adjustments
Overcommit tuning
Chargeback / showback
Cluster expansion
This is where finance meets engineering.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 1</a> defines policies.
Day 2 fights drift.
Detect misconfigurations
Enforce standards
Handle exceptions
Reconcile “special cases”
Without this, entropy wins.Day 2 success is measured socially, not technically.
Self-service reliability
Automation success rates
Time-to-resource
Support ticket volume
Developer trust
A stable platform feels boring. That’s success.Day 2 never freezes architecture.
Introduce new workload types
Add regions / clusters
Enable new services
Deprecate old patterns
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> must evolve without reset.
VCF Day 2 = continuous operations
Includes incidents, upgrades, security, scale
<br>Validates <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 0</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 1</a> decisions
Workload type becomes irrelevant
Boring Day 2 is the highest compliment
<br>Why not explore <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a> or <a data-href="VCF Installer" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Installer</a> as platform enablers.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Day-N Operations/VCF Day 2 Tasks.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:27:50 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Day 1 Tasks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br><img alt="day-n-tasks.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation Day 1 tasks start after the platform exists and focus on making it usable, consumable, and policy-driven—without yet running real business workloads.If Day 0 pours concrete, Day 1 frames the building and installs utilities.
Day 0 → Platform exists
Day 1 → Platform is configurable &amp; consumable
Day 2 → Platform is used &amp; operated
Day 1 is where intent, policy, and abstraction appear.This is where business structure enters the system.
<br>Define <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
<br>Define <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Map projects to: Supervisor Namespaces
Resource boundaries Define quotas and limits
This is not Kubernetes yet—it’s VCF’s business abstraction layer.From “admins only” to multi-role access.
Define administrative roles
Map identity groups to roles
Separate: <br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s (colloquially known as Platform Admins)
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>s (colloquially known as Tenant Admins)
Developers Enable delegated self-service
<br>This is where “secure <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a>” becomes real.Networking shifts from fabric to consumption.
Project-level networking
Tenant Tier-1 gateways
NAT, routing, firewall policies
Load balancer enablement
Network isolation per project
Infrastructure networking (Day 0) becomes tenant networking.Turn raw storage into governed capacity.
Define storage policies (performance, availability)
<br>Assign policies to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br>Enable <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> / NFS / VMFS consumption
Set quotas and constraints
This prevents noisy neighbors and capacity abuse.Expose compute without exposing chaos.
Define resource pools
Assign clusters to projects
Enable placement policies
<br>Configure <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> / <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> behavior
Compute becomes schedulable capacity, not hardware.This is where container platforms appear.
<br>Enable <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Configure: <br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s
Kubernetes versions
CNI / CSI integration
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters <br>Kubernetes exists because Day 1 enabled it, not because <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> magically does containers.Where humans stop clicking.
<br>Enable <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br>Define <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s
Approval flows
Day-1 actions exposed as APIs
Service Catalog creation
This is the front door for tenants.This is preventative control, not enforcement after damage.
Quotas
Naming standards
Placement constraints
Lifecycle constraints
Compliance policies
<br>Day 1 policies determine how painful <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a> is.Before workloads, you need visibility.
Enable logging pipelines
Metrics collection
Alert baselines
Capacity visibility
You can’t operate what you can’t see.
No real business workloads
No app-specific tuning
No scaling incidents
No break/fix operations
Day 1 is still design-heavy, not ops-heavy.
VCF Day 1 = platform enablement
<br>Introduces <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenancy</a>, policy, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">automation</a>
No real workloads yet
Sets the rules for everything that follows
Good Day 1 → boring, predictable Day 2
