<br>Check out <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> to see what comes after day one, where theory and preparation meets the challenges of real-world production workloads.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Day-N Operations/VCF Day 1 Tasks.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:26:14 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[FinOps and Capacity]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a>Cost Management (FinOps and Capacity) helps you analyze your infrastructure expenses. In this way, you can identify areas that are most suitable to use capacity management for optimal utilization of your resources.<br>You can use the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="FinOps and Capacity" data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">FinOps</a> (or “cost management”) capabilities to monitor infrastructure-related costs and associated services or license expenses with greater precision.Capacity Management consists of 3 sets of capabilities: assess, optimize and plan.Capacity optimization helps you right-size or reclaim any underutilized or wasted resources.
<br><a data-href="Workload Placement" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/workload-placement.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Placement</a> lets you optimize virtual machines and storage across clusters to reduce resource contention and maintain optimum system performance.
By using What-If Analysis, you can plan for an increase or decrease in workload or capacity requirements in your virtual infrastructure.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Capacity and Cost Optimization/FinOps and Capacity.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:24:05 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Identity Broker]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:security" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#security">#security</a>VCF Identity Broker (vIDB) is the identity-federation service used by VCF Single Sign-On (SSO) to provide a unified authentication configuration across multiple components in a VCF environment.vIDB centralizes authentication across the major VCF infrastructure components so that administrators and users can sign in once and seamlessly access those systems using a corporate identity provider (IdP) of choice.A practical way to think of it:
vIDB = the “SSO engine”
VCF SSO = the fleet-level “SSO product experience” that drives vIDB configuration and pushes/coordinates it across components
In real deployments, vIDB is positioned as the central place where you integrate with upstream identity sources (for example AD/LDAPS, or “corporate IdPs” such as Okta/Entra/ADFS), and then VCF components are configured to trust/use that SSO configuration.<br>At a high level, VCF Identity Broker is an identity federation/intermediary service that sits between your enterprise identity provider (e.g., Okta, Microsoft Entra ID/Azure AD, Ping Identity, ADFS, LDAP/OpenLDAP) and the VCF platform services (like <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, and the <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>/<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> stack).It:
Accepts authentication from an external IdP using modern protocols (e.g., SAML 2.0, OpenID Connect) or directory services (LDAP/AD).
Issues federated/standard tokens to VCF components to enable central SSO across the environment.
Provides user and group provisioning integration (SCIM, Just-In-Time provisioning, LDAP sync) so that IdP users and groups can be mapped into VCF RBAC.
vIDB acts as a universal “identity broker” in a federation chain—it trusts your enterprise IdP and then vouches for those identities to VMware Cloud Foundation services.The vIDB service is described in the field as supporting at least:
Embedded mode (configured inside the management domain’s vCenter context; no separate deployment) <br>Runs inside the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>’s <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> (VCF management cluster).
Easier to deploy, ideal for smaller or single-instance VCF environments.
Doesn’t require a separate appliance. <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Appliance</a> mode (a stand-alone vIDB appliance cluster) Deployed as a stand-alone appliance cluster (often a three-node cluster for high availability).
Recommended for larger, production, or fleet-wide SSO use cases.
Provides scalability and resilience across multiple VCF instances. <br>Once enabled, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> SSO aims to make authentication consistent across VCF components.Instead of logging separately into:
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> / <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> UI
VCF Operations for Logs, Networks, etc.
you authenticate once via your enterprise IdP, and VCF Identity Broker handles the rest, issuing tokens and enabling access to all components with a common identity.<br>By centralizing authentication, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> reduces administrative overhead (no separate local accounts to manage on each component) and supports modern enterprise identity standards.VCF Identity Broker supports a range of identity sources:
Modern cloud IdPs: Okta, Ping Identity, Microsoft Entra ID / Azure AD, ADFS.
Traditional directory services: Active Directory via LDAP, OpenLDAP. Centralized authentication and SSO—better user experience and reduced login friction.
Integrates with corporate IdPs—enables MFA, policy enforcement, and audit logging from your enterprise identity layer.
Scalable deployment options—embedded for simplicity, appliance for scale/resilience. Adds an additional component to deploy and manage (especially in appliance mode).
Requires careful role mapping and RBAC planning so that IdP groups/roles map correctly to VCF permissions.
Legacy components may not participate in SSO the same way — they might still require local accounts even after VCF Identity Broker is configured.
A very real operational problem in multi-tenant systems is: Users get recreated/reidentified when you switch identity providers (or change claims, subject formats, etc.).
If a tenant starts on IdP-A and later moves to IdP-B, you want a controlled way to preserve user access and authorization mappings.
Remapping is the “bridge” that avoids breaking RBAC simply because the upstream identity changed.
Remapping is usually about reconciling user identities inside the platform’s internal user store / directory representation when the upstream IdP changes. It’s not “magic federation”—it’s an administrative identity-correlation operation.
Upstream IdP (Okta/Entra/ADFS/LDAP-backed federation)
Authenticates the human. Issues identity assertions / tokens.
vIDB (VCF Identity Broker)
Provides VCF SSO: consistent auth configuration across VCF components.
VCF Automation OIDC Services / IdP Proxy
Provides tenant-aware OIDC proxying for relying parties and/or for tenant-specific auth experiences inside the Automation/Cloud Director plane. <br>VCF Identity Broker is the central identity federation and Single Sign-On facilitator in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>
It integrates your chosen identity provider with VCF components, allowing a single set of credentials and seamless access across services.
<br>Supports modern authentication protocols and multiple IdP types, helping enterprises align <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> with corporate identity strategies.
vIDB is the identity federation service underpinning VCF SSO, aimed at consistent login across VCF components
VCF Automation as an OIDC IdP proxy is a separate capability (vCloud Director lineage) that enables tenant-aware OIDC proxying.
User remapping between IdPs exists to preserve access/RBAC continuity when tenants change upstream identity sources.
<br>API access tokens in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> are commonly handled via exchanging a refresh token at .../oauth/provider/token.
<br>PKCE matters for modern public clients; <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>-related guidance explicitly calls for “public OIDC client with PKCE enabled” in some integration scenarios.
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> or <a data-href="Security Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/security-and-compliance/security-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Security Management</a> are two tangentially-related topics that you can navigate from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/VCF Identity Broker/VCF Identity Broker.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:21:39 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[User Roles]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>Roles assigned to users and groups are an essential part to identity and access management in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>You can leverage identity providers with <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s to enable single sign-on to provision users and groups. Once the users and groups are added to the&nbsp;<a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>, they must be assigned roles to enable specific permissions and access to different features within&nbsp; <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>VCF Automation has several levels of user roles. These different levels control access to the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>, the <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s that produce or consume the <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s, Catalog Items, access to IaaS Services, and the ability for users to use or see individual parts of the user interface. These different levels give <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s different tools to apply any level of granularity that is required by their operational needs.<br>Here are the predefined user roles in **<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>. You can visit each link to see more details about them.
Organization Roles <br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization User</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Auditor</a> Project Roles <br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Auditor</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Advanced User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Advanced User</a>
<br><a data-href="Project User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project User</a> **Supervisor Roles <br><a data-href="Supervisor Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/supervisor-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Administrator</a> <br>
Defer to Identity Provider
User permissions can also be determined based on information received from the identity provider for the <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.
<br><a data-href="Organization Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a> could be a good area to explore after getting acquainted with the user roles here. Additionally, you can find a more detailed listing of what permissions these roles have in <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/User Roles.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:20:57 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[SDDC Manager]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br>See also: <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a><br><img alt="sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" target="_self"><br>SDDC Manager is the foundational lifecycle-management and orchestration engine of <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.It is responsible for deploying, configuring, upgrading, and maintaining the entire VCF stack as a single, validated system rather than as independent products.<br><img alt="sddc-manager-8f57b8cd-3a43-48cc-98dc-b9cdf6132d20.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-8f57b8cd-3a43-48cc-98dc-b9cdf6132d20.webp" target="_self">If you think of VCF as a factory-built private cloud, SDDC Manager is the factory control system that ensures every component is installed correctly, stays in a supported state, and evolves safely over time.<br><img alt="sddc-manager-1.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-1.webp" target="_self"><br>
UI Deprecation Warning
In VCF 9.0+, Broadcom’s docs state that <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/building-your-private-cloud-infrastructure/sddc-manager-workflows.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com" rel="noopener nofollow" class="external-link is-unresolved" title="SDDC Manager Workflows in VMware Cloud Foundation 9.0" href="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/building-your-private-cloud-infrastructure/sddc-manager-workflows.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_self">SDDC Manager UI is being deprecated</a> and that SDDC Manager workflows can now be found in VCF Operations and vSphere Client—so many “platform lifecycle” workflows show up there now. ([
This is SDDC Manager’s primary job.SDDC Manager performs end-to-end lifecycle operations across the VCF stack:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> (hypervisor)
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
Other optional components.
Key characteristics:
Uses validated upgrade bundles
Enforces component compatibility
Executes sequenced, automated upgrades
Provides rollback and precheck logic
This is not just patching: It is system-level lifecycle orchestration.SDDC Manager is responsible for:
Initial VCF bring-up
Creating: Management Domain
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VI (Workload) Domains</a> Adding: Hosts
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Clusters</a>
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s Ensuring: Correct networking
Correct certificate trust
Correct inventory alignment Without SDDC Manager, you do not have VCF: That simple!—You will only have a loosely assembled VMware products.SDDC Manager acts as the system-of-record for:
What components exist
Their versions
Their relationships
Their lifecycle state
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> manages virtualization.
SDDC Manager manages the cloud system itself.SDDC Manager enforces:
Supported topologies
Supported versions
Supported upgrade paths
If you try to:
Upgrade NSX independently
Modify components outside supported flows
You risk breaking VCF supportability.
<br>This is intentional: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> favors predictability over freedom.It is not:
A tenant portal
A developer platform
A policy engine
A workload orchestrator
A replacement for vCenter, NSX Manager, or Kubernetes APIs
<br>Those functions live elsewhere (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, etc.).
SDDC Manager manages the cloud itself; everything else manages what runs inside that cloud.
Without SDDC Manager:
Enterprises would manually assemble components
Version skew would be common
Upgrades would be risky and expensive
Supportability would collapse
With SDDC Manager:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> becomes repeatable
Lifecycle becomes deterministic
VMware/Broadcom can guarantee outcomes
This is why SDDC Manager is non-optional in VCF.
SDDC Manager is the backbone of VCF
It owns lifecycle, topology, and compatibility
It enforces validated, supported states
It is infrastructure-centric, not tenant-centric
Without it, VCF does not exist as a product
<br>Since we are onto management and provisioning, <a data-href="VCF Installer" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Installer</a> can be the next topic to dive into.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/SDDC Manager/SDDC Manager.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:18:44 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[SDDC]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a><br><img alt="workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" target="_self"><br>Within <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, an SDDC is the foundational architectural model that virtualizes all core data-center resources (compute, storage, networking, and management) and delivers them as software services.<br>SDDC is the “what”, while <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is the “productized implementation” of that model.In an SDDC:<br>No hardware-specific configuration is required by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenants</a>. Everything is expressed as policies, APIs, and declarative intent.<br>If you think of SDDC as an interface, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is an implementation of that interface.Or in simpler terms, You cannot “install an SDDC”.
You deploy VCF, and the result is an SDDC.As a very simplistic analogy:
SDDC → “Cloud computing”
VCF → “AWS (but for private cloud)”
Inside VCF, SDDC enables:
Uniform resource abstraction <br>A VM workload and a Kubernetes workload are both “<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workloads</a>” Policy-driven behavior <br>Placement, <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, security, backups are rules, not scripts Lifecycle coherence <br>Upgrade <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> together, safely and repeatably Multi-tenancy <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>, quotas, RBAC Cloud-like operations on-prem <br>Self-service, APIs, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, chargeback SDDC is not:
A single product
Just virtualization
Just Kubernetes
A UI
<br>A <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> feature
It is the system-level design philosophy that VCF enforces.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>’s value proposition is:
“You don’t assemble an SDDC yourself anymore: We ship one.”
That’s why:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> has strict BOMs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> enforces lifecycle orchestration
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> tightly integrates ops + automation + infra
This is intentional: freedom at the top, rigidity at the bottom.
SDDC = architecture
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> = implementation of that architecture
In VCF, everything (compute, storage, network, ops) is software-defined
SDDC enables cloud-like behavior on private infrastructure
You deploy VCF, and you get an SDDC: That simple.
<br><a data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Private Cloud</a> could be a topic of interest to look at right after SDDC.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/SDDC.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:17:44 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Cloud]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>VMware Cloud is the umbrella brand and strategy for VMware’s cloud-delivered offerings, covering public cloud, hybrid cloud, and managed private cloud use cases.It is not a single product.<br>Think of VMware Cloud as the distribution and consumption model, while <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> (VCF) is the core platform architecture underneath many of those offerings.
VMware Cloud is how VMware delivers and operates VMware platforms as a service across public, private, and hybrid clouds.
VCF is often the engine; VMware Cloud is the service wrapper.Examples include:
VMware Cloud on AWS
VMware Cloud on Azure
VMware Cloud on Google Cloud
VMware Cloud on OCI
These provide:
Native VMware stacks
Operated as managed services
Tight integration with hyperscaler services
From the customer’s point of view:<br>
“I get <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>/<a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>/<a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> without running the platform myself.”
This is where things look very similar to VCF:
VMware (or a partner) runs VCF on your behalf
Can be hosted: On your premises
In a partner data center You consume it as a cloud service
Regardless of the flavor, VMware Cloud aims to deliver:
Consistent VMware operational model
Reduced platform operational burden
Predictable lifecycle management
Enterprise-grade security and compliance
Hybrid portability (move workloads across clouds)
It is not:
A replacement for Kubernetes-native clouds
A single UI or API
A single SKU
Always customer-operated
It is a portfolio strategy, not a monolith.VMware Cloud = “VMware runs it for you”
VCF = “The platform being run”
vSphere/NSX = “The building blocks”
Or in cloud terms:
VMware Cloud ≈ AWS Managed Services
VCF ≈ AWS internal platform (you don’t see it directly)
vSphere/NSX ≈ EC2 / VPC equivalents Customers want cloud economics
But need enterprise control
And want to reuse VMware skills and tooling
VMware Cloud is VMware’s answer to:
“Give me cloud without forcing me to rewrite everything.” VMware Cloud is a service model, not a product
It spans public, private, and hybrid clouds
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is often the underlying platform
VMware Cloud reduces operational responsibility
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="VMware Validated Solutions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Validated Solutions</a> too.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-cloud/vmware-cloud.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/VMware Cloud/VMware Cloud.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:15:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Virtual Appliance]]></title><description><![CDATA[See also: <a data-href="VCSA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>A vSphere Appliance (*or “virtual appliance”) is a prepackaged, hardened virtual machine that bundles an OS, application, configuration, and lifecycle tooling into a single deployable unit.A VMware-style appliance typically includes:
=======
<br>Check out <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> to see what comes after day one, where theory and preparation meets the challenges of real-world production workloads.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Day-N Operations/VCF Day 1 Tasks.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 23:24:05 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><img alt="vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" target="_self">VCF Operations&nbsp;helps your organization build, manage, operate and secure your private cloud infrastructure by deploying and maintaining its fleet-level components, providing visibility and enhanced performance across the workload and infrastructure stack, and helping your organization stay compliant with regulatory standards and organizational guidelines.VCF Operations has these functional areas:
<br><a data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fleet Management</a> Enables operational consistency and efficient resource management of the&nbsp;VCF infrastructure at scale. <br><a data-href="Operations Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operations Management</a> Provides monitoring and optimization of performance, cost and capacity, and faster troubleshooting. <br><a data-href="Workload Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Operations</a> &nbsp;Ensures that critical applications are running as expected. <br><a data-href="Performance Monitoring" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Performance Monitoring</a> Ensures applications have continuous access to resources <br><a data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">FinOps and Capacity</a> Helps you analyze your infrastructure expenses and optimize capacity usage. <br><a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a> Provides support for migrating and interconnecting workloads within and across VCF private cloud. <br><a data-href="Security Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/security-and-compliance/security-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Security Management</a> Provides security management to ensure that your VCF private cloud is operationally secure. VCF Operations does not:
Own tenancy boundaries
Gate workload creation
Enforce business approval flows
Define org/project constructs
Those remain in:
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>
Upstream automation layers
VCF Operations observes those constructs after the fact.Day 0 / Day 1 → VCF-A - Who can create? - What can be created? - Under what policies? Day 2 → VCF-O - Is it healthy? - Is it over/under-utilized? - Is it behaving strangely?
Here is a very high-level look at VCF’s control plane:VCF (the platform)
├── VCF Automation (formerly Aria Automation)
├── VCF Operations (formerly Aria Operations)
├── Supervisor / vSphere
└── Workloads
Here is how things looks from each layer’s point of view:<br>Once a workload cluster is instantiated in a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, it has no awareness of <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> constructs such as Organization or Project—Those concepts exist only at the governance layer (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>) and are not part of the runtime execution model (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>).<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Operations Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operations Management</a>, <a data-href="Performance Monitoring" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Performance Monitoring</a>, or <a data-href="Workload Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Operations</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/VCF Operations.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 23:14:41 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[appliances]]></title><link>./https://vcf.wtf/appliances.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">appliances.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 23:06:35 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Virtual Appliance]]></title><description><![CDATA[
see also: <a data-href="VCSA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>
