>>>>>>> c0778dc (new article)
A minimal, locked-down OS
The application(s)
Configuration defaults
Upgrade mechanisms
Health checks
Backup/restore hooks
Support boundaries (“only change things this way”)
The key idea is:
You manage the appliance as a product, not as a general-purpose OS.
Usually yes, but conceptually they can be:
<br>One VM (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>)
Multiple tightly-coupled VMs (some NSX / telco components)
But still treated as one product unit
From the operator’s perspective:
You deploy “the appliance”
You don’t manage its internals individually
Once you accept that:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> is a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> components are appliances
Then the stack becomes very consistent:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> runs everything
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> orchestrates everything
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Appliance</a>s are how VMware ships control planes Kubernetes is just another control surface layered on top Multiple VMs ≠ Appliance unless:If you deploy 3 random VMs and wire them together yourself — that’s not an appliance.<br>Check out <a data-href="VMware Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-cloud/vmware-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud</a> to see how cloud looks like from the lens of <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Virtual Appliance/Virtual Appliance.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:14:27 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tenants in Supervisor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a>
<br>In vSphere Supervisor a tenant is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Tenants in Supervisor" data-href="Tenants in Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace-bound</a>.
There is no separate tenant object inside Kubernetes.
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> is the tenant boundary at the vSphere-Kubernetes interface.
If you assume:
Tenant = Project → you’ll design the wrong thing
Tenant = Kubernetes namespace → you’ll under-secure
Tenant = Supervisor Namespace → things line up
<br>
“tenant namespace” is an informal shorthand for <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">supervisor namespace</a>. <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s are <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> overlays. They do not define the tenant.
<br>Kubernetes namespaces inside <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>s are secondary scopes.<br>In <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> each tenant is realized as one (or more) <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s.<br>
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> sits above, provides governance (Organizations, Projects, quotas) and self-service, but does not define tenancy by itself.This is sometimes “informally” expressed as “tenant namespaces”. What is meant by it is a Supervisor Namespace.Or more precisely: In a Supervisor Cluster tenant == supervisor namespace (there is a 1-1 relationship).<br>In vSphere Supervisor, tenancy is realized through <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, which serve as the execution and isolation boundary for tenants.When people say:
“tenant namespace”
“project namespace”
“customer namespace”
They almost always mean:<br>
A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> allocated to that tenant.
<br>Kubernetes does not have a separate construct for this: It is a <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> concept, projected as a (Supervisor) namespace.<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> can contain:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pods</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMs</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Entire guest Kubernetes clusters</a>
Tenant
└── Supervisor Namespace ├── VM workloads ├── Pod workloads └── Guest K8s Cluster └── many Kubernetes namespaces ^ these are distinct from the "Supervisor Namespace" they are regular Kubernetes `Kind:Namespace` resources. (/api/v1/namespaces) -- i.e., a cluster-scoped Kubernetes API resource of kind "Namespace", defined in the core (v1) API group, used to provide a logical scope for namespaced resources. -- i.e. "a good old Kubernetes namespace"; NOT a Supervisor Namespace. -- vSphere Supervisor does not see, or care about the namespaces in this guest cluster. vSphere Supervisor see the "Guest Cluster" as a resource; that's the end of the level of its granularity. To be more precise: The Supervisor is not aware of, and does not manage, Kubernetes namespaces inside the Guest Cluster. --- * These namespaces exist only inside the Guest Cluster * They are not visible to the Supervisor * They are not related to Supervisor Namespaces in any structural way * They are ordinary Kubernetes namespaces, no different from what you’d find in a kind/minikube/EKS/AKS cluster
<br>This is the <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> Layer of tenancy.VCF Environment
└── vSphere (vCenter) └── Supervisor Cluster └── Supervisor Namespace ← TENANT BOUNDARY
At this layer:
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> Has: Resource limits
Storage policies
Network segments
RBAC bindings <br>Is created and owned by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Maps to: <br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> constructs
Datastore permissions This is where hard multitenancy lives.<br><img alt="supervisor-cluster.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster.webp" target="_self">This is logical tenancy, not execution tenancy.It is the automation and consumption layer.Organization
└── Project └── Deployment / Blueprint └── (Targets a Supervisor Namespace) <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> Business / administrative grouping <br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> Quota + governance container These map downwards, but they don’t execute workloads themselves.<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> defines a tenant from a runtime and security perspective.<br>At <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, Organizations and Projects define:
Ownership
Billing
<br><a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>
Access workflows
But not execution boundaries.
VCF Environment (Rackspace)
└── Supervisor Cluster ├── ns-cocacola ← Tenant: Coca-Cola ├── ns-pepsi ← Tenant: Pepsi └── ns-pizzahut ← Tenant: Pizza Hut
Each tenant is a supervisor namespace.<br><img alt="Supervisor-Namespace.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-namespace.png" target="_self">For Coca-Cola (example):
Fixed CPU / memory quota
Dedicated or isolated NSX segment
Approved storage policies
RBAC scoped to Coca-Cola admins
Ability to run: Pods
VMs
Guest Kubernetes clusters That namespace is the tenant boundary.<br>Layer <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> on top of this:Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke-Prod └── Deployments → targets ns-cocacola Organization: Pepsi
└── Project: Pepsi-Shared └── Deployments → targets ns-pepsi
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s and <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s map to <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s—they DO NOT replace them.Automation gives:
Self-service catalogs
Approval workflows
Policy as code
Lifecycle orchestration
But the tenant still “lives” at the Supervisor Namespace.
Note that the company and product names used in this section are for illustrative purposes—to give realistic analogies—only.
Scope
<br><a data-href="vCenter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
Storage policies
Responsibilities
Create Supervisor Namespaces
Set quotas
Attach networks
Bind tenant identities
Enforce platform guardrails
Power level
God-mode
Not visible to customers
Scope
<br>One <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> (e.g., ns-cocacola)
Kubernetes API within that namespace
Responsibilities
Manage workloads
Deploy guest clusters
Configure service
Delegate access internally
Cannot
See other tenants
Modify quotas
Escape namespace
This is who you hand the kubeconfig to.
Scope
Kubernetes RBAC inside tenant (supervisor) namespace
Possibly inside guest clusters
Responsibilities
Deploy apps
Manage services
Consume secrets
No infrastructure privilegesScope
Automation policies
Catalogs
Projects
Approvals
This role:
Often held by Rackspace
Sometimes delegated partially to tenants Secrets do not cross Supervisor Namespaces
Identity trust roots often terminate there
Network policy enforcement happens there
Audit logs are scoped there
So when you say tenant == Supervisor Namespace,
then:
Security
Compliance
Billing
Automation
all align clearly.<br>You can shift gears and check out some basic concepts such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Appliance" data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">what a Virtual Appliance is</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Tenants in Supervisor.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 16:13:33 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Administrative Roles in VCF]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>In VMware Cloud Foundation, Platform Admin and Tenant Admin are useful conceptual terms, but not official role names in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.VCF defines explicit, documented roles such as:
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>
(and related Auditor / User roles)
The distinction is intentional and fundamental.<br>VCF separates infrastructure ownership from consumption <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">governance</a>: platform infrastructure is operated outside <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, while <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s and <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>s govern what runs within tenant boundaries.<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> has <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenant</a>-level authority.<br>An <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> represents the tenant boundary in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.They manage:
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>-level configuration
Tenant users and role assignments
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>-wide quotas and policies
<br><a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> within the organization
They cannot:
Modify platform topology
Upgrade core infrastructure
Affect other organizations
Bypass platform guardrails
<br>The <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> is a <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>-scoped operational authority.<br>A <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> manages consumption and operations within a single <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>, which maps to one (typical, but can be more than one) <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>.<br>
The <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> can create <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, assign users and groups, and allocate quotas to restrict the configurations available to the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Tenants in Supervisor" data-href="Tenants in Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenants</a>.
|<br>
By creating <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, you can isolate security and networking objects across tenants in a single&nbsp;NSX deployment.
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>s manage:
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> users and access
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload</a> provisioning (VMs, Kubernetes clusters, services)
Project-scoped quotas and approvals
Day-to-day operational policies
Their authority is strictly bounded by:
<br>The <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
Platform-defined constraints
Without this separation:
Tenants could break upgrade paths
Platform consistency would erode
Supportability would collapse
One tenant could impact others
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> deliberately trades tenant flexibility for platform predictability, safety, and lifecycle integrity.
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> is the true tenant administrator in VCF 9
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> governs consumption within a tenant
The separation protects multi-tenancy, lifecycle management, and supportability
This boundary is foundational to VCF’s architecture
<br><a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a> is the logical follow-up to this section, which dives into more details of predefined roles and privileges in **<a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/administrative-roles-in-vcf.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Administrative Roles in VCF.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 15:32:29 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Roles and Permissions]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>Here is an overview of who can access what parts of the <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> Organization Portal, and what they can do with the privileges that their role grants.
Overview page—All roles
My Account (User Profile)—All roles
<br>View <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Auditor</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> (your projects)
<br><a data-href="Project Advanced User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Advanced User</a> (your projects)
<br><a data-href="Project Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Auditor</a> (your projects)
Create and Delete Projects
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br>Edit <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s (users, roles, settings)
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br>View <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Organization Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Auditor</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> (your projects)
<br><a data-href="Project Advanced User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Advanced User</a> (your projects)
