<br>You might want to look at <a data-href="VCF Advanced Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/vcf-capabilities/vcf-advanced-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Advanced Services</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Fleet and Domain Model/VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 15:17:40 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/how-many-vcf-instances-per-vcf-fleet-0.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/how-many-vcf-instances-per-vcf-fleet-0.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>See also: <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, a Project is a logical, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant-scoped</a> construct used for workload organization, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, and self-service consumption.It exists at the automation and policy layer, not the virtualization layer.A Project is a logical grouping within an organization.Projects:
Represent application teams or environments
<br>Contain one or more <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters
<br>Are mapped to one or more <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s
Define resource entitlements and policy boundaries
Key properties:
Projects can be renamed
<br>Projects cannot be deleted if they contain <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS clusters</a>
A VKS cluster belongs to exactly one Project
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> cannot span multiple Projects
Projects act as the bridge between organizational intent and infrastructure execution.Projects group workloads, users, quotas, policies, and lifecycle controls under a common administrative boundary. It is “a governed slice of cloud capacity” exposed to consumers.<br>Projects live primarily in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (formerly vRealize Automation / Aria Automation).It is not:
<br>A <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Cluster" data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere cluster</a>
A Kubernetes cluster
A resource pool
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> (though it may map to one)
Instead, it is a control-plane abstraction that binds together multiple lower-level constructs.VCF Instance └── Organization └── Project ├── Users and Roles ├── Policies and Quotas ├── Cloud Zones ├── Workload Deployments └── Supervisor Namespaces / VKS Clusters
<br>A project represents a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant</a> or sub-tenant:
Different teams
Different applications
Different environments (prod, staging, dev)
Each project is isolated from others by policy.Projects define who can do what:
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Project User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project User</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Advanced User" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-advanced-user.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Advanced User</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Auditor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-auditor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Auditor</a>
These roles govern:
Who can deploy workloads
<br>Who can modify <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s
Who can see usage or costs
Projects define where workloads can land:
Which Cloud Zones they can use
Resource quotas (CPU, memory, storage)
Network constraints
Storage policies
This prevents a single tenant from exhausting shared infrastructure.Projects are the context in which users deploy:
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s
Kubernetes clusters (e.g., Supervisor-backed)
Application blueprints
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> operations (scale, update, destroy)
Everything a user deploys is always within a project.A Project maps to:
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>
One or more Kubernetes clusters
A set of Kubernetes namespaces inside those clusters
But the Project itself is not Kubernetes-native.
It’s a management abstraction above Kubernetes.Think of it as:
“A governance wrapper around Kubernetes and VM resources.”
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> supports both one-to-one and one-to-many mappings between Projects and <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s; the choice is an architectural pattern, not a platform constraint.Very common, very clean:Organization: Coca-Cola
├── Project: Coke-Prod → ns-coke-prod
├── Project: Coke-Stage → ns-coke-stage
└── Project: Coke-Dev → ns-coke-dev
This provides:
Clean blast-radius isolation
Clear RBAC and quotas per environment
Easy mental model
Common in regulated / prod-heavy setups
This is a design choice, not a platform requirement.(Equally valid, also common in larger deployments)Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke ├── ns-coke-dev ├── ns-coke-stage └── ns-coke-prod
This provides:
<br>Shared <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> (same people, same blueprints)
Environment separation handled at namespace level
Easier cross-env promotion workflows
Fewer projects to manage
<br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>:
A Project is a logical tenant boundary
It governs who can deploy what, where, and how
It sits above infrastructure and below the organization
It is the unit of consumption for developers and teams
<br>It enables <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a>, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, and self-service
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Consumption Abstractions/Project.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 15:14:05 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Blueprint]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a>A Blueprint is a declarative deployment template that defines what can be requested, how it is configured, where it may land, and under which policies and approvals.<br>A&nbsp;<a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> Design <a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a> is a prescriptive end-to-end design for a&nbsp;VCF <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Fleet Management" data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fleet</a> in a commonly requested architecture topology, created to help accelerate time to value when building a new&nbsp;VMware Cloud Foundation platform.A Blueprint has a prescriptive selection of deployment models chosen from the design library to conform to the design profile of the&nbsp;Blueprint.A Blueprint can be deployed as is, with no alterations, or can be used as template where any of the deployment models can be substituted for alternatives from the same category within the design library.&nbsp;<br>A Blueprint reflects the initial deployment of a&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Fleet Management" data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a> and supports expansion in a variety of ways to support the needs of your organization.A Blueprint provides a set of planning, implementation and design elements (requirements and recommendations) based on the chosen deployment models.<br>Blueprints in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> are governed deployment templates that define allowed workload patterns, configuration inputs, placement constraints, and approval policies. They orchestrate resource creation but are not part of the runtime execution layer.Once a deployment is created, the Blueprint can be deleted and the workload keeps running: It’s not a part of the runtime layer.User ↓
Blueprint ← governance + intent ↓
Project ← who / where / policy ↓
Supervisor Namespace ↓
vSphere / Kubernetes runtime <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>: Business boundary (e.g. Verizon)
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>: <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> scope (e.g. US-East)
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a>: Allowed patterns inside that scope
Organization: Verizon
└── Project: US-East ├── Blueprint: Standard App VM ├── Blueprint: GPU Pod └── Blueprint: 3-Node K8s Cluster
Each Blueprint:
<br>targets specific <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>(s)
enforces constraints
hides complexity from requesters
Typically it defines:Examples:
A VM
A vSphere Pod
A Guest Kubernetes cluster
A multi-tier app (VM + LB + storage) CPU / memory sizes
Environment variables
Image versions
Feature toggles
Secret references (not secret values) <br>Which <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>(s) are allowed
Which storage policies are allowed
Which networks are allowed
Size limits
Placement rules Who can request it
Who must approve it
Lease duration
Cost visibility / chargeback tags
<br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, the terms template and blueprint are related but not interchangeable. They operate at different abstraction layers and serve different purposes in the lifecycle of infrastructure and workloads.
A template defines what a single resource looks like.
A blueprint defines how multiple resources come together.
A template is a reusable, preconfigured artifact that represents one resource, typically:
VM Template A golden VM image (OS + patches + base software)
Used to rapidly deploy identical VMs OVF/OVA Templates <br>Portable packaged <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>s Content Library Templates <br>Shared across <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> instances and <a data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Domain</a>s Infrastructure-level
Static
Low abstraction
No logic, no dependencies
Consumed by automation tools (not orchestrating anything themselves)
A Template says:
“This is what a machine looks like when it’s born.”
In contrast, a single Blueprint can define these following components:
2 application VMs
1 database VM
A load balancer
A network segment
Placement rules
Lifecycle actions
That entire topology is deployed as one logical unit.
Blueprints consume templates.
Here is possible flow:
Template: Ubuntu 22.04 VM with hardened baseline Blueprint: Uses that template
Defines how many instances
Attaches networks
Applies policies
Adds lifecycle logic So:
Templates = building blocks
Blueprints = architectural plans
In Kubernetes terms (for intuition):
Template ≈ Container Image
Blueprint ≈ Helm Chart / Application Manifest
Understanding this distinction prevents common mistakes:
❌ Treating templates as reusable environments
❌ Expecting templates to handle lifecycle logic
❌ Trying to encode business logic inside VM images
Correct mental model:
Templates are static
Blueprints are dynamic and declarative
As a quick comparison:
Template
→ A reusable VM or image
→ Low-level, static, infrastructure-focused
Blueprint
→ A declarative application/environment definition
→ High-level, orchestrated, lifecycle-aware
<br>You might want to check concepts like <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, or <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, which are related to Blueprints.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Consumption Abstractions/Blueprint.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 15:04:10 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Private Cloud]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>A VCF Private Cloud is the highest level of management and consumption for the underlying <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> resources. A VCF Private Cloud can contain one or more VCF Fleets.<br>VCF Private Cloud is the customer-operated private cloud deployment model built on <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>
It delivers cloud-like operations, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, and lifecycle management on customer-owned or customer-controlled infrastructure (on-prem or dedicated colocation).
VCF Private Cloud = “You run the cloud, using VMware’s cloud platform.”
VCF Private Cloud is opinionated and integrated:
<br>Single lifecycle authority (<a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>)
<br>Validated stack (<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>)
Declarative operations
Strong separation of platform vs tenant
Built-in multi-tenancy
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> → <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> automation
This is fundamentally different from “installing vSphere and calling it a cloud.”These components are installed, upgraded, and validated as one system.VCF Private Cloud is deliberately split:
<br>Runs in the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> / <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>
Controls lifecycle, upgrades, topology <br>Used by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenants</a>
<br>Exposed via <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">policies</a>
<br>Runs workloads in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload (VI) Domains / Clusters</a>
This mirrors public cloud responsibility boundaries.VCF Private Cloud supports enterprise-grade multi-tenancy:
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s → business tenants
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s → sub-tenants (teams, environments) <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a> / <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s → execution boundaries
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="NSX Segment" data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segmentation</a> → network isolation
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Domains</a> / clusters → failure &amp; lifecycle isolation <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenancy</a> is logical and policy-driven, not per-cluster by default.VCF Private Cloud can be deployed on:
On-premises data centers
Dedicated colocation
Partner-hosted environments
<br>What matters is control, not location. <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> optimizes for control and predictability, not infinite elasticity:
VCF Private Cloud ≈ “like AWS, but you run AWS yourself”
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> ≈ Cloud provider internal control plane
<br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s ≈ Accounts and subscriptions
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>s ≈ Capacity pools VCF Private Cloud is customer-operated cloud infrastructure
<br>Built on <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>
Strong separation of platform vs tenant
<br>Enterprise-grade <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a> and lifecycle
Cloud outcomes without giving up control
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>, as they are important topology elements in VCF Private Cloud.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Private Cloud.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 14:56:47 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Management Components]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>VCF management components are the platform control-plane services responsible for lifecycle management, networking, security, observability, and automation of the entire VCF instance, and are deployed exclusively in the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>.<br>Here are the management components of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> Inventory
Cluster logic
Resource scheduling
API surface for everything else <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts (management cluster) Run the Management VMs
Often capacity-isolated <br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (<a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> + control plane) Networking for management workloads
Overlay, routing, firewalling
Required even if workload domains use different topologies <br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Lifecycle orchestration
Domain creation
Upgrade coordination
Configuration drift control These are management components even though they feel “optional”:
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> (formerly vRealize / Aria Operations) Telemetry ingestion
Capacity planning
Health modeling
Alert correlation VCF Operations for Logs (if deployed) Centralized logging
Audit &amp; forensic workflows <br>These belong in the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> because:
They observe everything
They are trusted with cross-domain data
They are not tenant-scoped <br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (formerly vRealize / Aria Automation) <br>Tenant abstraction (<a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>)
Approval flows
Policy enforcement
<br><a data-href="Blueprint" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/blueprint.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Blueprint</a> execution
Self-service APIs Even though it models consumer behavior, it is still a management component because:
It enforces platform policy
It brokers infrastructure authority
It is not itself a tenant workload
Often overlooked, but these are part of the management plane too:
Identity Integration AD / LDAP
<br>OIDC (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vIDB</a>, external IdP) Certificates Internal PKI
Trust distribution Secrets and credentials Platform credentials
Not tenant secrets These may not be a single product, but they are a functional plane of the management domain.A good litmus test is as follows:
If a tenant can delete it without breaking the cloud, it is not a management component.
<br>Other topological constructs such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>, <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Edge" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Edge</a> are all good options to dive from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-management-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Management Components.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 14:56:04 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Edge]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br><img alt="vcf=edge=AD_4nXcv6rA 1.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf=edge=ad_4nxcv6ra-1.webp" target="_self"><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, VCF Edge refers to the extension of the VCF platform model to edge locations—sites that are geographically distributed, resource-constrained, and often operationally remote, but still need enterprise-grade consistency, security, and lifecycle management.In short:
VCF Edge brings “the VCF way” to thousands of small, remote sites—without turning each site into a snowflake.
<br><img alt="VCF-Edge-1 1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-edge-1-1.png" target="_self">Edge sites typically have constraints that central data centers do not:
Small host counts (often 2–4 nodes)
Limited on-site staff (or none)
Intermittent or high-latency connectivity (an edge-site not having Internet connectivity for a month is not uncommon)
Strict uptime requirements
Local data-residency or latency needs
VCF Edge is about operating under those constraints without abandoning platform discipline.<br>However, even at the edge, the core <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> principles remain:
Centralized lifecycle control
Validated configurations
Strong isolation and security
Declarative operations
Consistent operational model
What changes is scale, footprint, and placement—not the philosophy.Central / Regional Site
├── Management Domain (SDDC Manager, vCenter, NSX)
├── Automation &amp; Ops
│
└── Edge Sites (many) ├── Small Workload Domain (or cluster) ├── Local workloads (VMs / K8s) ├── Local networking &amp; security └── Centrally managed lifecycle
So:
While, management stays centralized
execution happens at the edge
Depending on use case:
Telco workloads (RAN, core, MEC)
Retail store systems
Factory / OT workloads
Branch office services
Latency-sensitive apps
These workloads:
Run locally
Are managed remotely
Must survive site isolation <br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> governs lifecycle
Platform admins operate from a hub
Edge sites follow validated patterns Workloads keep running if disconnected
Local failover is possible
Management resumes when connectivity returns
This balance is critical for an edge site.VCF Edge supports:
Single-tenant edge (most common)
Logical multi-tenancy via: <br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="NSX Segment" data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segmentation</a> But:
Physical isolation per tenant is less common at edge
Operational simplicity is prioritized
Edge is where: Hyperscalers struggle with footprint and latency Enterprises need consistency across thousands of sites Telco and regulated industries dominate Unlike a traditional cloud or data center (where workloads are centralized to regions), edge is decentralized, and geographically spread. This is topologically opposite to a typical cloud deployment. <br>
<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Core</a> → Headquarters data center VCF Edge → Branch offices or cell sites (for Telco) <br>
<a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> → Central IT command center Edge clusters → Remote, self-sufficient execution zones <br>Essentially, the same VCF <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> rules apply, but with different topological constraints, different connectivity requirements, at a smaller, but vastly-distributed scale.
VCF Edge extends VCF to remote, constrained sites
Management remains centralized
Workloads run locally and survive disconnection
Edge is a pattern, not a separate product
It prioritizes consistency over customization
<br>Looking at <a data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Domain</a>, and specifically <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>, and <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> could be the next venue to explore from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Edge.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 14:53:35 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf" length="0" type="false"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Domain]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br><img alt="workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" target="_self"><br>You create <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> to run consumer workloads.<br>For the first workload domain in your environment,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> deploys a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> instance and an <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> instance in the Management Domain. For each additional workload domain,&nbsp;VCF Operations deploys an additional vCenter instance.New Workload Domains can share the same NSX Manager cluster with an existing Workload Domain or you can deploy a new NSX Manager cluster.<br>Workload domains cannot use the NSX Manager cluster for the <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>.A Workload Domain (or VI (virtual infrastructure) Workload Domain)
<br>is created after <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>
hosts customer workloads
Typical separation: Prod vs non-prod
Regulated vs unregulated
Performance-sensitive vs general A VCF Domain is to VCF what a Kubernetes cluster is to Kubernetes-based platforms.It gives you:
Failure domain isolation
Security boundary
Upgrade blast-radius control
Operational independence
Without VCF Domains, everything would be patched, upgraded, and potentially broken together.<br>In <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>:
A VCF Domain is a backing infrastructure boundary
It is mapped to: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s <br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> never creates or upgrades domain: It only consumes them.<br>In <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>:
A VCF Domain is an observed object
Used for: Capacity planning
Health scoring
Performance analytics
Alerting Operations has zero authority over its lifecycle.
VCF Domain is a foundational VCF concept
Defined and lifecycle-managed by SDDC Manager
<br>Not a <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> concept
<br>Not a <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> concept
BUT both products depend on it, yet neither owns it
Primary purpose: isolation, lifecycle control, and scalability
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>’s fleet and domain model by looking at <a data-href="VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Domain/Workload Domain.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 14:48:26 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VLAN]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="VLANs-33-1024x709.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vlans-33-1024x709.png" target="_self">A VLAN (Virtual Local Area Network) is a logical segmentation of a Layer-2 network that allows multiple independent broadcast domains to coexist on the same physical switching infrastructure.
A VLAN lets you pretend one physical network is many separate networks.
Devices in different VLANs behave as if they are on different switches, even when plugged into the same one.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> uses both VLAN and VXLAN, whilee VXLAN (via <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>) is the primary and modern networking model.
VLANs → for the underlay (physical network connectivity)
VXLAN → for the overlay (tenant / workload networking)
<br>
Workloads never live directly on VLANs. They live on VXLAN-backed logical networks provided by <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>.
This is the real physical fabric: Switches, routers, NICs.
Uses traditional VLANs
Carries: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> management traffic
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> transport traffic (VTEP traffic) Designed to be simple, scalable, and stable
This is where actual tenant and workload networking happens.
Implemented using VXLAN
<br>Managed by <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
Provides: Logical switches
Distributed routing
Microsegmentation
NAT, LB, firewalling, etc. VXLAN is used to:
Create L2 networks over L3 infrastructure
Allow massive scale (up to ~16 million segments vs 4096 VLANs)
Decouple network topology from physical constraints
<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>:
Every workload network = VXLAN-backed logical segment
Encapsulated inside UDP packets
Carried across the underlay VLANs
So effectively:VM / Pod ↓
Logical Switch (VXLAN) ↓
NSX Transport Node ↓
VLAN-backed physical network
Here is a comparison table:Without VLANs:
Every device hears every broadcast
Security boundaries are weak
Networks don’t scale cleanly
With VLANs:
Broadcast traffic is contained
Security and isolation improve
Networks become modular and scalable Each VLAN is identified by a VLAN ID (typically 1–4094)
VLAN ID = logical network identity
Access Port
Carries traffic for one VLAN
Frames are untagged
Typical for end devices (servers, VMs, appliances)
Trunk Port
Carries traffic for multiple VLANs
Frames are tagged with VLAN IDs
Used between switches, hypervisors, routers
On trunk links, Ethernet frames include:
VLAN ID
Priority bits (QoS)
This is how a switch knows which logical network a frame belongs to.One VLAN usually maps to one IP subnet — but they are not the same thing.
Devices in the same VLAN can communicate directly
Devices in different VLANs require a router or L3 switch
This is called inter-VLAN routing
In VMware-based environments:
VLANs are used for underlay networking
Examples: Management
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br>Storage (<a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>)
<br>Overlay transport (<a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> TEPs) <br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> overlays (segments) may sit on top of VLAN-backed transport networks.So, VLANs are still foundational, even in overlay-driven designs.
VLAN = logical Layer-2 network
Provides broadcast isolation
Uses tagging on trunk links
Distinct from IP subnets
Still critical in modern virtualized and cloud platforms
<br>Let’s move up a few levels up the stack and observe <a data-href="VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/Infrastructure Primitives/VLAN.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 14:43:55 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vlans-33-1024x709.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vlans-33-1024x709.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Big Picture]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="About VCF" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/about-vcf.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">About VCF</a><br><img alt="vcf-overview.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" target="_self"><br>VMware Cloud Foundation (VCF) is a unified platform to design, plan, deploy, and manage your <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> by using <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">automation</a> capabilities.That is one of the core tenents of VCF, and thus, it requires clarification before anything else.In VCF-speak, the phrase “a workload is a workload” is not a tautology—it’s a deliberate abstraction boundary.It means that VCF intentionally collapses many very different execution models into a single management concept, and refuses to care about their internal form unless it must.Below is the precise meaning, layered from philosophy, to architecture, to consequences.From VCF’s point of view, a workload is simply “something that consumes resources and is governed by policy.”It is not:
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>
a Container
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod VM</a>
<br>a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> pod
<br>a <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>
a Helm release
Those are implementation details.VCF asks only:
Where does it run?
Who owns it?
What resources does it consume?
What policies apply?
What lifecycle rules govern it?
If those questions can be answered, VCF is satisfied.VCF exists above:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Kubernetes
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM</a>s
Containers
If VCF tried to manage each kind of workload differently, it would:
explode in complexity
duplicate logic
couple business policy to runtime mechanics
So instead, VCF defines:
Workload = Policy + Placement + Lifecycle + Resources
Everything else is delegated downward.All of the following are equally valid workloads in VCF:VCF deliberately does not rank or privilege any of these.In VCF, a workload is anything that consumes platform resources and is subject to platform policy—its internal shape is intentionally irrelevant.
VCF intentionally erases runtime distinctions
Governance &gt; implementation
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> is the abstraction bridge
If two things consume resources and obey policy, VCF treats them identically
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> makes it possible.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> converts:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pods</a> to lightweight VMs
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes</a> objects to vSphere-managed entities
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a> to policy and tenancy units From below, everything is Kubernetes.
<br>From above, everything is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> resources. VCF sits above Supervisor, so it sees:
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespaces</a>
Quotas
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Policy" data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policies</a>
The kind or form of the workload becomes irrelevant.VCF does NOT care:
whether the workload uses containerd or not
<br>whether it’s a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">PodVM</a> or classic VM
whether it runs Go, Java, or Bash
whether it was deployed via Helm, kubectl, or Terraform
whether it is “cloud-native” or “legacy”
Those are runtime-layer concerns, not platform-layer concerns.
A power grid doesn’t care if you plug in a toaster or a server rack—only how much power you draw and what safety rules apply.
This is why statements like these are true:
“Pod workloads are not special.”
“VM workloads are not special.”
“Guest clusters are just workloads.”
“Infrastructure doesn’t care about your app model.”
So, you don’t fight against the platform to fit the workload in; you design the workload to fit the platform’s (opinionated) invariants.To internalize VCF, don’t think in:
Pods vs VMs
Containers vs Processes
Control Planes vs Data Planes
<br>Instead, think in <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>:
Who owns this?
What are its limits?
How is it created and destroyed?
How does it fail?
How is it audited?
Don’t anchor your designs to what runs. Anchor them to how they are governed.If this does not make sense initially, give it some time and revisit this page once you navigate this website further. I assure you it will eventually click.<br>For now, let’s keep a mental note of this, and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="About VCF" data-href="About VCF" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/about-vcf.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">dive deeper into the VCF rabbit hole</a>.VMware Cloud Foundation<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>At its core, vSphere is a compute, storage, and network abstraction layer: A distributed operating system for data centers.It manages large collections of infrastructure, such as CPUs, storage, networking, GPUs, and DPUs as a seamless and dynamic operating environment, and also manages the complexity of a data center.&nbsp;
It virtualizes physical infrastructure into managed CPU, storage, and networking resources.vSphere
├── ESX (data plane)
├── vCenter Server (control plane)
└── Integrated services (HA, DRS, vMotion, etc.)
vSphere is a distributed system that provides the following:<br>The two core components of VMware&nbsp;vSphere are <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br>
Whereas <a data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a> is the Web UI that interacts with the APIs of vSphere components.vSphere is a product contract, not a system.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> are the systems that implement that contract.Here is how vSphere facilitates LCM:
<br>Lifecycle management via pre-staging <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> images.
<br>Near-zero-downtime live patching for <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
<br>vSphere as a platform, manages <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a> performance in several dimensions:
With its GPU support, vSphere improves workload performance for modern AI workloads
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> enables automatic load balancing of resources allocated to workloads in a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>.
Storage DRS optimizes VM data placement as the VM is created and used over time.
Moving workloads seamlessly across the fabric, and ensuring things are always ship-shape, is what vSphere excels at:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">High Availability</a> with&nbsp;vSphere automatically restarts your VMs following physical machine failure.
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> provides continuous availability of any application in the event of a hardware failure with no data loss or downtime.
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> enables live migration of virtual machines with no disruption to users or loss of service, eliminating the need to schedule application downtime for planned server maintenance. Storage vMotion avoids downtime for planned storage maintenance. At vSphere security is by default, not an afterthought:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Identity Federation</a> with Microsoft Entra ID, ADFS and Okta.
Virtual Machine Encryption: Data-at-rest encryption for virtual machine data and disks.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Trust Authority" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Trust Authority</a>: Remote attestation for sensitive workloads.
Yesn’t.Saying “vSphere is ‘ESX and vCenter’.” is colloquially common, but technically incomplete.<br>See <a data-href="vSphere, ESX, and vCenter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere, ESX, and vCenter</a> for a more nuanced analysis.<br>You might also want to check <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> for an idea of what vSphere directly controls, and what capabilities it has.<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, one of the core components that makes vSphere, vSphere.vSphere<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>NSX enables network connectivity, operations, and scale. It uses a software-defined approach to networking that spans data centers, clouds and application frameworks.NSX abstracts network services from the underlying hardware, enabling programmable infrastructure through APIs. You can implement policies and workflows to automate tasks like network provisioning, security enforcement, load balancing, streamlining operations, and improving efficiency.NSX provides a complete set of logical networking capabilities and services, including logical switching, routing, distributed load balancing, virtual private network (VPN), quality of service (QoS), and monitoring.Enable logical Layer 2 overlay extensions across a routed (Layer 3) fabric within and across data center boundaries.Dynamic routing between virtual networks that is performed in a distributed manner in the hypervisor kernel, and scale-out routing with active-active failover with physical routers. Static routing and dynamic routing protocols are supported, including support for IPv6.Complete data plane isolation among tenants with a separate routing table, network address translation (NAT), and edge firewall support in each VRF on the&nbsp;Support for bridging between VLANs configured on the physical network and&nbsp;NSX overlay networks, for seamless connectivity between virtual and physical workloads.Site-to-site and unmanaged VPN for cloud gateway services.By using&nbsp;NSX, you can move workloads between racks and data centers by decoupling them from the underlying networks.Centralized policy configuration and enforcement across multiple locations from a single pane of glass, enabling network-wide consistent policy, operational simplicity, and simplified disaster recovery architecture.Enable consistent networking and security across data center sites, and across private cloud boundaries, irrespective of underlying physical topology or cloud platform.NSX can manage the provisioning, deployment, operations and retirement of networking infrastructure and applications from a central control pane.<br>You can automate infrastructure operations and offload manual tasks with workflows and agile templating using tools such as&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, Terraform, and Ansible.&nbsp;<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>s provide isolated network environments within a shared infrastructure. You can use Virtual Private Cloud (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Private Cloud" data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>) constructs to provision and manage network resources to business units or project teams independently, with granular control over networking policies and resource allocation.<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> for a more technical overview about NSX internal, or look at <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>, or <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>.NSX<br>vSAN&nbsp;aggregates local or direct-attached capacity devices of all <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts in a cluster and creates a single storage pool shared across all ESX hosts in the&nbsp;
vSAN cluster.Use&nbsp;vSAN&nbsp;as a VI administrator or storage administrator to enhance storage performance by aggregating local storage into a single shared pool across all hosts in a&nbsp;vSAN cluster.<br>You can use vSphere features that require shared storage, such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere HA</a>, vSphere <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>, and vSphere <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, without the need for external shared storage.vSAN provides operational consistency from edge to cloud, with complete visibility and lifecycle management of compute and storage from a single UI.You can perform consistent, VM-centric operations by using policy-based management. Within the vSAN ESA, per-VM policies increase flexibility of management, enabling compression policies, or customize data services on a per-VM basis.<br>Want some L2/L3 network magic? Then check out <a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>.vSAN<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>
