creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 21:28:25 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-image_15bfae.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-image_15bfae.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a> ← merge this article into “guest cluster”<br><img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/69/2015/12/Workload-Domain.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/5-2/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/5-0/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/b160a13c-2ace-43bd-8ea6-999e66bf83ac.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">In VMware Cloud Foundation, a Workload Cluster is a cluster dedicated to running tenant workloads—VMs or Kubernetes-backed workloads—as opposed to running the platform itself.It lives inside a Workload Domain (VI Domain) and is where actual business applications execute.In plain terms:
Workload Clusters run applications; Management Clusters run the cloud.
VCF Platform
│
├── Management Domain
│ └── Management Cluster (platform services only)
│
└── Workload Domain (VI Domain) ├── Workload Cluster A ← tenant workloads ├── Workload Cluster B ← tenant workloads └── Workload Cluster C ← tenant workloads A Workload Domain can contain multiple Workload Clusters Each cluster is an operational and failure boundary Tenants never see the Management Cluster, but they consume resources from Workload Clusters Depending on how VCF is used, a Workload Cluster may host: Traditional virtual machines App servers, databases, legacy systems Managed via vCenter Governed via VCF Automation (orgs, projects, policies) Supervisor-backed workloads Guest clusters (e.g., TKG) PodVM-based workloads Namespaces mapped to projects The cluster itself is workload-agnostic; policy determines what lands there.This split is critical: Tenants use clusters Platform Admins operate clusters This is where: CPU, memory, storage are consumed Network traffic flows Availability and performance matter most Each Workload Cluster provides: Fault isolation Upgrade isolation Security boundaries A problem in one cluster should not affect others.Clusters are upgraded: Under SDDC Manager control In a controlled, validated sequence Independently of other clusters (within constraints) It is not: A management plane A place for SDDC Manager or NSX Managers A tenant abstraction by itself A free-for-all environment A Workload Cluster is shared infrastructure, not a tenant.Important nuance: Tenancy does not equal cluster Multiple tenants can share: The same Workload Cluster While remaining isolated via: Organizations Projects Namespaces NSX micro-segmentation Clusters are capacity and fault boundaries, not business boundaries. Workload Cluster → Kubernetes worker node pool Management Cluster → Kubernetes control plane Namespaces / Projects → Tenant isolation VCF Automation → Policy and governance layer You scale, isolate, and govern above the cluster. Strong fault isolation Predictable lifecycle Flexible placement strategies Supports mixed workload types More moving parts Requires capacity planning Requires clear cluster placement policy VCF optimizes for enterprise-scale control, not minimal topology. Workload Clusters are where applications run They live inside Workload (VI) Domains They are operated by Platform Admins They can host VM and Kubernetes workloads They are shared but strongly governed If you want, next we can: Contrast Workload Cluster vs Supervisor Cluster Explain how projects map to clusters Walk through placement and scheduling decisions Discuss anti-patterns (overloading a single cluster) ]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/workload-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/Workload Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:56:57 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/69/2015/12/Workload-Domain.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/69/2015/12/Workload-Domain.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[SDDC]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" target="_self"><br>Within <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, an SDDC is the foundational architectural model that virtualizes all core data-center resources (compute, storage, networking, and management) and delivers them as software services.<br>Think of SDDC as the “what”, while <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is the “productized implementation” of that model.In an SDDC:<br>No hardware-specific configuration is required by <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenants</a>. Everything is expressed as policies, APIs, and declarative intent.If you think of SDDC as an interface, VCF is an implementation of that interface.Or in mor simpler terms, You cannot “install an SDDC”.
You deploy VCF, and the result is an SDDC.As a very simplistic analogy:
SDDC → “Cloud computing”
VCF → “AWS (but for private cloud)”
Inside VCF, SDDC enables:
Uniform resource abstraction <br>A VM workload and a Kubernetes workload are both “<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workloads</a>” Policy-driven behavior <br>Placement, <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, security, backups are rules, not scripts Lifecycle coherence <br>Upgrade <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> together, safely and repeatably Multi-tenancy <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>, quotas, RBAC Cloud-like operations on-prem <br>Self-service, APIs, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, chargeback SDDC is not:
A single product
Just virtualization
Just Kubernetes
A UI
A vCenter feature
It is the system-level design philosophy that VCF enforces.VCF’s value proposition is:
“You don’t assemble an SDDC yourself anymore: We ship one.”
That’s why:
VCF has strict BOMs
VCF enforces lifecycle orchestration
VCF tightly integrates ops + automation + infra
This is intentional: freedom at the top, rigidity at the bottom.
SDDC = architecture
VCF = implementation of that architecture
In VCF, everything (compute, storage, network, ops) is software-defined
SDDC enables cloud-like behavior on private infrastructure
You deploy VCF, and you get an SDDC: That simple.
<br><a data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Private Cloud</a> could be a topic of interest to look at right after SDDC.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/SDDC.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:55:18 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-domain-b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tenants in Supervisor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>
<br>In vSphere Supervisor a tenant is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Tenants in Supervisor" data-href="Tenants in Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace-bound</a>.
There is no separate tenant object inside Kubernetes.
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> is the tenant boundary at the vSphere-Kubernetes interface.
If you assume:
Tenant = Project → you’ll design the wrong thing
Tenant = Kubernetes namespace → you’ll under-secure
Tenant = Supervisor Namespace → things line up
“tenant namespace” is an informal shorthand for supervisor namespace. Organizations and Projects are governance overlays. They do not define the tenant.Kubernetes namespaces inside guest clusters are secondary scopes.<br>In <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> each tenant is realized as one (or more) <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s.<br>
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> sits above, provides governance (Organizations, Projects, quotas) and self-service, but does not define tenancy by itself.This is sometimes “informally” expressed as “tenant namespaces”. What is meant by it is a Supervisor Namespace.Or more precisely: In a Supervisor Cluster tenant == supervisor namespace (there is a 1-1 relationship).<br>In vSphere Supervisor, tenancy is realized through <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, which serve as the execution and isolation boundary for tenants.When people say:
“tenant namespace”
“project namespace”
“customer namespace”
They almost always mean: A Supervisor Namespace allocated to that tenant. Kubernetes does not have a separate construct for this: It is a vSphere concept, projected as a namespace.A Supervisor Namespace can contain:
Pods
VMs
Entire guest Kubernetes clusters
Tenant
└── Supervisor Namespace ├── VM workloads ├── Pod workloads └── Guest K8s Cluster └── many Kubernetes namespaces
VCF Environment
└── vSphere (vCenter) └── Supervisor Cluster └── Supervisor Namespace ← TENANT BOUNDARY
At this layer:
Supervisor Namespace Has: Resource limits
Storage policies
Network segments
RBAC bindings Is created and owned by vCenter
Maps to: Resource pools
NSX constructs
Datastore permissions
This is where hard multitenancy lives. <br><img alt="supervisor-cluster.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster.webp" target="_self"><br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>This is logical tenancy, not execution tenancy.It is the automation and consumption layer.Organization
└── Project └── Deployment / Blueprint └── (Targets a Supervisor Namespace) Organization Business / administrative grouping Project Quota + governance container These map downwards, but they don’t execute workloads themselves.<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> defines a tenant from a runtime and security perspective.<br>At <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, Organizations and Projects define:
Ownership
Billing
<br><a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>
Access workflows
But not execution boundaries.
VCF Environment (Rackspace)
└── Supervisor Cluster ├── ns-cocacola ← Tenant: Coca-Cola ├── ns-pepsi ← Tenant: Pepsi └── ns-pizzahut ← Tenant: Pizza Hut
Each tenant is a supervisor namespace.<br><img alt="Supervisor-Namespace.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-namespace.png" target="_self">For Coca-Cola (example):
Fixed CPU / memory quota
Dedicated or isolated NSX segment
Approved storage policies
RBAC scoped to Coca-Cola admins
Ability to run: Pods
VMs
Guest Kubernetes clusters
That namespace is the tenant boundary. Layer VCF automation on top of this:Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke-Prod └── Deployments → targets ns-cocacola Organization: Pepsi
└── Project: Pepsi-Shared └── Deployments → targets ns-pepsi
Organizations and Projects map to Supervisor Namespaces — they do not replace them.Automation gives:
Self-service catalogs
Approval workflows
Policy as code
Lifecycle orchestration
But the tenant still “lives” at the Supervisor Namespace.Scope
vCenter
Supervisor Cluster
NSX
Storage policies
Responsibilities
Create Supervisor Namespaces
Set quotas
Attach networks
Bind tenant identities
Enforce platform guardrails
Power level
God-mode
Not visible to customers
Scope
One Supervisor Namespace (e.g., ns-cocacola)
Kubernetes API within that namespace
Responsibilities
Manage workloads
Deploy guest clusters
Configure service
Delegate access internally
Cannot
See other tenants
Modify quotas
Escape namespace
This is who you hand the kubeconfig to.
Scope
Kubernetes RBAC inside tenant (supervisor) namespace
Possibly inside guest clusters
Responsibilities
Deploy apps
Manage services
Consume secrets
No infrastructure privileges
Scope
Automation policies
Catalogs
Projects
Approvals
This role:
Often held by Rackspace
Sometimes delegated partially to tenants
<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:secrets" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#secrets">#secrets</a>
Secrets do not cross Supervisor Namespaces
Identity trust roots often terminate there
Network policy enforcement happens there
Audit logs are scoped there
So when you say tenant == Supervisor Namespace,
then:
Security
Compliance
Billing
Automation
all align clearly.
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Tenants in Supervisor.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:51:46 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cluster.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Administrative Roles in VCF]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>In VMware Cloud Foundation, Platform Admin and Tenant Admin are useful conceptual terms, but not official role names in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.VCF defines explicit, documented roles such as:
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>
(and related Auditor / User roles)
This page uses Platform Admin as a conceptual responsibility boundary, and Organization / Project Administrator as the official tenant-facing roles defined by VCF.The distinction is intentional and fundamental.<br>VCF separates infrastructure ownership from consumption <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Governance" data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">governance</a>: platform infrastructure is operated outside <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, while <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s and <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>s govern what runs within tenant boundaries.<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> has <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Tenant</a>-level authority.<br>An <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> represents the tenant boundary in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.They manage:
Organization-level configuration
Tenant users and role assignments
Organization-wide quotas and policies
Governance within the organization
They cannot:
Modify platform topology
Upgrade core infrastructure
Affect other organizations
Bypass platform guardrails
<br>The <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> is a <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>-scoped operational authority.<br>A <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> manages consumption and operations within a single <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>, which maps to one (typical, but can be more than one) <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>.<br>
The <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> can create <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, assign users and groups, and allocate quotas to restrict the configurations available to the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Tenants in Supervisor" data-href="Tenants in Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-in-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenants</a>.
|<br>
By creating <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, you can isolate security and networking objects across tenants in a single&nbsp;NSX deployment.
Project Administrators manage:
Project users and access
Workload provisioning (VMs, Kubernetes clusters, services)
Project-scoped quotas and approvals
Day-to-day operational policies
Their authority is strictly bounded by:
<br>The <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>
Platform-defined constraints
Without this separation:
Tenants could break upgrade paths
Platform consistency would erode
Supportability would collapse
One tenant could impact others
VCF deliberately trades tenant flexibility for platform predictability, safety, and lifecycle integrity.
Organization Administrator is the true tenant administrator in VCF 9
Project Administrator governs consumption within a tenant
The separation protects multi-tenancy, lifecycle management, and supportability
This boundary is foundational to VCF’s architecture
<br><a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a> is the logical follow-up to this section, which dives into more details of predefined roles and privileges in **<a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/administrative-roles-in-vcf.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Administrative Roles in VCF.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:51:33 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Operations Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> delivers the observability, analytics, and operational intelligence layer for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> environments. It focuses on understanding system behavior, maintaining platform health, and enabling proactive operations across compute, storage, and networking—both in real time and over longer planning horizons.<br>Where <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> answers “what should be deployed and governed?”,<br>
<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> answers “how is the platform behaving, and where are risks emerging?”VCF Operations continuously ingests telemetry, events, metrics, and logs from across the VCF stack to provide operators with actionable insights rather than raw data.Provides a holistic, continuously evaluated view of platform health across domains and components.
Validates configuration consistency against VMware best practices
Detects drift, misconfigurations, and version incompatibilities
Surfaces health scores and risk indicators at fleet, domain, and component levels
Helps operators move from reactive firefighting to preventive maintenance
This provides a continuous “wellness check” for the entire VCF environment.Enables rapid root-cause analysis when issues arise.
Correlates symptoms across compute, storage, and networking layers
Analyzes historical trends to distinguish transient issues from systemic problems
Provides guided troubleshooting workflows and impact analysis
Reduces mean time to detect (MTTD) and mean time to resolution (MTTR)
Instead of isolated alerts, diagnostics focus on cause-and-effect relationships.Centralizes and contextualizes logs generated across the VCF stack.
Aggregates logs from infrastructure and platform components
Enables search, filtering, and correlation across time and services
Supports security investigations, audits, and post-incident analysis
Complements metrics-based monitoring with forensic-level visibility
Logs become evidence, not noise.Monitors and analyzes the health, performance, and behavior of networking components.
Tracks latency, packet loss, throughput, and flow patterns
Detects anomalies and deviations from normal traffic behavior
Helps identify bottlenecks, misrouted traffic, and configuration issues
Provides visibility across logical and physical networking layers
This bridges the traditional gap between virtual networking abstractions and real network behavior.Delivers insight into capacity, performance, and reliability of storage resources.
Monitors IOPS, latency, throughput, and utilization trends
Predicts capacity exhaustion and performance degradation
Identifies imbalanced workloads and storage hotspots
Supports informed decisions around scaling and optimization
Storage operations turn capacity planning from guesswork into data-driven forecasting.VCF Operations is:
Observability and operational intelligence
Predictive and preventive rather than purely reactive
Focused on platform behavior and risk
VCF Operations is not:
A workload deployment or provisioning system
A policy enforcement or approval engine
A tenant-facing self-service layer VCF Operations is the operational nervous system of VCF
It emphasizes insight, correlation, and prediction—not just monitoring
It complements VCF Automation by ensuring the platform remains healthy, performant, and secure over time
Its value compounds as environments scale and diversify
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Observability and Health/Operations Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:42:48 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Services and Standalone Components]]></title><description><![CDATA[Create declarative <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a>s and upstream Kubernetes clusters by using <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Kubernetes Service</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/overview/vsphere-supervisor-services-and-standalone-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Overview/vSphere Supervisor Services and Standalone Components.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:01:36 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[ESX]]></title><description><![CDATA[ESX is the virtualization platform where you create and run <a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s and <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a>s, Kubernetes <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a>s, and AI/ML <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload</a>s.&nbsp;
ESX is a Type-1 (bare-metal) hypervisor
Runs directly on hardware
Owns: CPU scheduling
Memory management
Device virtualization Does not coordinate clusters by itself
You can run standalone ESX without vCenter, but:
No clustering
<br>No <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
<br>No <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br>No <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> orchestration
ESX is a hypervisor, it is not a traditional Linux OS.In ESX, there is no general-purpose userland like you’d expect in Linux or Windows.ESX is a purpose-built, bare-metal hypervisor operating system whose kernel (VMKernel) directly manages hardware resources and runs virtual machines.<br>Exploring the relationship between <a data-href="vSphere, ESX, and vCenter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere, ESX, and vCenter</a> may clarify some of of the dangling question marks, if you have any.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/ESX.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:00:43 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload]]></title><link>./https://vcf.wtf/workload.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Workload.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 15:00:20 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[workload-placement-1545135394507]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 14:29:57 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Live Recovery]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vlr-a720af5a-d03d-4555-ae37-d66544841463.cq5dam.web.1280.1280.jpeg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vlr-a720af5a-d03d-4555-ae37-d66544841463.cq5dam.web.1280.1280.jpeg" target="_self">VMware Live Recovery is VMware’s modern, unified disaster-recovery (DR) and cyber-recovery capability, designed to protect VCF-managed workloads against outages, site failures, and ransomware, with minimal downtime and minimal data loss.
VMware Live Recovery = continuous protection + fast failover + clean recovery, natively aligned with VCF operations.
VMware Live Recovery is not a hypervisor feature and not just storage replication.<br>It lives at the platform services / operations layer of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>.
Site failure
Cluster outage
Maintenance windows gone wrong Encrypted VMs
Malicious data corruption
Need for clean rollback instead of “latest replica” Near-zero RPO (seconds)
Change-block tracking
Continuous replication rather than periodic snapshots Automated failover / failback
Application-aware recovery ordering
Network remapping and IP preservation Roll back to a known-good state
Avoid restoring infected replicas
Immutable recovery points (depending on the backing storage) Protect workloads: on-prem → on-prem
on-prem → cloud
cloud → cloud Strong alignment with hybrid VCF deployments
Primarily:
VM workloads
vSAN-backed storage
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF-managed domains</a>
It is not:
A Kubernetes-native backup system
A replacement for application-level backups
A secrets-or-identity-recovery tool
^ all these remain separate concerns.You can think of VCF as enforcing invariants:
“Workloads must be recoverable within defined SLOs.”
VMware Live Recovery is the enforcement mechanism for the resilience invariant:
If a site fails → recover
If data is corrupted → rewind safely
If ransomware hits → recover clean, fast, and confidently
VLR is
<br>Not <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br>Not <a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a>
Not a backup product
Not a Kubernetes-native DR
Those solve mobility or data protection, not platform-level resilience orchestration.
VMware Live Recovery is VCF’s unified DR + cyber-recovery platform
Designed for low RPO, fast RTO, and clean recovery
Successor mindset to SRM, built for ransomware-era threats
Operates at the VCF Operations layer, not the hypervisor
Focused on VM workloads, not containers or apps directly
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 0 Tasks</a>, <a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> could be nice places to visit from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmware-live-recovery.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Workload Mobility and Resilience/VMware Live Recovery.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 14:28:02 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vlr-a720af5a-d03d-4555-ae37-d66544841463.cq5dam.web.1280.1280.jpeg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vlr-a720af5a-d03d-4555-ae37-d66544841463.cq5dam.web.1280.1280.jpeg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Operations HCX]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="hcx-bc63de63-befa-4cff-941b-d69c413dd8ac.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/hcx-bc63de63-befa-4cff-941b-d69c413dd8ac.original.png" target="_self"><br>VCF Operations HCX is VMware’s integrated workload mobility and migration platform built into <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>. It combines the power of VMware Hybrid Cloud Extension (HCX) with VCF’s operational tooling to simplify application migration, workload rebalancing, and business continuity across data centers and clouds.You can perform secure and automated migrations without requiring changes to applications or network configurations.Thus, you can place workloads based on business requirements. The platform minimizes downtime during migrations, improves scalability, and supports compliance and security throughout workload transitions.<br>HCX stands for Hybrid Cloud eXtension—it’s not just another name for <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>. It’s a comprehensive application mobility platform from VMware that enables workload migration, workload rebalancing, and business continuity across data centers and clouds.VCF Operations HCX has the following capabilities:
Seamless workload migration. Migrate VMs and applications in waves live or in bulk with minimal or zero downtime.
Network extension. Extend networks while preserving IP addresses and topologies to maintain application connectivity.
Inter-and intra-VCF mobility. Enable workload mobility within and across multiple&nbsp;VCF instances, including site-to-site and region-to-region migrations.
Application placement optimization. Enables high-performance application mobility across different environments, making it easier to optimize workload placement based on business requirements.
At its heart, VCF Operations HCX is an application mobility platform that:
**Connects environments—on-premises data centers, private clouds, and public clouds—with optimized, secure network interconnectivity.
Enables workload migration—live or bulk migration of virtual machines (VMs) and applications between environments with minimal downtime.
Supports hybrid cloud adoption—making it easier to modernize, consolidate, or balance workloads across sites.
Essentially, it extends the capabilities of VCF so that moving workloads into, out of, or around your VCF estate is seamless and automated.VCF Operations HCX automates the process of moving VMs and applications from one environment to another. This includes:
Live migrations (zero or near-zero downtime)
Bulk migrations for large-scale moves
Cross-platform migrations (including non-vSphere sources in some scenarios)
Network extension so IPs/MACs remain consistent during migration
This makes migrations faster, less error-prone, and less disruptive than traditional approaches.HCX builds a secure, encrypted interconnect between sites that:
Extends Layer-2 networks across sites
Preserves VM networking so that workloads keep their addresses
Provides optimized tunnels tailored for high-speed bulk movement
Cloud adoption isn’t a one-time event — usage patterns change. HCX enables:
Moving workloads based on performance needs
Rebalancing for cost or compliance reasons
Continuous optimization of where workloads run
This is key in hybrid environments where business needs or performance requirements evolve over time.VCF Operations HCX has deeper integration with VCF:
Unified management &amp; single sign-on with other VCF components
Shared licensing managed through VCF Operations
Integrated planning &amp; execution workflows with VCF Operations for Networks
Easier deployment with a single unified HCX Manager appliance
That means less separate manual setup and a smoother experience from discovery to execution.Imagine you’re relocating a city’s services (libraries, police stations, hospitals) to a new smart city:
Traditional migration = manually moving each building piece by piece.
VCF Operations HCX = building a dedicated transit corridor where services can shift live without interruption, while preserving all their connections and addresses — all orchestrated by a central operations dashboard instead of manual labor.
<br>vMotion is VMware’s native live-migration technology for moving a running VM between <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts (including memory and CPU state), usually within the same <a data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Domain</a> or cluster.HCX doesn’t replace vMotion; it leverages it as one migration method (called “HCX vMotion”) when moving workloads between HCX-connected sites. It also supports:
Cold Migration: Powered-off VMs
Bulk Migration: Parallel, batched workloads
Replication-Assisted vMotion: Parallel live migrations via replication + vMotion
So, vMotion is a component inside HCX’s larger orchestration and connectivity framework. VCF Operations HCX is VMware’s integrated workload mobility solution within VMware Cloud Foundation.
It simplifies application migration and workload rebalancing across on-prem, hybrid, and multi-cloud environments.
Via optimized network extension and interconnects, it preserves application connectivity and minimizes disruption.
Recent integrations with VCF improve deployment, management, and operational workflows.
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 0 Tasks</a>, <a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> could be nice places to visit from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Workload Mobility and Resilience/VCF Operations HCX.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 14:24:29 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/hcx-bc63de63-befa-4cff-941b-d69c413dd8ac.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/hcx-bc63de63-befa-4cff-941b-d69c413dd8ac.original.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[FinOps and Capacity]]></title><description><![CDATA[Cost management helps you analyze your infrastructure expenses. In this way, you can identify areas that are most suitable to use capacity management for optimal utilization of your resources.You can use the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="FinOps and Capacity" data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">FinOps</a> or <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="FinOps and Capacity" data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cost Management</a> capabilities to monitor infrastructure-related costs and associated services or license expenses with greater precision.Capacity Management consists of 3 sets of capabilities: assess, optimize and plan.Capacity optimization helps you right-size or reclaim any underutilized or wasted resources.
<br><a data-href="Workload Placement" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/workload-placement.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Placement</a> lets you optimize virtual machines and storage across clusters to reduce resource contention and maintain optimum system performance.
By using What-If Analysis, you can plan for an increase or decrease in workload or capacity requirements in your virtual infrastructure.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Capacity and Cost Optimization/FinOps and Capacity.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 14:20:57 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workflow]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="workflow-1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png" target="_self">Workflows consist of a schema, workflow variables, and input and output parameters.The workflow schema is the main component of a workflow as it defines all the workflow elements and the logical connections between them. The workflow variables and parameters are the properties that workflows use to transfer data.<br><img alt="vro-image-1024x622.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vro-image-1024x622.webp" target="_self"><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, there isn’t a single “workflow engine” owned by only one product. Different parts of VCF create/execute different kinds of workflows:<br>VCF Automation is the place where you typically design and run “<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">day-1</a>” style workflows tied to requests (catalog items, provisioning, configuration, approvals, extensibility, etc.). Its value prop explicitly includes orchestration and extensibility.<br>Under the hood, these workflows commonly leverage an <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Operations" data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Orchestrator</a> (formerly vRealize Orchestrator) integrated/embedded with the automation stack. It is executed by <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> which is a part of the <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> stack.<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> is primarily the ops brain: monitoring, alerting, capacity, compliance, etc.. It can run actions (and sometimes chain remediation) in response to alerts.<br>Actual workflow automation is done through <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a>, which is explicitly described as a “workflow automation solution” and can create and run workflows.<br><a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> saves a workflow token every time a workflow runs, recording the details of that specific workflow run.Workflows receive input parameters and generate output parameters when they run.Most workflows require a certain set of input parameters to run. An input parameter is an argument that the workflow processes when it runs. The user, an application, another workflow, or an action passes input parameters to a workflow for the workflow to process when it runs.For example, if a workflow resets a virtual machine, the workflow requires the name of the virtual machine as an input parameter.A workflow's output parameters represent the result from the workflow run. Output parameters can change when a workflow or a workflow element runs. During a workflow run, the workflow can receive the output parameters of other workflows as input parameters.For example, if a workflow creates a snapshot of a virtual machine, the output parameter for the workflow is the resulting snapshot.Workflow elements process data that they receive as input parameters, and set the resulting data as workflow variables or output parameters.Read-only workflow variables act as global constants for a workflow. Writable variables act as a workflow’s global variables.You can use variables to transfer data between the elements of a workflow.You can obtain variables in the following ways:
Define variables when you create a workflow.
Set the output parameter of a workflow element as a workflow variable.
Inherit variables from a configuration element.
A workflow schema is a graphical representation that shows the workflow as a flow diagram of interconnected workflow elements. The workflow schema is the most important element of a workflow as it determines its logic.When users run a workflow, they provide the values for the input parameters of the workflow in the workflow presentation.A workflow token represents a workflow that is running or has finished running.A workflow is an abstract description of a process that defines a generic sequence of steps and a generic set of required input parameters. When you run a workflow with a set of input parameters, you receive an instance of this abstract workflow that behaves according to the specific input parameters you give it. This specific instance of a finished or a running workflow is called a workflow token.Workflow Token Attributes are the specific parameters with which a workflow token runs.The workflow token attributes are an aggregation of the workflow's global variables and the specific input and output parameters with which you run the workflow token.<br>Next, you might want to look into <a data-href="Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows</a>, or you can check out <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/Workflow.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 14:06:06 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[workflow-1]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/workflow-1.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 13:46:04 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[IaaS]]></title><description><![CDATA[IaaS (infrastructure as a service) is a cloud computing model where you rent fundamental IT infrastructure—instead of owning and managing physical hardware.IaaS provides fundamental computing resources where the consumer can deploy and run arbitrary software, including operating systems and applications.In plain terms:
IaaS = someone else runs the data center; you control the machines.
The cloud provider gives you raw building blocks:
Compute → virtual machines (VMs)
Storage → block, object, file storage
Networking → virtual networks, IPs, load balancers, firewalls
You decide:
Which OS to run
How to configure the machine
What software to install
How to secure and scale it
Analogy:
Owning hardware → buying a house
IaaS → renting an empty apartment (walls and plumbing are there; furniture and rules are up to you) Amazon Web Services → EC2
Microsoft Azure → Virtual Machines
Google Cloud → Compute Engine
All of these give you VMs, networks, and storage—but no application opinion.Example:
IaaS → “Give me a Linux box”
PaaS → “Run my app”
SaaS → “Just let me use the app” Maximum control and flexibility
Works for legacy apps
Fine-grained networking &amp; security
Familiar mental model for infra engineers You manage OS patching and security
Higher operational burden
Easier to misconfigure
Less opinionated guardrails <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>-style VM workloads map very naturally to IaaS
VCF abstracts hardware, but still exposes infra
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes-on-VCF</a> starts moving you away from pure IaaS toward PaaS-like models
<br>That’s why <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">a workload is a workload is a workload</a>: From the platform’s perspective, VMs and pods are both just scheduled consumers of infrastructure.
IaaS = rented infrastructure
You control the OS and above
Most flexible, most responsibility
Foundation layer beneath PaaS and SaaS
Conceptually closest to traditional virtualization
<br>From here, going back to the beginning and exploring <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> with an understanding of what IaaS is, is not a bad choice.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Background and Context/IaaS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 03:56:47 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Multi-Tenancy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>In a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>-based platform, tenant isolation is realized through vSphere <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, which serve as the enforced execution boundary for workloads.<br>A single tenant may be associated with one or more <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, typically aligned to <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="