<br>Other topological constructs such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Cluster</a>, <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Edge" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Edge</a> are all good options to dive from here.VCF Management ComponentsVCF InstanceVCF Instance<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br><img alt="how-many-vcf-instances-per-vcf-fleet-0.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/how-many-vcf-instances-per-vcf-fleet-0.png" target="_self">In VMware Cloud Foundation, these three terms describe different scopes of control, stacked hierarchically from largest (fleet) to smallest (domain).<br><img alt="vcf-fleet-image_15bfae.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-fleet-image_15bfae.png" target="_self">If you only remember one thing:
Fleet → Instance → Domain
Management across clouds → One cloud → Parts of that cloud
<br>A <a data-href="VCF Fleet" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet</a> is a logical grouping of multiple <a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>s that are managed, observed, or governed together.It is a meta-layer, not a runtime construct.
Multiple data centers
Multiple regions
Core + Edge
Possibly different purposes (prod, DR, sovereign, etc.) Fleet-wide visibility
Cross-instance posture (versions, compliance, drift)
<br>Centralized operations and <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>
Consistent policies and standards Fleet = “My private cloud estate”
<br>A <a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a> is one deployed VCF system:
<br>One <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>
<br>One <a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a>
One lifecycle authority
This is the unit of deployment and lifecycle.
Independently installed
Independently upgraded
Independently failed / recovered
Self-contained control plane
Examples:
One on-prem private cloud
One regional cloud
One large edge aggregation site
<br>A Domain is a logical partition inside a <a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a>, used to separate management concerns, workload types, or failure domains.There are two major kinds:
Created first
Hosts: <br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>
<br>Management <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>s Runs the platform itself One or more per instance
Host: Tenant workloads
<br>Application clusters (i.e., <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>s) Independently scalable and isolatable Domain = “A major subsystem within a Cloud”
VCF Fleet
│
├── VCF Instance (DC-West)
│ ├── Management Domain
│ ├── Workload Domain – Prod
│ └── Workload Domain – Dev
│
├── VCF Instance (DC-East)
