CLIs are just API clients
Using these APIs preserves VCF invariants and supportability
<br>Since it’s related to APIs, you might want to check out what a <a data-href="Gated SDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/gated-sdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Gated SDK</a> is.VCF SDKs, APIs, and CLIs<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br><img alt="vcf-installer-Image-0.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-0.webp" target="_self"><br>VCF Installer is the one-time (or rare-use) bootstrap and bring-up tool for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>VCF Installer’s sole purpose is to stand up the very first VCF environment and hand control over to <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.<br>If <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> is the factory control system, VCF Installer is the factory construction crew that builds the factory in the first place.<br><img alt="vcf-installer-image-134.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-installer-image-134.webp" target="_self">VCF Installer exists to answer a very specific question:
“Given raw hardware, how do I get to a fully functional VCF Management Domain with SDDC Manager running?”
Once that answer is executed successfully, VCF Installer is done.VCF Installer is responsible for:
Validating hardware readiness
Validating network configuration
Validating DNS / NTP / IPAM
Validating credentials and certificates
Orchestrating the initial deployment of: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> on hosts
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> components <br>This is <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> only work.Before anything is deployed, VCF Installer runs extensive prechecks, including:
Hardware compatibility (HCL alignment)
Network reachability
MTU consistency
IP pool correctness
Time synchronization
DNS forward/reverse lookup
Credential access
Think of it as a fail-fast safety gate: Better to stop early than build a broken cloud.VCF Installer typically operates with:
Structured input (JSON / guided wizard)
Explicit topology definitions
Explicit IP assignments
You declare what you want, and the installer executes a deterministic build.<br>There is no concept of “incremental evolution” here: That belongs to <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.It is not:
A lifecycle manager
A long-running control plane
A tenant or consumption interface
A policy engine
An operations tool
After bring-up:
It is not used daily
It does not manage upgrades
It does not manage workload domains
<br>Those responsibilities move entirely to the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>.Once installation completes:
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> becomes the authoritative owner
VCF Installer steps out of the picture
You can think of it as:
VCF Installer creates SDDC Manager; SDDC Manager creates and manages everything else.
A natural question is: “Why not just use SDDC Manager from the start?”Because:
SDDC Manager itself must be deployed
That deployment requires validated sequencing
That sequencing must run before SDDC Manager exists
VCF Installer solves this bootstrapping paradox.
VCF Installer → kubeadm init
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> → Kubernetes control plane (after init)
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> → Higher-level UX / APIs for consumers
You don’t run kubeadm init every day, and you don’t run VCF Installer every day either.
VCF Installer is a Day-0 tool
It bootstraps the Management Domain
<br>It deploys the <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> itself
It performs strict prechecks and validation
After success, it is effectively retired
<br>Why not look into <a data-href="VCF Fleet Deployment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-fleet-deployment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet Deployment</a>?VCF InstallerSupervisor ClusterSupervisor ClusterBlueprintBlueprint<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a>VCF Automation enables IT teams and cloud service providers to deliver a self-service private cloud for AI, Kubernetes, and VM-based applications.<br>The solution simplifies the process of provisioning and scaling a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">multi-tenant</a> private cloud with out-of-the-box Infrastructure as a Service (<a data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">IaaS</a>) offerings, accelerating the time to market for applications while maintaining control using policy-based governance.<br>VCF Automation provides <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> at the request and lifecycle level—controlling who can deploy which patterns, under what constraints and approvals—while runtime security, drift detection, and continuous enforcement are handled by downstream platforms.VCF Automation has the following capabilities:
<br><a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>: Provides a set of cloud services to meet the needs of application teams
<br><a data-href="Provider Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>: Supports IT teams and cloud service providers to effectively manage, deliver, and scale cloud services across multiple vCenter and VCF instances.
<br><a data-href="Organization Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a>: Provides capabilities that enable the organization administrator of a Line of Business or a tenant to further organize and govern resources allocated to them among application teams.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>: Provides the capability to run Kubernetes workloads directly on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and to create <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">upstream Kubernetes clusters</a> within dedicated <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>.
<br>From here, you can jump to <a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>, <a data-href="Provider Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>.<br>
Also, <a data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">User Roles</a> and <a data-href="Project Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/project-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Management</a> are other good candidates to explore. Or, dive directly into <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.VCF Automation<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br><img alt="vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vfc-operations-fleet-management-01cbba60-ff79-48cf-abff-2810a485f098.webp" target="_self">VCF Operations&nbsp;helps your organization build, manage, operate and secure your private cloud infrastructure by deploying and maintaining its fleet-level components, providing visibility and enhanced performance across the workload and infrastructure stack, and helping your organization stay compliant with regulatory standards and organizational guidelines.VCF Operations has these functional areas:
<br><a data-href="Fleet Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/managing-the-cloud/fleet-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fleet Management</a> Enables operational consistency and efficient resource management of the&nbsp;VCF infrastructure at scale. <br><a data-href="Operations Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operations Management</a> Provides monitoring and optimization of performance, cost and capacity, and faster troubleshooting. <br><a data-href="Workload Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Operations</a> &nbsp;Ensures that critical applications are running as expected. <br><a data-href="Performance Monitoring" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Performance Monitoring</a> Ensures applications have continuous access to resources <br><a data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">FinOps and Capacity</a> Helps you analyze your infrastructure expenses and optimize capacity usage. <br><a data-href="VCF Operations HCX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vcf-operations-hcx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations HCX</a> Provides support for migrating and interconnecting workloads within and across VCF private cloud. <br><a data-href="Security Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/security-and-compliance/security-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Security Management</a> Provides security management to ensure that your VCF private cloud is operationally secure. VCF Operations does not:
=======
Supervisor Namespaces are the hard isolation boundary in VCF
Organizations and Projects provide governance, not isolation
Tenants may span multiple namespaces
VCF Automation governs consumption without compromising isolation
This layered design is foundational to VCF’s security and supportability
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Multi-Tenancy.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 02:40:24 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Developing Workflows with VCF Operations Orchestrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[Workflow development involves using the workflow editor in&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator, the Orchestrator APIs, and the JavaScript, Python, Node.js, and PowerShell scripting languages.What does the workflow development involve?The process for developing a custom workflow involves a series of steps. Depending on the type of workflow that you are developing, you might follow a different sequence of step or skip a step. For example, you can create a workflow without custom scripting.Generally, developing a workflow involves the following steps. Create a new workflow or create a duplicate of an existing workflow from the standard library. Provide general information about the workflow. Define the input and output parameters of the workflow. Lay out and link the workflow schema to define the logical flow of the workflow. Bind the input and output parameters of each schema element to workflow variables. Write the necessary scripts for scriptable task elements or custom decision elements. Create the workflow presentation from the&nbsp; Input Form &nbsp;tab. Validate the workflow. Practices for developing workflowsYou can follow best practices for developing Orchestrator workflows by multiple users and in a clustered environment. Each developer has a dedicated test standalone Orchestrator instance for creating and developing workflows. As VCF Automation can only have single Orchestrator instance integrated to it, this should be a separate standalone instance. Workflows are saved as maven projects on a shared source code control system. To ensure optimal performance of the Orchestrator production deployment, it is best to import workflows in a scheduled period. Working with the workflow editorYou create and edit workflows in the Orchestrator workflow editor. The workflow editor is the Integrated Development Environment (IDE) of&nbsp;VCF Operations orchestrator&nbsp;for developing workflows.The workflow editor consists of tabs where you edit the components of your workflows. Summary. Provide general information about the workflow, such as the workflow name, description, tags, and version number. The Summary tab can also be used to configure the server restart behavior and workflow run failure behavior. Variables. Define the variables for your workflow. Variables were previously known as attributes. Input/Output. Define the input and output parameters of your workflow. The input parameters provide the data that the workflow processes during the workflow run. The output parameters are provided when the workflow run finishes. Schema. Build your workflow by dragging workflow schema elements from the workflow palette on the left side of the Schema tab. By clicking an element in the schema diagram, you can define and edit the element's behavior. Input Form. Define the layout of the user input dialog box that appears when users run a workflow. You arrange the parameters and variables into presentation steps and tabs to ease identification of parameters in the input parameters dialog box. You define the constraints on the input parameters that users can provide in the presentation by setting the parameter properties. You can also add external validation for your workflow by using actions. Version History. View and manage the version history of the workflow. Compare and restore versions and push and pull workflows to and from your integrated Git repository. Audit. View information about events related to the workflow such as, when it was saved, when a workflow run was performed, and when a workflow run was finished. ]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/developing-workflows-with-vcf-operations-orchestrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/Developing Workflows with VCF Operations Orchestrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 22 Dec 2025 14:59:21 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCloud Director]]></title><description><![CDATA[VMware vCloud Director (VCD) is a cloud-management and multi-tenancy layer built on top of <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>. It was designed primarily for service providers (ISPs, telcos, MSPs) to offer VMware-based clouds to multiple customers in a clean, isolated, self-service way.
vSphere → virtualization engine (hypervisors, clusters, VMs)
VCD → cloud abstraction + multi-tenant control plane
VCF → opinionated full stack (compute + storage + networking + ops)
vSphere does not have native multitenancy, VCD enables multitenancy.
VCD → sell VMware-based cloud to others VCF Automation → run your own internal cloud
Cloud Layer
────────────
vCloud Director ← multi-tenant cloud manager Automation Layer
────────────
VCF Automation / Aria Automation Infrastructure
────────────
vSphere + vSAN + NSX Hardware
────────────
Bare metal
<br><img alt="vcd-000.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcd-000.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vcd-26274c8be-3a18-40f1-adf0-8281a9feb4d8.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcd-26274c8be-3a18-40f1-adf0-8281a9feb4d8.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vcd-6adff3c1-ab57-4412-bdd8-2caa7cbd3982.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcd-6adff3c1-ab57-4412-bdd8-2caa7cbd3982.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vcd-3-Screen-Shot-2020-07-02-at-2.01.05-PM.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcd-3-screen-shot-2020-07-02-at-2.01.05-pm.webp" target="_self">No.
vSphere = hypervisor + cluster management
VCD = separate product that consumes vSphere
<br>VMware’s product web pages for Cloud Director explicitly state that VCD operates within the VMware Cloud Foundation platform as an integrated cloud-management layer: VCD is described as helping to “[efficiently […] operate and manage your managed private and public cloud services using VMware Cloud Director within the VMware Cloud Foundation platform](<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://www.vmware.com/products/cloud-infrastructure/cloud-director" rel="noopener nofollow" class="external-link is-unresolved" href="https://www.vmware.com/products/cloud-infrastructure/cloud-director" target="_self">VMware Cloud Director | Leading Cloud Service Delivery Platform</a>.However, in the baseline VCF component lists and core architectural docs, the docs list things like vSphere, vSAN, NSX, SDDC Manager, VCF Automation but not VCD as a base building block.
*Historically: no.
Today: “it depends on the SKU and use case.”**
VMware Cloud Foundation (VCF) is aimed at:
Enterprises
Private cloud
Platform teams
<br>Automation (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
VMware vCloud Director (VCD) is aimed at:
Service providers
Telcos
Hosted private cloud
Customer-facing tenancy
VCF does not require VCD, and most enterprise VCF deployments do not use it.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcloud-director/vcloud-director.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/vCloud Director/vCloud Director.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 25 Dec 2025 00:48:33 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcd-000.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcd-000.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VPC]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Private Cloud" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-private-cloud.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Private Cloud</a> ← merge]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vpc.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/Infrastructure Primitives/VPC.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:31:01 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Management Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2019/09/1.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/5-2/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/b8d5ddd7-899b-4c34-8947-4acbd57f8f72.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/5-2/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/9fa12b4a-ec40-44f0-91b7-9cb5272a39cc.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">In VMware Cloud Foundation, the Management Cluster is the foundational cluster that runs the platform itself.
It hosts the management plane—the services that build, operate, upgrade, and secure the rest of the cloud.Put simply:
If the Management Cluster is down, you can’t manage the cloud—only the workloads keep running.
The Management Cluster is part of the Management Domain (a special Workload Domain).
It is created first during Day-0 bring-up and is non-optional.Typical components include: SDDC Manager vCenter Server (management vCenter) NSX Managers vSAN management services Optional: Operations / Automation services (depending on deployment) These components do not belong to tenants. They belong to the platform.It runs the services that: Define topology Enforce lifecycle sequencing Validate upgrades Maintain inventory and state All VCF lifecycle operations (create domain, expand cluster, upgrade stack) are coordinated from here.Tenant workloads do not run here (by design): No tenant VMs No tenant Kubernetes workloads No customer apps This protects: Stability Security Upgrade safety It is not: A tenant cluster A workload execution environment A shared resource pool for apps Optional or replaceable Treating it like a general-purpose cluster is a serious anti-pattern.This separation ensures: Predictable upgrades (no tenant interference) Clear blast-radius control Strong security boundaries Operational sanity at scale It’s the same pattern used by: Kubernetes (control plane vs worker nodes) Public clouds (provider plane vs customer plane) Management Cluster → Kubernetes control plane nodes Workload Clusters → Kubernetes worker nodes SDDC Manager → Cluster lifecycle operator You wouldn’t run apps on the Kubernetes control plane; same rule applies here. Management Cluster is typically: Small (minimum viable size) Highly available Strictly protected If it fails: Existing workloads keep running You lose management, scaling, and upgrades until restored The Management Cluster runs the cloud, not the workloads It is part of the Management Domain It hosts SDDC Manager, vCenter, NSX Managers It is isolated, mandatory, and high-blast-radius Treat it as sacred infrastructure If you want, next we can: Compare Management Cluster vs Supervisor Cluster Walk through failure scenarios and recovery Discuss why tenants should never land here Map this to VCF Day-0 / Day-1 / Day-2 flows ]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/management-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/Management Cluster.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:24:49 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2019/09/1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2019/09/1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Platform Admin]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2018/09/Screen-Shot-2018-09-19-at-9.50.30-AM.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/a97cd01f-78bd-4c75-9033-bf9cbb5aa51c.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2021/03/Viewer_Role_Assigned-1024x352.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://vmtechie.blog/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/image-4.png?w=1024" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">In VMware Cloud Foundation, a Platform Admin is the role responsible for building, operating, and protecting the cloud platform itself, whereas a Tenant Admin operates within the boundaries that the platform defines.The distinction is intentional and fundamental.
Platform Admins manage the cloud; Tenant Admins manage what runs on the cloud.
Platform Admins control: VCF bring-up and expansion Workload Domains (create, expand, retire) Cluster topology Host add/remove End-to-end upgrades (ESXi, vCenter, NSX, vSAN) Version compatibility and validation This authority is exercised primarily via SDDC Manager.Platform Admins define and enforce: Supported topologies Approved upgrade paths Networking architecture (NSX fabrics, segments) Certificate and trust boundaries Global availability and DR patterns They prevent configuration drift and unsupported states.Platform Admins own: Physical and virtual isolation boundaries Network micro-segmentation at fabric level Root trust (certificates, identity backends) Auditability and compliance posture They decide what is possible, not just what is allowed.Platform Admins can: Enable multi-tenancy Define Organizations Set global quotas and policies Choose which services are exposed to tenants But they do not day-to-day operate tenant workloads.Tenant Admins operate inside the sandbox provided by the platform: Organization- or Project-scoped administration User and role management (within tenant) Quotas and approvals (within limits) Workload provisioning (VMs, Kubernetes, services) Policies related to consumption They cannot: Change platform topology Upgrade core infrastructure Bypass platform validation Affect other tenants Without this separation: Tenants could break upgrade paths Platform consistency would collapse Supportability would be impossible One tenant could affect another VCF deliberately trades flexibility for predictability and safety at the platform layer.Think of a public cloud provider: AWS/Azure Platform Team → Platform Admin Your AWS Account Admin → Tenant Admin You can do a lot in your account —
but you cannot upgrade AWS itself.That boundary is exactly what VCF recreates on-prem.A Platform Admin is not: A super tenant A convenience role Just “another admin with more permissions” It is a different class of responsibility with structural authority.Platform Admins are expected to: Understand deep system interactions Respect lifecycle invariants Make decisions with global blast radius Prioritize stability over local optimization In most enterprises, there should be very few of them. Platform Admins own the cloud itself Tenant Admins own consumption within it The split protects multi-tenancy, upgrades, and supportability Platform Admin ≠ “stronger tenant admin” This separation is foundational to VCF’s design If you want, next we can: Map exact VCF roles to Platform vs Tenant Admin Walk through a real workflow showing the handoff Identify anti-patterns where this boundary is violated ]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/platform-admin.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Platform Admin.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:21:09 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2018/09/Screen-Shot-2018-09-19-at-9.50.30-AM.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2018/09/Screen-Shot-2018-09-19-at-9.50.30-AM.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tenant Admin]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://www.cloud13.ch/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/vRealize-Automation-Enterprise-VPC.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://vmtechie.blog/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/image-4.png?w=1024" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vsphere/vsphere-supervisor/7-0/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/f65e8ece-4543-4e7a-a658-b65f724fdd0f.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">In VMware Cloud Foundation, multi-tenancy is the ability to securely host multiple independent consumers (tenants) on the same physical cloud infrastructure, while preserving isolation, governance, and lifecycle safety.VCF does not implement multi-tenancy at a single layer.
It is layered, intentional, and asymmetric.
VCF separates infrastructure tenancy from consumption tenancy.
This is the key to understanding everything else.Where it lives
Workload Domains Clusters NSX segments Resource pools Who owns it
Platform / Cloud Admins What it provides
Strong isolation Failure-domain separation Compliance boundaries Important
Infrastructure tenancy is coarse-grained Tenants do not see this layer Think: “Which hardware and fabric does this workload ultimately land on?”Where it lives
Organizations Projects Policies, quotas, approvals This layer is primarily owned by VCF Automation.Organizations
Top-level tenant boundary Represents a company, business unit, or customer Defines identity, access, quotas, and governance Projects
Sub-tenants within an organization Environment- or team-scoped (Dev / Test / Prod, Team A / Team B) This is where true SaaS-like multi-tenancy exists.Depending on workload type:
vSphere constructs Backed by resource pools, folders, NSX isolation Supervisor Namespaces Mapped (typically) 1-to-1 with Projects Enforced by vSphere + Kubernetes RBAC Key subtlety
Supervisor Namespaces are execution boundaries, not business tenants.
They implement tenancy; they are not the tenant itself.VCF Infrastructure (shared)
│
├── Organization: Acme
│ ├── Project: Acme-Prod → Supervisor Namespace ns-acme-prod
│ ├── Project: Acme-Dev → Supervisor Namespace ns-acme-dev
│ └── Project: Acme-Test → Supervisor Namespace ns-acme-test
│
├── Organization: Globex
│ ├── Project: Globex-Prod → Supervisor Namespace ns-globex-prod
│ └── Project: Globex-Dev → Supervisor Namespace ns-globex-dev Organizations = business tenants Projects = operational sub-tenants Namespaces = runtime enforcement It is not:
Just Kubernetes namespaces Just vCenter folders Just NSX segments A single RBAC model VCF deliberately avoids one-layer tenancy, because no single layer can satisfy:
Security Governance Lifecycle safety Operational clarity Isolation is compositional, not singular.
Strong isolation without hardware duplication Clear separation of duties Supports enterprise and service-provider use cases Preserves lifecycle determinism Conceptually complex Multiple abstractions to understand Requires discipline in mapping orgs/projects/namespaces VCF optimizes for large-scale, regulated environments, not minimalism.But: no single analogy maps perfectly — this is a hybrid cloud model.
Multi-tenancy in VCF is layered Organizations &amp; Projects define business tenancy Supervisor Namespaces enforce runtime isolation Workload Domains protect lifecycle and failure domains This design balances power, safety, and scale If you want, next we can:
Walk through RBAC flows across org → project → namespace Compare VCF multi-tenancy vs pure Kubernetes Discuss anti-patterns (where people get this wrong) Map multi-tenancy to chargeback / showback models
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenant-admin.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Tenant Admin.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:20:22 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://www.cloud13.ch/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/vRealize-Automation-Enterprise-VPC.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://www.cloud13.ch/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/vRealize-Automation-Enterprise-VPC.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cloud Services Console]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2024/08/featured-image.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/cloud-foundation/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2025/07/vmc-accounts_roles_02.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/euc/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2015/06/Enterprise-Scale-and-Management1.png?crop=1&amp;h=324&amp;w=576" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">Cloud Services Console (CSC) is VMware’s SaaS control plane for identity, organizations, subscriptions, and service access across VMware cloud offerings.
It is not an infrastructure tool and not VCF itself—it’s the global account &amp; entitlement layer that sits above VCF.If vCenter answers “what is running?”, CSC answers:
“Who are you, what are you entitled to, and which VMware services can you access?”
VMware SaaS Layer
└── Cloud Services Console (CSC) ├── Identity &amp; Org management ├── Subscriptions &amp; entitlements └── Access to VMware cloud services On-prem / Private Cloud
└── VCF ├── vSphere / NSX / vSAN └── SDDC Manager Runs as: VMware-hosted SaaS Audience: Org owners, platform leads, service-provider admins Does not touch datapaths or place workloads Defines Organizations Manages users, roles, and access Integrates with enterprise IdPs (SSO) This is business identity, not vCenter RBAC.
Shows what your org is entitled to: VCF subscriptions Optional VMware services Central place to view contracts → services CSC does not meter usage—that’s elsewhere.From CSC you access:
Support portals VMware cloud SaaS Management consoles (where applicable) Think of CSC as the front door, not the engine room.CSC ≠ BSC
CSC is VMware-global; BSC is VCF-specific.
CSC knows about your subscriptions VCF consumes those entitlements CSC does not: Provision domains Run LCM Enforce quotas Observe performance That work stays on-prem with VCF components.
❌ Not part of the VCF runtime ❌ Not an ops or automation tool ❌ Not a billing/metering engine ❌ Not a tenant boundary for workloads It’s administrative and commercial, by design.If VCF is:
“Your private cloud platform”
Then CSC is:
“Your VMware account and service access hub”
Comparable to a cloud provider account console, not a cluster manager.
Cloud Services Console = SaaS identity &amp; entitlement layer Global across VMware services Adjacent to VCF, not embedded in it Often confused with Business Services Console—they serve different roles If you want next, we can draw a clean diagram showing CSC → BSC → Usage Meter → VCF, or map Organization concepts across CSC, BSC, and VCF Automation side-by-side.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/cloud-services-console.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Cloud Services Console.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:13:22 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2024/08/featured-image.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2024/08/featured-image.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workflow]]></title><description><![CDATA[merge to key workflow concepts and also move it to somewhere else.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:13:13 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Data Services Manager]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/dsm/data-services-manager/2-1/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/2840bcee-02a4-4da0-a4de-7017c7f33fb7.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://i0.wp.com/cormachogan.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/dsm_deploy_small.jpg?ssl=1" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">VMware Data Services Manager (DSM) is a Database-as-a-Service (DBaaS) control plane that lets platform teams offer databases as a managed service on top of VCF infrastructure—while keeping infrastructure, security, and lifecycle control centralized.It answers:
“How do we provide self-service databases without giving users raw VM access?”
VCF
├── vSphere / vSAN / NSX
├── SDDC Manager (infra lifecycle)
│
└── VMware Data Services Manager ├── Control Plane (policies, APIs, UI) └── Data Plane └── Database VMs (Postgres, MySQL, etc.) Runs on: VCF infrastructure Consumes: vSphere, NSX, storage policies Exposes: A database service interface to users DSM is above infrastructure, below applications.
Provision databases in minutes Automated: Day-0 setup Day-1 operations Day-2 patching &amp; upgrades Consistent configurations every time No more hand-built “special” DB VMs.
Platform team controls: VM templates Storage policies Network placement Backup &amp; security posture Application teams control: DB provisioning Scaling (within limits) Credentials (scoped) This maps cleanly to enterprise governance models.Databases are deployed with:
Approved VM shapes Approved storage classes Approved NSX segments Approved HA / backup models Users pick “what”, not “how”.DSM automates:
Database-aware backups Snapshots Restore workflows Optional replication patterns This is database lifecycle, not just VM lifecycle.DSM is not required for VCF.DSM targets enterprises modernizing gradually, not cloud-native purists.This distinction matters:
SDDC Manager: Patches ESXi, NSX, vCenter DSM: Patches databases Manages DB templates Controls DB version drift They are complementary, not overlapping.If VCF is:
“Infrastructure as a managed fleet”
Then DSM is:
“Databases as a managed service on that fleet”
Comparable to:
AWS RDS (conceptually) Azure SQL (conceptually) …but on-prem / private cloud, with enterprise control.Enterprises want:
Self-service databases Fewer snowflake DB VMs Safer operations Faster delivery Without:
Giving developers vCenter access Losing compliance control Rewriting everything for Kubernetes DSM is VMware’s answer to that middle ground.
VMware Data Services Manager = DBaaS control plane Runs on, but is not part of, VCF core Enforces policy, separation of duties, and lifecycle automation Best for VM-based enterprise databases Optional, but powerful for platform teams If you want, next we can:
Compare DSM vs Aria Automation DB blueprints Map DSM to AWS RDS concepts Or discuss why DSM struggles (and where it shines) in real deployments Just tell me which direction you want to go.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/vmware-data-services-manager.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/VMware Data Services Manager.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:12:36 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/dsm/data-services-manager/2-1/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/2840bcee-02a4-4da0-a4de-7017c7f33fb7.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/dsm/data-services-manager/2-1/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/2840bcee-02a4-4da0-a4de-7017c7f33fb7.original.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Skyline]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/4-5/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/78/2022/01/Skyline-Screenshot.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2024/12/ClusterHealth-Figure-01.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">Yes — VMware Skyline is still part of the VMware ecosystem in VCF 9.x, but its role has shifted.
It is not a core runtime component of VCF, but a supportability and proactive intelligence service that complements VCF fleet operations, especially for production environments.VMware Skyline is a proactive support and health intelligence service that continuously analyzes your VMware environment and surfaces: Configuration risks Known issues Upgrade blockers Security advisories Best-practice deviations It answers:
“What is likely to break, and what should I fix before it does?”
VCF Environment
├── vCenter / ESXi
├── NSX
├── vSAN
├── SDDC Manager
│
└── Skyline ├── Telemetry collection ├── Health &amp; risk analysis └── Proactive recommendations
Key point:
Skyline observes the fleet — it does not control it.
Skyline is VCF-adjacent, not VCF-core.In VCF 9.x: Skyline continues to support: vSphere NSX vSAN SDDC Manager Skyline findings are especially valuable for: LCM readiness Upgrade prechecks Fleet hygiene However: Some operational insights now overlap with: Aria Operations Built-in health checks Skyline remains support-driven, not ops-driven Skyline correlates your environment against: Known VMware issues Field advisories Support KB patterns This is knowledge you cannot replicate locally.Before you run LCM in VCF: Skyline can flag: Unsupported configs Known bad upgrade paths Latent drift issues Think of it as:
“Support’s brain looking at your fleet before you upgrade.”
Skyline shines when: You have many domains You have many vCenters You want a single risk posture view This aligns naturally with VCF fleet management.Skyline is insight, not control.Skyline is the supportability lens.If SDDC Manager is:
“The mechanic that performs maintenance”
Then Skyline is:
“The service engineer who tells you what will fail next month.” You run production VCF You care about upgrade safety You want fewer Sev-1 support cases You operate at fleet scale Small lab / dev-only VCF Short-lived environments You already accept reactive support VMware Skyline is still relevant with VCF 9.x It is not a core VCF runtime component It provides proactive, VMware-global intelligence Best viewed as a support copilot for VCF fleets Especially valuable for LCM and large environments If you want, next we can: Contrast Skyline vs Aria Operations explicitly Walk through how Skyline feeds into upgrade decisions Or discuss whether Skyline is still worth enabling in smaller VCF estates Just tell me which direction you want to go.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/vmware-skyline.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/VMware Skyline.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:11:39 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/4-5/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/4-5/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/f3148087-2d46-4bdd-8144-71b73b43cadb.original.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Fleet Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[— with a focus on License, Lifecycle, Identity &amp; Access, Certificates, Passwords, Configuration, and Tags<img alt="Image" src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2017/12/Blog-img-1.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-5-2-and-earlier/5-2/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/20023967-0880-4402-ab33-0f8a5aa01b72.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://i0.wp.com/vstellar.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/VCF-Single-NSX-Domain.png?ssl=1" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">Fleet management in VCF is the centralized, policy-driven governance of many infrastructure instances (hosts, clusters, domains, appliances) across their entire lifecycle—from onboarding and entitlement to upgrades, credentials, certificates, configuration drift, and metadata.Think “operating system for infrastructure fleets,” not “one-off cluster admin.”A fleet typically includes: Multiple Workload Domains Multiple vCenter Servers NSX Managers &amp; Edge Clusters ESXi hosts (often hundreds or thousands) Supporting appliances (SDDC Manager, vSAN, etc.) Fleet management answers:
“How do we keep all of these consistent, compliant, secure, and up-to-date over years?”
Below is a layered view, aligned with how VCF actually works. Central license inventory Assignment to: vCenter / ESXi NSX vSAN Alignment with subscription usage SDDC Manager VCF Usage Meter VCF Business Services Console Licenses are fleet-level entitlements, not per-host snowflakes.
VCF ensures: No silent overuse No orphaned entitlements Auditable usage SDDC Manager Bring-up (Day-0) Patching &amp; upgrades (Day-2) Version skew prevention Compatibility matrices (vSphere, NSX, firmware) Upgrades are coordinated across domains Versions are locked as a bill of materials Drift is actively prevented You upgrade the fleet, not “a vCenter here and there.” vCenter SSO External IdPs (AD / LDAP / OIDC) Role-based access (RBAC) VCF Automation Organizations &amp; Projects Consistent role models Central auth sources Separation of duties across domains Key point:
IAM is federated but standardized across the fleet.
No bespoke admin models per domain. vCenter ESXi hosts NSX Managers &amp; Edges Internal APIs Trust relationships Certificate sprawl Expiration risk Manual rotation = outage risk Centralized visibility via SDDC Manager Supported rotation workflows Integration with enterprise CAs Certificates are fleet-scale secrets, not local files. Appliance passwords Service accounts Inter-component credentials Bootstrap secrets Password rotation must be: Coordinated Non-disruptive Auditable VCF: Tracks credentials centrally Rotates safely Prevents “unknown admin password” scenarios This is operational hygiene at scale. Cluster settings (HA, DRS, admission control) NSX transport &amp; policies Storage policies Network constructs Domain-level invariants Configuration is declared once and enforced everywhere.
VCF: Applies opinionated defaults Detects unsupported deviations Blocks actions that would break fleet integrity This is closer to policy enforcement than “config files.” Automation targeting Chargeback / showback Compliance classification Ownership &amp; environment labeling Tags provide horizontal metadata across: Domains Clusters VMs Datastores Think of tags as:
“The control plane’s labeling system for infrastructure objects.”
Without tags, automation becomes brittle.Fleet Management in VCF
├── SDDC Manager
│ ├── Lifecycle (LCM)
│ ├── Credentials
│ ├── Certificates
│ ├── Configuration invariants
│
├── Business Layer
│ ├── Usage Meter
│ └── Business Services Console
│
├── Identity &amp; Access
│ ├── vCenter SSO
│ └── External IdP
│
└── Metadata └── Tags &amp; policies ❌ Not day-to-day VM operations ❌ Not per-cluster customization ❌ Not “click-ops” admin work ❌ Not application management It operates above those layers. vCenter / NSX → manage a data center VCF Fleet Management → manage a company of data centers Like the difference between: Managing one Linux server Managing an entire Kubernetes platform fleet Fleet management is the core value proposition of VCF It spans license, lifecycle, identity, secrets, certs, config, and metadata Centralization + opinionation is the feature, not a limitation VCF treats infrastructure as a long-lived, governed fleet, not pets If you want next, we can: Map these pillars to Day-0 / Day-1 / Day-2 operations Contrast VCF fleet management vs Kubernetes fleet management Or deep-dive into one pillar (certs, IAM, LCM) with concrete flows Just tell me which direction you want to go.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/fleet-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Fleet Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:10:09 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2017/12/Blog-img-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogs.vmware.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/75/2017/12/Blog-img-1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cost Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[is <a data-href="FinOps and Capacity" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/finops-and-capacity.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">FinOps and Capacity</a>delete this and add aliases.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/cost-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Capacity and Cost Optimization/Cost Management.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:03:54 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VDS]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="Image" src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vsphere/vsphere/7-0/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.original.png" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://community.cisco.com/t5/image/serverpage/image-id/25797iDE4135CC8FF87D97/image-size/large?px=999&amp;v=v2" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved"><br><img alt="Image" src="https://ipwithease.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/distributed-switch-vs-standard-switch.jpg" referrerpolicy="no-referrer" target="_self" class="is-unresolved">A VDS (vSphere Distributed Switch) is a cluster-wide virtual switch that provides consistent networking configuration across all ESXi hosts.
It centralizes network policy (port groups, uplinks, security, QoS) instead of configuring each host individually.VCF standardizes on VDS as the baseline virtual networking fabric.VMware Cloud Foundation
└── vSphere └── vCenter Server └── vSphere Distributed Switch (VDS) ├── ESXi Host A ├── ESXi Host B └── ESXi Host C └── Port Groups → VM vNICs Implemented by: VMware vSphere Managed in: VMware vCenter Server Used by: ESXi hosts, VMs, NSX transport nodes Centralized L2 switching Consistent port group configuration NIC teaming &amp; uplinks Traffic shaping, security, VLAN tagging Host lifecycle safety (no per-host drift) Think of it as:
“One virtual switch, shared by the whole cluster.”
VCF requires VDS because automation and upgrades depend on consistency.A Distributed Port Group defines: VLAN ID(s) Security policies (promiscuous mode, MAC changes) Traffic shaping Teaming / failover VM vNICs attach to port groups, not directly to the switch.This is where confusion often arises. VDS = underlay L2 switch NSX = overlay networking NSX creates overlay segments Overlay traffic is encapsulated (GENEVE) Encapsulated packets ride over VDS uplinks NSX does not replace VDS — it depends on it.
In VCF: Management Domain has a predefined VDS Workload Domains get their own VDS NSX transport zones bind to VDS uplinks Lifecycle (patching, expansion) assumes VDS presence You rarely “design” VDS in VCF — it’s opinionated and enforced. ❌ Not a router (no L3) ❌ Not an NSX Segment ❌ Not a tenant boundary ❌ Not optional in VCF If VDS is:
“A shared Ethernet switch for ESXi hosts”
Then NSX Segment is:
“A logical network built on top of that switch.”
Different layers, different jobs. VDS is the foundational virtual switch in VCF Provides centralized, cluster-wide L2 networking Required for NSX and VCF lifecycle operations NSX overlays run on top of VDS, not instead of it If you want, next we can explicitly trace a packet:
VM vNIC → NSX Segment → VDS → NSX Edge → Physical network
That walkthrough usually locks the mental model in place.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vds.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/VDS.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 22:02:38 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vsphere/vsphere/7-0/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/content/broadcom/techdocs/us/en/vmware-cis/vsphere/vsphere/7-0/_jcr_content/assetversioncopies/6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.original.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vNUMA]]></title><description><![CDATA[Let’s start with physical NUMA.<img alt="NUMA-1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/numa-1.png" target="_self">NUMA stands for non-uniform memory accessNUMA is a physical server architecture used by modern multi-socket systems.
Each CPU socket has: Its own local memory
Faster access to that local memory Accessing memory attached to another socket is slower
non-uniform here does not mean “processes access memory unevenly”; it is from a hardware perspective, and simply means “memory access latency is not the same for all memory locations”Hence: Memory access time is not uniformYou can think of it as:
Two cities (CPU sockets)
Each city has its own warehouse (memory)
Shipping inside the city is fast
Shipping between cities takes longer
NUMA provides massive performance gain if locality is respected.Assume there is a workload that:
Runs on CPU-0
But frequently accesses memory on CPU-1
Then, performance will drop due to latency and cache penalties. This is invisible at the OS level unless NUMA-aware.In a NUMA-aware system, CPU threads are scheduled to prefer running on CPUs that are near the memory they already use, not the other way around.
All DRAM is: Equidistant (or close enough)
Reached through a shared memory controller or fabric Differences exist, but: They are not tied to CPU identity
They are mostly hidden from software Software does not (and cannot) reason about “which CPU core owns which memory” From the OS perspective: “Memory is one big pool” Latency variance exists, but not topologically anchored.
In contrast, in NUMA, each CPU socket has its own local memory controller and DRAM; remote memory is reached via an interconnect and is slower.vNUMA is how a hypervisor exposes NUMA topology to a VM.
The VM sees virtual NUMA nodes
Each vNUMA node has: vCPUs
Assigned memory Guest OS can schedule intelligently inside the VM
vNUMA is NUMA-awareness for virtual machinesWithout vNUMA:
Guest OS thinks memory is uniform
Hypervisor silently shuffles memory
Cache locality is lost
With vNUMA:
Guest OS: Allocates memory locally
Schedules threads close to memory Databases, JVMs, etc., perform much better
Tangential (but not directly-related-to) NUMA is SR-IOV.<br><img alt="sriovarchitecture.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sriovarchitecture.png" target="_self">SR-IOV allows one physical PCIe device (NIC, GPU, HBA) to present:
One Physical Function (PF)
Multiple Virtual Functions (VFs)
The number of VFs an SR-IOV-enabled device can expose is fundamentally limited by the device’s hardware design, firmware, and onboard resources.SR-IOV devices expose a capability like:Total VFs supported: NThis value is:
Burned into silicon
Sometimes further capped by firmware
Sometimes configurable downward (but not upward)
Typical real-world numbers:
8
16
32
64
128
(High-end SmartNICs may go higher)
You cannot exceed this, no matter what the OS or hypervisor wants.Each VF:
Can be assigned directly to a VM
Bypasses the hypervisor datapath
When a VF is assigned:
The VF is bound to the VM
The VM sees it as a native PCIe device
The guest driver talks directly to hardware
Packets do not traverse: vSwitch
vNIC
vDS
software datapaths <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> does not schedule or inspect traffic
This is why SR-IOV delivers:
Near bare-metal latency
Deterministic throughput
Minimal jitter <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> flexibility (often)
Snapshot support (often)
Hypervisor mediation
Some observability
They solve different problems:An SR-IOV VF is physically attached to:
A PCIe root complex
Which belongs to one NUMA node
If:
VM vCPUs run on NUMA node 0
SR-IOV NIC VF is on NUMA node 1
You now have remote memory + remote I/O: Worst-case latency scenario.This is critical for performance workloads.When using SR-IOV:
Align: VM vCPUs
VM memory
PCIe device To the same NUMA node
This may require:
NUMA-aware placement
Host pinning
Careful cluster design
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/vNUMA.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 21:05:13 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/numa-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/numa-1.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCPU]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vCPU.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcpu.webp" target="_self"><br>In the context of <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, a vCPU (virtual CPU) is a logical processor that vCenter assigns to a <a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>, abstracting and time-sharing the physical CPUs (pCPUs) of the underlying <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.You can think of it as CPU time and execution context, not a physical core.<br>A vCPU is a scheduling unit presented to a <a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>, which the <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> scheduler maps onto physical CPU cores or hardware threads on demand.A VM with 4 vCPUs does not get 4 dedicated cores: It gets permission to run up to 4 execution threads concurrently when physical CPU time is available.A vCPU is not:
a physical core
pinned hardware (unless you explicitly do CPU pinning)
a guaranteed slice of CPU time
A vCPU is:
a schedulable execution context
<br>backed by <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>’s CPU scheduler
mapped dynamically to cores or hyperthreads
exposed to the guest OS as a CPU socket or core <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> uses time-slicing + SMT awareness
Multiple vCPUs can run on the same physical core at different times There is no 1:1 relationship unless: CPU affinity is configured (rare, advanced, some Telco use cases demand it)
Real-time workloads are used vCenter itself does not execute workloads. It:
Defines VM configuration (number of vCPUs)
Enforces resource policies: CPU limits
CPU reservations
Shares <br>Coordinates placement decisions (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>)
Observes performance (CPU Ready, Co-Stop, etc.)
<br>The actual execution and scheduling happens on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts.When you assign vCPUs, you also define topology:
Sockets
Cores per socket
Example:
4 vCPUs as 1 socket × 4 cores
or 2 sockets × 2 cores
This affects:
Guest OS licensing
<br><a data-href="NUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NUMA</a> behavior
Cache locality
Some applications (databases, especially)
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> lets you control this explicitly.Oversubscription is normal, expected, and intentional.In real environments:
Physical cores: 32
Total vCPUs across VMs: 200+
This is normal.This will work because:
Most VMs are idle most of the time
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> schedules based on demand
Problems only appear when too many vCPUs want to run at once
CPU Ready Time is one of the key metrics here:
vCPU wants to run but can’t get scheduled.
Start small (1–2 vCPUs)
Scale up, not down
Avoid wide VMs unless needed
Watch: CPU Ready
Co-Stop (for multi-vCPU VMs) Prefer fewer vCPUs with higher utilization over many idle vCPUs vCPU = schedulable execution context, not a core
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> defines and governs, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> executes and schedules
Oversubscription is by design
More vCPUs ≠ more performance
Correct sizing matters more than raw allocation
<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vcpu.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/vCPU.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 21:05:08 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcpu.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcpu.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMDK]]></title><description><![CDATA[In VMware virtualization, VMDK stands for Virtual Machine Disk. It is the file format used by VMware to represent a virtual hard disk—the persistent storage attached to a virtual machine.A VMDK file behaves like a physical hard drive, but for a VM.
From the guest OS point of view, it looks like /dev/sda, C:\, etc.
From the <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>’s point of view, it’s one or more files on a datastore.VMDKs are stored on VMware datastores, which may be backed by:
VMFS (block storage)
NFS
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
Local disks
Object storage (via vSAN ESA / integrations)
A “VMDK” is usually not a single file:
Ends in .vmdk
Contains metadata: Disk size
Geometry
Provisioning type
Backing extent file name Examples: disk-flat.vmdk
disk-s001.vmdk, disk-s002.vmdk Holds the actual data blocks
Snapshots and special configurations add more files.In the VMware ecosystem:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> handles block I/O
VMDK is the disk abstraction
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> manages lifecycle
Storage Policy Based Management (SPBM) governs behavior
<br>All of this is orchestrated under <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.<br>You might want to check out Inventory Objects such as <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>s or <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/Virtual Machine Primitives/VMDK.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 21:04:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Distributed Virtual Switch]]></title><description><![CDATA[In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, a Distributed Virtual Switch (DVS) is the standard, centralized virtual networking fabric used across <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts in a <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>.<br><img alt="vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" target="_self"><br>In VCF, a Distributed Virtual Switch is the mandatory, centrally managed L2 networking fabric that ensures every <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host behaves identically so that <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, lifecycle management, and <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> can work reliably at scale.DVS provides consistent networking configuration, policy enforcement, and operational control at scale—something VCF depends on to behave predictably.DVS can be seen as:<br>
One logical network switch that spans many <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts,
configured once, and applied everywhere.
<br>Instead of configuring networking host-by-host, you configure it centrally, and every participating <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host follows that definition.VCF is opinionated and automated. Networking must be:
Deterministic
Centrally managed
<br>Compatible with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">lifecycle automation</a>
Consistent across hosts and clusters
That’s why VCF mandates DVS (not standard vSwitches) for system and workload networking.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts do not own the switch config — vCenter does.
VCF automation (bring-up, scaling, patching, upgrades) assumes:A standard vSwitch breaks all of this because it is host-local and imperative.Typical VCF DVS port groups include:
Management
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> Host TEPs VM networks (VLAN-backed)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> / Kubernetes traffic (when applicable)
VCF may create multiple DVS instances, for example:
One for system domain
One per workload domain <br>DVS ≠ <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
DVS provides L2 switching
NSX builds overlay networking (Geneve tunnels, logical segments) on top of DVS
You can have:
<br>DVS without NSX (<a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a>-backed networking)
<br>However, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> requires DVS underneath
So DVS is the foundational substrate, not the SDN layer.
DVS is a control-plane object <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> caches its config locally, but authority lives in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> If vCenter is temporarily unavailable Traffic keeps flowing
You just can’t change switch config VCF LCM expects DVS invariants Port groups, uplinks, MTU, and teaming must match what SDDC Manager expects DVS is not optional in VCF
It is owned by vCenter, not hosts
It enables automation, scale, and consistency
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> depends on it, but it is not NSX itself
Standard vSwitches are fundamentally incompatible with VCF’s design goals
<br>Diving into <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> might be the next logical step from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/distributed-virtual-switch.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/Distributed Virtual Switch.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 20:56:33 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-dvs-6e9e9fbf-e102-4f9c-a036-3a4bd255d7bf.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[CSP]]></title><link>./https://vcf.wtf/csp.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">CSP.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 20:55:38 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCenter Server]]></title><description><![CDATA[vCenter&nbsp;is the service through which you manage multiple hosts connected in a network pool host resources.vCenter Server runs as a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/virtual-appliance/virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> (<a data-href="VCSA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcsa.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>) — a prebuilt VM — on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.Concretely:
vCenter is not bare metal
It is deployed as an OVA
That OVA becomes one VM (sometimes functionally “a group of services”, but still a single VM)
Internally, that VM runs:
A hardened Linux-based OS
vCenter services
Database (embedded or external, depending on scale)
Physical hardware
└── ESX └── vCenter Server Appliance (VM) └── vCenter services vCenter Server is the centralized control plane
