Many tenants (Pepsi, Coca Cola, Sprite, Pizza Hut)
Each tenant has an external Vault (or Vault instance) with paths that can overlap: credentials/db/finance is a common example Sync into an internal OpenBao (or internal Vault) via ESO
Inject into workloads via Vault Sidecar Injector
You want no path collisions and no possibility of cross-tenant access
There are two separate problems:
Storage namespace collision in internal OpenBao
Runtime authorization when workloads fetch secrets (injection)
<br>
Note: Only Organization Administrator is able to create secrets in the current system; not sure if the same applies for the VCF Secret Service. That’s something to keep in mind.
See <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>
this is the first half of the problem.Based on the official VCF Secret Service docs, a lot of the “last-mile consumption” is already solved (create secret → store it → inject it into pods/VMs as files), but tenancy isolation is explicitly coarse and largely stops at the Supervisor Namespace boundary. It’s there, but it’s not the fine-grained. That is any OpenBao secret bound to a namespace is visible to any workload in that namespace.That should be fine since tenants are effectively namespace-bound.The “Managing Secrets…” doc spells out delivery formats:
vSphere Pods → file mount under /vault/secrets/&lt;user-provided-name&gt;
VM Service VMs → disk-based transfer + read-only mount
VKS (guest) cluster pods → file mount similar to vSphere Pods
This solves consistent delivery semantics per workload type.
All service accounts have read access to all secrets of that namespace.
^ that is the granularity we get. Which may or may not be fine based on the customers’ requirements.Also it’s worth noting that any notion of Organization/Project tenancy in the Secret Store model does not exist by architecture (which is also fine because secrets are namespace-bound, and tenants are also namespace-bound).None of the flows refer to Organization/Project at all. They are consistently “pick a Supervisor namespace; secrets live there”.That’s consistent with what we discussed earlier: governance constructs don’t appear at runtime.The docs show a pattern like secret/data/&lt;namespace&gt;/&lt;secretName&gt; for retrieval.
Secrets are stored in a “corresponding namespace” (meaning: per Supervisor namespace).
VKS isolation is only at Supervisor namespace level (explicit).
Within a namespace, all service accounts can read all secrets (explicit).
So the tenancy story is not missing — it’s just coarse:
Tenant isolation = Supervisor Namespace isolation (and nothing finer is guaranteed).
A safe mapping consistent with the doc’s retrieval convention would look like:
External: credentials/db/finance
Internal: secret/data/&lt;supervisor-namespace&gt;/credentials/db/finance
(or secret/data/&lt;supervisor-namespace&gt;/&lt;some-secret-name&gt; that contains those K/Vs)
That avoids cross-tenant collisions because the Supervisor namespace becomes the first path segment.According to the docs, all tenants share the same unified internal secrets store (OpenBao).In the doc’s annotation model, you specify a secret “path” in the injector annotation. They show:
vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject-secret-...: "secret/data/demo/db-cred"
Inject Secrets in to a vSphere …
So for Pepsi, if you used the flattened name approach, you’d inject like:
secret/data/pepsi/auth__finance__db__creds
…and because the auth role is tied to the namespace (example role demo), Pepsi workloads would authenticate with role pepsi and read from the pepsi/* prefix. ✅ In this doc model, within a tenant’s Supervisor namespace, any Pepsi workload can access any Pepsi secret.
❌ Restricting secrets to only pods in a specific Kubernetes namespace inside the tenant is not supported here (especially for VKS guest clusters).
✅ OpenBao paths look like secret/data/&lt;supervisor-namespace&gt;/&lt;secretName&gt; (KV v2 style).
✅ In shared OpenBao, prevent collisions by ensuring the first path segment is the tenant namespace (pepsi, cocacola, …).
VCF Secret Store Service does have guardrails that prevent a Coca-Cola workload from mounting Pepsi secrets, as long as you stay within the supported model.But those guardrails are namespace-scoped, not “tenant-aware in the abstract”, and they rely on how identities and roles are provisioned, not on OpenBao magically inferring tenancy.The guardrails are not:
“OpenBao automatically understands tenants”
“Vault paths are globally protected by magic”
They are:
The Vault/OpenBao token that a workload receives is issued in the context of a specific Supervisor Namespace.
That token is not shared across namespaces.
So:
A Coca-Cola workload never gets the same token as a Pepsi workload
Tokens are not reusable across namespaces
This is enforced by Supervisor, not by Kubernetes RBAC alone.The injector examples in the docs consistently show:
a role name tied to the namespace (e.g. demo)
secrets read from secret/data/&lt;namespace&gt;/...
That implies (and matches how VMware typically wires these systems): Each Supervisor Namespace has a corresponding OpenBao role and policy.
You don’t see the policy YAML in the docs, but the model only works if: role pepsi → policy allows secret/data/pepsi/*
role cocacola → policy allows secret/data/cocacola/*
Otherwise the examples would be unsafe.
A pod can’t just arbitrarily say:
vault.hashicorp.com/agent-inject-secret-foo: secret/data/pepsi/db
from another namespace, because:
the injector runs with Supervisor context
the auth role used is bound to the namespace
the token issued is constrained by that role
So even if a Coca-Cola pod requests a Pepsi path, the read fails.
That’s the critical point: request ≠ authorization.
ref:
“All service accounts have read access to all secrets of that namespace.”
That sentence is not saying:
“All namespaces can read all secrets.”
It’s saying:
“Within one Supervisor Namespace, we don’t give you finer-grained scoping.”
If we ensure that:
Pepsi secrets are materialized under secret/data/pepsi/...
Coca-Cola secrets under secret/data/cocacola/...
Then VCF Secret Store Service guardrails already align with that:
Pepsi workloads authenticate as “Pepsi namespace”
Pepsi role can only read secret/data/pepsi/*
Coca-Cola role cannot read Pepsi paths
So yes: If we respect the namespace-prefix contract, the rest of the consumption plumbing is already handled safely by VCF Secret Store Service.
We are not punching a hole in the security model by doing the sync.The model breaks only if you bypass the intended trust boundaries, for example:
A single ESO instance with a token that can write/read all tenant prefixes
Manually creating secrets in the wrong namespace
Reusing roles or tokens across namespaces
Exposing OpenBao externally and letting workloads authenticate out-of-band
Those are operator errors, not product gaps — but they’re exactly what auditors look for.VCF Secret Store Service enforces tenant isolation at the Supervisor Namespace boundary by issuing namespace-scoped identities and policies for secret access. As long as tenant secrets are materialized under their corresponding namespace paths, cross-tenant secret access is prevented by design. Fine-grained intra-namespace isolation is intentionally not provided.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/secrets-federation-notes.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Secrets Federation Notes.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 20:29:18 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vcf-services-image_b975c3]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 24 Dec 2025 15:22:30 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-services-image_b975c3.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor-VCF-Automation Relationship]]></title><description><![CDATA[┌────────────────────────────┐
