They are:
Resource-governed containers
Backed by: vSphere Networking (<a data-href="NSX" href="vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>)
<br>vSphere Storage (<a data-href="vSAN" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>)
vSphere RBAC A tenant can have more than one Supervisor Namespace; however, those namespaces are not individual tenants.
Tenancy is a business/trust concept. Supervisor Namespaces are execution slices that implement tenancy.
vCenter / API / UI ↓
Supervisor Namespace created ↓
Namespace appears in Kubernetes ↓
kubectl can now interact with it
^ This is the opposite of upstream Kubernetes.In a vSphere Supervisor cluster, tenant namespaces are created and owned by vSphere as Supervisor Namespaces. Kubernetes users cannot create namespaces directly; kubectl is used only to interact with namespaces after vSphere has provisioned them.
Supervisor Namespaces are created by vSphere
<br>kubectl create ns is not how tenancy is established. This will be explicitly denies on the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>.
There is no concept of a regular tenant namespace on Supervisor
Kubernetes reflects what vSphere creates
Namespace lifecycle is deliberately centralized for safety
In a Supervisor cluster, Kubernetes cluster-admin privileges do not grant authority over physical resource allocation. Namespace creation and resource envelopes are owned by vSphere, and Kubernetes operates strictly within those bounds.Tenant: Coca-Cola
├── ns-coke-prod
├── ns-coke-stage
└── ns-coke-dev Tenant: Coca-Cola
├── ns-coke-us
├── ns-coke-eu
└── ns-coke-apac ## VCF Automation Representation Organization: Coca-Cola
├── Project: Coke-Prod → ns-coke-prod
├── Project: Coke-Stage → ns-coke-stage
└── Project: Coke-Dev → ns-coke-dev ^ One organization, multiple projects,
Each project maps to (ideally) one Supervisor Namespace.
But this is also possible: Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke ├── ns-coke-dev ├── ns-coke-stage └── ns-coke-prod The only inverant is one supervisor namespace cannot belong
to multiple projects. Namespaces are unique per supervisor cluster.
Supervisor clusters are *isolation domains*, so global
uniqueness enforcement would have been 1) artificial
and 2) painful. Organization
└── Project └── Supervisor Namespace(s)
From vSphere's perspective, a Pod, VM, or VM-based Pod is just scheduled compute.Project is an automation construct.
Defined by Automation Admin persona.
Mapped to one or more Supervisor Namespaces.
Invisible to vSphere / Kubernetes.
Their purpose is to govern requests, not execution.
<br>From the <a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/kubernetes-runtimes/tkg/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>’s perspective, Organizations and Projects do not exist; similarly there is no concept of an organization or project inside the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> either.Supervisor namespaces intentionally mimic Kubernetes semantics:From the developer's laptop, they feel like ordinary Kubernetes namespaces.Here is where they differ though (mostly around ownership and LCM)in Supervisor namespaces, resource governance is outside Kubernetes.In Kubernetes:
CPU/memory limits = ResourceQuota
Storage = StorageClass + PVC
Network = CNI rules
In Supervisor:
CPU/memory = vSphere resource pools
Storage = datastore policies
Network = NSX segments
Limits are hard boundaries, not advisory
So when you say:
"This namespace gets 8 vCPU and 64 GB RAM"
That's not a Kubernetes promise---that's vSphere enforcing physics.Security model is in vSphere, not in KubernetesKubernetes RBAC applies inside the box vSphere already drew.That’s why certain Kubernetes admin actions are silently blocked even when RBAC says “allowed”.From Kubernetes’ POV:
It looks like a CNI plugin
In reality:
NSX owns: L2/L3 segments
Firewall rules
Load balancers Kubernetes asks politely. NSX decides.This matters for:
NetworkPolicy
Ingress behavior
Multi-tenant isolation
In vanilla K8s:
PVC requests storage
Cluster tries to satisfy it
In Supervisor:
PVC must map to pre-approved storage policies
Datastore capabilities are enforced externally
StorageClass ≈ view of vSphere policy, not a free-form construct.The goal of this abstraction is to:
Let Kubernetes users feel at home
Let infrastructure teams retain determinism
Avoid “Kubernetes ate my datacenter” chaos
So Supervisor namespaces are:
Kubernetes-compatible interfaces to vSphere-owned sandboxes Supervisor namespaces intentionally impersonate Kubernetes namespaces
Kubernetes sees them as native; operations are externally enforced
vSphere owns: lifecycle
resource limits
security boundaries Kubernetes operates within those constraints
Supervisor Namespace names are unique only within a Supervisor cluster, and every Supervisor Namespace is governed by exactly one Project; Organizations do not directly own namespaces.Supervisor Namespace names are not globally unique, nor organization-wide unique.<br>They are unique per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>.<br>Supervisor Namespaces are always associated with a <a data-href="Project" href="vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>.Organization
└── Project └── Supervisor Namespace(s) Namespace names are: ❌ not global
❌ not org-unique
❌ not project-unique
✅ unique per Supervisor cluster Namespace: belongs to exactly one Project
indirectly belongs to one Organization
never floats independently Here’s a concrete example:Org: Verizon
Project: West-Coast - Supervisor Cluster: sjc-01 - Namespace: edge-prod - Supervisor Cluster: lax-01 - Namespace: edge-prod ← same name, totally fine Project: East-Coast - Supervisor Cluster: iad-01 - Namespace: edge-prod ← also fine <br>Namespace names are <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>-scoped
Projects are mandatory governance owners
Organizations are containers of projects, not namespaces
Any apparent contradiction is UI simplification, not platform behavior
]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Control and Consumption/Supervisor Namespace.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 22:15:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Blueprint]]></title><description><![CDATA[A Blueprint is a declarative deployment template that defines what can be requested, how it is configured, where it may land, and under which policies and approvals.Blueprints live in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>Blueprints in <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> are governed deployment templates that define allowed workload patterns, configuration inputs, placement constraints, and approval policies. They orchestrate resource creation but are not part of the runtime execution layer.Once a deployment is created, the Blueprint can be deleted and the workload keeps running: It’s not part of the runtime layer.User ↓
Blueprint ← governance + intent ↓
Project ← who / where / policy ↓
Supervisor Namespace ↓
vSphere / Kubernetes runtime
Kubernetes YAML answers:
“How do I create this thing?”
Blueprints answer:
“Who is allowed to create which thing, under what rules, and with whose approval?” Organization: business boundary (e.g. Verizon)
<br><a data-href="Project" href="vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>: governance scope (e.g. US-East)
Blueprint: allowed patterns inside that scope
Organization: Verizon
└── Project: US-East ├── Blueprint: Standard App VM ├── Blueprint: GPU Pod └── Blueprint: 3-Node K8s Cluster
Each Blueprint:
targets specific Supervisor Namespace(s)
enforces constraints
hides complexity from requesters
Typically it defines:Examples:
A VM
A vSphere Pod
A Guest Kubernetes cluster
A multi-tier app (VM + LB + storage) CPU / memory sizes
Environment variables
Image versions
Feature toggles
Secret references (not secret values) <br>Which <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>(s) are allowed
Which storage policies are allowed
Which networks are allowed
Size limits
Placement rules Who can request it
Who must approve it
Lease duration
Cost visibility / chargeback tags
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>]]></description><link>vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/blueprint.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Blueprint.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:37:08 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> supports both one-to-one and one-to-many mappings between Projects and Supervisor Namespaces; the choice is an architectural pattern, not a platform constraint.Very common, very clean:Organization: Coca-Cola
├── Project: Coke-Prod → ns-coke-prod
├── Project: Coke-Stage → ns-coke-stage
└── Project: Coke-Dev → ns-coke-dev
Why teams choose this
Clean blast-radius isolation
Clear RBAC and quotas per environment
Easy mental model
Common in regulated / prod-heavy setups
This is a design choice, not a platform requirement.(Equally valid, also common in larger deployments)Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke ├── ns-coke-dev ├── ns-coke-stage └── ns-coke-prod
Why teams choose this
Shared governance (same people, same blueprints)
Environment separation handled at namespace level
Easier cross-env promotion workflows
Fewer projects to manage
]]></description><link>vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/project.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Project.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:33:56 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCloud Director 1]]></title><description><![CDATA[VMware vCloud Director (VCD) is a cloud-management and multi-tenancy layer built on top of vSphere. It was designed primarily for service providers (ISPs, telcos, MSPs) to offer VMware-based clouds to multiple customers in a clean, isolated, self-service way.
vSphere → virtualization engine (hypervisors, clusters, VMs)
VCD → cloud abstraction + multi-tenant control plane
