Here is how things looks from each layer’s point of view:<br>Once a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload cluster</a> is instantiated in a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, it has no awareness of <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> constructs such as Organization or Project—Those concepts exist only at the governance layer (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>) and are not part of the runtime execution model (<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>).<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="Operations Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/operations-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Operations Management</a>, <a data-href="Performance Monitoring" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/performance-monitoring.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Performance Monitoring</a>, or <a data-href="Workload Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Operations</a>.VCF Operations<br><a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br>See also: <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a><br><img alt="sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-6a0b9b75-d909-4618-9afb-738d12d0c16a.webp" target="_self"><br>SDDC Manager is the foundational lifecycle-management and orchestration engine of <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>.It is responsible for deploying, configuring, upgrading, and maintaining the entire VCF stack as a single, validated system rather than as independent products.<br><img alt="sddc-manager-8f57b8cd-3a43-48cc-98dc-b9cdf6132d20.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-8f57b8cd-3a43-48cc-98dc-b9cdf6132d20.webp" target="_self">If you think of VCF as a factory-built private cloud, SDDC Manager is the factory control system that ensures every component is installed correctly, stays in a supported state, and evolves safely over time.<br><img alt="sddc-manager-1.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/sddc-manager-1.webp" target="_self"><br>
UI Deprecation Warning
In VCF 9.0+, Broadcom’s docs state that <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/building-your-private-cloud-infrastructure/sddc-manager-workflows.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com" rel="noopener nofollow" class="external-link is-unresolved" title="SDDC Manager Workflows in VMware Cloud Foundation 9.0" href="https://techdocs.broadcom.com/us/en/vmware-cis/vcf/vcf-9-0-and-later/9-0/building-your-private-cloud-infrastructure/sddc-manager-workflows.html?utm_source=chatgpt.com" target="_self">SDDC Manager UI is being deprecated</a> and that SDDC Manager workflows can now be found in VCF Operations and vSphere Client—so many “platform lifecycle” workflows show up there now. ([
This is SDDC Manager’s primary job.SDDC Manager performs end-to-end lifecycle operations across the VCF stack:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> (hypervisor)
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
Other optional components.
Key characteristics:
Uses validated upgrade bundles
Enforces component compatibility
Executes sequenced, automated upgrades
Provides rollback and precheck logic
This is not just patching: It is system-level lifecycle orchestration.SDDC Manager is responsible for:
Initial VCF bring-up
Creating: Management Domain
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Workload Domain" data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VI (Workload) Domains</a> Adding: Hosts
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Cluster" data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Clusters</a>
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a>s Ensuring: Correct networking
Correct certificate trust
Correct inventory alignment Without SDDC Manager, you do not have VCF: That simple!—You will only have a loosely assembled VMware products.SDDC Manager acts as the system-of-record for:
What components exist
Their versions
Their relationships
Their lifecycle state
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> manages virtualization.
SDDC Manager manages the cloud system itself.SDDC Manager enforces:
Supported topologies
Supported versions
Supported upgrade paths
If you try to:
Upgrade NSX independently
Modify components outside supported flows
You risk breaking VCF supportability.
<br>This is intentional: <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> favors predictability over freedom.It is not:
A tenant portal
A developer platform
A policy engine
A workload orchestrator
A replacement for vCenter, NSX Manager, or Kubernetes APIs
<br>Those functions live elsewhere (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>, <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, etc.).
SDDC Manager manages the cloud itself; everything else manages what runs inside that cloud.
Without SDDC Manager:
Enterprises would manually assemble components
Version skew would be common
Upgrades would be risky and expensive
Supportability would collapse
With SDDC Manager:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> becomes repeatable
Lifecycle becomes deterministic
VMware/Broadcom can guarantee outcomes
This is why SDDC Manager is non-optional in VCF.
SDDC Manager is the backbone of VCF
It owns lifecycle, topology, and compatibility
It enforces validated, supported states
It is infrastructure-centric, not tenant-centric
Without it, VCF does not exist as a product
<br>Since we are onto management and provisioning, <a data-href="VCF Installer" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vcf-enablers/vcf-installer/vcf-installer.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Installer</a> can be the next topic to dive into.SDDC ManagerWorkflowWorkflowSDDCSDDCVCF Operations OrchestratorVCF Operations Orchestrator]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/the-big-picture.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">The Big Picture.canvas</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 14:40:10 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vcf-overview.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Namespace]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br><img alt="vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg" target="_self">A Supervisor Namespace (vSphere Namespace) defines the resource and security boundary within which workloads—such as vSphere Pods, virtual machines, and VKS clusters—run on a vSphere Supervisor.A namespace is the fundamental construct that binds together:
Resource allocation
Access control
Workload isolation
Policy enforcement
<br>All workloads deployed through the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> operate within a Supervisor Namespace (vSphere Namespace).A Supervisor Namespace:
Defines where workloads can run
Controls how much compute, memory, and storage they can consume
Establishes administrative and security boundaries
<br>Acts as the bridge between <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> infrastructure and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubernetes workloads</a>
<br>Namespaces are created and managed by <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>s, not by Kubernetes users.When a Supervisor Namespace is created:
<br>A corresponding <a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> is created in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
CPU, memory, and storage limits can be defined
Quotas apply to all workloads within the namespace
Limits are enforced at the infrastructure layer
<br>If the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> spans multiple <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> clusters (zones), the namespace’s resource allocation is distributed across all participating clusters.Example:
If a namespace is assigned 300 MHz CPU across a three-zone Supervisor:
Each cluster contributes 100 MHz
Scheduling is balanced across zones
Access to a Supervisor Namespace is controlled through:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> Single Sign-On (SSO)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">External identity providers (OIDC)</a>
Administrators assign permissions to users or groups, defining what operations they can perform inside the namespace.This access model governs:
Who can deploy workloads
Who can view or modify resources
Who can manage storage and policies
A Supervisor Namespace can host:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s (VM-backed Kubernetes pods)
<br><a data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Machine</a>s
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS cluster components</a>
All workloads deployed within a namespace inherit its resource constraints and access rules.A Supervisor Namespace is not the same as a Kubernetes namespace, even though it appears similar at first glance.A Supervisor Namespace contains Kubernetes namespaces, but is not itself one.
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> creates a namespace in the Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> allocates backing resources and policies.
Namespace becomes visible to Kubernetes users.
Workloads can be deployed using standard Kubernetes tooling. Kubernetes users cannot create or delete vSphere namespaces.
<br>Namespace lifecycle is owned by <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, not Kubernetes.
Namespace limits cannot be overridden from inside the cluster. <br>Namespace names are unique per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>, not globally.
The same namespace name may exist on multiple Supervisors.
<br>A namespace belongs to exactly one <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s belong to a single <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>.
Example:Organization: AcmeCorp
├── Project: Retail
│ ├── Namespace: prod
│ └── Namespace: stage
└── Project: Logistics └── Namespace: prod
Here, prod appears multiple times but in different Supervisor contexts.<br>A <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> is a governance construct used to group and manage namespaces.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s define ownership and intent
They map to one or more Supervisor Namespaces
They are not visible inside Kubernetes
<br>They exist only in the <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> control plane
Projects allow administrators to:
Apply policies
Enforce quotas
Track ownership
Control access Supervisor Namespaces are Kubernetes-compatible, but not Kubernetes-native.
They look and behave like Kubernetes namespaces to workloads, but their lifecycle, limits, and permissions are governed entirely by vSphere.
Supervisor Namespaces are the execution boundary for workloads.
<br>They are created and managed by <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, not Kubernetes.
They enforce compute, storage, and security limits.
Kubernetes operates inside these boundaries.
<br><a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s and <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s exist above namespaces to provide <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>.
<br>Supervisor Namespaces are unique per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> and not globally unique.
You might want to check out:
<br><a data-href="Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/adding-security-policies-to-a-supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace</a>
<br><a data-href="Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/kubectl-in-supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Kubectl in Supervisor Cluster</a>
<br><a data-href="Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/deploy-a-confidential-vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod</a>
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Supervisor Namespace.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 07:07:57 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-namespace-37c6e878-6516-41b4-a1d1-cba97506cfa1.original.svg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Domain]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br>A VCF Domain is a core <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a> platform construct.
<br>It is defined and lifecycle-managed by VCF itself (via <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a>).
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes it for <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant</a> self-service and provisioning.
<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> observes it for monitoring, health, and capacity.
<br>A VCF Domain is an isolated <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> unit inside VCF with its own full stack:Each domain is independently lifecycle-managed (upgrade cadence, patch windows, scaling).<br>A&nbsp;VCF Domain in a&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Instance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-instance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Instance</a> consists of the following components:
<br>One <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> instance.
<br>One or more <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>s with <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere HA</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="DRS" data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere DRS</a> enabled.
<br>At least one <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Distributed Virtual Switch" data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Distributed Switch</a>es per cluster for system traffic and <a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a>s for workloads.
<br>Dedicated <a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> instance, either specifically for the&nbsp;VCF Domain or shared between&nbsp;VCF Domains, for configuring and implementing software-defined networking.
<br>Optional: One or more <a data-href="NSX Edge Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-edge-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Edge Cluster</a>s, added after you create the Workload Domain, that connects the workloads in the Workload Domain for logical switching, logical dynamic routing, and load balancing.
One or more shared storage allocations as principal or supplemental storage.
There are two types of VCF Domains:
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> is created during the deployment or convergence process.
<br><a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> runs consumer workloads on <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a>.
<br><a data-href="Management Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/management-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Domain</a> and <a data-href="Workload Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/workload-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Workload Domain</a> gives further context about VCF Domains.<br>You might also want to check out <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>’s fleet and domain model by looking at <a data-href="VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/fleet-and-domain-model/vcf-fleet,-vcf-instance,-and-vcf-domains.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Fleet, VCF Instance, and VCF Domains</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Design and Abstractions/Architectural Constructs/VCF Topology/VCF Domain/VCF Domain.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:53:40 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VMware Validated Solutions]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br>The purpose of VMware-Validated Solutions is to deploy a VMware-designed <a data-href="SDDC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/sddc.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC</a> to deliver common business use cases.<br><img alt="vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" target="_self">VMware Validated Solutions (VVS) are prescriptive, end-to-end solution blueprints built on top of VMware Cloud Foundation that combine architecture, configuration, workflows, and lifecycle guidance into a tested and supportable outcome.A VMware Validated Solution is a known-good way to solve a concrete problem on VCF — designed, tested, and supported as a whole.They answer a very practical question:<br>
“Given <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, how do I implement this specific enterprise capability correctly and safely?”
A VVS is more than documentation. It typically includes:
Component topology
Trust boundaries
Network flows
Failure domains
Scale assumptions Exact settings (not suggestions)
Supported variants
Guardrails and constraints
Explicit “do / don’t” guidance <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 0 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-0</a> (deployment)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-1</a> (onboarding, enablement)
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day-2</a> (upgrade, scale, recover) How the solution evolves with VCF upgrades
What breaks compatibility
What is safe to automate
Everything is validated together, not in isolation.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a platform, not an opinionated solution by default.Enterprises, however, want outcomes, such as:
Secure multi-tenancy
Kubernetes at scale
Identity-integrated access
Backup, DR, or compliance alignment
Without validated solutions:
Every customer invents their own pattern
Outcomes vary wildly
Support becomes guesswork
Validated Solutions reduce design risk and support friction.<br>Here, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is a programmable substrate, and Validated Solutions as approved programs.While names and scope evolve, common categories include:
Secure Cloud Infrastructure
Identity and Access Integration
Kubernetes Platform Enablement
Multi-tenant Cloud Architecture
Business Continuity / DR
Compliance-aligned deployments
Each one narrows a broad platform into a specific, repeatable design.They are not:
Reference “ideas”
Whitepapers
One-off examples
Mandatory architectures You can deviate—but once you do, you own the risk.
For architects and platform owners, Validated Solutions provide:
Faster time to value
Reduced design ambiguity
Predictable upgrades
Clear escalation paths Less freedom
Opinionated choices
Slower adoption of bleeding-edge features
This trade-off is deliberate.
VMware Validated Solutions are prescriptive, supported blueprints
They sit above VCF, not beside it
They reduce risk by constraining choice
They align architecture, operations, and lifecycle
Deviating is allowed—but unsupported paths are yours to own
<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="VCF Roles and Permissions" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/vcf-roles-and-permissions.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Roles and Permissions</a>, <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>, <a data-href="Policy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy</a>, or <a data-href="Policy as Code" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/policy-as-code.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy as Code</a> as the next few concepts to explore.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/vmware-validated-solutions/vmware-validated-solutions.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/VMware Validated Solutions/VMware Validated Solutions.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:40:15 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmware-validated-vvd-sddc-40-poster-1024x610.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Day 0 Tasks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br><img alt="day-n-tasks.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" target="_self">VMware Cloud Foundation Day 0 tasks are everything required to prepare and bootstrap the platform before any tenant, workload, or higher-level automation exists.<br>Think of Day 0 as laying the concrete and pouring the foundation—after this, you can build floors (<a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>) and move people in (<a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a>).
Day 0: Make the platform exist
Day 1: Configure and extend the platform
Day 2: Operate workloads on the platform
VCF is very opinionated: nothing meaningful can happen until Day 0 is clean and correct.These are outside VCF but mandatory.
Rack &amp; cable hosts
Power, cooling, BIOS/firmware
NTP, DNS, IPAM
VLANs / MTU (often jumbo frames)
Out-of-band management (iDRAC / iLO)
If this is wrong, everything later becomes “mysteriously flaky.”<br>Before VCF can orchestrate anything, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> must exist.
<br>Install <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> on all hosts
Apply compatible firmware and drivers
Validate hardware against VCF BOM
Configure basic networking (vmnics, MTU)
These hosts are raw compute, not yet part of any SDDC.This is the true start of VCF.
<br>Deploy <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Appliance
Connect it to: DNS
NTP
Identity source Verify reachability to all ESX hosts
From this point on, VCF owns lifecycle.This creates the core control plane SDDC.Includes automated deployment of:
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> <a data-href="Management Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/management-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Management Cluster</a>
This is where VCF becomes a self-hosting platform.After this, you no longer treat components individually.Baseline platform networking is established.
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> fabric initialization
Transport zones
Edge nodes (management edges)
Tier-0 / Tier-1 gateways
Initial firewall policies This defines how everything can talk later.Foundational access control.
<br>Integrate <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> / <a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> with: LDAP / AD / Identity Provider Define platform admin roles
Secure service accounts
Without this, automation has no authority.Often underestimated, always painful if skipped.
CA strategy (internal vs external)
TLS certificates for: <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="SDDC Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/sddc-manager/sddc-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">SDDC Manager</a> Trust alignment across components
This is where future mTLS, OIDC, and zero-trust efforts live or die.This is about future safety.
Validate VCF BOM
Enable lifecycle management workflows
Confirm patching &amp; upgrade paths
Confirm supportability state
<br>If skipped, <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> turns into firefighting.
No tenants
