No business logic
Day 0 is pure platform plumbing.
VCF Day 0 = platform existence
It is non-negotiable and opinionated
Focuses on infrastructure, identity, network, and lifecycle
No tenants, no workloads, no business logic
<br>Done right → <a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a> and <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> feel boring (the best outcome)
]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Day-N Operations/VCF Day 0 Tasks.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:28:10 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/day-n-tasks.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workflow]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:lifecycle" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#lifecycle">#lifecycle</a><br><img alt="workflow-1.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png" target="_self">Workflows consist of a schema, workflow variables, and input and output parameters.The workflow schema is the main component of a workflow as it defines all the workflow elements and the logical connections between them. The workflow variables and parameters are the properties that workflows use to transfer data.<br><img alt="vro-image-1024x622.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vro-image-1024x622.webp" target="_self"><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, there isn’t a single “workflow engine” owned by only one product. Different parts of VCF create/execute different kinds of workflows:<br>VCF Automation is the place where you typically design and run “<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 1 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">day-1</a>” style workflows tied to requests (catalog items, provisioning, configuration, approvals, extensibility, etc.). Its value prop explicitly includes orchestration and extensibility.<br>Under the hood, these workflows commonly leverage an <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Operations" data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Orchestrator</a> (formerly vRealize Orchestrator) integrated/embedded with the automation stack. It is executed by <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> which is a part of the <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> stack.<br><a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> is primarily the ops brain: monitoring, alerting, capacity, compliance, etc.. It can run actions (and sometimes chain remediation) in response to alerts.<br>Actual workflow automation is done through <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a>, which is explicitly described as a “workflow automation solution” and can create and run workflows.<br><a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a> saves a workflow token every time a workflow runs, recording the details of that specific workflow run.Workflows receive input parameters and generate output parameters when they run.Most workflows require a certain set of input parameters to run. An input parameter is an argument that the workflow processes when it runs. The user, an application, another workflow, or an action passes input parameters to a workflow for the workflow to process when it runs.For example, if a workflow resets a virtual machine, the workflow requires the name of the virtual machine as an input parameter.A workflow's output parameters represent the result from the workflow run. Output parameters can change when a workflow or a workflow element runs. During a workflow run, the workflow can receive the output parameters of other workflows as input parameters.For example, if a workflow creates a snapshot of a virtual machine, the output parameter for the workflow is the resulting snapshot.Workflow elements process data that they receive as input parameters, and set the resulting data as workflow variables or output parameters.Read-only workflow variables act as global constants for a workflow. Writable variables act as a workflow’s global variables.You can use variables to transfer data between the elements of a workflow.You can obtain variables in the following ways:
Define variables when you create a workflow.
Set the output parameter of a workflow element as a workflow variable.
Inherit variables from a configuration element.
A workflow schema is a graphical representation that shows the workflow as a flow diagram of interconnected workflow elements. The workflow schema is the most important element of a workflow as it determines its logic.When users run a workflow, they provide the values for the input parameters of the workflow in the workflow presentation.A workflow token represents a workflow that is running or has finished running.A workflow is an abstract description of a process that defines a generic sequence of steps and a generic set of required input parameters. When you run a workflow with a set of input parameters, you receive an instance of this abstract workflow that behaves according to the specific input parameters you give it. This specific instance of a finished or a running workflow is called a workflow token.Workflow Token Attributes are the specific parameters with which a workflow token runs.The workflow token attributes are an aggregation of the workflow's global variables and the specific input and output parameters with which you run the workflow token.<br>Next, you might want to look into <a data-href="Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/running-vcf-operations-orchestrator-workflows.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Running VCF Operations Orchestrator Workflows</a>, or you can check out <a data-href="VCF Operations Orchestrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/vcf-operations-orchestrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations Orchestrator</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/platform-operations-and-services/platform-services-and-management/workflow-management/workflow.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Platform Operations and Services/Platform Services and Management/Workflow Management/Workflow.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:23:44 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workflow-1.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vMotion]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br><img alt="vmotion_migration_process.jpg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg" target="_self"><br>vMotion is <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>’s live-migration mechanism that moves a running VM from one <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host to another with no downtime.<br>In <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>, vMotion is foundational plumbing—it’s how higher-level services (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, maintenance workflows) actually move workloads.<br><img alt="vMotion-pagetrace2.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion-pagetrace2.webp" target="_self">VCF
└── vSphere ├── DRS → decides *when/where* to move ├── HA → may trigger restarts (not vMotion) └── vMotion → performs the *move* <br>Implemented by: <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br>Orchestrated via: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
<br>Consumed by: <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, maintenance mode, admin actions DRS decides. vMotion moves. Pre-copy: VM memory is copied to the destination while the VM keeps running.
Iterative sync: Dirty pages are recopied until the delta is tiny.
Switchover: VM is briefly quiesced (milliseconds), CPU state flips.
Resume: VM continues on the new host with the same IP/MAC.
No reboot. No app restart.
Shared storage access
L2 network reachability
Compatible CPU features (or EVC)
vMotion-enabled VMkernel network with sufficient bandwidth
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> designs these prerequisites in by default.
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> load balancing (automatic)
Host maintenance mode (drain before patching)
Hardware refresh (zero-downtime)
Policy remediation (after placement decisions)
<br>You rarely “use vMotion” directly in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a>—it’s constantly in use under the hood.
Not a scheduler (it doesn’t decide)
Not a failover mechanism
Not application-aware
Not cross-site DR by itself
It is transport, not policy.
“VCF places workloads with vMotion” → No. DRS places; vMotion moves.
“vMotion is free” → No. It consumes network and CPU headroom.
“vMotion fixes capacity issues” → No. It redistributes load only.
vMotion doesn’t choose destinations, and it doesn’t judge priorities—it just moves things safely when told.
vMotion = zero-downtime VM movement
Core building block for DRS and maintenance
Always present and assumed in VCF designs
Necessary—but never sufficient—by itself
<br><a data-href="VCF Day 0 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-0-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 0 Tasks</a>, <a data-href="VCF Day 1 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-1-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 1 Tasks</a>, or <a data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Day 2 Tasks</a> could be nice places to visit from here.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Workload Mobility and Resilience/vMotion.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:22:47 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vmotion_migration_process.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Placement]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a><br><img alt="workload-placement-1545135394507.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png" target="_self"><br>Workload Placement in <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> is the coordinated outcome of automation intent, <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere" data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> scheduling (<a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>), networking availability (<a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>), storage policy (<a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>), and runtime mobility (<a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>).<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> is the mechanism, not the decision-maker.Workload Placement is a pipeline, not a switch—shaken, but not stirred:Intent → Eligibility → Initial Placement → Continuous Optimization → Recovery
Each stage is owned by a different layer of VCF.Answers: “what am I allowed to run, and where?”
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> (formerly Aria Automation) The user requests a workload (VM, Kubernetes cluster, pod)
Constraints are applied: <br><a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>
Quotas and approvals
<br>Target workload <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Domain" data-href="VCF Domain" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-domain/vcf-domain.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">domain</a> / cluster
Storage policy
Network intent There is no vMotion here: This is just pre-placement filtering.Answers: “Which clusters can even accept this?”
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> Cluster compatibility
HA admission control
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> limits
Storage policy compatibility
<br><a data-href="NSX Segment" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/object-model/nsx-segment.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Segment</a> &amp; transport availability
Anything that fails here is never considered for placement.<br>This is where <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> takes the helm.
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> Chooses the best host at power-on time
Considers: CPU &amp; memory headroom
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vNUMA" data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NUMA</a> alignment
<br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a> shares
Affinity / anti-affinity rules This happens before the VM ever runs.
This is placement — not vMotion.
<br>This is where <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> appears.
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> + <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> <br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> Load imbalance
Hotspots
Policy drift
Host entering maintenance
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> is:
How VMs move
NOT *why they move HA Host fails
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> re-places VMs on surviving hosts
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> may later rebalance
This is reactive placement, NOT optimization.<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> matters more than what’s seen on the surface.
<br><a data-href="NSX Manager" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx-manager.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Manager</a> / <a data-href="VCF Edge" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/vcf-topology/vcf-edge.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Edge</a>
Placement is invalid if:
Segment is not available on target host
Transport zone mismatch
Edge capacity insufficient (north–south)
Networking can veto otherwise valid placements.<br>Especially for Kubernetes (<a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>)
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>
<br><a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> (for K8s)
Placement requires:
Policy-compatible datastore
Accessibility from host
Topology alignment (for StatefulSets, etc.)
For Kubernetes:
PVC → StorageClass → Storage Policy
<br><a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> enforces this during placement
So things are a tad bit more involved than “VCF places workloads using vMotion”.VCF places workloads using DRS decisions; vMotion is only the transport.
Workload placement in VCF is layered and collaborative
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> decides, <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> moves
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> re-places after failure
<br><a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> and storage can block or shape placement
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> governs who can ask for what
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/capacity-and-cost-optimization/workload-placement.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Capacity and Cost Optimization/Workload Placement.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:22:05 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/workload-placement-1545135394507.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:operations" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#operations">#operations</a>Workload Operations focuses on ensuring that applications—whether virtual machine–based or container-based—are available, performant, and delivering the expected end-user experience. It bridges the gap between infrastructure health and actual workload behavior, allowing operators to reason about issues in terms of applications rather than underlying components.At its core, Workload Operations answer:
Is the application running correctly from the user’s point of view—and if not, where is the breakdown?
Workload Operations continuously assess whether applications are functioning as intended.
<br>Tracks <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a> availability and responsiveness
Monitors performance indicators relevant to application behavior
Detects degradations before they escalate into outages
Distinguishes between infrastructure noise and real workload impact
This ensures operators focus on what matters to consumers, not just raw resource metrics.Beyond infrastructure signals, workload operations account for how applications are perceived by users.
Correlates performance data with service responsiveness
Helps identify issues that are invisible at the host or cluster level
Supports prioritization of incidents based on user impact
Improves alignment between platform teams and application owners
In effect, it reframes operations around service outcomes, not components.<br>For container-based applications, <a data-href="VCF Operations" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> provides native awareness of Kubernetes workloads running on the platform.
<br>Automatic discovery of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>-managed Kubernetes environments
<br>Granular visibility into vSphere Kubernetes Service (<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>) clusters
Monitoring at cluster, namespace, and workload levels
Correlation between container behavior and underlying infrastructure signals
This tight integration eliminates blind spots that traditionally exist between virtualization and Kubernetes operations.By correlating workload-level symptoms with infrastructure-level signals, workload operations significantly shorten troubleshooting cycles.
Rapid isolation of whether issues originate in compute, storage, networking, or the application layer
Reduced hand-offs between infrastructure and platform teams
Faster root-cause identification for mixed VM and container environments
Improved mean time to resolution (MTTR)
Instead of “ping-pong debugging,” operators get end-to-end context.Workload Operations is:
Application-centric rather than component-centric
Equally applicable to VM-based and container-based workloads
Focused on availability, performance, and user impact
Workload Operations is not:
A deployment or CI/CD system
A replacement for application-level instrumentation
A tenant self-service or governance mechanism Workload Operations shift operational focus from infrastructure health to application outcomes
Native integration with Supervisor and VKS enables deep visibility for Kubernetes workloads
Correlated insights reduce troubleshooting time and operational friction
The end goal is reliable applications with predictable user experience, not just healthy infrastructure
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Automation" data-href="VCF Automation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/observability-and-health/workload-operations.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Observability and Health/Workload Operations.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:21:29 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Administrator]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a><br>In <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>, Supervisor Administrator is a new, platform-level role introduced to formalize control over the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> itself, and it sits orthogonally to— not above or below—the traditional <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> / <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> roles.<br>
Supervisor Administrator manages the platform that hosts tenants, while <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> manages the tenants themselves, and <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> manages what runs inside those tenants.
VCF separates responsibilities cleanly into three distinct administrative planes, each with its own roles:→ “How the Kubernetes substrate itself is operated”This is where the Supervisor Cluster lives.→ “Who consumes the infrastructure and how”<br>This is where <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s, <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s, and quotas live.→ “What runs on top of it”<br>This is where Kubernetes <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workloads</a>, namespaces, and apps live.<br>Scope: <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> (platform level)Primary responsibility:
<br>Operates and governs the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> itself
Manages cluster-level capabilities that all tenants depend on
Typical responsibilities:
<br>Configure and manage <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a> lifecycle
Control Supervisor services (e.g., Kubernetes control plane, CSI, CNI, storage integrations)
<br>Define which <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s can exist
<br>Enable or disable platform features available to <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>s
Maintain host, networking, and storage alignment required for Kubernetes workloads
Supervisor Administrator does not manage application workloads or tenant namespaces.From the Supervisor Administrator’s point of view:
“I run the Kubernetes platform that everyone else builds on.”
<br><a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> is the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenant-level</a> authority.<br>Scope: <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a> (tenant boundary)Role type: Consumer / tenant administratorResponsibilities:
<br>Create and manage <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s
Assign users to projects and roles
Define quotas and usage limits
Control access within their organization
Govern how their organization consumes platform capacity
They do not manage the Supervisor Cluster itself.<br>From the <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a>’s perspective:
“I manage my organization’s slice of the platform.”
<br><a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a> has <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload-level</a> control over the project they have access to.<br>Scope: Single <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a> within an <a data-href="Organization" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/organization.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization</a>Responsibilities:
Manage Kubernetes workloads (clusters, namespaces, services)
Manage users within the project
Configure project-level policies and resources
<br>They operate inside boundaries defined by the <a data-href="Organization Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/organization-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Administrator</a> and enforced by the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a>.<br>From <a data-href="Project Administrator" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-administrator.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Administrator</a>’s point of view:
“I manage workloads, not the platform.”
Supervisor Administrator
│
├── Organization Administrator
│ ├── Project Administrator
│ │ └── Application / Workload Operators
│ └── Project Users
│
└── (Multiple Organizations) Supervisor Admin ≠ Super Org Admin
They operate at different abstraction layers
Historically, roles like this were blurry or implicit (vSphere Admin, Cloud Admin, etc.).VCF introduces clear separation of concerns:This aligns VCF with cloud provider models (for, i.e., AWS control plane vs account admins).<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/supervisor-administrator.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Supervisor Administrator.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:20:16 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Automation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:governance" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#governance">#governance</a>VCF Automation enables IT teams and cloud service providers to deliver a self-service private cloud for AI, Kubernetes, and VM-based applications.<br>The solution simplifies the process of provisioning and scaling a <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">multi-tenant</a> private cloud with out-of-the-box Infrastructure as a Service (<a data-href="IaaS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/background-and-context/iaas.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">IaaS</a>) offerings, accelerating the time to market for applications while maintaining control using policy-based governance.<br>VCF Automation provides <a data-href="Governance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/governance-and-compliance/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> at the request and lifecycle level—controlling who can deploy which patterns, under what constraints and approvals—while runtime security, drift detection, and continuous enforcement are handled by downstream platforms.VCF Automation has the following capabilities:
<br><a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>: Provides a set of cloud services to meet the needs of application teams
<br><a data-href="Provider Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>: Supports IT teams and cloud service providers to effectively manage, deliver, and scale cloud services across multiple vCenter and VCF instances.
<br><a data-href="Organization Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a>: Provides capabilities that enable the organization administrator of a Line of Business or a tenant to further organize and govern resources allocated to them among application teams.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>: Provides the capability to run Kubernetes workloads directly on <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and to create <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">upstream Kubernetes clusters</a> within dedicated <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespaces</a>.
<br>From here, you can jump to <a data-href="Cloud Services" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>, <a data-href="Provider Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>.<br>
Also, <a data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">User Roles</a> and <a data-href="Project Management" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/project-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project Management</a> are other good candidates to explore. Or, dive directly into <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/VCF Automation.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:19:16 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Constructs]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a><br>See also: <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>A vSphere Construct is:
A first-class infrastructure object that is _natively defined, owned, and enforced by the vSphere control plane (ESX + vCenter), not by Kubernetes or higher-level automation layers.
<br>Think of it as a primitive in vSphere’s own vocabulary. These are things that exist because <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> exists; they are not abstractions layered on top.
Virtual Machine
<br><a data-href="vCPU" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vcpu.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCPU</a>
<br><a data-href="vNUMA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vnuma.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vNUMA</a>
<br><a data-href="vApp" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vapp.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vApp</a> <br><a data-href="Resource Pool" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/resource-pool.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Resource Pool</a>
Shares / Limits / Reservations
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> rules
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> Admission Control Datastore
<br><a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> Object
<br>VM disk (<a data-href="VMDK" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vmdk.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMDK</a>)
Storage Policy Port Group
<br><a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>
<br><a data-href="VM NIC" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/vm-nic.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM NIC</a>
<br><a data-href="VLAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/architectural-constructs/infrastructure-primitives/vlan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VLAN</a> / overlay constructs Snapshot
Clone
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>
Storage vMotion
<br><a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> restart
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a>
<br>All of these are authoritative in <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> and enforced by:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br>and <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>
If you want to get closer to the metal, all of these are relevant areas to explore:
