 pods use hardware-backed memory encryption to protect guest memory from being accessed by the hypervisor or other privileged components.This capability is powered by AMD Secure Encrypted Virtualization–Encrypted State (SEV-ES).A confidential vSphere Pod is a Kubernetes Pod that runs inside a virtual machine configured with SEV-ES: This ensures that:
Memory contents are encrypted
CPU register state is protected
The hypervisor cannot read or tamper with guest memory
This is especially useful for workloads that require strong isolation guarantees, such as handling sensitive data or running regulated workloads.To enable confidential vSphere Pods, the following requirements must be met:
<br>The <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host must run on hardware that supports AMD SEV-ES. <br><a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> 7.0 Update 2 or later is required.
SEV-ES must be enabled in the system BIOS.When enabling SEV-ES, configure the following: Minimum SEV non-ES ASID count
This value must be set to:
number of SEV-ES VMs + number of confidential vSphere Pods + 1 Example: 100 SEV-ES VMs
128 confidential vSphere Pods
→ Minimum value = 229 The maximum allowed value is typically 500, depending on hardware. To deploy a confidential pod, you enable SEV-ES at the pod specification level.Create a YAML manifest with the following key elements:
Enable confidential pod support via annotation
Explicitly set memory requests and limits (they must match)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata: name: photon-pod namespace: my-podvm-ns annotations: vmware/confidential-pod: enabled
spec: restartPolicy: Never containers: - name: photon image: wcp-docker-ci.artifactory.eng.vmware.com/vmware/photon:1.0 command: ["/bin/sh"] args: ["-c", "while true; do echo hello, world!; sleep 1; done"] resources: requests: memory: "512Mi" limits: memory: "512Mi" Memory requests and limits must be identical for confidential pods.
Apply the manifest:kubectl apply -f &lt;yaml-file&gt;.yaml
Once submitted:
<br>The Scheduler selects an <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host that supports SEV-ES
If no compatible host is available, the Pod remains unscheduled
If scheduled successfully, the Pod runs with encrypted memory
You can verify the pod deployment using:kubectl describe pod &lt;pod-name&gt;
From the vSphere side, administrators can see the pod listed with:Encryption Mode: Confidential Compute Confidential vSphere Pods use AMD SEV-ES to protect memory contents.
Encryption is enforced at the hardware level and is transparent to workloads.
The feature requires: Compatible hardware
ESX 7.0 U2 or later
BIOS configuration for SEV-ES Configuration is done declaratively using Kubernetes YAML.
The Supervisor ensures scheduling only onto capable hosts.
<br>You might want to learn move about <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/deploy-a-confidential-vsphere-pod.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:11:25 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/confidential-compute-919a15ce-e4d4-4a68-a3fa-583edda06ab5.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/confidential-compute-919a15ce-e4d4-4a68-a3fa-583edda06ab5.original.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:security" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#security">#security</a><br>A Supervisor that uses <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> networking supports network security policies defined through a SecurityPolicy Custom Resource (CRD).<br>These policies allow you to enforce network-level controls for workloads running on the Supervisor, including <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Pod</a>s and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Virtual Machine" data-href="Virtual Machine" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/virtual-machine-primitives/virtual-machine.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">virtual machines</a>, by leveraging NSX’s distributed firewall capabilities.As a DevOps user, you can define and apply a SecurityPolicy CRD to enforce network security rules within a Supervisor namespace.Security policies apply to:
<br><a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s
<br>VMs running in the Supervisor (including <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Guest Cluster" data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS cluster nodes</a>)
Other workloads within the same namespace <br>Access to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>
Permissions to apply Kubernetes custom resources
Create a YAML file that defines the desired network security rules using the SecurityPolicy CRD.Apply the policy to the target namespace using kubectl:kubectl apply -f policy-name.yaml
This action instructs the NSX Operator to translate the policy into NSX distributed firewall rules.You can inspect the applied policy using standard Kubernetes commands.kubectl get securitypolicy policy-name
kubectl describe securitypolicy policy-name
Security policies applied through Kubernetes are also visible in the NSX Manager UI.From the NSX interface, administrators can:
View applied firewall rules
Monitor enforcement status
Troubleshoot traffic flows <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF</a> provides network security for <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s through SecurityPolicy CRDs.
Policies are applied at the namespace level.
<br>Enforcement is handled by <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>, not Kubernetes itself.
Policies protect traffic between vSphere Pods, VMs, and external networks.
<br>Management is possible via both kubectl and the <a data-href="NSX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> UI.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “Supervisor Namespace”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/adding-security-policies-to-a-supervisor-namespace.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Control and Consumption/Adding Security Policies to a Supervisor Namespace.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:10:57 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Storage]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> components, applications, and workloads need to store and retrieve data. Some applications and objects might use transient fast storage, while others require storage that persists.A vSphere Zone is a fault domain that can fail independently from another zones.&nbsp;<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> supports different storage topologies for zones. These topologies define how datastores are attached to&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts and how they behave during zone failures.<br>A zonal datastore is local to a single vSphere Zone. It is attached to all the&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts that are part of the underlying cluster.
It can replicate data to provide higher availability within the zone.
Its availability depends on the zone. If the zone goes down, the zonal datastore also goes down.
Examples of a zonal datastore include: non-stretched vSAN, non-stretched vSAN storage cluster, non-stretched VMFS or NFS external storage.
<br>A cross-zonal datastore spans multiple vSphere Zones. It is attached to&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts from all the zones it covers.
It can be stretched storage, for example, stretched vSAN, or non-stretched storage that pools hosts from multiple zones, for example, non-stretched vSAN storage cluster.
It typically replicates data across zones.
It stays available if one of the zones goes down.
Examples of a cross-zonal datastore: stretched vSAN, stretched vSAN storage cluster, metro storage cluster, non-stretched vSAN or vSAN storage cluster deployed from hosts across multiple zones.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> uses storage policies to integrate with storage available in your <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> environment. The policies represent datastores and manage storage placement of such components and objects as control plane VMs,&nbsp;vSphere Pod ephemeral disks, and container images. You might also need policies for storage placement of persistent volumes and VM content libraries. If you use&nbsp;<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, the storage policies also dictate how the&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>&nbsp;cluster nodes are deployed.<br>Storage policies support any shared datastores in your environment, such as VMFS, NFS, <a data-href="vSAN" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>, and vSAN ESA.<br>Depending on your <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> storage environment and the needs of DevOps, you can create several storage policies for different classes of storage. When you enable a&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> and set up <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespace</a>s, you can assign different storage policies to be used by various objects, components, and workloads.<br>For example, if a&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a> mounts three types of virtual disks and your vSphere storage environment has three classes of datastores, Bronze, Silver, and Gold, you can create storage policies for all datastores. You can then use the Bronze datastore for ephemeral and container image virtual disks, and use the Silver and Gold datastores for persistent volume virtual disks.<br><img alt="vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp" target="_self"><br>Image Service, an&nbsp;<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> component, is responsible for pulling container images from the image registry and transforming them into virtual disks to run inside the pod.<br><img alt="esx-can-cache-images-966c000f-edb1-4d4e-9c72-c5f571cc1647.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/esx-can-cache-images-966c000f-edb1-4d4e-9c72-c5f571cc1647.original.png" target="_self">Certain Kubernetes workloads that DevOps run on a namespace require persistent storage to store data permanently.<br>Persistent storage can be used by&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s,&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, VMs, and other workloads you run on the namespace. To make persistent storage available to the DevOps team, the vSphere administrator creates storage policies that describe different storage requirements and classes of services. The administrator then assigns storage policies and configures storage limits at a namespace level.<br><img alt="supervisor-cns-csi-8a7c342c-4c0b-4e84-9ab2-cf06dd7dc420.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-cns-csi-8a7c342c-4c0b-4e84-9ab2-cf06dd7dc420.original.png" target="_self"><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> uses several components to integrate with vSphere storage.<br>The <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> component resides in&nbsp;<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>. It is an extension of&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> management that implements provisioning and lifecycle operations for persistent volumes.When provisioning persistent volumes, the component interacts with the vSphere First Class Disk functionality to create virtual disks that back the volumes. In addition, the CNS server component communicates with the Storage Policy Based Management to guarantee a required level of service to the disks.<br>The <a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> also performs query operations that allow vSphere administrators to manage and monitor persistent volumes and their backing storage objects through&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-storage.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Storage.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:10:37 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vspehere-pod-storage-9dad3179-6c73-4460-ab9d-5578df57a385.webp&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a>At its core, vSphere is a compute, storage, and network abstraction layer: A distributed operating system for data centers.It manages large collections of infrastructure, such as CPUs, storage, networking, GPUs, and DPUs as a seamless and dynamic operating environment, and also manages the complexity of a data center.&nbsp;
It virtualizes physical infrastructure into managed CPU, storage, and networking resources.vSphere
├── ESX (data plane)
├── vCenter Server (control plane)
└── Integrated services (HA, DRS, vMotion, etc.)
vSphere is a distributed system that provides the following:<br>The two core components of VMware&nbsp;vSphere are <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br>
Whereas <a data-href="vSphere Client" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a> is the Web UI that interacts with the APIs of vSphere components.vSphere is a product contract, not a system.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> are the systems that implement that contract.Here is how vSphere facilitates LCM:
<br>Lifecycle management via pre-staging <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> images.
<br>Near-zero-downtime live patching for <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
<br>vSphere as a platform, manages <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VMware Cloud Foundation" data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a> performance in several dimensions:
With its GPU support, vSphere improves workload performance for modern AI workloads
<br><a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a> enables automatic load balancing of resources allocated to workloads in a <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/vsphere-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a>.
Storage DRS optimizes VM data placement as the VM is created and used over time.
Moving workloads seamlessly across the fabric, and ensuring things are always ship-shape, is what vSphere excels at:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">High Availability</a> with&nbsp;vSphere automatically restarts your VMs following physical machine failure.
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/fault-tolerance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> provides continuous availability of any application in the event of a hardware failure with no data loss or downtime.
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> enables live migration of virtual machines with no disruption to users or loss of service, eliminating the need to schedule application downtime for planned server maintenance. Storage vMotion avoids downtime for planned storage maintenance. At vSphere security is by default, not an afterthought:
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Identity Broker" data-href="VCF Identity Broker" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/vcf-identity-broker/vcf-identity-broker.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Identity Federation</a> with Microsoft Entra ID, ADFS and Okta.
Virtual Machine Encryption: Data-at-rest encryption for virtual machine data and disks.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Trust Authority" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/security-services/vsphere-trust-authority.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Trust Authority</a>: Remote attestation for sensitive workloads.
Yesn’t.Saying “vSphere is ‘ESX and vCenter’.” is colloquially common, but technically incomplete.<br>See <a data-href="vSphere, ESX, and vCenter" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere, ESX, and vCenter</a> for a more nuanced analysis.<br>You might also want to check <a data-href="vSphere Constructs" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/overview/vsphere-constructs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Constructs</a> for an idea of what vSphere directly controls, and what capabilities it has.<br>You might want to check out <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, one of the core components that makes vSphere, vSphere.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/vSphere.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 06:03:33 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VKS Cluster Storage]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a><br><img alt="vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png" target="_self"><br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters, like other workloads running in a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, require persistent storage.Persistent storage for VKS clusters is provided through integration with vSphere storage services, using storage policies and CSI-based provisioning.To provide persistent storage to VKS clusters, a vSphere administrator defines storage policies that describe required storage characteristics (such as performance, availability, and placement rules).These storage policies are then:
Assigned to a vSphere Namespace
Exposed to VKS clusters deployed within that namespace
The storage policies determine:
Which datastores can be used
How volumes are provisioned
How placement and availability rules are enforced
Based on the assigned storage policies:
<br>The <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> automatically creates corresponding Kubernetes StorageClasses
These StorageClasses are made available inside the VKS cluster
Each storage policy results in two StorageClass variants:
One with Immediate volume binding
One with WaitForFirstConsumer volume binding
This allows DevOps teams to choose the appropriate provisioning behavior based on workload requirements.VKS clusters integrate with vSphere storage using Paravirtual CSI (pvCSI).
pvCSI is a modified version of the standard vSphere CNS-CSI driver
It runs inside the VKS cluster
It handles all storage-related operations initiated from the cluster
The pvCSI driver does not communicate directly with vCenter or CNS. Instead:
The pvCSI driver forwards storage requests to the Supervisor
The Supervisor routes the request to CNS (Cloud Native Storage)
<br><a data-href="CNS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a> performs the actual storage operation in vSphere
Unlike CNS-CSI, pvCSI:
Does not require vCenter credentials
Operates using a service account within the namespace
Relies on the Supervisor for secure mediation
<br><img alt="vks-pv-creation-a7a9c4ee-5c78-40fe-9406-6ee986c5d4d9.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-pv-creation-a7a9c4ee-5c78-40fe-9406-6ee986c5d4d9.original.png" target="_self">The following sequence describes how a persistent volume is created in a VKS cluster:
A DevOps engineer creates a PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) in the VKS cluster.
The request is received by the pvCSI driver.
pvCSI forwards the request to the Supervisor.
The Supervisor invokes the CNS API in vCenter to create the volume.
Once the volume is created, the information propagates back through the Supervisor.
The PVC and corresponding PV appear as Bound in both: The VKS cluster
The Supervisor view This ensures consistent visibility and lifecycle tracking across all layers.
VKS clusters rely on vSphere storage policies for persistent storage.
Storage policies determine where and how volumes are provisioned.
The Supervisor mediates all storage operations between VKS and vSphere.
pvCSI enables secure, credential-free storage operations from inside the cluster.
Storage resources appear consistently in both the VKS cluster and Supervisor views.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VKS”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-storage.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/Platform Integration/VKS Cluster Storage.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:57:36 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vks-storage-61c36ee0-7cbe-4798-b1af-4538767171e9.original.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VKS Cluster Networking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VKS" data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “VKS”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/platform-integration/vks-cluster-networking.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/Kubernetes Runtimes/VKS/Platform Integration/VKS Cluster Networking.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:57:16 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Security]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:security" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#security">#security</a><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> leverages vSphere security features and provisions&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters that are secure by default.<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> is an add-on module to <a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> that is able to leverage the security features that are built into&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> and <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.<br>The&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> encrypts all secrets stored in the database (etcd). The secrets are encrypted via a local encryption key file, which is provided at boot by&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>. The decryption key is stored in memory (tempfs) on the&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> nodes and on disk in encrypted form within <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> database. The key is available in clear text to the root users of each system.&nbsp;
All etcd connections are authenticated with certificates that are generated at installation and rotated during upgrades.&nbsp;<br>
In&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>, you can run <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod" data-href="Deploy a Confidential vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/deploy-a-confidential-vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">run confidential vSphere Pods</a> on compatible systems. You can create confidential&nbsp; vSphere Pods by adding Secure Encrypted Virtualization-Encrypted State (SEV-ES) as a security enhancement.<br>A <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster is secure by default. Restrictive Pod Security Admission is configured in <a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> Clusters.&nbsp;If developers need to run privileged pods or root containers, at a minimum, a cluster administrator must create a RoleBinding that grants the necessary access&nbsp;<br>
VKS cluster has tenancy. As a result, there is no privilege escalation avenue for cluster operators or users: The authentication token used to access a&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> cluster is scoped such that the token cannot be used to access the&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> or other&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters. This prevents cluster operators, or individuals who might try to compromise a cluster, from using their root-level access to capture a vSphere Administrator's token when they log in to a&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>
cluster.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-security.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Security.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:54:11 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Inventory]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <br><img alt="supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg" target="_self">The&nbsp;vSphere Supervisor Inventory is a representation of the&nbsp; Supervisor folder and its associated resources.<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> configures separate&nbsp;Supervisor folders for each&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Cluster" data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor</a> and all the associated resources. The namespaces and control plane VMs are mapped under the respective&nbsp;Supervisor folder isolating them from the resources of other&nbsp;Supervisors, even though names of namespaces must be unique within&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>.<br>The&nbsp; <a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s within each namespace are segregated into a folder called&nbsp;“vSphere Pods”. This ensures their isolation from other VMs and&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> Clusters that are in the same namespace and allows distinct and precise privilege allocation.<br>Each&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a> folder includes all workload entities created under it, such as VMs deployed through VM Service and&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a><br>
clusters (<a data-href="Guest Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/guest-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Guest Cluster</a>s). Additionally, each&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Namespace</a><br>
folder contains a subfolder named&nbsp;vSphere Pods which contains all the&nbsp;<a data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pod</a>s associated with the <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Supervisor Namespace" data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">namespace</a>.&nbsp;<br>
Since <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Pod" data-href="vSphere Pod" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/architecture-and-core-concepts/vsphere-pod.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod VMs</a> primarily serve infrastructure purposes, the&nbsp;
vSphere Pods folder is configured with restrictive permissions to prevent users from performing any direct operations on the pods.<br><img alt="supervisor-vsphere-folder-structure-f8d271d6-e7e2-4e2d-b18c-4ed4d1ea612a.original.png" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-vsphere-folder-structure-f8d271d6-e7e2-4e2d-b18c-4ed4d1ea612a.original.png" target="_self"><br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-inventory.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Inventory.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:53:40 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-inventory-43ae694e-d039-47d3-825c-224b30358eaa.original.svg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Networking]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> leverages several components and technologies to establish management-plane and workload-plane networking.<br><img alt="supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="supervisor-nsx-segment-networking-c19ee74a-d0e9-4f05-b19f-e5fd1f5438ed.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-nsx-segment-networking-c19ee74a-d0e9-4f05-b19f-e5fd1f5438ed.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="single-mgmt-zone-nsx-segment-networking-77b549f9-eb55-4a44-93c4-8d12fd81e9c0.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/single-mgmt-zone-nsx-segment-networking-77b549f9-eb55-4a44-93c4-8d12fd81e9c0.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="supervisor-networking-with-avi-f7f80972-bfe1-493a-93eb-e5b000a5e516.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-with-avi-f7f80972-bfe1-493a-93eb-e5b000a5e516.original.svg" target="_self"><br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-networking.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Networking.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:53:27 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-networking-vds-0fbea852-92c6-4d8b-b33f-5a175b46acd9.original.svg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Components]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <br><img alt="supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg" target="_self"><br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> has the following components:
<br>Supervisor control plane VM. You can select to deploy the&nbsp; Supervisor with either one or three control plane VMs. For control plane <a data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, three VMs are recommended. The three&nbsp; Supervisor control plane VMs are load balanced as each one of them has its own IP address.
<br><a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> and Cluster API (CAPI). Modules running on the&nbsp;Supervisor and enable the provisioning and management of&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters.
<br>Virtual Machine Service. A module that is responsible for deploying and running stand-alone VMs and VMs that make up&nbsp;<a data-href="VKS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/kubernetes-runtimes/vks/vks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a> clusters.
<br>Spherelet. An additional process called Spherelet is created on each host. It is a kubelet that is ported natively to <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and allows the <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> host to become part of the Kubernetes cluster.
<br>Container Runtime Executive (CRX) component. CRX is similar to a VM from the perspective of hostd and&nbsp;<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vCenter Server" data-href="vCenter Server" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>. CRX includes a paravirtualized Linux kernel that works together with the hypervisor. CRX uses the same hardware virtualization techniques as VMs and it has a VM boundary around it. A direct boot technique is used, which allows the Linux guest of CRX to initiate the main init process without passing through kernel initialization. This allows&nbsp; vSphere Pods to boot nearly as fast as containers.
<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/supervisor-internals-and-platform-integration/vsphere-supervisor-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Supervisor Internals and Platform Integration/vSphere Supervisor Components.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:53:19 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/supervisor-hla-0b627ecf-2348-4545-bd0c-2f2707c56e2e.original.svg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:architecture" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#architecture">#architecture</a> A mode / capability of a vSphere cluster
Means: “This vSphere cluster has Kubernetes enabled and is running the Supervisor control plane” or less wordy: “*a vSphere cluster with Supervisor enabled”. Not a physical thing by itself
Think of it as a feature flag + control plane. A vSphere Cluster with Supervisor enabled
A concrete, addressable object: ESX hosts
=======
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Automation layers (i.e., <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
This is similar to saying “a Docker container does not know which Jira project paid for the VM it runs on”.vSphere / ESX
└── Supervisor Cluster └── Supervisor Namespace └── TKG Workload Cluster (guest cluster) ├── Kubernetes API ├── Nodes = VMs └── Apps / Pods ]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/kubernetes-runtimes/tkg/tkg.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Kubernetes Runtimes/TKG/TKG.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:13:25 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Guest Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>Once a workload cluster (<a data-href="TKG" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/kubernetes-runtimes/tkg/tkg.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">TKG</a>) is bound to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/control-and-consumption/supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>:
✅ The cluster knows which Supervisor Namespace it lives in
❌ It has no intrinsic knowledge of: Organization
Project
Automation constructs
Approval flows
Business tenancy
<br>^ all of these concepts stop at the **<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> boundary. <br>When a workload cluster is bound to a Supervisor Namespace, we are talking about a TKG workload cluster created by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.That implies:
The cluster is created via Supervisor APIs
<br>It is <a data-href="vSphere Namespaces" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespaces</a>-scoped
It is lifecycle-managed by vSphere
It runs on ESX using VM-based worker nodes
So, in this model:<br>
Guest cluster == <a data-href="TKG" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/kubernetes-runtimes/tkg/tkg.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">TKG</a> workload cluster]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/kubernetes-runtimes/tkg/guest-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Kubernetes Runtimes/TKG/Guest Cluster.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:07:10 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tenants are Bound to Namespaces]]></title><description><![CDATA[
The <a data-href="provider administrator" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">provider administrator</a> can create <a data-href="projects" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">projects</a>, assign users and groups, and allocate quotas to restrict the configurations available to the <a data-href="tenants" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenants</a>.
<br>
By creating <a data-href="projects" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">projects</a>, you can isolate security and networking objects across tenants in a single&nbsp;NSX deployment.
<br><a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a><br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>]]></description><link>vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/tenants-are-bound-to-namespaces.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Concepts/Tenancy in VCF/Tenants are Bound to Namespaces.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:17:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Client]]></title><description><![CDATA[VMware vSphere Client is:
A web UI (HTML5 / JS)
Running inside either <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> (embedded) or <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>
Consuming backend APIs
It consumes REST and legacy SOAP / internal APIs
Functionally: It is an API consumer
It behaves differently depending on where it is placed:
Same UI codebase:
Connected to ESX → host-scoped
Connected to vCenter Server → environment-scoped
The UI is not “smart”: The backend defines reality.vSphere is a product contract, not a system.<br>
<a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> and <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> are the systems that implement that contract.]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Access and Interfaces/vSphere Client.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:12:51 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Constructs]]></title><description><![CDATA[A vSphere construct is:
*A first-class infrastructure object that is _natively defined, owned, and enforced by the vSphere control plane (ESX + vCenter), not by Kubernetes or higher-level automation layers.
Think of it as a primitive in vSphere’s own vocabulary.Below are objects that exist because vSphere exists — they are not abstractions layered on top.
Virtual Machine
vCPU
vNUMA
vApp Resource Pool
Shares / Limits / Reservations
DRS rules
HA admission control Datastore
vSAN object
VM disk (VMDK)
Storage policy Port Group
Distributed Virtual Switch
VM NIC
VLAN / overlay constructs Snapshot
Clone
vMotion
Storage vMotion
HA restart
Fault Tolerance
All of these are authoritative in VMware vSphere and enforced by:
VMware ESXi
VMware vCenter Server
These are foreign concepts to vSphere — it may host them, but it does not own them:
Kubernetes Pod
Kubernetes Deployment
Kubernetes Service
Kubernetes ReplicaSet
Kubernetes Namespace (in the K8s sense)
Kubernetes ServiceAccount
vSphere sees these as resource consumers, not objects with meaning.A <a data-href="VM Workload" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM Workload</a> is built entirely out of vSphere constructs.<br>
A <a data-href="Pod Workload" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod Workload</a> is built out of Kubernetes constructs, even though it ultimately consumes vSphere resources.## VM Workload VM ├─ vCPU ├─ vMemory ├─ VMDK ├─ Port Group └─ Resource Pool
Pod ├─ Container ├─ CPU request/limit ├─ Memory request/limit ├─ ServiceAccount └─ Namespace
]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/vsphere-constructs.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Object Model/vSphere Constructs.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:12:13 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere and vCenter]]></title><description><![CDATA[
vSphere is the platform (the whole virtualization stack)
vCenter Server is the control plane that manages the coordinates of that platform
ESX is the hypervisor that runs on hardware and executes VMs.
I mentally see (but don’t tell) this as “vSphere is just marketing”:
There is nothing I can curl called vSphere. it is “air”. <img alt="what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" src="assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" target="_self">VMware vSphere is a product suite, not a single binary.To be clear: vSphere is a product name, or a platform name. Its components are the concrete things that actually do the work.vSphere includes: ESX is the bare-metal hypervisor. <br>
<a data-href="vCenter Server" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> provides centralized management. Platform features: vMotion (live VM migration)
HA/DRS
Resource pools
Distributed switches
Storage policies
Fault tolerance You cannot have vSphere without ESX. You can have ESX without vCenter (but it will be very limited). Connects many ESX hosts.
Maintains inventory and state
Enforces cluster-level logic.
Orchestrates features that require coordination. vMotion between hosts
DRS placement decisions
Cluster HA
Supervisor Cluster (for Kubernetes / VCF) vCenter Server is a set of backend services:
Inventory (hosts, clusters, VMs)
State and configuration database
<br>Scheduling logic (<a data-href="DRS" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>)
<br><a data-href="HA" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> coordination
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> orchestration
RBAC, roles, permissions
APIs (REST, SOAP)
<br><img alt="What-is-VMware-vSphere-vSphere-Client.jpg" src="assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.jpg" target="_self"><br>There is exactly ONE UI name (“<a data-href="vSphere Client" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/access-and-interfaces/vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a>”), but it can connect to TWO different backends.
vSphere Server
ESX Hosts
## Mode 1
Browser ↓
ESX Host ↓
Embedded vSphere Client ## Mode 2
Browser ↓
vCenter Server ↓
vSphere Client ↓
Many ESX hosts
<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> is a logical grouping of ESX hosts that vCenter treats as a single resource pool and failure domain.
It exists only in vCenter
ESX hosts do not know they are “in a cluster”.
When you create a cluster in vCenter Server, you are telling:
“*These ESX hosts agree to be scheduled, balanced, and failed over together.”This enables cluster-level logic, such as
DRS (Distributed Resource Scheduler): vCenter decides which host should run which VM.
When to rebalance the load. <br>Uses <a data-href="vMotion" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> to move VMs between hosts. HA (High Availability) Hosts run a lightweight HA agent.
If a host dies: Other hosts detect it
vCenter (or preconfigured HA logic) restarts VMs elsewhere. Shared resource abstraction Instead of thinking: Host A: 64 cores Host B: 64 cores vCenter presents Cluster: 128 cores VM placement and limits are logical, not physical.A vSphere Cluster is not:Because from an operator’s perspective:
Hosts act like a pool
Failures are absorbed
Workloads move transparently
But architecturally: The cluster is an illusion created by vCenter. <br>A vSphere cluster is a <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>-defined scheduling and failure domain over multiple <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts,[ Physical Servers ] ↓ ESX (many hosts) ↓ vCenter Server ↓ vSphere features &amp; automation ]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/component-relationships/vsphere-and-vcenter.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Core Components/Component Relationships/vSphere and vCenter.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:10:53 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Provider Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>IT teams and <a data-href="CSP" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CSP</a>s can model <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a> by using the concept of Organizations in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> Is a "tenant" organization-bound, or project-bound, or a mixture?
This approach allocates resources and manages users specific to each Organization.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> in the last one-pager review, F and S recommended the partitioning of the secret path at either project, or namespace level—I don’t remember which one. Identify pros/cons of each approach and choose a solution that is aligned with their vision.
<br>This capability provides isolated environments with dedicated network setup. IT Teams and CSPs can monitor resource usage, control permissions, and provide <a data-href="managed services" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">managed services</a> while ensuring security through comprehensive <a data-href="network isolation" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">network isolation</a>.]]></description><link>vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/provider-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Provider Management.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:09:39 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kubectl in Supervisorlandia]]></title><description><![CDATA[Connected to Supervisor Cluster:kubectl config use-context &lt;supervisor-context&gt;
kubectl get ns NAME STATUS AGE
default Active
kube-system Active
kube-public Active
kube-node-lease Active
my-team-a Active
my-team-b Active
Here, there is no such thing as a “regular Kubernetes namespace” in the tenant sense.
The namespace here:
Cannot be created freely.
Map to <a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> inventory objects.
Quotas, storage, and networking are externally-enforced.
Connected to a guest clusterkubectl get ns
kubectl create ns foo
kubectl delete ns foo
All of these will work as expected.
Supervisor namespaces → owns the cluster.
Guest cluster namespace → normal Kubernetes semantics.
# check Supervisor-specific APIs
kubectl api-resources | grep -i vm virtualmachines vmoperator.vmware.com # look at the nodes
kubectl get nodes -o wide # look for VM Operator
kubectl get pods -A | grep vmoperator
Supervisor cluster nodes typically show:
<br><a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>-backed control-plane VMs.
Special node labels
VM Operator components
Guest clusters look like:
Standard linux nodes
kubelet-managed lifecycle
No VM Operator CRDs. In a Supervisor cluster, tenant namespaces are Kubernetes namespaces whose lifecycle, limits, and security are owned by vSphere.
In a guest cluster, namespaces are owned entirely by Kubernetes.
<br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> ]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/control-and-consumption/kubectl-in-supervisorlandia.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Control and Consumption/Kubectl in Supervisorlandia.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 12:53:23 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Does Supervisor Exist]]></title><description><![CDATA[Kubernetes didn’t replace VMs.
It replaced application scheduling semantics.VMware’s bet was:
"Instead of forcing Kubernetes to run on top of vSphere,
we'll make Kubernetes a native execution mode of vSphere."
Supervisor is that bet made concrete.
vSphere = substrate
Supervisor = Kubernetes-native personality of vSphere
VCF Automation = enterprise automation layer on top
<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>]]></description><link>vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/overview/why-does-supervisor-exist.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Overview/Why Does Supervisor Exist.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 00:08:11 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Organization Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> improves governance for users and resources by enabling <a data-href="organization administrator" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">organization administrator</a>s create and assign projects and vSphere Namespaces tailored for different application teams.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> make a list of roles and what capabilities each these roles do. For example, "what does an 'organization administrator' do; what are other kinds of admins?"
<br>Organization administrators can set resource limits and policies while delegating network management through Virtual Private Clouds (<a data-href="VPC" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VPC</a>s) for application teams. <br>Additionally, <a data-href="Policy as Code" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Policy as Code</a> enables organization administrators to enforce instance-centric policies for Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) resources from a central location for compliance and reducing the risk of human error.]]></description><link>vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/organization-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Organization Management.md</guid><pubDate>Sat, 20 Dec 2025 17:02:42 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Cloud Services]]></title><description><![CDATA[VCF Automation (<a data-href="VCF-A" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF-A</a>) provides a set of cloud services which are accessible on a self-service basis using multiple interfaces, including UI, CLI, and API.<br>With this interface, users can provision the following types of <a data-href="workload" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a>s:
VMs
Kubernetes workloads
Networking
Volumes
Secret stores
Databases
Harbor container registries
External DNS
Certificates
AI workloads
<br>Additionally, application teams can also provision resources on a self-service basis from Catalogs which are backed by pre-configured <a data-href="workload template" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload template</a>s. These self-service options help developers focus on application development instead of managing the underlying infrastructure.]]></description><link>vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/cloud-services.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Cloud Services.md</guid><pubDate>Sat, 20 Dec 2025 16:52:00 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Workload Mobility]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a> <a data-href="HCX" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HCX</a> is a workload mobility platform for migration and interconnection of workloads within and across VCF <a data-href="private cloud" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">private cloud</a>s.You can perform secure and automated migrations without requiring changes to applications or network configurations. Important features include multiple migration types, such as live and bulk migration, as well as network extension, which preserves existing IP addresses and network topologies. Thus, you can place workloads based on business requirements. The platform minimizes downtime during migrations, improves scalability, and supports compliance and security throughout workload transitions.]]></description><link>vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/workload-mobility.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Operations/Workload Mobility and Resilience/Workload Mobility.md</guid><pubDate>Sat, 20 Dec 2025 04:25:55 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[F