94fee0e-aa08-4ea3-9a97-252cc21af9d2.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-isolated-094fee0e-aa08-4ea3-9a97-252cc21af9d2.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-combined-ec332fe0-48fb-4df8-98d9-39532459a54b.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-combined-ec332fe0-48fb-4df8-98d9-39532459a54b.original.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vsphere-supervisor-management-isolated-c4acf25c-6f36-45e0-b698-7d874e8fffe9.original.svg" src="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-management-isolated-c4acf25c-6f36-45e0-b698-7d874e8fffe9.original.svg" target="_self"><br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="vSphere Supervisor" data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to “vSphere Supervisor”</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/overview/vsphere-supervisor-deployment-options.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSphere/Platform Extensions/vSphere Supervisor/Overview/vSphere Supervisor Deployment Options.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 28 Dec 2025 05:52:23 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-simple-2a666aae-dc08-4c32-97fc-39152205b6a8.original.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;./https://vcf.wtf/assets/vsphere-supervisor-simple-2a666aae-dc08-4c32-97fc-39152205b6a8.original.svg&quot;&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor Services]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:kubernetes" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#kubernetes">#kubernetes</a> <br>Supervisor Services are platform-level extensions for the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/platform-extensions/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> that provide cloud-native infrastructure capabilities by packaging functionality as Kubernetes Operators and service bundles that run on the <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>.These services enable foundational capabilities such as Kubernetes consumption, storage services, registry operations, DNS management, ingress controllers, and more— all integrated directly into the vSphere control plane.Supervisor Services are:
<br>Installed and managed per <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>
Controlled by platform administrators
Versioned and upgradeable independently
<br>Consumed <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Multi-Tenancy" data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/tenancy-in-vcf/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">by tenants</a> or platform components
<br>In addition to core production Supervisor Services, there is a Supervisor Services Labs Catalog that includes experimental or community services which can be installed on <a data-href="Supervisor Cluster" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/inventory-objects/supervisor-cluster.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Cluster</a>s but are not yet part of the core catalog.
Labs services are typically not supported at the same guarantee level as core Supervisor Services and may be subject to change. Formerly known as the Tanzu Kubernetes Grid Service
Provides APIs to create and manage Kubernetes clusters
Enables declarative Kubernetes lifecycle management via Supervisor APIs. UI component for resource consumption inside Namespaces
Displays resources in the vSphere Client UI under Workload Management
Improves namespace Kubernetes consumption UX Framework for stateful services using vSAN
Enables highly available object and block storage services for cloud-native workloads Integrates Velero with Supervisor Kubernetes
Enables backup/restore of Kubernetes resources and volumes
Natively integrated into Supervisor cluster workflows Leverages cert-manager primitives
Issues certificates for workloads running on Supervisor or tenant clusters
Helps with workload TLS termination and secure communication Adds a container registry within the Supervisor cluster
Supports image scanning, signing, and lifecycle policies
Works with ingress and DNS services for external access
Ingress Controller (Contour):
Provides ingress routing and load balancing for Kubernetes workloads
Integrates with Envoy for traffic proxying
ExternalDNS:
Automatically updates DNS records based on exposed service endpoints
Connects to external DNS providers for dynamic record management
Supervisor Management Proxy:
Facilitates communication between management and workload networks when isolated
Ensures Supervisor components can reach required management endpoints
NSX Management Proxy:
Previously used for similar connectivity needs but is now deprecated in favor of Supervisor Management Proxy Enables native Supervisor APIs to expose data services to tenants
Integrates the Data Services Manager (DSM) with Supervisor Cluster workload consumption paths
Secret Store Service:
Native secret storage capabilities for Kubernetes workloads
ArgoCD Service:
Provides a GitOps delivery model for application deployments
Useful for declarative automation and continuous deployment workflows Supervisor Services are the core platform building blocks that make vSphere Supervisor extensible and cloud-capable.
These services cover Kubernetes lifecycle, storage, registry, ingress, DNS, certificate management, backup, data services consumption, secrets, and more.
They are installed per Supervisor Cluster, managed by platform administrators, and consumed by tenant workloads or automation layers like VCF Automation.
There is also a Labs Catalog for experimental or early-stage Supervisor Services.
