ncoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[My Mental Model]]></title><description><![CDATA[I think of mental models as compression algorithms for reality.A mental model is an internal, simplified representation of how something works in the real world. It’s the framework the mind uses to understand, predict, and decide—often without conscious awareness.It is a map, not the territory.In my view, a mental model is:
A conceptual structure in the mind
Built from experience, learning, and assumptions
Used to explain cause → effect and anticipate outcomes
It answers questions like:
“If I do X, what will probably happen?”
“Why did that fail?”
“What matters here—and what doesn’t?”
Imagine driving in a foreign city.
The actual city is reality: complex, messy, and full of detail
Your mental model is a rough subway map in your head
That map:
Omits small streets
Distorts distances
Focuses only on what helps you get from A → B
It is useful precisely because it ignores detail—even if it’s inaccurate in places.That is what this (mostly) directed acyclic graph of documents (with occasional—intentional—loops) is trying to establish for <a data-href="VMware Cloud Foundation" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/vmware-cloud-foundation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VMware Cloud Foundation</a>: A navigable mental map, not an exhaustive representation of reality.The goal is not to describe everything, but to surface the abstractions that help me (and you, dear reader) reason correctly.Mental models exist because the human brain cannot process full reality in real time.Mental models:
Reduce cognitive load
Enable faster decisions
Allow generalization from experience
A single concept can be viewed through multiple overlapping mental models.For example, a database can be seen as:
A storage engine
A consistency system
A failure domain
A political boundary (ownership and control) Each model is incomplete on its own.
Taken together, they are powerful.
This document intentionally favors some mental models over others—not because they are “more correct,” but because they are more useful for the problems at hand.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="index" data-href="index" href="./https://vcf.wtf/index.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to Index</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/about-me/my-mental-model.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">About Me/My Mental Model.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 03:10:08 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSAN]]></title><description><![CDATA[vSAN&nbsp;aggregates local or direct-attached capacity devices of all <a data-href="ESX" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/core-components/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts in a cluster and creates a single storage pool shared across all ESX hosts in the&nbsp;
vSAN cluster.Use&nbsp;vSAN&nbsp;as a VI administrator or storage administrator to enhance storage performance by aggregating local storage into a single shared pool across all hosts in a&nbsp;vSAN cluster.<br>You can use vSphere features that require shared storage, such as <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="HA" data-href="HA" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/ha.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere HA</a>, vSphere <a data-href="vMotion" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/workload-mobility-and-resilience/vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a>, and vSphere <a data-href="DRS" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsphere/object-model/cluster-services/drs.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, without the need for external shared storage.vSAN provides operational consistency from edge to cloud, with complete visibility and lifecycle management of compute and storage from a single UI.You can perform consistent, VM-centric operations by using policy-based management. Within the vSAN ESA, per-VM policies increase flexibility of management, enabling compression policies, or customize data services on a per-VM basis.<br>Want some L2/L3 network magic? Then check out <a data-href="Distributed Virtual Switch" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/distributed-virtual-switch.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Distributed Virtual Switch</a>.]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/core-runtimes/vsan/vsan.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Core Runtimes/vSAN/vSAN.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:36:28 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project User]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Project Users can only access the catalog and request catalog items. They can perform <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a> actions on their own deployments. They cannot use the IaaS services console.<br><a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="User Roles" data-href="User Roles" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/user-roles.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">← Back to User Roles</a>]]></description><link>./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-automation/tenancy-and-access-control/organization-management/user-roles/project-user.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Control Planes/VCF Automation/Tenancy and Access Control/Organization Management/User Roles/Project User.md</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[Volkan Özçelik]]></dc:creator><pubDate>Sat, 27 Dec 2025 02:21:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Project Advanced User]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href="./https://vcf.wtf?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>Project Advanced Users work within their <a data-href="Project" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/concepts/design-and-abstractions/consumption-abstractions/project.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Project</a>s to request Catalog Items and create resources using the services console. They can perform <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="VCF Day 2 Tasks" data-href="VCF Day 2 Tasks" href="./https://vcf.wtf/vcf/control-planes/vcf-operations/day-n-operations/vcf-day-2-tasks.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Day 2</a