]]></description><link>supervisor-and-supervisor-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Supervisor and Supervisor Cluster.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:29:46 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Automation]]></title><description><![CDATA[enables IT teams and cloud service providers (<a data-href="CSP" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CSP</a>s) to deliver a self-service private cloud for AI, Kubernetes, and VM-based applications.<br>The solution simplifies the process of provisioning and scaling a <a data-href="multi-tenant" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">multi-tenant</a> private cloud with out-of-the-box Infrastructure as a Service (<a data-href="IaaS" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">IaaS</a>) offerings, accelerating the time to market for applications while maintaining control using policy-based governance.VCF Automation provides governance at the request and lifecycle level—controlling who can deploy which patterns, under what constraints and approvals—while runtime security, drift detection, and continuous enforcement are handled by downstream platforms.<br><a data-href="Governance" href="vcf/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a><br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>VCF Automation has the following capabilities:
<br><a data-href="Cloud Services" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/cloud-services.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Cloud Services</a>: Provides a set of cloud services to meet the needs of application teams
<br><a data-href="Provider Management" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/provider-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Provider Management</a>: Supports IT teams and cloud service providers to effectively manage, deliver, and scale cloud services across multiple vCenter and VCF instances.
<br><a data-href="Organization Management" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/organization-management.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Organization Management</a>: Provides capabilities that enable the organization administrator of a Line of Business or a tenant to further organize and govern resources allocated to them among application teams.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>: Provides the capability to run Kubernetes workloads directly on ESX hosts and to create upstream Kubernetes clusters within dedicated namespaces.( <a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a>: Further explanation needed )
]]></description><link>vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Main Componets/engine/VCF-A/VCF Automation.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:22:12 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Virtual Appliance]]></title><description><![CDATA[A VMware appliance is a prepackaged, hardened virtual machine that bundles an OS, application, configuration, and lifecycle tooling into a single deployable unit.A VMware-style appliance typically includes:
A minimal, locked-down OS
The application(s)
Configuration defaults
Upgrade mechanisms
Health checks
Backup/restore hooks
Support boundaries (“only change things this way”)
The key idea is:
You manage the appliance as a product, not as a general-purpose OS.
Usually yes, but conceptually they can be:
One VM (vCenter)
Multiple tightly-coupled VMs (some NSX / telco components)
But still treated as one product unit
From the operator’s perspective:
You deploy “the appliance”
You don’t manage its internals individually
Once you accept that:
vCenter is a VM
Supervisor components are appliances
Then the stack becomes very consistent:
<a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> runs everything
<br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> orchestrates everything
<br><a data-href="Appliance" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Appliance</a>s are how VMware ships control planes Kubernetes is just another control surface layered on top Multiple VMs ≠ appliance unless:If you deploy 3 random VMs and wire them together yourself — that’s not an appliance.<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>]]></description><link>virtual-appliance.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Virtual Appliance.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:21:36 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCenter Server]]></title><description><![CDATA[vCenter Server runs as a <a data-href="Virtual Appliance" href="virtual-appliance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Virtual Appliance</a> (<a data-href="VCSA" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCSA</a>) — a prebuilt VM — on <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.Concretely:
vCenter is not bare metal
It is deployed as an OVA
That OVA becomes one VM (sometimes functionally “a group of services”, but still a single VM)
Internally, that VM runs:
A hardened Linux-based OS
vCenter services
Database (embedded or external, depending on scale)
Physical hardware
└── ESX └── vCenter Server Appliance (VM) └── vCenter services
<br><img alt="ESXi-vs-vSphere-vs-vCenter-overview.png.webp" src="assets/esxi-vs-vsphere-vs-vcenter-overview.png.webp" target="_self">]]></description><link>vcenter-server.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vCenter Server.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:14:13 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/esxi-vs-vsphere-vs-vcenter-overview.png.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/esxi-vs-vsphere-vs-vcenter-overview.png.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VM Workload and Pod Workload]]></title><description><![CDATA[In VCF, a workload is:
A unit of compute that consumes CPU, memory, storage, and networking, and is subject to lifecycle, policy, and governance.
VCF doesn’t care what the workload is at a philosophical level. It cares about:
How it is instantiated
How it is isolated
How it is scheduled
How it is governed
Which control plane owns it
one machine per workloadA VM workload is a traditional virtual machine:
Runs on ESX
Has its own guest OS
Is managed by vCenter
Uses <a data-href="vSphere construct" href="vsphere-construct.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere construct</a>s directly <br><a data-href="vCenter Server" href="vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> is the authoritative control plane
VCF Automation wraps vCenter, but does not replace it CPU / memory allocated per VM
Strong isolation via hypervisor boundaries
Overcommitment controlled at ESX level Create VM
Power on/off
Snapshot
Clone
Patch guest OS
Backup VM image VM policies
Placement rules
Affinity / anti-affinity
HA / DRS
Backup &amp; DR policies
many disposable units forming a service.A pod workload is a Kubernetes Pod running on the vSphere Supervisor Cluster.A pod on the vSphere Supervisor Cluster is not a traditional Kubernetes pod.
It is a vSphere Pod — Kubernetes-shaped, but vSphere-implemented.Key point:
A pod workload is not a VM pretending to be a container. Supervisor pods are VMs implementing container semantics, not containers implemented as VMs. A Supervisor pod is a Kubernetes Pod whose execution unit is a micro-VM, where the VM boundary replaces the Linux container boundary. The VM is the isolation primitive
The Pod is the semantic primitive
The container image is payload, not a process model
So the VM is not “pretending to be a container” —
it is implementing the Pod abstraction using a VM instead of a process.
Pod (Kubernetes API object) └─ Backed by └─ Ultra-lightweight VM └─ ESX └─ Hardware
It is:
A Kubernetes-native unit
Scheduled by Kubernetes
Governed by Kubernetes APIs
Backed by vSphere under the hood Kubernetes API (Supervisor cluster) is authoritative
vCenter supplies infrastructure, not lifecycle semantics
VCF Automation governs Kubernetes intent, not individual pods CPU / memory requested via Kubernetes requests &amp; limits
Scheduler decides placement
Isolation via: Namespaces
RBAC
Pod security
(Optionally) VM-backed pod runtimes Declarative (YAML)
Reconciliation-based
Pods are ephemeral
Restart ≠ failure
Replacement is normal Namespace-level quotas
Admission control
Image policies
Network policies VM workloads → legacy, stateful, pet-like systems
Pod workloads → cloud-native, stateless, cattle-like systems
VCF’s value is:
Running both on the same physical infrastructure, with unified policy and automation, without forcing one model onto the other.
Trying to manage pods like VMs breaks Kubernetes.
Trying to manage VMs like pods breaks operational reality.VCF keeps them separate but coordinated.<br>A pod workload in VCF is a Kubernetes-native execution unit scheduled and governed by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> Kubernetes control plane, consuming vSphere resources indirectly through Kubernetes abstractions—unlike a VM workload, which is a hypervisor-managed, OS-bearing unit directly governed by vCenter.
“Pod workload” ≠ “small VM”
Pod workloads are Kubernetes-first, not vSphere-first
VMs are stateful machines
Pods are replaceable execution instances
VCF supports both because enterprises need both
]]></description><link>vm-workload-and-pod-workload.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VM Workload and Pod Workload.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 19:11:39 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere, ESX, and vCenter]]></title><description><![CDATA[Saying “vSphere is ESX and vCenter” is colloquially common, but technically incomplete.Because vSphere is a platform, it is NOT a single product.<a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> is VMware’s virtualization platform built on <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts managed by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>, together providing cluster-level services such as <a data-href="HA" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>, <a data-href="DRS" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>, and Kubernetes integration.But still, that term is mostly, contextually “good enough” because, in practice:
You never run production vSphere without vCenter
ESX alone is just a hypervisor, not a platform
vCenter alone does nothing Type-1 (bare-metal) hypervisor
Runs directly on hardware
Owns: CPU scheduling
Memory management
Device virtualization Does not coordinate clusters by itself
You can run standalone ESXi without vCenter, but:
No clustering
<br>No <a data-href="HA" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a>
<br>No <a data-href="DRS" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>
<br>No <a data-href="vMotion" href="vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> orchestration Centralized control plane
Manages: <br><a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
Clusters
Resource pools
Policies Orchestrates: vMotion
DRS
HA
Lifecycle
vCenter does not run workloads — it tells ESX what to do. In ESX, there is no general-purpose userland like you’d expect in Linux or Windows.ESX is a purpose-built, bare-metal hypervisor operating system whose kernel (VMkernel) directly manages hardware resources and runs virtual machines.]]></description><link>vsphere,-esx,-and-vcenter.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vSphere, ESX, and vCenter.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 18:55:30 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vCloud Director]]></title><description><![CDATA[VMware vCloud Director (VCD) is a cloud-management and multi-tenancy layer built on top of vSphere. It was designed primarily for service providers (ISPs, telcos, MSPs) to offer VMware-based clouds to multiple customers in a clean, isolated, self-service way.
vSphere → virtualization engine (hypervisors, clusters, VMs)
VCD → cloud abstraction + multi-tenant control plane
VCF → opinionated full stack (compute + storage + networking + ops)
vSphere does not have native multitenancy, VCD enables multitenancy.
VCD → sell VMware-based cloud to others VCF Automation → run your own internal cloud
Cloud Layer
────────────
vCloud Director ← multi-tenant cloud manager Automation Layer
────────────
VCF Automation / Aria Automation Infrastructure
────────────
vSphere + vSAN + NSX Hardware
────────────
Bare metal
<img alt="vcd-000.svg" src="assets/vcd-000.svg" target="_self"><br><img alt="vcd-26274c8be-3a18-40f1-adf0-8281a9feb4d8.webp" src="assets/vcd-26274c8be-3a18-40f1-adf0-8281a9feb4d8.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vcd-6adff3c1-ab57-4412-bdd8-2caa7cbd3982.webp" src="assets/vcd-6adff3c1-ab57-4412-bdd8-2caa7cbd3982.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vcd-3-Screen-Shot-2020-07-02-at-2.01.05-PM.webp" src="assets/vcd-3-screen-shot-2020-07-02-at-2.01.05-pm.webp" target="_self">No.
vSphere = hypervisor + cluster management
VCD = separate product that consumes vSphere
<br>VMware’s product web pages for Cloud Director explicitly state that VCD operates within the VMware Cloud Foundation platform as an integrated cloud-management layer: VCD is described as helping to “[efficiently […] operate and manage your managed private and public cloud services using VMware Cloud Director within the VMware Cloud Foundation platform](<a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="https://www.vmware.com/products/cloud-infrastructure/cloud-director" rel="noopener nofollow" class="external-link is-unresolved" href="https://www.vmware.com/products/cloud-infrastructure/cloud-director" target="_self">VMware Cloud Director | Leading Cloud Service Delivery Platform</a>.However, in the baseline VCF component lists and core architectural docs, the docs list things like vSphere, vSAN, NSX, SDDC Manager, VCF Automation but not VCD as a base building block.
*Historically: no.
Today: “it depends on the SKU and use case.”**
VMware Cloud Foundation (VCF) is aimed at:
Enterprises
Private cloud
Platform teams
<br>Automation (<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
VMware vCloud Director (VCD) is aimed at:
Service providers
Telcos
Hosted private cloud
Customer-facing tenancy
VCF does not require VCD, and most enterprise VCF deployments do not use it.]]></description><link>vcloud-director.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vCloud Director.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 18:47:17 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/vcd-000.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/vcd-000.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vcd-000]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="assets/vcd-000.svg" target="_self">]]></description><link>assets/vcd-000.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vcd-000.svg</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 18:47:12 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/vcd-000.svg" length="0" type="image/svg+xml"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/vcd-000.svg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere]]></title><description><![CDATA[At its core, it is a compute, storage, and network abstraction layer: A distributed operating system for data centers.It manages large collections of infrastructure, such as CPUs, storage, networking, GPUs, and DPUs as a seamless and dynamic operating environment, and also manages the complexity of a data center.&nbsp;
It virtualizes physical infrastructure into managed CPU, storage, and networking resources.vSphere
├── ESXi (data plane)
├── vCenter Server (control plane)
└── Integrated services (HA, DRS, vMotion, etc.)
vSphere is a distributed system that provides the following;vSphere is a datacenter operating system.The two core components of VMware&nbsp;vSphere:
<a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
<br>and <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> <br><a data-href="High Availability" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">High Availability</a> with&nbsp;vSphere automatically restarts your VMs following physical machine failure.
<br><a data-href="Fault Tolerance" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Fault Tolerance</a> provides continuous availability of any application in the event of a hardware failure with no data loss or downtime.
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href="vmotion.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> enables live migration of virtual machines with no disruption to users or loss of service, eliminating the need to schedule application downtime for planned server maintenance. Storage vMotion avoids downtime for planned storage maintenance. Identity federation with Microsoft Entra ID, ADFS and Okta.
Virtual Machine Encryption: Data-at-rest encryption for virtual machine data and disks.
<br><a data-href="vSphere Trust Authority" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Trust Authority</a>: Remote attestation for sensitive workloads.
]]></description><link>vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Main Componets/engine/vSphere/vSphere.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 17:58:46 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Pod]]></title><description><![CDATA[A vSphere Pod is a Kubernetes Pod whose sandbox runs inside a lightweight VM (via <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>]), not inside a container runtime on a shared Linux node.So:
API semantics → Kubernetes
Runtime semantics → vSphere / VM
Traditional Kubernetes Pods:
Share a Linux kernel
Rely on namespaces + cgroups
Are fast and efficient
But have weaker isolation (from a hypervisor POV)
vSphere Pods were created to:
Give VM-grade isolation
While keeping Pod-level developer UX
For multi-tenant / regulated environments
This matters a lot for:
Service providers
Telco
Regulated enterprise workloads
“Pods from different customers must never share a kernel”
Regular Kubernetes:Node (Linux)
└── kubelet ├── Pod A ├── Pod B └── Pod C vSphere Pods:ESXi
├── Pod-VM A
├── Pod-VM B
└── Pod-VM C No shared container runtime
No shared kubelet per “node”
Each pod is scheduled directly by vSphere
Kubernetes still thinks it’s scheduling Pods — but vSphere translates that into VM placement.So in vSphereland, “One Pod ~= Tiny VM”<br><img alt="vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" src="assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vsphere-pod-298459bc-258c-4430-81a5-fb5330d7ce24.webp" src="assets/vsphere-pod-298459bc-258c-4430-81a5-fb5330d7ce24.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vsphere-pod-4.png" src="assets/vsphere-pod-4.png" target="_self">
Kubernetes: Decides which pod should run vSphere: Decides where the pod-VM runs
Enforces CPU, memory, NUMA, HA, DRS
This is what “Kubernetes-native mode” really looks like under the hood. From the Pod’s perspective:
It has an IP
It mounts volumes
It exposes ports
Under the hood:
Networking is NSX-backed
Storage is datastore-policy-backe
Attach/detach happens at VM granularity
Again: Pod UX, VM machinery.
Despite the VM runtime, vSphere Pods still use:
Pod specs
Containers
Init containers
ConfigMaps
Volume mounts
Pod lifecycle (create/delete/restart)
Kubernetes Services (with some constraints)
So developers mostly don’t care—and that is by design. Regular Pod → process in a shared OS
vSphere Pod → process in its own micro-VM
Or:
Regular K8s → Linux container model
vSphere Pods → “micro-VM container” model
Essentially: vSphere Pods are not regular Kubernetes Pods
They are Pod-shaped workloads backed by per-Pod VMs
Kubernetes API semantics remain intact
Runtime isolation is hypervisor-level
This is intentional and central to Supervisor’s design
]]></description><link>vsphere-pod.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vSphere Pod.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 17:45:06 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/vsphere-pod-d7cddcdc-2c10-4459-999e-bfa73ee28e8c.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vsphere-pod-4]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="assets/vsphere-pod-4.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>assets/vsphere-pod-4.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vsphere-pod-4.png</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 17:16:08 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/vsphere-pod-4.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/vsphere-pod-4.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor]]></title><description><![CDATA[The vSphere Supervisor lives as a set of Kubernetes control-plane VMs running on ESX hosts, instantiated, wired, and governed by <a data-href="vCenter Server" href="vcenter-server.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a>.<br>
<img alt="supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" src="assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" target="_self">
<br>Runs on: <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>
Created and managed by: VMware vCenter Server
Implemented as: Kubernetes control-plane VMs
<br>Distributed across <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a> hosts
<br>Backed by <a data-href="vSAN" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a> / datastores
<br>Networked via <a data-href="NSX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> (or <a data-href="VDS" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsan/vds.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VDS</a> in simpler setups) When you “enable Supervisor” in vCenter:
vCenter:
Creates a special-purpose Kubernetes cluster
Instantiates its control plane as VMs
Pins it tightly to: Cluster membership
Networking
Storage Treats it as part of the infrastructure, not a tenant workload
So the Supervisor is:
Not a workload cluster
Not user-managed Kubernetes
Not a vSphere product you install
It is an infrastructure service owned by vCenter.Physical Hosts
└─ ESX └─ vCenter Server (control plane) └─ Supervisor Cluster (Kubernetes control plane VMs) ├─ Supervisor Namespaces ├─ vSphere Pods └─ Guest / Workload Clusters
The vSphere Supervisor is a Kubernetes control plane deployed as system-managed VMs on ESX, whose lifecycle is owned entirely by vCenter Server and whose purpose is to expose Kubernetes semantics directly on vSphere infrastructure.
The vSphere Supervisor physically lives as vCenter-managed Kubernetes control-plane VMs running on ESX hosts inside a vSphere cluster.
<br>vSphere Supervisor is the foundation of VCF <a data-href="consumption" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">consumption</a> and can be enabled during workload domain creation or directly in vCenter.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> "consumption" is discussed in several meetings. It seems like standard nomenclature. Learn what it is.
<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> Is vSphere Supervisor a type of vSphere deployment. Follow-up: what really is vSphere?
Is it part of VCF-A or VCF-O?
It transforms vSphere clusters into modern application platforms by embedding a platform-level Kubernetes control plane directly into ESX hosts, exposing a unified declarative API surface.<br>This integration allows end users to provision and manage workloads, including VMs, containers via <a data-href="vSphere Pods" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Pods</a>, full Kubernetes clusters through <a data-href="VKS" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VKS</a>, <a data-href="OCI image registries" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">OCI image registries</a>, and data services through a consistent API interface.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> what kinds or registries, "bring your own", harbor, cloud? all?
<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> why embedding the control plane into ESX hosts is such a big thing? wasn't that possible before. Isn't an ESX a "linux machine" at a high level anyway? What makes this so unique and innovative?
<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> is the "unified declarative API surface" k8s API, and custom resources? What kind(s) of Custom Resources?
<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> what "really" is a vSphere Pod? Enough with all the marketing language!
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> maintains enterprise-grade governance, security, and operational consistency through <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>,&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Operations" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-o/vcf-operations.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Operations</a>, and&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> is vSphere Supervisor a higher-level abstraction around the above; or is it a separate entity that communicates (i.e. supervises) those sub-entities?
<br>vSphere Supervisor's <a data-href="vSphere Namespaces" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespaces</a> provide the foundation for multi-tenancy, enabling GitOps-based workflows, and delivering cloud-like self-service in private data centers.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> so tenancy is namespace-bound?
<br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>
<br>Use <a data-href="NSX Virtual Private Clouds" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX Virtual Private Clouds</a> (VPC) workload networks. This configuration is a requirement for using&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>
<br>Determine if a <a data-href="Single-Zone Supervisor" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Single-Zone Supervisor</a> or <a data-href="Multi-Zone Supervisor" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Zone Supervisor</a> deployment is required: In VCF 9.0, a Supervisor deployed in a single-zone configuration cannot be converted to a multi-zone deployment after enablement. You must determine the target deployment model before initiating the Supervisor enablement process.
<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> what is single-zone versus multi-zone? Single-Zone Deployment: A Single-Zone Supervisor deployment uses a single vSphere cluster to host both workloads and Supervisor management components. <br>Additional <a data-href="vSphere Zone" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Zone</a>s can be added after initial enablement. However, these zones are used exclusively for workload placement and do not host <a data-href="Supervisor control plane components" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor control plane components</a>. <br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> what are Supervisor control plane components? <br>
Multi-Zone Deployment: A Multi-Zone Supervisor deployment uses three <a data-href="vSphere cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere cluster</a>s, placing each cluster into a <a data-href="vSphere Zone" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Zone</a>. vSphere Zones are used by workloads and Supervisor management components to deliver high availability and expose each cluster as an independent, consumable availability zone. This configuration provides a resilient, HA-capable platform. Additional vSphere Zones can be added after initial enablement. However, these additional zones are available for workload consumption only, not for Supervisor control plane components. Single Host: Also a Single-Zone Supervisor with a single Control Plane VM deployed to a single ESX host, with vSphere HA disabled. While it shares the same characteristics as other single-zone deployments, in this configuration, any host failure results in downtime for the Supervisor Control Plane and potentially for associated workloads. <br>
Easy Supervisor: This is a Single-Zone simplified deployment that uses workload networking on top of <a data-href="vSphere Distributed Switch" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Distributed Switch</a>, designed as a fast and simple starting point for proof-of-concept environments and production deployments leveraging vSphere Distributed Switch. An Easy Supervisor deployment consists of: One Supervisor Control Plane VM
A shared network for both workload and management traffic
No load balancer <br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> does that imply that normally workload and management traffic is spilt? <br>It is <a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> running in special Kubernetes-enabled mode.
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> consumes what Supervisor exposes.
<br><img alt="supervisor-conceptual.webp" src="assets/supervisor-conceptual.webp" target="_self">You can think of Supervisor as vSphere with Kubernetes fused into its control plane.<br><img alt="ks-ns.png" src="assets/ks-ns.png" target="_self"><br><img alt="supervisor-diagram.webp" src="supervisor-diagram.webp" target="_self"><br>When you enable Supervisor on a <a data-href="vSphere cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere cluster</a>, you are activating a capability inside vSphere.
<br>Supervisor runs inside <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
<br>Uses <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> as the <a data-href="control plane" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">control plane</a>.
<br>Creates <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s.
Exposes Kubernetes APIs, backed by native vSphere primitives.
So conceptually, Supervisor is vSphere operating in "Kubernetes-native mode".<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s are not Kubernetes namespaces.If classic vSphere is "run VMs", Supervisor vSphere is "Run anything (VMs, Pods, services)" with the same primitives.
<br>Supervisor runs on <a data-href="ESX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/esx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESX</a>.
It enables Kubernetes semantics backed by vSphere primitives.
<br><a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> is optional and sits above Supervisor.
<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s look like Kubernetes namespace on purpose.vSphere (authoritative substrate)
└── Supervisor ├── Kubernetes API (authoritative for some things) └── vSphere API/UI (authoritative for others)
There is no promise that:
every UI action has a YAML equivalent
or that YAML is the “source of truth” for all infra
Instead:
some things are Kubernetes-first
some things remain vSphere-first
Kubernetes manifest → vSphere policy enforcement.
Create VMs via VirtualMachine CRDs (VM Operator)
Create Pods / Deployments
Attach storage
Attach networks (within guardrails) PVCs backed by vSphere storage policies
Datastore selection via StorageClasses
Policy-based placement Declare “I need this secret”
Injector materializes it
VCF Secret Service enforces access <br>Pods/VMs attach to <a data-href="NSX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a>-backed segments
Load balancers exposed via K8s Service abstractions
You don’t manage NSX topology in YAML, but you consume it declaratively. Infrastructure topology
Tenancy and Governance constructs (Organization, Projects, Quoatas at Provider level, Approval, Chargeback) Those live in VCF Automation / vSphere UI, not Kubernetes. So: vSphere Supervisor exposes a Kubernetes-native API surface for workload consumption (pods, VMs, storage, networking), while infrastructure topology, tenancy, and governance remain vSphere- and Automation-controlled.<br><img alt="vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" src="assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vsphere-supervisor-cf6fb05a-eddd-448c-a4ff-fee4f42f207a.webp" src="assets/vsphere-supervisor-cf6fb05a-eddd-448c-a4ff-fee4f42f207a.webp" target="_self"><br>
<img alt="vsphere-supervisor-c3733e8c-9204-4e01-8b0c-5bc816bdbf77.webp" src="assets/vsphere-supervisor-c3733e8c-9204-4e01-8b0c-5bc816bdbf77.webp" target="_self">]]></description><link>vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Main Componets/engine/vSphere Supervisor/vSphere Supervisor.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 17:04:23 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/supervisor-cluster-placement.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:59:25 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/vsphere-with-tanzu-vm-service.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Automation and VCF Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img alt="vcf-operations.webp" src="assets/vcf-operations.webp" target="_self">VCF-O does not:
Own tenancy boundaries
Gate workload creation
Enforce business approval flows
Define org/project constructs
Those remain in:
VCF-A
Supervisor
Upstream automation layers
VCF-O observes those constructs after the fact.
Day 0 / Day 1 → VCF-A - Who can create? - What can be created? - Under what policies? Day 2 → VCF-O - Is it healthy? - Is it over/under-utilized? - Is it behaving strangely?
VCF (the platform)
├── VCF Automation (formerly Aria Automation)
├── VCF Operations (formerly Aria Operations)
├── Supervisor / vSphere
└── Workloads
Here is how things looks from each layer’s point of view:<br>Once a workload cluster is instantiated in a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>, it has no awareness of <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> constructs such as Organization or Project—Those concepts exist only at the governance layer (VCF-A) and are not part of the runtime execution model (Supervisor).]]></description><link>vcf-automation-and-vcf-operations.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF Automation and VCF Operations.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:26:04 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/vcf-operations.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/vcf-operations.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[TKG]]></title><description><![CDATA[TKG (Tanzu Kubernetes Grid) is VMware’s CNCF-conformant Kubernetes distribution, integrated deeply with <a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>.TKG, in this context is: Upstream Kubernetes + VMware’s opinionated lifecycle, security, and infrastructure integration.
Runs on vSphere
Worker nodes are VMs
<br>Created and managed via <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
Tightly integrated with: <br><a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> networking (<a data-href="NSX" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/nsx/nsx.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">NSX</a> / <a data-href="VDS" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsan/vds.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VDS</a>)
<br>vSphere storage (<a data-href="vSAN" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsan/vsan.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSAN</a>, <a data-href="CNS" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsan/cns.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CNS</a>)
vSphere IAM / RBAC boundaries Inside the guest cluster:
Kubernetes sees: Namespaces
RBAC
CRDs
Workloads It does not see: Organizations
Projects
Approval flows
Business tenancy Those live outside the cluster, enforced by:
<br><a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>
<br><a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>
<br>Automation layers (i.e., <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>)
This is similar to saying “a Docker container does not know which Jira project paid for the VM it runs on”.vSphere / ESX
└── Supervisor Cluster └── Supervisor Namespace └── TKG Workload Cluster (guest cluster) ├── Kubernetes API ├── Nodes = VMs └── Apps / Pods ]]></description><link>tkg/tkg.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">TKG/TKG.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:13:25 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Guest Cluster]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a><br>Once a workload cluster (<a data-href="TKG" href="tkg/tkg.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">TKG</a>) is bound to a <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>:
✅ The cluster knows which Supervisor Namespace it lives in
❌ It has no intrinsic knowledge of: Organization
Project
Automation constructs
Approval flows
Business tenancy
<br>^ all of these concepts stop at the **<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> boundary. <br>When a workload cluster is bound to a Supervisor Namespace, we are talking about a TKG workload cluster created by the <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>.That implies:
The cluster is created via Supervisor APIs
<br>It is <a data-href="vSphere Namespaces" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Namespaces</a>-scoped
It is lifecycle-managed by vSphere
It runs on ESX using VM-based worker nodes
So, in this model:<br>
Guest cluster == <a data-href="TKG" href="tkg/tkg.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">TKG</a> workload cluster]]></description><link>tkg/guest-cluster.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">TKG/Guest Cluster.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:07:10 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vMotion]]></title><link>vmotion.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vMotion.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 16:03:54 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tenants in Supervisor]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>
In vSphere Supervisor a tenant is namespace-bound.
There is no separate tenant object inside Kubernetes.
<br>A <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> is the tenant boundary at the vSphere-Kubernetes interface.
If you assume:
Tenant = Project → you’ll design the wrong thing
Tenant = Kubernetes namespace → you’ll under-secure
Tenant = Supervisor Namespace → things line up
“tenant namespace” is an informal shorthand for supervisor namespace. Organizations and Projects are governance overlays. They do not define the tenant.Kubernetes namespaces inside guest clusters are secondary scopes.<br>In <a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a> each tenant is realized as one (or more) <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s.<br>
<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> sits above, provides governance (Organizations, Projects, quotas) and self-service, but does not define tenancy by itself.This is sometimes “informally” expressed as “tenant namespaces”. What is meant by it is a Supervisor Namespace.Or more precisely: In a Supervisor Cluster tenant == supervisor namespace (there is a 1-1 relationship).<br>In vSphere Supervisor, tenancy is realized through <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s, which serve as the execution and isolation boundary for tenants.When people say:
“tenant namespace”
“project namespace”
“customer namespace”
They almost always mean: A Supervisor Namespace allocated to that tenant. Kubernetes does not have a separate construct for this: It is a vSphere concept, projected as a namespace.A Supervisor Namespace can contain:
Pods
VMs
Entire guest Kubernetes clusters
Tenant
└── Supervisor Namespace ├── VM workloads ├── Pod workloads └── Guest K8s Cluster └── many Kubernetes namespaces
VCF Environment
└── vSphere (vCenter) └── Supervisor Cluster └── Supervisor Namespace ← TENANT BOUNDARY
At this layer:
Supervisor Namespace Has: Resource limits
Storage policies
Network segments
RBAC bindings Is created and owned by vCenter
Maps to: Resource pools
NSX constructs
Datastore permissions
This is where hard multitenancy lives. <br><img alt="supervisor-cluster.webp" src="assets/supervisor-cluster.webp" target="_self"><br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>This is logical tenancy, not execution tenancy.Organization
└── Project └── Deployment / Blueprint └── (Targets a Supervisor Namespace) Organization Business / administrative grouping Project Quota + governance container These map downwards, but they don’t execute workloads themselves.<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a> defines a tenant from a runtime and security perspective.<br>At <a data-href="VCF-A" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-a.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF-A</a> Organizations and Projects define:
Ownership
Billing
<br><a data-href="Governance" href="vcf/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a>
Access workflows
But not execution boundaries.
VCF Environment (Rackspace)
└── Supervisor Cluster ├── ns-cocacola ← Tenant: Coca-Cola ├── ns-pepsi ← Tenant: Pepsi └── ns-pizzahut ← Tenant: Pizza Hut
Each tenant is a supervisor namespace.<br><img alt="Supervisor-Namespace.png" src="assets/supervisor-namespace.png" target="_self">For Coca-Cola (example):
Fixed CPU / memory quota
Dedicated or isolated NSX segment
Approved storage policies
RBAC scoped to Coca-Cola admins
Ability to run: Pods
VMs
Guest Kubernetes clusters
That namespace is the tenant boundary. Layer VCF automation on top of this:Organization: Coca-Cola
└── Project: Coke-Prod └── Deployments → targets ns-cocacola Organization: Pepsi
└── Project: Pepsi-Shared └── Deployments → targets ns-pepsi
Organizations and Projects map to Supervisor Namespaces — they do not replace them.Automation gives:
Self-service catalogs
Approval workflows
Policy as code
Lifecycle orchestration
But the tenant still “lives” at the Supervisor Namespace.Scope
vCenter
Supervisor Cluster
NSX
Storage policies
Responsibilities
Create Supervisor Namespaces
Set quotas
Attach networks
Bind tenant identities
Enforce platform guardrails
Power level
God-mode
Not visible to customers
Scope
One Supervisor Namespace (e.g., ns-cocacola)
Kubernetes API within that namespace
Responsibilities
Manage workloads
Deploy guest clusters
Configure service
Delegate access internally
Cannot
See other tenants
Modify quotas
Escape namespace
This is who you hand the kubeconfig to.
Scope
Kubernetes RBAC inside tenant (supervisor) namespace
Possibly inside guest clusters
Responsibilities
Deploy apps
Manage services
Consume secrets
No infrastructure privileges
Scope
Automation policies
Catalogs
Projects
Approvals
This role:
Often held by Rackspace
Sometimes delegated partially to tenants
<br><a href=".?query=tag:secrets" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#secrets">#secrets</a>
Secrets do not cross Supervisor Namespaces
Identity trust roots often terminate there
Network policy enforcement happens there
Audit logs are scoped there
So when you say tenant == Supervisor Namespace,
then:
Security
Compliance
Billing
Automation
all align clearly.
]]></description><link>tenants-in-supervisor.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Tenants in Supervisor.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 14:35:58 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/supervisor-cluster.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/supervisor-cluster.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF Operations]]></title><description><![CDATA[VCF Operations&nbsp;helps your organization build, manage, operate and secure your private cloud infrastructure by deploying and maintaining its fleet-level components, providing visibility and enhanced performance across the workload and infrastructure stack, and helping your organization stay compliant with regulatory standards and organizational guidelines.VCF Operations has these functional areas:
