Simplifies full stack deployment.
]]></description><link>vcf/what-does-vcf-do.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/What Does VCF Do.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:23:56 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Multi-Tenancy]]></title><description><![CDATA[In a VCF-based platform, each customer tenant is represented by one or more <a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> <a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>s. These namespaces form the hard isolation boundary for compute, network, storage, and identity, while <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a> provides <a data-href="Governance" href="vcf/governance.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Governance</a> and self-service on top.<br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>]]></description><link>vcf/tenancy-concepts/multi-tenancy.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Tenancy Concepts/Multi-Tenancy.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:21:49 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tenants are Bound to Projects]]></title><description><![CDATA[
The <a data-href="provider administrator" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">provider administrator</a> can create <a data-href="projects" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">projects</a>, assign users and groups, and allocate quotas to restrict the configurations available to the <a data-href="tenants" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">tenants</a>.
<br>
By creating <a data-href="projects" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">projects</a>, you can isolate security and networking objects across tenants in a single&nbsp;NSX deployment.
<br><a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="vcf/tenancy-concepts/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a><br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a>]]></description><link>vcf/tenancy-concepts/tenants-are-bound-to-projects.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Tenancy Concepts/Tenants are Bound to Projects.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 13:17:50 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[VCF-A]]></title><description><![CDATA[See <a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.]]></description><link>vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-a.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Main Componets/engine/VCF-A/VCF-A.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 12:37:56 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere and vCenter]]></title><description><![CDATA[
vSphere is the platform (the whole virtualization stack)
vCenter Server is the control plane that manages the coordinates of that platform
ESXi is the hypervisor that runs on hardware and executes VMs.
I mentally see (but don’t tell) this as “vSphere is just marketing”:
There is nothing I can curl called vSphere. it is “air”. <img alt="what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" src="assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" target="_self">VMware vSphere is a product suite, not a single binary.To be clear: vSphere is a product name, or a platform name. Its components are the concrete things that actually do the work.vSphere includes: ESXi is the bare-metal hypervisor. <br>
<a data-href="vCenter Server" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter Server</a> provides centralized management. Platform features: vMotion (live VM migration)
HA/DRS
Resource pools
Distributed switches
Storage policies
Fault tolerance You cannot have vSphere without ESXi. You can have ESXi without vCenter (but it will be very limited). Connects many ESXi hosts.
Maintains inventory and state
Enforces cluster-level logic.
Orchestrates features that require coordination. vMotion between hosts
DRS placement decisions
Cluster HA
Supervisor Cluster (for Kubernetes / VCF) vCenter Server is a set of backend services:
Inventory (hosts, clusters, VMs)
State and configuration database
<br>Scheduling logic (<a data-href="DRS" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">DRS</a>)
<br><a data-href="HA" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">HA</a> coordination
<br><a data-href="vMotion" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> orchestration
RBAC, roles, permissions
APIs (REST, SOAP)
<br><img alt="What-is-VMware-vSphere-vSphere-Client.jpg" src="assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.jpg" target="_self"><br>There is exactly ONE UI name (“<a data-href="vSphere Client" href="vsphere-client.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Client</a>”), but it can connect to TWO different backends.
vSphere Server
ESXi Hosts
## Mode 1
Browser ↓
ESXi Host ↓
Embedded vSphere Client ## Mode 2
Browser ↓
vCenter Server ↓
vSphere Client ↓
Many ESXi hosts
<br>A <a data-href="vSphere Cluster" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Cluster</a> is a logical grouping of ESXi hosts that vCenter treats as a single resource pool and failure domain.
It exists only in vCenter
ESXi hosts do not know they are “in a cluster”.
When you create a cluster in vCenter Server, you are telling:
“*These ESXi hosts agree to be scheduled, balanced, and failed over together.”This enables cluster-level logic, such as
DRS (Distributed Resource Scheduler): vCenter decides which host should run which VM.
When to rebalance the load. <br>Uses <a data-href="vMotion" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vMotion</a> to move VMs between hosts. HA (High Availability) Hosts run a lightweight HA agent.
If a host dies: Other hosts detect it
vCenter (or preconfigured HA logic) restarts VMs elsewhere. Shared resource abstraction Instead of thinking: Host A: 64 cores Host B: 64 cores vCenter presents Cluster: 128 cores VM placement and limits are logical, not physical.A vSphere Cluster is not:Because from an operator’s perspective:
Hosts act like a pool
Failures are absorbed
Workloads move transparently
But architecturally: The cluster is an illusion created by vCenter. <br>A vSphere cluster is a <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a>-defined scheduling and failure domain over multiple <a data-href="ESXi" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESXi</a> hosts,[ Physical Servers ] ↓ ESXi (many hosts) ↓ vCenter Server ↓ vSphere features &amp; automation ]]></description><link>vsphere-and-vcenter.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vSphere and vCenter.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 11:59:41 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp" length="0" type="image/webp"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/what-is-vmware-vcenter-vs-vsphere-vs-esxi.webp"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor-Namespace]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="assets/supervisor-namespace.png" target="_self">]]></description><link>assets/supervisor-namespace.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/Supervisor-Namespace.png</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 05:41:22 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/supervisor-namespace.png" length="0" type="image/png"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/supervisor-namespace.png"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere construct]]></title><description><![CDATA[A vSphere construct is:
*A first-class infrastructure object that is _natively defined, owned, and enforced by the vSphere control plane (ESXi + vCenter), not by Kubernetes or higher-level automation layers.
Think of it as a primitive in vSphere’s own vocabulary.Below are objects that exist because vSphere exists — they are not abstractions layered on top.
Virtual Machine
vCPU
vNUMA
vApp Resource Pool
Shares / Limits / Reservations
DRS rules
HA admission control Datastore
vSAN object
VM disk (VMDK)
Storage policy Port Group
Distributed Virtual Switch
VM NIC
VLAN / overlay constructs Snapshot
Clone
vMotion
Storage vMotion
HA restart
Fault Tolerance All of these are authoritative in VMware vSphere and enforced by:
VMware ESXi
VMware vCenter Server
These are foreign concepts to vSphere — it may host them, but it does not own them:
Kubernetes Pod
Kubernetes Deployment
Kubernetes Service
Kubernetes ReplicaSet
Kubernetes Namespace (in the K8s sense)
Kubernetes ServiceAccount
vSphere sees these as resource consumers, not objects with meaning.A <a data-href="VM Workload" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VM Workload</a> is built entirely out of vSphere constructs.<br>
A <a data-href="Pod Workload" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Pod Workload</a> is built out of Kubernetes constructs, even though it ultimately consumes vSphere resources.## VM Workload VM ├─ vCPU ├─ vMemory ├─ VMDK ├─ Port Group └─ Resource Pool
Pod ├─ Container ├─ CPU request/limit ├─ Memory request/limit ├─ ServiceAccount └─ Namespace
]]></description><link>vsphere-construct.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vSphere construct.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 05:31:55 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Governance]]></title><description><![CDATA[Governance in VCF is the set of mechanisms that decide who is allowed to request which platform capabilities, under what constraints, with what approvals, and for how long — before anything is created.What Governance is not:Governance does not watch workloads.
It decides whether they are allowed to exist in the first place.Governance (VCF Automation)
├── Organizations
├── Projects
├── Blueprints
├── Entitlements
├── Approvals
├── Quotas
└── Leases Execution (vSphere / Supervisor)
├── Namespaces
├── Resource pools
├── Networks
└── Workloads
Nothing in the execution layer knowns governance exists.
Governance defines who may open the door.
Execution decides what happens after they are inside the house.
In other words, governance is “pre-creation” control, not runtime policing.]]></description><link>governance.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Governance.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 04:41:38 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Client]]></title><description><![CDATA[VMware vSphere Client is:
A web UI (HTML5 / JS)
Running inside either ESXi or vCenter
Consuming backend APIs
It consumes REST and legacy SOAP / internal APIs
Functionally: It is an API consumer
It behaves differently depending on where it is placed:
Same UI codebase:
Connected to ESXi → host-scoped
Connected to vCenter Server → environment-scoped
The UI is not “smart”: The backend defines reality.vSphere is a product contract, not a system.
<a data-href="ESXi" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">ESXi</a> and <a data-href="vCenter" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vcenter.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vCenter</a> are the systems that implement that contract.]]></description><link>vsphere-client.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">vSphere Client.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 04:02:51 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[What-is-VMware-vSphere-vSphere-Client]]></title><description><![CDATA[<img src="assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.jpg" target="_self">]]></description><link>assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Assets/What-is-VMware-vSphere-vSphere-Client.jpg</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 03:51:04 GMT</pubDate><enclosure url="assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.jpg" length="0" type="image/jpeg"/><content:encoded>&lt;figure&gt;&lt;img src="assets/what-is-vmware-vsphere-vsphere-client.jpg"&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kubectl in Supervisorlandia]]></title><description><![CDATA[Connected to Supervisor Cluster:kubectl config use-context &lt;supervisor-context&gt;
kubectl get ns NAME STATUS AGE
default Active
kube-system Active
kube-public Active
kube-node-lease Active
my-team-a Active
my-team-b Active
Here, there is no such thing as a “regular Kubernetes namespace” in the tenant sense.
The namespace here:
Cannot be created freely.
Map to <a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a> inventory objects.
Quotas, storage, and networking are externally-enforced.
Connected to a guest clusterkubectl get ns
kubectl create ns foo
kubectl delete ns foo
All of these will work as expected.
Supervisor namespaces → owns the cluster.
Guest cluster namespace → normal Kubernetes semantics.
# check Supervisor-specific APIs
kubectl api-resources | grep -i vm virtualmachines vmoperator.vmware.com # look at the nodes
kubectl get nodes -o wide # look for VM Operator
kubectl get pods -A | grep vmoperator
Supervisor cluster nodes typically show:
ESXi-backed control-plane VMs.
Special node labels
VM Operator components
Guest clusters look like:
Standard linux nodes
kubelet-managed lifecycle
No VM Operator CRDs. In a Supervisor cluster, tenant namespaces are Kubernetes namespaces whose lifecycle, limits, and security are owned by vSphere.
In a guest cluster, namespaces are owned entirely by Kubernetes.
<br><a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> ]]></description><link>kubectl-in-supervisorlandia.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Kubectl in Supervisorlandia.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 03:11:34 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[vSphere Supervisor Services and Standalone Components]]></title><description><![CDATA[Create declarative <a data-href="workload" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">workload</a>s and upstream Kubernetes clusters by using <a data-href="vSphere Kubernetes Service" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Kubernetes Service</a> and <a data-href="Supervisor Services" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Services</a>.<br><a data-href="Supervisor Namespace" href="supervisor-namespace.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Supervisor Namespace</a>]]></description><link>vcf/main-componets/parts/vsphere-supervisor-services-and-standalone-components.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Main Componets/parts/vSphere Supervisor Services and Standalone Components.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 02:30:39 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Untitled]]></title><description><![CDATA[Drag from below or double clickSpace + Drag to panCtrl + Scroll to zoom]]></description><link>untitled.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Untitled.canvas</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 01:56:33 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[test]]></title><description><![CDATA[test --- a
