It replaced application scheduling semantics.VMware’s bet was:
"Instead of forcing Kubernetes to run on top of vSphere,
we'll make Kubernetes a native execution mode of vSphere."
Supervisor is that bet made concrete.
vSphere = substrate
Supervisor = Kubernetes-native personality of vSphere
VCF Automation = enterprise automation layer on top
<a data-href="vSphere Supervisor" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere-supervisor/vsphere-supervisor.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere Supervisor</a>]]></description><link>why-does-supervisor-exist.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Why Does Supervisor Exist.md</guid><pubDate>Sun, 21 Dec 2025 00:08:11 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Supervisor-VCF-A Relationshipt]]></title><description><![CDATA[┌────────────────────────────┐
│ VCF Automation (vRA) │ ← lifecycle, blueprints, polic
├────────────────────────────┤
│ vSphere Supervisor │ ← Kubernetes-native control plane
├────────────────────────────┤
│ vSphere (ESXi + vCenter) │ ← compute, storage, networking
├────────────────────────────┤
│ Hardware │
└────────────────────────────┘ Supervisor: Exposes Kubernetes + VM APIs
Owns runtime enforcement VCF Automation: Consumes Supervisor APIs
Provides self-service, governance, orchestration Supervisor enables capabilities
VCF Automation operationalizes them<a data-href="vSphere" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vsphere/vsphere.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">vSphere</a>]]></description><link>supervisor-vcf-a-relationshipt.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">Supervisor-VCF-A Relationshipt.md</guid><pubDate>Sat, 20 Dec 2025 20:10:32 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Provider Management]]></title><description><![CDATA[<a href=".?query=tag:tenancy" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#tenancy">#tenancy</a> <br>IT teams and <a data-href="CSP" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">CSP</a>s can model <a data-href="Multi-Tenancy" href="vcf/tenancy-concepts/multi-tenancy.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">Multi-Tenancy</a> by using the concept of Organizations in&nbsp;<a data-href="VCF Automation" href="vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/vcf-automation.html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">VCF Automation</a>.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> Is a "tenant" organization-bound, or project-bound, or a mixture?
This approach allocates resources and manages users specific to each Organization.<br>
<a href=".?query=tag:todo" class="tag is-unresolved" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow" data-href="#todo">#todo</a> in the last one-pager review, Fanny and Stephen recommended the partitioning of the secret path at either project, or namespace level---I don't remember which one. Identify pros/cons of each approach and choose a solution that is aligned with their vision.
<br>This capability provides isolated environments with dedicated network setup. IT Teams and CSPs can monitor resource usage, control permissions, and provide <a data-href="managed services" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">managed services</a> while ensuring security through comprehensive <a data-href="network isolation" href=".html" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">network isolation</a>.]]></description><link>vcf/main-componets/engine/vcf-a/provider-management.html</link><guid isPermaLink="false">VCF/Main Componets/engine/VCF-A/Provider Management.md</guid><pubDate>Sat, 20 Dec 2025 17:58:09 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title><![CDATA[Links to Trace so that the computer does not OOMKill Itself]]></title><description><![CDATA[
